<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/ofd12b.gif">

<CENTER><P><A HREF="/ofd/hmofd_e.html"><IMG SRC="/images/ofd12.gif"></A>
</P></CENTER>

<H1><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">IRS 1 C</FONT></H1>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<P>The <B>Indian satellite IRS 1C</B> was launched in spring 1996 and operates at a
height of 817 km. Since 1979 the Indian government is active in satellite
remote sensing, but only now they are making the data commercially available
worldwide. The IRS 1C special characteristic is the <B>high resolution
of its PAN-sensor</B>, which introduces a new area of satellite remote
sensing. Currently high resolution data is available from Russia but not
covering the whole Earth. The IRS&nbsp;covers the Earth with a ground resolution
of<B> 5,8 m.</B> New applications will be made possible in the areas of
landscape planning, city planning and cartography. </P>

<P>The satellite images from Europe are received by the German ground station
of Neustrelitz and distributed worldwide. The revisit time of the IRS satellite
is between 5 and 24 days.</P>

<P><B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><FONT SIZE=+2>IRS 1 C information</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1 >
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P><B>IRS 1C Pan</B></P></CENTER></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P><B>IRS 1C LISS-III</B></P></CENTER></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P><B>IRS 1C WiFS</B></P></CENTER></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD><B>Ground resolution</B></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P>5,8 m</P></CENTER></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P>23,5 m</P></CENTER></TD>
<TD><CENTER><P>188 m</P></CENTER></TD>
</TR>
