<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Significant Events</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2>Significant Events in the Field of Alcoholism and other Drug Addictions</H2>
<DL>
  <DT><B>1935</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Bill W. and Dr. Bob S. found <A HREF="http://www.alcoholics-anonymous.org">Alcoholics Anonymous (AA)</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1943</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.yale.edu">Yale University</A> establishes Summer School of Alcohol Studies
  under E.M. Jellinek. <BR>
  <BR>
  Du Pont begins first corporate employee assistance program. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1944</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Marty Mann founds the National Committee for Education on
  Alcoholism, today known as the National Council on
  Alcoholism and Drug Dependence. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1949</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.hazelden.org">Hazelden Foundation</A> begins treating alcoholics in Minnesota. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1950</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Use of antabuse to treat alcoholism begins. <BR>
  <BR>
  National Institute of Mental Health establishes a special
  division on alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  Lois W. founds <A HREF="http://solar.rtd.utk.edu/~al-anon">Al-Anon</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
  Marty Mann's Primer on Alcoholism is published. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">American Medical Association (AMA)</A> resolves to create a
  special committee to develop a program for &quotmedicine's
  aggressive participation in the work of solving the problems
  of alcoholism.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1951</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>&quotMinnesota Model&quot--comprehensive treatment, including a full
  continuum of care and using the philosophy of <A HREF="http://www.alcoholics-anonymous.org">AA</A>--begins at
  Willmar State Hospital. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1952</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">AMA</A> first defines alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  R. Brinkley Smithers establishes the Christopher D. Smithers
  Foundation, a charitable organization whose major interest
  is in the disease of alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1953</B> <BR>

  <DD><A HREF="http://www.alcoholics-anonymous.org">AA</A> publishes 12 Steps. <BR>
  <BR>
    <DT><B>1954</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Ruth Fox, MD establishes the New York City Medical Society
  on Alcoholism, today known as the <A HREF="http://users.aol.com/asamoffice">American Society of
  Addiction Medicine (ASAM)</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
 <DT><B>1956</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">AMA</A> develops landmark resolution calling for broad
  acceptance of alcoholics in general hospitals and urges
  hospital administrators to provide adequate and appropriate
  services. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1957</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>American Hospital Association passes resolution to help
  prevent discrimination against alcoholics. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.fordham.edu">Fordham University</A> School of Social Services offers first
  full university course on alcoholism for credit. <BR>
  <BR>
 <DT><B>1960</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>E.M. Jellinek publishes The Disease Concept of Alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
 <DT><B>1962</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.yale.edu">Yale</A> Center of Alcohol Studies begins transfer to <A HREF="http://www.rutgers.edu">Rutgers
  University</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
 <DT><B>1963</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.apha.org">American Public Health Association</A> adopts an official
  statement on alcoholism, identifying it as a treatable
  illness. <BR>
  <BR>
 <DT><B>1965</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>American Psychiatric Association urges its members to learn
  about alcoholism and that health insurance plans cover
  alcoholism treatment. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1966</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Two federal Appeals Court decisions support disease concept
  of alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  President Johnson appoints first National Advisory Committee
  on Alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1967</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">AMA</A> passes resolution identifying alcoholism as a &quotcomplex&quot
  disease and recognizes that medical components are
  medicine's
  responsibility. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1968</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Federal Advisory Committee on Traffic Safety acknowledges
  substantial role alcohol plays in car crashes. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1969</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>President Johnson signs the &quotPublic Services Amendments Act
  of 1968&quot which provides $22 million in federal matching
  funds to build and staff specialized facilities in community
  mental health centers for the prevention and treatment of
  alcoholism and other drug addictions. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1970</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Congress passes the &quotComprehensive Alcohol Abuse and
  Alcoholism Prevention Treatment and Rehabilitation Act,&quot 
  known as the Hughes Act for its sponsor in the Senate,
  Harold E. Hughes.  The legislation establishes the <A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and 
Alcoholism (NIAAA)</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
  &quotComprehensive Drug Abuse and Control Act&quot classifies
  controlled substances according to their medical use and
  potential for harmful use. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1971</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>National Commission on Marijuana and Drug Abuse issues its
  final report, which identifies alcohol as the nation's
  number-one drug problem.   It also recommends ending
  prosecution for possession of marijuana for private use and
  calls for a single federal agency to combine all drug
  efforts. <BR>
  <BR>
  American Journal of Psychiatry and Annals of Internal
  Medicine publish the &quotCriteria for the Diagnosis of
  Alcoholism.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  The Association of Labor-Management Administrators and
  Consultants on Alcoholism, now known as the Employee
  Assistance Professionals Association, meets for the first
  time. <BR>
  <BR>
  American College of Internal Medicine includes alcoholism
  questions on the board examinations. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1972</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="pubs.html">The Alcoholism Report</A>, the first newsletter devoted
  exclusively to the field of alcoholism, begins publication. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.fda.gov">Food and Drug Administration</A> approves use of methadone for
  treating heroin addiction. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1973</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>U.S. investigators first describe in published reports fetal
  alcohol syndrome (FAS), the common pattern of birth defects
  observed in children born to alcoholic mothers. <BR>
  <BR>
  First federal Drug Strategy for Drug Abuse and Drug Traffic
  Prevention released.  It primarily targets illicit drugs. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/deahome.htm">Drug Enforcement Agency</A> created by the federal government. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1974</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Congress creates the <A HREF="http://www.nida.nih.gov">National Institute on Drug Abuse</A>. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1975</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Federal White Paper on Drug Abuse concludes that total
  elimination of drug abuse is unlikely but that government
  &quotcan contain the problem and limit its adverse effects.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1976</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>NCADD conducts Operation Understanding, a news conference in
  Washington, DC where 52 prominent individuals publicly
  acknowledge their recovery from alcoholism. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1977</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>President Carter calls for the decriminalization of
  marijuana. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1978</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.prideusa.org">Parent Resources Institute on Drug Education (PRIDE)</A> signals
  beginning of organizing movement among anti-drug parents. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1980</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>President Carter appoints National Commission on Alcoholism
  and Other Alcohol Related Problems chaired by Senator Harold
  Hughes which meets only once. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.gran-net.com/madd/madd.htm">Mothers Against Drunk Driving</A>, powerful grassroots advocacy
  group, forms. <BR>
  <BR>
  Per capita alcohol consumption in US peaks. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1981</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.usps.gov">U.S. Postal Service</A> issues a first-class stamp imprinted
  with &quotAlcoholism.  You can beat it!&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  Nancy Reagan begins &quotJust Say No&quot anti-drug campaign. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1982</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>The federal Block Grant Program transfers responsibility for
  the delivery of treatment and prevention services to the
  states. <BR>
  <BR>
  Former First Lady Betty Ford lends her name to a treatment
  center for alcoholism and other drug addictions. <BR>
  <BR>
  Children of Alcoholics Foundation established. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1983</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>First certification exam for addiction medicine specialty
  offered in California. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1984</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>The National Minimum Drinking Age Act requires all states to
  make purchase or public possession of alcoholic beverages
  illegal for anyone under the age of 21 or lose federal
  funding for highways. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1985</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Federal excise taxes on distilled spirits increase for the
  first time since 1951. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://pathfinder.com/time">Time</A> magazine heralds the &quotnew temperance&quot movement. <BR>
  <BR>
  First appearance of crack cocaine focuses enormous public
  attention on the illegal drug problem. <BR>
  <BR>
  American Academy of Psychiatrists in Alcoholism and
  Addictions founded. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1986</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Anti-Drug Abuse Act authorizes $4 billion to fight drugs,
  primarily through law enforcement. <BR>
  <BR>
  President Reagan issues executive order mandating federal
  Drug-Free Workplace program. <BR>
  <BR>
  Partnership for a Drug-Free America launches nation's
  biggest public service advertising effort. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1987</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>President Bush formally announces the &quotWar on Drugs.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  Drug Policy Foundation begins serving as the voice of the
  drug legalization movement. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">AMA</A> calls all drug dependencies diseases whose treatment is
  a legitimate part of medical practice. <BR>
  <BR>
  Weekly Reader survey reveals that 36% of fourth graders
  report they have felt pressure to try beer, wine or
  distilled spirits. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1988</B> <BR>
  
  <DD><A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/ ">U.S. Supreme Court</A> declines to overturn Veteran's
  Administration regulation--later changed by an act of
  Congress--that classifies alcoholism as &quotwillful
  misconduct.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  Office of National Drug Control Policy is created by the
  Anti Drug Abuse Act. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.dot.gov">U.S. Department of Transportation</A> requires drug testing of
  industry employees in safety sensitive positions. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://users.aol.com/asamoffice">ASAM</A> awarded seat in the <A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">AMA</A> house of delegates. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1989</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Mandated by federal law, the following label begins
  appearing on all alcoholic beverage containers:  <A HREF="govwarn.html">&quotGovernment
  Warning:</A>  1) According to the Surgeon General, women should
  not drink alcoholic beverages during pregnancy because of
  the risk of birth defects; 2) Consumption of alcoholic
  beverages impairs your ability to drive a car or operate
  machinery and may cause health problems.&quot<BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1990</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>The federal government publishes specific recommendations
  about the consumption of alcoholic beverages in <A HREF="health.html">&quotDietary
  Guidelines for Americans&quot</A> for the first time.  Urging
  abstinence for some groups and moderation for other adults,
  the guidelines define the limits as no more than two drinks
  each day for men, and no more than one for women. <BR>
  <BR>
  The Sensible Advertising and Family Education Act, which
  would require health and public safety messages in alcoholic
  beverage advertising, is introduced. <BR>
  <BR>
  Senator Harold Hughes founds the Society of Americans for
  Recovery (SOAR). <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1991</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Federal excise taxes on beer and wine increase for the first
  time in 40 years. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1992</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>The Americans With Disabilities Acts extends job protection
  (except in safety-sensitive positions) to alcoholics and
  recovering drug addicts in the private sector. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1993</B> <BR>
  
  <DD>President Clinton includes a treatment benefit for
  alcoholism and other drug addictions in his national health
  care reform proposal. <BR>
  <BR>
  <DT><B>1995 </B> <BR>
  
  <DD>Federal government acknowledges health benefits of moderate
  drinking in revised <A HREF="health.html">&quotDietary Guidelines for Americans.&quot</A><BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/ ">U.S. Supreme Court</A> gives brewers right to include alcohol
  content of their product on containers for the first time
  since Prohibition. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/ ">U.S. Supreme Court</A> upholds right of public schools to test
  student athletes for drug use. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.dot.gov">U.S. Department of Transportation</A> requires alcohol testing
  of industry employees in safety sensitive positions. <BR>
  <BR>
  <A HREF="http://www.fda.gov">U.S. Food and Drug Administration</A> approves prescription use
  of naltrexone in treatment for alcoholism. <BR>
</DL>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>
