<HEAD>

<TITLE>Congressional Update - 5/1/96</TITLE>
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H1><IMG SRC="graphics/capital.gif" ALIGN="MIDDLE"> Congressional Update</H1>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>104TH CONGRESS - PENDING LEGISLATION AS OF 8/8/96</FONT></B><BR>
<BR>
<B>CRIME BILL</B>
<PRE>Bill Numbers:	HR728/S3

Description:	Rescinds 1994 Crime Act Funding for substance 
		prevention, education efforts.

Action:		House passed;  under consideration by Senate 
		Judiciary Committee.

</PRE>
<B>FALSE ID ACT OF 1995</B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR1552

Description:	Strengthens enforcement of laws to prohibit 
		possession and distribution of false Ids.

Action:		None to date.

</PRE>
<B>SAMHSA REAUTHORIZATION</B>
<PRE>Bill Numbers:	S1180

Description:	Clinton administration & Senate proposal to convert 
		Substance Abuse Block Grant into Performance 
		Partnership Grants.  Maintains separate Demonstration 
		Programs for CSAT AND CSAP.

Action:		None taken by House; passed by Senate.

</PRE>
<B>YOUTH DEVELOPMENT BLOCK GRANT</B>
<PRE>Bill Numbers:	S 673/HR 2807

Description:	Committee bill includes strengthened focus on substance 
		abuse prevention efforts; requires substance abuse expert 
		to be included on community boards. 
	
Action:		None taken by the House; passed by Senate Labor & 
		Human Resources Committee.

</PRE>
<B>PUBLIC HOUSING</B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 117

Description:	Gives public housing directors greater ability to evict or 
		bar residents with alcohol or other drug problems by 
		eliminating restrictions on swift evictions.

Action:		Passed by House;  Under consideration by  Senate 
		Banking Committee.
</PRE>
<A NAME="FPA"> </A>
<B><A HREF="alert3.html">FAMILY PRIVACY PROTECTION ACT</A></B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 1271

Description:	Requires additional notification and consent of parents 
		of minors participating in federally supported surveys and 
		questionnaires.

Action:		Passed by House; approved by Senate Government Affairs 
		Committee.

</PRE>
<B>COMPREHENSIVE ALCOHOL POLICY ACT</B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3479

Description:	Restricts advertising aimed at kids, limit tax deductions and 
		market promotion program and provide health and safety 
		information.

Action:		None taken to date.
</PRE>
<A NAME="SOC"> </A>
<B><A HREF="alert5.html">SAVING OUR CHILDREN &quotAMERICAN RENEWAL ACT&quot</A></B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3467

Description:	Limits educational requirements for treatment providers.

Action:		None taken to date.
</PRE>
<A NAME="SRA"> </A>
<B><A HREF="alert6.html">STATES' RIGHTS ACT</A></B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3548

Description:	Renames the condition on federal funds requiring a 21-year-old 
		minimum drinking age.

Action:		None taken.
</PRE>
<B>HAROLD HUGHES COMMISSION ON ALCOHOLISM ACT</B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3600

Description:	Establishes a commission to study federal agencies and programs 
		related to alcoholism and find ways to improve research, treatment 
		and prevention efforts.

Action:		House introduced 6/6/96, Senate introduced 7/11/96.
</PRE>
<A NAME="DSAB"> </A>
<B><A HREF="alert4.html">DISTILLED SPIRITS ADVERTISING BAN</A></B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3644

Description:	Prohibits advertising of distilled spirits on television and radio.

Action:		None taken.
</PRE>
<A NAME="WRL"> </A>
<B><A HREF="alert8.html">WELFARE REFORM LEGISLATION</A></B>
<PRE>Bill Number:	HR 3734

Description:	Denies cash assistance and food stamps to those convicted of felony 
		drug use, possession or distribution.  Also allows religious 
		institutions to receive federal funds for treatment and prevention.

Action:		Passed by House and Senate.  President expected to sign.
</PRE>
<BR>
<P>
<I>For more information about these and and other federal policy developments concerning
alcohol and other drugs, subscribe to <A HREF="pubs.html">The Alcoholism Report</A>.</I><BR>
