<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Use of Alcohol and Other Drugs Among Women</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2>Use of Alcohol and Other Drugs Among Women</H2>
  <H3><I>ALCOHOL</I></H3>
  <HR>
  <H4>CONSUMPTION RATES, PATTERNS & TRENDS</H4>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>40.4% of females ages 12 or older report using alcohol
  during the past month; 2.1% drink heavily (defined as 5 or
  more drinks per day on each of 5 or more days in the past
  month), up from 1.4% in 1988 </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">US Department of Health &
  Human Services {USDHHS}</A>, Preliminary Excerpts from the 1992
  National Survey on Drug Abuse, Advance Report, No. 3, 6/93,
  pp. 7, 10). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Use of alcohol is highest among women ages 18 to 25
  </B><FONT SIZE=2><I>(Ibid., p. 7). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Non-use of alcohol is highest (74%) among women who have
  less than a high school education </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">National Institute on
  Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism</A>, Eighth Special Report to US
  Congress on Alcohol and Health, 9/93, p. 8). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>While the overall prevalence of alcohol use during
  pregnancy decreased from 1985 to 1988, it remained high for
  those already at high-risk for poor pregnancy outcomes:
  smokers, the unmarried, young and poorly educated </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (M
  Serdula, et. al., "Trends in Alcohol Consumption by Pregnant
  Women, 1985 through 1988," Journal of the <A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">American Medical
  Association</A> {JAMA}, Vol. 265, No. 7, 2/91, p. 878). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Women ages 65 and older are the group most likely to
  consume more than two drinks per day </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, Eighth Special
  Report, op. cit. p. 9). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <H4>ALCOHOL-RELATED PROBLEMS</H4>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>4.1 million American women ages 18 and older can be
  classified as alcoholic or problem drinkers.  Of these, 3.7
  million are white and 0.3 million are non-white </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>,
  Epidemiologic Report, 1/92). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>A national survey of women's drinking found sexual
  dysfunction to be the most consistent predictor of chronic
  problem drinking </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, Eighth Special Report, op. cit. p.
  21). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>A recent study linking victimization to alcohol problems
  found that almost 90% of alcoholic women were physically or
  sexually abused as children </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (BA Miller, et. al.,
  "Interrelationships Between Victimization Experience and
  Women's Alcohol Use," Journal of Studies on Alcohol,
  Supplement No. 11, 1993, pp. 107-117). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Alcohol or other drug use may make women more vulnerable
  to rape.  A 1988 survey of female college students found
  that 53% of rape victims had used alcohol or both alcohol
  and other drugs beforehand.  64% reported alcohol or other
  drug use by the rapist </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (J. Collins & P Messerschmidt,
  "Epidemiology of Alcohol-Related Violence," <A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">Alcohol Health &
  Research World {AHRW}</A>, Vol. 17, No. 2, 1993, p. 95). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Alcohol is present in more than one-half of all incidents
  of domestic violence, with women most likely to be battered
  when both partners have been drinking </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Ibid., p. 96). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>From 1979 to 1990, alcohol-related traffic fatalities
  declined 12% for males but increased 21% for females </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>,
  Trends in Alcohol-Related Fatal Traffic Crashes, United
  States:  1979-1990, 11/92). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <H4>HEALTH & TREATMENT ISSUES</H4>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>Women metabolize alcohol less efficiently than men,
  leading to higher blood alcohol concentrations over a
  shorter period of time and higher vulnerability to liver
  damage </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, Eighth Special Report, op. cit., p. xxvi). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Some studies suggest that alcohol consumption may be
  associated with a 10% increase in a woman's risk of
  developing breast cancer </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (M Longnecker, "Alcohol Consumption
  in Relation to Risk of Cancers of the Breast and Large
  Bowel," <A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">AHRW</A>, Vol. 16, No. 3, 1992, p. 224). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Among college women, there is a strong link between
  dieting and eating disorders and problem drinking </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (D Krahn,
  et. al., "The Relationship of Dieting Severity and Bulimic
  Behaviors to Alcohol and Other Drug Use in Young Women,"
  Journal of Substance Abuse, Vol. 4, 1992, p. 341). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>An examination of admissions records in a variety of
  health care settings indicates that women with alcohol
  problems wait longer to seek help and are more likely than
  men to use mental health services and other non-alcohol
  specific treatment programs when they do </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (CW Weisner, et.
  al., "Gender Disparities in Treatment for Alcohol Problems,"
  <A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">JAMA</A>, Vol. 286, No. 14, 1992, pp. 1872-1876). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Women make up nearly a quarter of all individuals in
  treatment for alcoholism </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A>, National Drug and
  Alcoholism Treatment Unit Survey, Main Findings, 1991, p.
  31). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Lack of child care is one of the most frequently reported
  barriers to treatment for alcoholic women </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, "Women and
  Alcohol," Alcohol Alert, No. 10, 1990, p. 3). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Women make up 35% of the <A HREF="http://www.alcoholics-anonymous.org">Alcoholics Anonymous (AA)</A>
  membership.  Among AA members ages 30 and under, 43% are
  women </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (General Services Branch of <A HREF="http://www.alcoholics-anonymous.org">Alcoholics Anonymous,
  Inc.</A>, 1992 Membership Survey). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
<BR>
  <H3><I>OTHER DRUGS</I></H3>
<HR>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>Some researchers have suggested that the lower prevalence
  of illicit drug use by women may be offset by a higher
  prevalence of use of medically prescribed drugs </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.nida.nih.gov">National
  Institute on Drug Abuse {NIDA}</A>, "Socioeconomic and
  Demographic Correlates of Drug and Alcohol Use," 1992, p.
  22). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Typical nonmedical users of sedatives are white females
  from the ages of 20 to 40 </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.nida.nih.gov">NIDA</A>, Drug Abuse and Drug Abuse
  Research:  Third Triennial Report to Congress, 1991, p.
  191). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>More girls ages 12 to 17 (6.5%) than boys (5.7%) in the
  same age group report current use of an illicit drug</B><FONT SIZE=2><I> 
  (<A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A>, 1992 National Household Survey, op. cit., p. 6). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Among female inmates, 40% reported using drugs (heroin,
  cocaine or crack, LSD and PCP) daily in the month preceding
  their current offense </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (US Department of Justice Statistics,
  <A HREF="http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs">Bureau of Justice Statistics</A>, National Update, Vol. 1, No.
  4, 4/92, p. 8). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <FONT SIZE=2>Compiled 5/94</FONT>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B><A HREF="problems.html">Alcoholism and Alcohol-Related Problems</A></B><BR>
<BR>
<LI><B><A HREF="youthalc.html">Youth and Alcohol</A ></B><BR>
<BR>
<LI><B><A HREF="defects.html">Alcohol-Related Birth Defects</A></B><BR>
<BR>
<LI><B><A HREF="workplac.html">Alcohol and Other Drugs in the Workplace</A></B><BR>
</UL>
