<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Alcohol-Related Birth Defects</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<H2>Alcohol-Related Birth Defects</H2>
  <H3><I>ALCOHOL</I></H3>
  <HR>
  <H4>DEFINITIONS</H4>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>Fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS) is linked to birth defects
  and is the leading known cause of preventable mental
  retardation.  FAS can be prevented by abstaining from
  alcohol consumption during pregnancy </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (B Anderson & E Novick,
  Fetal Alcohol Syndrome and Pregnant Women Who Abuse Alcohol: 
  An Overview of the Issue and the Federal Response, <A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">US
  Department of Health and Human Services {USDHHS}</A>, 1992, p.
  1.). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
    <B> FAS is characterized by a cluster of congenital birth
  defects that develop in the infants of some women who drink
  heavily during pregnancy.  These defects include prenatal
  and postnatal growth deficiency; facial malformations such
  as a small head circumference, flattened midface, sunken
  nasal bridge and flattened and elongated philtrum; central
  nervous system dysfunction; and varying degrees of major
  organ system malformations </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.samhsa.gov">Substance Abuse and Mental
  Health Services Administration {SAMHSA}</A>, Center for
  Substance Abuse Treatment, Improving Treatment for Drug-Exposed Infants, <A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A> Pub. No {SMA} 93-2011, 1993, p. 8). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Fetal alcohol effects (FAE) is characterized by milder or
  less frequent signs of FAS.  Low birth weight, subtle
  behavioral problems, or a partial display of physical
  malformations, may be seen in the newborns of women who
  consumed less alcohol during pregnancy than women whose
  newborns have FAS </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and
  Alcoholism {NIAAA}</A>, Alcohol and Birth Defects:  The Fetal
  Alcohol Syndrome and Related Disorders, USDHHS Pub. No.
  {ADM} 87-1531, 1987, p. 12). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <H4>INCIDENCE/PREVALENCE</H4>
  <UL>
  
  <LI> <B>An FAS rate of 3.7/10,000 births is reported by the
  Centers for Disease Control's Birth Defects Monitoring 
  Program, which uses the FAS diagnosis made during the
  neonatal period </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.cdc.gov">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</A>,
  "Fetal Alcohol Syndrome - United States, 1979-1992,"
  Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Review, 5/7/93, p. 339).  </I></FONT><B>The
  number of FAE cases is far greater than full FAS </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>,
  Alcohol and Birth Defects, op. cit. p. 12). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Making a diagnosis of FAS/FAE at birth is difficult
  because facial characteristics are difficult to discern</B><FONT SIZE=2><I> 
  (Anderson, op. cit., p. 4)</I></FONT><B> and  some features such as
  behavioral and cognitive functioning problems are not
  observable at birth </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (N Day, "The Effects of Prenatal
  Exposure to Alcohol," Alcohol Health & Research World, Vol.
  16, No. 3, 1992, p. 239).  </I></FONT><B>As a result, data on FAS/FAE
  incidence based on use of medical records and registry of
  birth defects are low </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, Eighth Special Report to US
  Congress on Alcohol and Health, 9/93, p.204). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>While the overall prevalence of alcohol use during
  pregnancy decreased from 1985 to 1988, it remained
  high for those already at high-risk for poor pregnancy
  outcomes:  smokers, the unmarried, young, and poorly
  educated </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (M Serdula, et. al., "Trends in Alcohol Consumption
  by Pregnant Women, 1985 through 1988," <A HREF="http://www.ama-assn.org">Journal of the
  American Medical Association</A>, Vol. 265, No. 7, 2/20/91, p.
  878). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <H4>RISKS AND CONSEQUENCES</H4>
  
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>The amount of damage produced by prenatal alcohol exposure
  depends on the stage of fetal development, biological and
  environmental variables, and the frequency and quantity of
  the mother's alcohol consumption </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.niaaa.nih.gov">NIAAA</A>, Eighth Special
  Report, op. cit. p. 204). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Pregnant women consuming between one and two drinks per
  day are twice as likely as nondrinkers to have a
  growth-retarded infant weighing less than 5.5 pounds </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (PS
  Cook, et. al., Alcohol, Tobacco and Other Drugs May Harm the
  Unborn, <A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A> Pub. No. {ADM} 90-1711, 1990, p. 16). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Newborns whose mothers drink heavily (an average of five
  drinks per day, especially in the last three months of
  pregnancy) may show signs of alcohol withdrawal such as
  tremors, sleeping problems, inconsolable crying, and
  abnormal reflexes </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Cook, op. cit., p. 17). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Newborns with perinatal alcohol and other drug exposure
  have hospital stays three times longer than those born to
  mothers who are drug-free </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Center on Addiction & Substance
  Use at Columbia University, The Cost of Substance Abuse to
  America's Health Care System, Report 1:  Medicaid Hospital
  Costs, 1993, p. 40). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Children with FAS commonly have problems with learning,
  attention, memory, and problem solving, along with a lack of
  coordination, impulsiveness, and speech and hearing
  impairments </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Anderson, op. cit., p. 4). </I></FONT> <BR> 
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>The total annual cost of treating the birth defects caused
  by FAS was estimated at $1.6 billion in 1985. For persons
  over 21 years the cost was $1.3 billion.  Neonatal intensive
  care for growth retardation due to FAS accounted for $118
  million </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Ibid. p. 1). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
<BR>
  <H3><I>OTHER DRUGS</I></H3>
<HR>
  <UL>
  <LI> <B>Current estimates show 40,000 to 375,000 drug-exposed
  babies are born per year.  These numbers reflect maternal
  use of illicit drugs only and would be much larger if
  alcohol and nicotine were included </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Cook, op. cit. p. 3). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>The actual number of drug-exposed infants may be seriously
  underestimated because hospitals lack systematic procedures
  for identifying these infants </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.gao.gov">General Accounting Office</A>,
  Drug-Exposed Infants:  A Generation at Risk, GAO/HRD-90-138,
  1990, p. 10) </I></FONT><B>and urine analysis can only detect maternal
  drug use within the past 24-72 hours </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Ibid., p. 20). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>The long-term effects of perinatal cocaine exposure are
  yet to be established.  The most consistent findings show
  obstetrical complications, low birth weight, smaller head
  circumference, abnormal neonatal behavior, and cerebral
  infarction at birth.  Children with this exposure are easily
  distracted, passive and face a variety of visual-perceptual
  problems and difficulties with fine motor skills </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (<A HREF="http://www.samhsa.gov">SAMHSA</A>,
  Office for Substance Abuse Prevention, Identifying the Needs
  of Drug-Affected Children:  Public Policy Issues, <A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A>
  Pub. No. {ADM} 92-1814, 1992, p. 3; Maternal Drug Abuse and
  Drug-Exposed Children:  Understanding the Problem, <A HREF="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">USDHHS</A>
  Pub. No. {ADM} 92-1949, 1992, p. 19). </I></FONT> <BR> 
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Large-scale studies confirm a positive association between
  physical defects among newborns and maternal smoking during
  pregnancy </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Cook, op. cit., p.22). </I></FONT> <BR>
  <BR>
  <LI> <B>Over 75% of all perinatally-acquired HIV infections are
  secondary to intravenous drug use by an infected mother or
  her sexual partner </B><FONT SIZE=2><I> (Maternal Drug Abuse, op. cit., p.11). </I></FONT>
  </UL>
  <FONT SIZE=2>Compiled 2/94</FONT>
<P>
<UL>
