<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Action Alert 12</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<B><A HREF="alert4.html"> SEAGRAM LIQUOR ADS SPREAD ON TV AND RADIO (11/1/96)
</A></B><BR>
<PRE>
Seagram has begun advertising its distilled spirits products on television and radio,
 in violation of its voluntary ban on broadcast advertising.
</PRE>
<B>BACKGROUND: </B>
<PRE>
Seagram's ads first appeared in Corpus Christi, Texas last spring.  Ads for Chivas 
Regal scotch, Crown Royal Canadian whiskey and Lime Twisted gin now appear 
on as many as 25 television and 50 radio stations throughout the United States.  
The largest markets include Boston, Houston, San Francisco and Milwaukee.  
Those campaigns continue to challenge the 50-year voluntary ban on broadcast 
liquor ads. 

On October 30 NCADD and other national organizations met with Reed Hundt,
Chairman of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), to discuss this issue.
Chairman Hundt has publicly expressed his concern about the ads, and is interested 
in investigating what actions the FCC can take.  NCADD has written to Chairman 
Hundt asking him to hold public hearings that would focus on the effect that distilled
spirits ads would have on children.  If you would like a copy of the letter, please 
contact the Public Policy Office at 202/737-8122, or e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:publicpolicy@ncadd.org">publicpolicy@ncadd.org</A>.
Chairman Hundt also expressed an interest in hearing from parents, teachers and 
others.  He needs public support in order to pursue this issue.  

</PRE>
<B>WHAT YOU CAN DO: </B>
<PRE>
<LI>	Write to Chairman Hundt and thank him for questioning Seagram's ads 
and encourage him to hold public hearings.

<LI>	Write to the other FCC commissioners and urge them to investigate the 
effect that these ads will have on children.


Address letters to:

		The Honorable Reed Hundt, Chairman
		The Honorable James H. Quello, Commissioner
		The Honorable Susan Ness, Commissioner
		The Honorable Rachelle Chong, Commissioner

		Federal Communications Commission
		1919 M Street, NW
		Washington, DC  20554

</PRE>

<B> TALKING POINTS </B>
<PRE>

<LI>	Since 1936 the Code of Good Practice of the Distilled Spirits Council of
	the United States (DISCUS) has urged members not to advertise on radio
	and television to avoid promoting liquor to underage persons.

<LI>	Respondents to a national poll (Eisner and Associates) who expressed 
	concern about TV liquor ads believed that the ads would make alcohol 
	problems worse.  78 percent said the ads would encourage young people to
	drink; 71 percent said they would contribute to alcoholism; and 60 percent 
	believed they would result in more drunk driving.  56 percent of the 
	respondents indicated opposition to the ads.  

<LI>	Television advertising for alcoholic beverages affects the manner, style and 
	meanings of drinking in society.  It defines drinking as positive and normative 
	behavior.  The ubiquity of the ads promotes an exaggerated view of the degree 
	of alcohol use in society.  Kids learn how, where, when and why to drink 
	from the ads.

<LI>	Television ads for distilled spirits will only add to the mix of problems that 
	parents already face as they try to raise their children.

If you have any questions or need additional information, please contact the Public Policy Office at 202/737-8122, or e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:publicpolicy@ncadd.org">publicpolicy@ncadd.org</A>.
</PRE>

<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=3><B><A HREF="alertdir.html" >More Action Alerts</A></B></FONT><BR>
</UL>
