<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Action Alert 11</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<B><A HREF="alert4.html">SEAGRAM'S TELEVISION ADVERTISING (9/30/96)</A></B><BR>
<PRE>
The Seagram Company is planning to expand television commercials for its 
distilled spirits products, in violation of its voluntary agreement to 
refrain from broadcast advertising, into new markets.  Chivas Regal and 
Crown Royal whiskey products are going to be advertised in Boston and 
Houston and are expected to air in Milwaukee, Portland, OR and San 
Francisco soon.
</PRE>
<B>BACKGROUND: </B>
<PRE>
This summer Seagram's began to advertise on television, despite the voluntary 
code of the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States (DISCUS) that opposes 
broadcast advertising.  NCADD and the Coalition for the Prevention of Alcohol 
Problems have been working to increase public opposition to this kind of 
advertising.  We have sent out several Action Alerts and letters and ran a full 
page advertisement in the New York Times asking Edgar Bronfman, Chairman 
of Seagram's, to end broadcast commercials.  (If you would like copies of the 
Action Alerts or the Times ad, please call the Public Policy Office at 202/737-8122, 
or e-mail at <A HREF="mailto:publicpolicy@ncadd.org">publicpolicy@ncadd.org</A>.)

In July, President Clinton called on Seagram's to discontinue its television ads 
and <A HREF="chart.html#DSAB">legislation has been introduced</A> in the House of Representatives to prohibit 
broadcast advertising of distilled spirits but no action has been taken.

If you have further questions about this legislation, please contact our Public 
Policy Office via e-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:publicpolicy@ncadd.org"> publicpolicy@ncadd.org</A>.
</PRE>
<B>WHAT YOU CAN DO: </B>
<PRE>
Protest this expansion of advertisements for distilled spirits by:

	Writing or calling television stations in the targeted areas.  Ask for 
a meeting with the station's general manager.

	Write letters to the editor of the newspapers in the targeted areas.

	Contact state and local elected representatives to get them involved.  
You can also try to engage the state alcoholic beverage control board in the issue.

You can also volunteer to provide the television stations with information and 
help on how to reduce alcohol-related problems.
</PRE>

<B> TALKING POINTS </B>
<PRE>
	Children already get an overdose of alcohol advertising on television ($588 
million in beer advertising).  The last thing they need is more television ads 
urging them to drink.

	Alcohol is the leading cause of death and injury among teenagers and young 
adults.  Alcohol use among high school students has been on the rise in the past two 
years; additional inducements to drink can only accelerate this trend.

	Opening up television to distilled spirits that targets 21 year-olds would 
inevitably appeal to 16-20 year-olds--just as we have seen with beer ads.

	President Clinton has called on Seagram's to maintain its voluntary ban on 
ads because they will expose our children to liquor before they know how to handle 
it or can legally do so.
</PRE>

<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=3><B><A HREF="alertdir.html" >More Action Alerts</A></B></FONT><BR>
</UL>
