<HEAD>

<TITLE>NCADD - Action Alert 4</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="R. Coleman, Occasional Designs">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<B><A HREF="chart.html#DSAB">DISTILLED SPIRITS ADVERTISING ON TELEVISION  (5/3/96)</A></B><BR>
<PRE>
Joseph E. Seagram & Sons company, in violation of the Distilled Spirits Council 
of the United States' (DISCUS) 50 year-old ban on broadcast advertising, has begun 
to advertise on television.  Advertising Age magazine reports the commercial first 
ran on March 20, 1996, on Prime Sports Network during an equestrian event.  Seagram 
said there has not been any public reaction.
</PRE>
<B>BACKGROUND: </B>
<PRE>
On March 21, the Coalition for the Prevention of Alcohol Problems sent out an Action 
Alert to Coalition members when Advertising Age reported that the Seagram Company 
trying to advertise its Absolut Vodka on television.  Twenty-two members signed on 
to letter.  A similar letter was sent to DISCUS, urging the distilled spirits 
industry to maintain its voluntary advertising ban. 

The Seagram Company seems determined to move ahead if its actions are not opposed 
by the public.  Collectively, we need to convey a strong message to the company that 
health, safety, religious, youth, disabilities and consumer groups will not tolerate 
the expansion of distilled spirits advertising into the electronic media.  For 
that reason, we request that you, and as many of your members, constituents, 
friends, colleagues, and associates as possible take immediate action to help 
keep youth-oriented television media off-limits to distilled spirits advertisers.

If you have further questions about this legislation, please contact our Public 
Policy Office via e-mail:  <A HREF="mailto:publicpolicy@ncadd.org"> publicpolicy@ncadd.org</A>.
</PRE>
<B>WHAT YOU CAN DO: </B>
<PRE>
Write to Edgar Bronfman, Jr., Chairman of Joseph E. Seagram and Sons, Inc., 375 Park 
Ave., New York City, NY, 10152 or call 212/572-7000 and express your disapproval 
of the ads and demand the Company's assurance that it will drop its plans advertise 
its distilled spirits products on television (see sample letter).

Write to Fred Meister, President of the Distilled Spirits Council of the United 
States, 1250 Eye Street, NW, Suite 900, Washington, D.C., 20005 or call 
202/628-3544.  Ask him what DISCUS is going to do to protect the viability 
of its Code of Good Practice.

Write to your representative and senators in the United States Congress at the 
U.S. House of Representatives, Washington, D.C., 20515 and the U.S. Senate, 
Washington, D.C. 20510  (see sample letter)
</PRE>

<B>SAMPLE LETTER: </B>
<PRE>
Dear Mr. Bronfman:

Your recent commercial on Prime Sports Network is a violation of the Distilled 
Spirits Council of the United States' (DISCUS) voluntary advertising code, to 
which you are a signatory.  I (we) expect your company to live up to its commitment, 
and abandon any plans for other broadcast advertising.

I (we) have applauded DISCUS' 50 year-old promise not to advertise on television 
or radio, which has helped to limit the amount of advertising that reaches children 
and adolescents, because young people are particularly susceptible to the commercial 
messages that glamorize or normalize drinking.  Drinking among high school students 
has increased over the last three years; additional inducements to drink distilled 
spirits can only accelerate this trend. 

I (we) have contacted my representative and senators in the United States Congress 
to express my (our) concern about Seagram's violation of DISCUS' advertising code.  
I (we) have urged them to consider restrictions on advertising in all media because 
the industry seems to be unable to monitor itself.
</PRE>


<B>SAMPLE LETTER TO CONGRESS: </B>
<PRE>
Dear Senator/Representative:

The Joseph E. Seagram and Sons Company, makers of distilled spirits, has recently 
violated the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States' (DISCUS) voluntary 
advertising code by advertising  on the Prime Sports Network.  I (we) ask you to 
contact the company and urge Seagrams to live up to its commitment, and abandon 
any future plans for broadcast advertising for distilled spirits.

I (we) have applauded DISCUS' 50 year-old promise not to advertise on television or 
radio, which has helped to limit the amount of advertising that reaches children and 
adolescents.  Young people, who are particularly susceptible to the commercial 
messages that glamorize or normalize drinking, are already under enormous pressure 
to drink.  Drinking among high school students has increased over the last three 
years; additional inducements to drink distilled spirits can only accelerate this 
trend. 

In the past, Congress has looked to the alcoholic beverage industry to monitor 
itself.  If members of the industry do not abide by voluntary guidelines, Congress 
should take steps to protect children and adolescents from alcohol advertising.   

Thank you for your time and consideration.
</PRE>
<UL>
