<HEAD>
<TITLE>CONTRACTS AWARDED FOR UNDERGROUND ROCK LABORATORY - NX 03/97</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="top" WIDTH="120" HEIGHT="40"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Contracts Awarded for Underground Rock Laboratory</H3>
<P>Nirex, the radioactive waste disposal company, has appointed a contractor to
construct a rock laboratory, if and only if, it receives planning permission
from the Secretary of State. </P>
<P>RCF Project Manager, David Lawrence, said: &quot;Setting up major contracts
like these takes many months.  The contracts have been put in place now to
ensure we can move forward in a timely way, if the Secretary of State gives
planning permission for the Rock Laboratory, and not before.&quot;</P>
<P>Construction of the proposed Rock Laboratory would create up to 170 jobs
directly. Approximately 120 people would be needed during the construction phase
and around 50 scientific staff would be employed to carry out experiments during
the life of the laboratory.</P>
<P>Significant indirect employment will also be generated.</P>
<P>The contracts contain special provisions which complement previous Nirex
initiatives to maximise opportunities for local business and employment.
Contractors will be required to publicise vacancies through the Whitehaven Job
Centre 'Job Bank'.</P>
<P>Mr Lawrence added: &quot;The core team of people which will be managing the
overall scheme is in place at our Greengarth offices in Cumbria and we're ready
to start work on site soon, subject to planning permission.&quot; </P>
<P>The Shaft-Sinking/Site Works and Science Design contracts which have been
awarded at this stage are worth, together, in the region of &#163;50 million.
</P>
<P>The Shaft-Sinking and Site Works contracts have been awarded to the
Cementation Joint Venture group, comprising Kvaerner Cementation and Cementation
Mining. </P>
<P>The Shaft-Sinking contract covers the sinking of two 5m shafts running
vertically to a depth of between 650m and 900m bOD, connected at the bottom by a
tunnel.  There are also some minor inset galleries. The Site Works contract
provides for the construction of  facilities such as winding houses, shaft
headworks, offices, workshops and stores as well as electrical, water and sewage
services, all of which are needed to support underground working.</P>
<P>The Science Design  contract has been won by the GIGA Joint Venture group,
whose principals are GeoScience Ltd, INTERA Inc. and Sir Alexander Gibb &amp;
Partners.</P>
<P>The contractor will produce detailed designs and plans for scientific
measurements which will be taken during the shaft-sinking phase.</P>
<P>Later in 1997 Nirex will award a second contract - the Science Execution
contract - to carry out detailed scientific measurements.  These measurements
will be carried out during the shaft-sinking in a programme integrated with the
construction works.</P>
<UL>
<LI> In May 1996, Norweb Contracting plc was awarded a &#163;1.2 million
contract to design, manufacture, install and commission HV and LV supplies,
transformers and switchgear for electrical power supply to the RCF site.
</LI>
<LI> In July 1996, a &#163;2 million contract for the refurbishment of the two
main winders was awarded to Markham &amp; Company Ltd. 
</LI>
<LI> To date Nirex has drilled 28 deep boreholes near Sellafield in West
Cumbria to test the rocks for their suitability as a location for the
construction of a repository for intermediate level and some low-level
radioactive wastes at Longlands Farm.  The next stage in the investigation
programme is to construct a Rock Laboratory.  The public inquiry into these
plans sat for 66 days and ended on 1 February 1996.  The inquiry inspector's
report is now with the Secretary of State for the Environment for decision.
</LI></UL>
<P>Note for Editors:</P>
<P>Phase 1 of the Rock Laboratory is as outlined above and is planned to take
about four years.</P>
<P>Phase 2 comprises the construction of three main galleries, each about 150m
long at a depth currently planned to be about 753m below the surface, and is
planned to take two years.</P>
<P>In Phase 3 two of the Phase 2 galleries will be extended up to 375m and 600m
and three further galleries up to 200m will be constructed.  This is currently
planned to take up to four years.</P>
<P>As estimated for the public inquiry, the three phases of the Rock Laboratory
are estimated at a total cost of &#163;124m for construction with a further &#163;71m
for scientific research, at 1995 prices.</P>
<P>A decision on whether to apply for planning permission for a Deep Waste
Repository at Longlands Farm will depend on the scientific results obtained.
Present planning envisages it will be taken on the basis of information from
Phase 1 of the RCF.  Phases 2 and 3 will involve additional science
investigation.</P>
<P><CITE><EM>NX 03/97 Friday 17th January 1997</EM></CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I> </P>
<P>Taryn Rock: 019467 24880 (office) 0385 336091 (mobile) 01900 827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton: 019467 24885 (office) 0836 387584 (mobile) 01900 817045
(home) </P>
