<title>RESPONSE TO CUMBRIA COUNTY COUNCIL - NX 02/97</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p><img src="images/nirsmlog.gif" alt="Nirex logo" align="top"
width="120" height="40"></p>

<hr>

<h3><font size="3">RESPONSE TO CUMBRIA COUNTY COUNCIL COMMITTEE
PAPER ON NIREX INTERNAL MEMORANDUM OF 10 DECEMBER 1996</font></h3>

<p><font size="3">Nirex has always said that there are scientific
uncertainties yet to be resolved. That, simply, is why a rock
laboratory is needed. The </font><a href="memorand.htm"><font
size="3">memorandum*</font></a><font size="3"> - by the Director
for Science, Dr John Holmes - challenged his team to continue the
search for rigorous answers, in the light of results from one of
many iterations of the safety modelling </font>cycle. That is his
management <font size="3">role.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">If the Sellafield site is not scientifically
suitable, Nirex has always said it will walk away. The document
confirmed that and also reflects the healthy level of scientific
debate within the Company.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">The kinds of issue covered in the memorandum
were thoroughly aired in the public inquiry into the rock
laboratory.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">Neither data arising since the Nirex 95 safety
assessment nor subsequent modelling, which is continuing, leads
the </font>Company<i> </i><font size="3">to change its view that
the Sellafield site holds good promise as a suitable deep
repository location.</font></p>

<p><font size="3">It as a great pity that the important
scientific debate about the disposal of radioactive waste, so
that it does not </font>pose<font size="1"><b> </b></font><font
size="3">a threat to our children and grandchildren, should be
turned into a political stunt.</font></p>

<p><a href="memorand.htm"><cite>* copy attached</cite></a></p>

<p><cite><em>NX 02/97 </em></cite><font size="3"><em>15th</em></font><cite><em>
January 1997</em></cite></p>

<p><i>Media Enquiries:</i> </p>

<p>Taryn Rock: 019467 24880 (office) 0385 336091 (mobile) 01900
827174 (home) </p>

<p>Nigel Monckton: 019467 24885 (office) 0836 387584 (mobile)
01900 817045 (home) </p>

