<HEAD>
<TITLE>Baseline conditions 'established' at Longlands Farm - NX01-97</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Baseline conditions 'established' at Longlands Farm</H3>
<P>An independent group of leading scientists has confirmed that 'baseline
conditions' have been established at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, which
Nirex is investigating as a potential site for a repository for radioactive
wastes.</P>
<P>The 'baseline' is the name given to the conditions in the groundwater system
prior to it being disturbed. Nirex has proposed the construction  of a rock
laboratory (or 'Rock Characterisation Facility' at the site. A public inquiry
into that proposal ended in February 1996.</P>
<P>&quot;The Company needs to understand the movement of water in rocks because
it is the main route by which radioactive substances could be transported back
to the surface at some future date&quot;, explained Nirex Director for Science,
Dr John Holmes. &quot;The sinking of the shaft of the Rock Laboratory is itself
a major experiment to disturb the system and measure the results. Therefore it
is important that this baseline is first established&quot;.</P>
<P>The Hydrogeological Review Group of scientists concluded that &quot;it
believes Nirex has satisfied the criteria set for baseline conditions and
fulfilled the commitment given at the public inquiry. The Group unequivocally
supports the Nirex conclusions that baseline conditions have been established&quot;.</P>
<P>Dr Holmes added: &quot;At the public inquiry, Nirex gave an assurance that
this peer-reviewed report on the baseline would be supplied to and discussed
with the Environment Agency. The report was forwarded to the Agency in December,
which provides them with an opportunity to give a view before the start of
underground characterisation.&quot;</P>
<P>To date, Nirex  has drilled 28 borehole in West Cumbria to test the rocks to
see if a repository for intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive<I></I>wastes
could be constructed at Longlands Farm. The next stage in the investigation
programme is to construct a Rock Laboratory. The public inquiry into these plans
ran for 66 days. The inquiry Inspector's report is now with the Secretary of
State for the Environment for decision.</P>
<P><A HREF="reports/96-004/96-004.htm">Link to Summary Report</A> S/96/004<BR><A
HREF="reports/96-006/96-006.htm">Link to Review Group Report</A> SA/96/006</P>
<P>Note to Editors</P>
<OL>
<LI> Copies of the Report on Baseline Conditions and the Report of the Peer
review are available from the Nirex press office.
</LI>
<LI> The Review Group Members are: Professor Peter Fritz
(Umweltforschungszentrum Leipzig-Halle GmbH - Germany) ; Dr Andreas Gautschi
(Nagra, Switzerland); Professor Gunnar Gustafson (Chalmers University of
Technology, Sweden),  Professor John Lloyd (University of Birmingham - United
Kingdom).
</LI></OL>
<P><CITE>NX 01/97 2nd January 1997</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)    01900
817045 (home)  
</P>
