<HEAD>
<TITLE>PET Traces Gas Movements - NX42-96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>PET Traces Gas Movements</H3>
<P>Scientists are using PET (positron emission tomography) to find out how gas
generated by radioactive waste and its containers could move through rock
structures deep underground over thousands of years.</P>
<P>The research is part of a major project called PROGRESS, funded jointly by
the European Union, Nirex, BfS of Germany, ONDRAF of Belgium, and POSIVA of
Finland. The aim is to improve understanding of gas generation and migration,
and validate computer models of these processes.</P>
<P>Nirex is investigating the rocks deep beneath a site at Longlands Farm, near
Sellafield, in West Cumbria, to assess their potential for the safe disposal of
intermediate and some low-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>Intermediate-level waste is typically immobilised in cement in stainless
steel drums which are expected to provide a very high level of containment for
at least 1,000 years. During this time, around 99% of the radioactivity will
have decayed away. Over time, the metallic and organic components of the waste
and its containers may degrade and produce gases such as methane, hydrogen and
carbon dioxide.</P>
<P>As part of the long term safety assessment, it is important to understand
how gases might migrate from a waste repository and whether they can affect
groundwater flow in the vicinity. Fifteen different sub-projects within the
PROGRESS programme are studying the processes involved in gas generation, and
the movement of gas through salt, clay and fractured rock. Experience gained by
oil companies in modelling natural gas migration from deep reservoirs will also
be called upon.</P>
<P>Nirex head of research and development, Dr Ian Crossland, said: &quot;Of
particular value is the PROGRESS work using positron emission tomography (PET)
to track the movement of gas through fracture networks in blocks of slate. It
will give an insight into the way gas travels in water saturated networks of
poorly connected fractures - which is how we understand the rock structure to be
in the area of West Cumbria we are investigating.&quot;</P>
<P>Laboratory-based PET experiments are to be backed by field scale gas
migration tests carried out in a shallow inclined borehole at the Longlands Farm
site. Helium, an inert gas, will be injected into bedrock and detected when it
rises through rock and drift deposits to the surface over the following months
and years.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;This involves techniques Nirex has developed at Reskajeage Quarry in
Cornwall,&quot; said Dr Crossland. &quot;We need to know how long the gas takes
to reach the surface and the area over which it disperses during migration.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Nirex is already monitoring the level of helium that occurs naturally in the
ground around Sellafield so that this can be discounted from experimental
results.</P>
<P>All the works in the PROGRESS programme is co-ordinated by AEA Technology at
Harwell. The PET work is being carried out by the University of Birmingham.</P>
<H3>Background information on PET</H3>
<P>Positron emission tomography (PET) is a recently-introduced laboratory
technique for showing the routes taken by fluids through labyrinthine networks.
Developed initially for medical applications, it involves doping the fluid with
a positron-emitting radionuclide tracer which produces two collinear 511 keV
gamma rays every time a positron combines with an electron.</P>
<P>Because these gamma rays will penetrate through the equivalent of 100mm of
steel, they can be detected, and the joint source of each pair of rays located,
from outside the slate blocks used in the PROGRESS project. This is carried out
by two large area positron-sensitive gamma ray detectors developed for the
continuous observation of flow through usefully large volumes of rock and other
opaque solids.</P>
<P>To assess the value of this technique in an industrial (rather than a
medical) environment, Nirex has carried out a series of small scale PET
experiments using water containing tracers of F-18 and Na-22 (half-lives of 110
minutes and 2.6 years, respectively). The fluid was pumped for over 90 hours
into artificial fractures machined in blocks of perspex, so that visual
observations of mass transfer could be compared with the PET results.</P>
<P><I>The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is the proposed
development of an underground rock laboratory (or Rock Characterisation
Facility) at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, to improve further the company's
understanding of local geology and hydrogeology.</I></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><CITE>NX42/96 23 December 1996</CITE></P>
