<HEAD>
<TITLE>International Experts Review Nirex Research - NX40-96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>International Experts Review Nirex Research</H3>
<P>A panel of international experts is undertaking a review of Nirex research
into groundwater conditions in West Cumbria.</P>
<P>The panel is chaired by Professor John Lloyd, Professor of Hydrogeology at
Birmingham University. Other members are Professor Peter Fritz from Germany, Dr
Gunnar Gustafson from Sweden and Dr Andreas Gautschi from Switzerland. All have
considerable experience of hydrogeology and hydrochemistry.</P>
<P>They are reviewing a report, prepared by Nirex and Golder Associates (UK)
Ltd, on baseline conditions at the Longlands Farm investigation site.</P>
<P>Dr Bob Chaplow, Nirex's Manager for Site Characterisation, said: &quot;At
the RCF Public Inquiry we said that baseline conditions had been established,
and gave an assurance that we would subject our view to further peer review. I
am delighted that such an eminent group of international specialists is
undertaking an independent assessment of this important aspect of our work.&quot;</P>
<P>The panel is due to complete its review of the report by the end of 1996.
Nirex will publish the report on baseline conditions, together with the panel's
review of it, early in 1997.</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>Nirex is currently investigating Longlands Farm near Sellafield as a
potential repository site for intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive
wastes. The next major step in this ongoing multi-million pound research
programme is to build a rock laboratory at Longlands Farm to increase further
Nirex's knowledge of the site.</I></LI></UL>
<P><B>Technical Background</B></P>
<P>Prior to the construction of the RCF, baseline conditions with regard to
groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry need to be established. Sufficient
information needs to have been acquired so that:</P>
<UL>
<LI> the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured with confidence and
used to develop and test models of the site; and
</LI>
<LI> there is a sufficient database on undisturbed conditions that the
properties of the potential repository zone can be interpreted within the
context of regional groundwater flow and hydrochemical models
</LI></UL>
<P><CITE>NX40/96 11 December 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
