<TITLE>Nirex Condemns 'Science' by Press Release.</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.04z"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Condemns 'Science' by Press Release.</H3>
<P>Nirex has kept no report* secret.  It was published at the Public Inquiry
almost a year ago and was examined thoroughly at that time.  It is extraordinary
that Dr Haszeldine and Professor Smythe now attack this report in a press
release.</P>
<P>The report is over 200 pages long and Haszeldine and Smythe have
deliberately taken the worst case from 20 models, ignoring all the rest.</P>
<P>If Nirex cannot show that a repository will be safe then the Company will
not be allowed to build it.  So if dangerous levels of radioactivity could
travel through half a mile of rock in 40 years, then Nirex could not proceed. 
If Haszeldine or Smythe had read the evidence they would see that the waste
canisters would last at least 1,000 years and possibly up to 10,000 years. </P>
<P>Nirex Director for Science, Dr John Holmes, said: &quot;This press release
is yet another example of the selective use of scientific information.  It's a
shame that a serious debate is now debased to science by press release.&quot;</P>
<P>The press release plucks a couple of pages from a 200-page report whose
purpose was precisely to determine the level to which underground shafts would
have to be sealed for safety.  It indicated that the required performance level
should be relatively easy to achieve.</P>
<P>For some reason, Haszeldine and Smythe neglect to mention in a four-page
press release that they gave evidence at the public inquiry into Nirex's plans
to build a Rock Laboratory (or 'Rock Characterisation Facility'), on behalf of
Greenpeace and Friends of the Earth respectively.</P>
<P>Dr Holmes added: &quot;Nirex science is subject to independent peer review,
unlike this release which has not been subject to the rigours of scientific
review.  Nirex does not yet have all the answers.  That is why we want to build
a Rock Laboratory.&quot;</P>
<P>* 'Geologists warn that Sellafield radioactive waste could leak in 40
years', press release from University of Glasgow issued on November 29 1996.</P>
<P><CITE>NX 38/96  29th November 1996  </CITE></P>
