<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Nirex Under Pressure at Sellafield</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.04z"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Under Pressure at Sellafield</H3>
<P></P>
<P>Measurements of water pressure in 21 deep boreholes around Sellalield, in
West Cumbria, are giving Nirex vital information on the controls on groundwater
flow beneath the area.</P>
<P>Water pressure in 161 separate zones, at depths to more than 1600 metres
below ground level, are currently being monitored in one of the world's most
comprehensive site characterisation programmes. These zones are fitted with
automatic logging equipment to record pressures and temperatures round the
clock, at 2-30 minute intervals.</P>
<P>These measurements are part of investigations to establish the extent to
which radionuclides from waste could eventually reach the surface by transport
in groundwater flowing through pores and fractures in the surrounding rocks.</P>
<P>The work is part of the Company's ongoing multi-million pound research
programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a
potential site for a deep underground repository for intermediate-level and some
low-level radioactive wastes. To increase further its understanding of the site,
Nirex has applied for permission to build a rock laboratory (Rock
Characterisation Facility) at Longlands Farm.</P>
<H3>Technical Details</H3>
<P>Over the last few years, Nirex has installed an increasingly detailed
network of monitoring instruments in its deep boreholes. These are concentrated
in and around the Potential Repository Zone at Longlands Farm, but some are
several kilometres away and will allow monitoring of the background conditions
undisturbed by testing and excavation activities.</P>
<P>Most downhole instrumentation for groundwater monitoring at Sellafield is
produced by Canadian company, Westbay, which manufactures modular monitoring
systems. They are configured down the boreholes with multiple zones separated by
inflatable packers. Nirex uses Westbay MP38 and MP55 modules in l00mm, 123mm and
157mm diameter boreholes. Some of the holes are vertical, others are inclined,
or deviated up to 36 degrees from the vertical.</P>
<P>Strings of retrievable transducers continually record fluid pressures and
temperatures in a number of zones - generally between six and fourteen in each
borehole, but with up to 30 in others. Some zones can also be accessed for
further hydrogeological testing and water sampling.</P>
<P>After installation of the monitoring equipment in the boreholes, the
perturbations in groundwater pressure caused by drilling the borehole and by the
installation are checked to confirm their dissipation over a &quot;settle-down&quot;
period. Monitoring then enables the natural patterns and trends to be
established - the baseline groundwater pressure conditions.</P>
<P>The equipment is so sensitive that, even deep underground it can record air
pressure (barometric) variations, and variations in rock mass responses to earth
tides. These natural variations are identified and removed to allow detection
and analysis of seasonal, long term or induced effects.</P>
<P>The overall objective is to identify any fluctuations in groundwater
conditions over an extended time period. The results are used to help create and
calibrate computer models of the groundwater flow system, as an input to long
term safety assessments. The water pressure data are augmented with information
from weather stations, stream and river gauging and other boreholes, such as
those monitored by the Environment Agency.</P>
<P>As well as monitoring and establishing the baseline hydrogeological
conditions, the array of boreholes has also been used to observe the response of
the groundwater system to pumping tests carried out in nearby boreholes. In one
test, involving a five-month programme, water was consecutively pumped from four
separate sections of a 990 metre deep borehole, along the line of one of the
proposed rock lab shafts at Longlands Farm. Pressure at varying depths in the
network of instrumented boreholes was monitored for changes every two minutes
from sensors in wells close to the test site, and at 30 minute intervals for
boreholes more than a few hundred metres away.</P>
<P>Anna Littleboy, Nirex's Manager for Hydrogeological Studies, said: &quot;We
are getting top quality data from the Westbay monitored boreholes. Pressure
changes as low as 1kPa to 2kPa (100 to 200mm water heads) have been identified
in response to pumping from a central borehole.&quot;</P>
<P>Anna continued: &quot;Nirex recognises that carrying out investigations
perturbs the groundwater pressures. Indeed, predicting and tracking such
disturbance is the essence of many of the tests. We need knowledge of the
groundwater pressures and their natural variations before construction of the
rock laboratory commences. Monitoring the perturbations caused by construction
or the rock laboratory is itself an important scientific experiment and will
provide information to improve our knowledge of the groundwater system.&quot;</P>
<P>Nirex's management contractor for these hydrogeological monitoring studies
is Sir Alexander Gibb &amp; Partners, with Soil Mechanics Limited responsible
for the Westbay instrumentation system. They have worked with Westbay, of
Canada, to adapt the system for installation and use in the Sellafield
investigations.</P>
<P><CITE>NX 37/96  29th November 1996  </CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
