<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Jobs Boost as Nirex Restarts Drilling</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.04z"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Jobs Boost as Nirex Restarts Drilling</H3>
<P>Fifteen to twenty jobs will be created as Nirex restarts deep drilling
activities in West Cumbria after a break of almost two years.<BR>
</P>
<P>The posts will range from support staff on the drilling rigs to
hydrogeologists, chemists, laboratory and office staff.<BR>
</P>
<P>Nirex Operations and Investigations Manager, Phil Davies, said: &quot;We
expect to start work on Nirex Borehole 16 - near Seascale - in the first week of
December. Our contractors have been working very hard to get their teams
together. This has included advertising locally for a wide range of positions.&quot;<BR>
</P>
<P>Nirex is assessing the suitability of Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a
potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and some low-level
radioactive waste.<BR>
</P>
<P>Nirex will also be completing a borehole at Longlands Farm, which was left
unfinished in 1995 to avoid disrupting sensitive hydrogeological monitoring
experiments at the site. This will be followed by Borehole 15 - near the
Blackbeck Bridge Inn, east of the BNFL Sellafield site.<BR>
</P>
<P>Phil Davies continued: &quot;Although our previous drilling and testing has
given us an understanding of the movement of water through the rocks beneath the
site, we still need more information about the chemical composition of the
water. Borehole 16 is the first of a series of boreholes intended to give us
this information.&quot;
<BR>
</P>
<P>Nirex and its contractors have drawn on their experience over the last few
years to reduce the environmental impact of the new sites. &quot;We have
designed these sites to be as small as possible, compatible with safe working.&quot;
added Mr Davies. &quot;In addition, we have very tight limits on noise levels,
particularly at night. Our intention is to cause as little disruption as
possible for people living and working around the sites.&quot;<BR>
</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>Nirex is assessing the suitability of a site near Sellafield as a
potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and certain low-level
radioactive wastes.  The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is the
proposed development of an underground rock laboratory (or 'Rock
Characterisation Facility') at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, to improve
further the Company's understanding of local geology and hydrogeology.  The
Inspector's report from a recent public inquiry into Nirex's application to
construct  the laboratory is expected to be sent to the Secretary of State in
mid-December.</I>
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX 35/96  18th November 1996  </CITE></P>
