<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nirex Science Surfs the Net - NX34-96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Science Surfs the Net</H3>
<P>Nirex has started to publish its scientific reports on the Internet. The
Company plans to have almost 1000 pages of information on its website before
Christmas.</P>
<P>Director for Science, Dr John Holmes, said: &quot;As part of our policy of
openess, Nirex is committed to publishing its scientific reports as widely as
possible. The Internet is an ideal way of making sure that these reports are
generally available.&quot; </P>
<P>The first documents contain some of the information presented at a public
inquiry into the Company's proposals to build a rock laboratory (or Rock
Characterisation Facility) at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield.</P>
<P>Nirex Science Liaison Manager, Bruce Alderman said: &quot;Our existing
website, which contains a range of information on our activities, together with
our press releases, has proved very successful. To make it more useful to the
scientific community we will in future be publishing our reports on the same
site.&quot;</P>
<P>Since early November, surfers have had access to six reports, on safety
assessment, gas generation, groundwater flow modelling and biosphere research.
From early December Nirex expects to expand the site with further reports and
evidence to the RCF Public Inquiry. These will include Nirex 95: A Preliminary
Analysis of the Groundwater Pathway for a Deep Repository at Sellafield.</P>
<P>Bruce Alderman continued: &quot;This is very much a trial of the system.
Some of these reports are very large, and contain detailed diagrams and
graphics. However, if the expanded site is a success it is certainly something
we shall continue to support as part of our efforts to ensure wide availability
for our research results.&quot;</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>Nirex is assessing the suitability of a site near Sellafield as a
potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and certain low-level
radioactive wastes.  The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is the
proposed development of an underground rock laboratory (or 'Rock
Characterisation Facility') at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, to improve
further the Company's understanding of local geology and hydrogeology.  The
Inspector's report from a recent public inquiry into Nirex's application to
construct  the laboratory is expected to be sent to the Secretary of State in
mid-December.</I></LI></UL>
<P><CITE>NX 34/96 14 November 1996</CITE></P>
