<HEAD>
<TITLE>Friends of the Earth Seek to Mislead</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Book Is Selective With Facts</H3>
<P>Nirex today said a new book (see Notes for Editors) was seeking to mislead
the public about the Company's science and publication programmes.</P>
<P>Dr John Holmes, Director for Science at Nirex, said: &quot;This book
'edited' by Haszledine and Smythe is simply a rehash of FoE and Greenpeace
evidence and some legal statements presented to the public inquiry where they
were available free. Nirex always makes its information freely available for
full and open peer review. There is no indication that any of the 'evidence'
published by FoE or Greenpeace has been subjected to independent peer review.</P>
<P>&quot;The 'evidence' was rebutted by Nirex at a public inquiry into Nirex's
application to develop a Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF) at a potential
deep disposal site near Sellafleld. It contains nothing new. Indeed, it leaves
out the totality of Nirex's evidence to the inquiry which comprised over 200
written reports and reference documents and spoken evidence from 18 witnesses.&quot;</P>
<P>Typical of the inaccuracies is the claim that determining the suitability of
the Sellafield site might cost as much as the Channel Tunnel. The planned
expenditure is a fraction of the total cost of the Tunnel.</P>
<P>The book ignores the evidence of the Royal Society, RWMAC and numerous
universities and learned institutions who have praised or contributed to the
quality of Nirex's scientific research. The &quot;independent&quot; experts all
appeared as witnesses for Greenpeace or FoE, who are pressure groups. FoE
themselves admitted at the public inquiry that &quot;many of the best scientists
and engineers were already under contract to Nirex&quot;.</P>
<P>There are a number of misrepresentations in the release:</P>
<UL>
<LI> RWMAC has not stated that it is proposing to quiz Nirex on &quot;secrecy&quot;.
</LI>
<LI> The quotes provided in background note 3 are highly selective and taken
out of context. They are not a reliable guide to the opinions of the people
quoted. The authors conveniently ignore the fact that the organisations they
quote support the construction of a Rock Laboratory.
</LI>
<LI> RWMAC is &quot;of the view that Nirex correctly justifies the RCF as an
integral, necessary part of the overall science programme...&quot;
</LI>
<LI> The Royal Society Study Group also said &quot;The RCF is an essential
component of the Nirex programme.&quot;
</LI>
<LI> It is complete and utter nonsense to claim that Nirex will seek planning
permission for a repository within<I> </I>weeks of tunnelling to their targeted
depth. FoE and the University of Glasgow have no foundation for such a claim.
</LI></UL>
<P>Dr John Holmes in his evidence to the inquiry said: &quot;Results from Phase
1 of the RCF could be inconclusive and provide insufficient confidence to
extrapolate models across the Potential Repository Zone (PRZ). In this case it
would be necessary to carry out further investigations over more of the PRZ
using the galleries planned for<I> </I>Phase 2 and possibly Phase 3, before a
decision on whether to propose repository development is made.&quot; The total
programme of work in all three phases could take 10 years.</P>
<P>Notes to Editors</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>Nirex is assessing the suitability of a site near Sellafleld as a
potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and certain low-level
radioactive wastes. The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is the
proposed development of an underground rock laboratory (or 'Rock
Characterisation Facility') at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, to improve
further the Company's understanding of local geology and hydrogeology. The
Inspector's report from a recent public inquiry into Nirex's application to
construct the laboratory is expected to be sent to the Secretary of State in
mid-December.</I></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><I>Evidence to the RCF Inquiry showed planned expenditure related to
Sellafield at &#163;238 million to 2002. That is approximately one tenth the
costs of constructing and fitting out the Channel Tunnel.</I></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><I>Release refers to &quot;Radioactive Waste Disposal at Sellafleld UK:
Site Selection, Geological and Engineering Problems.&quot; Haszledine and Smythe
(editors).</I></LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX 33/96  8th November 1996  </CITE></P>
