<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Friends of the Earth Seek to Mislead</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Friends of the Earth Seek to Mislead</H3> 
<P>Nirex is accusing Friends of the Earth of deliberately seeking to
mislead the public about the Company's science and publication programmes.</P>
<P>FoE had the opportunity to debate the issues surrounding Nirex plans to
build a rock laboratory or 'Rock Characterisation Facility' at Longlands
Farm near Sellafield, at a 66-day Public Inquiry which ended in February.</P>
<P>Dr John Holmes, Nirex Director for Science, said: &quot;After a careful
examination of our programme at the inquiry, it is preposterous to say that
Nirex is trying to hide data from the public.&quot;</P>
<P>Contrary to FoE claims, Nirex makes its research available, freely and
openly, for expert analysis and opinion.  The Company works closely with a
wide range of distinguished universities and academics.</P>
<P>As well as planned scrutiny by the Environment Agency, the Company's
work is reviewed by the independent Radioactive Waste Management Advisory
Committee (RWMAC).  It has also invited the Royal Society to review its
work.</P>
<P>A panel of international scientists is currently undertaking a review
of Nirex research into groundwater conditions in West Cumbria.  It is wrong
to say this would be reviewed &quot;behind closed doors&quot;. As FoE
admits (in a buried footnote in its press release of 31 October) the report
will be published early in 1997.</P>
<P>Dr Holmes added: &quot;No information is being kept secret from the
public or the scientific community.  We welcome comments by experts but FoE
has, as so often in the past, ignored comments from independent
organisations on the excellence of the work undertaken by the Company.&quot;</P>
<P>Nirex also condemned FoE's claims that the people of Cumbria may not be
able to drink water from their kitchen tap as &quot;pure scaremongering&quot;.</P>
<P>Dr Holmes said: &quot;The claim is ridiculous.  We would not wish to
proceed, nor would the safety watchdogs let us proceed, unless our research
shows the site is safe.&quot;</P>
<P>Nirex believes that the site at Longlands Farm shows good promise as a
potentially suitable location for a radioactive waste repository and that
its evidence to the Inquiry  confirmed that view.</P>
<P>To date, the Company has drilled 27 boreholes in the Sellafield area as
part of its investigation to see if the site has the potential to host a
deep underground repository for intermediate-level and some low-level
radioactive waste.</P>
<P>Nirex Chief Executive, Michael Folger, said: &quot;We have reached the
stage in our programme where it is necessary to go underground to address
remaining uncertainties in our assessment of the safety performance of a
potential repository.</P>
<P>&quot;The Rock Laboratory is purely a research facility, a fact
acknowledged by Cumbria County Council which refused the planning
application.  Indeed, many participants at the Inquiry recognised the
requirement for a Rock Lab as a necessary step is assessing the safety
performance of a potential repository site.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The granting of planning permission for a Rock Lab and its
construction would not commit us to developing a repository at Sellafield. 
If planning permission is given and underground  research subsequently
showed that the site would not be suitable, Nirex would walk away.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&#183; As part of its efforts to ensure wide availability for its
research results, Nirex science reports are to appear on its expanding
web-site on the Internet.  By November 8, surfers will have access to
reports on safety assessment, gas generation, groundwater flow modelling
and biosphere research.  </P>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX 32/96  31 October 1996  </CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)   
01900 817045 (home)  
</P>
