<HEAD>
<TITLE>Boxing Up Old Nuclear Plants - NX30-96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Boxing Up Old Nuclear Plants</H3>
<P></P>
<P>Nirex is testing the robustness and safety of two prototype 3m<SUP>3</SUP>
containers for disposing of decommissioned plant and irradiated debris from UK
nuclear installations. The tests include dropping the container from 25 metres
on to a solid surface.</P>
<P>Large metal items of intermediate-level radioactive waste will be
immobilised with cement grout in these high quailty boxes to form a monolithic
block that is easy to handle and stack robotically in a deep underground
repository.</P>
<P>Both prototype containers are made of 6mm thick stainless steel. They will
be loaded with simulated waste and subjected to a physically demanding series of
lift, stack and drop tests. The results will be compared closely with finite
element analyses to find out if computer simulations can accurately model the
complex buckling and deformation that may occur if a loaded box were severely
impacted.</P>
<P>Shape, size and structure of these containers are determined by a number of
factors:</P>
<UL>
<LI>They must fit securely in Nirex's standard transport containers for the
journey from waste producing sites to the repository. The maximum dimensions and
weight of a loaded transport container are limited by the capabilities of
British road and rail systems.</LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI>They need a large lid opening to facilitate the packaging of large items of
contaminated waste.</LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI>They must stack up to six high, fully loaded to 12 tonnes, and be
manufactured from materials whose integrity can be assured during interim
storage, transport to the repository and during emplacement operations at the
repository.</LI></UL>
<P>Steve Barlow, Containers Section Leader at Nirex, said: </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The most challenging aspect of this project is to achieve the largest
physical opening which can be securely sealed with a lid, whilst meeting
exacting operational safety demands set by the Company.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Our two prototypes are almost identical apart from lid size. The
smaller lid version is slightly simpler in structural design. It has a greater
area of steel between the opening and the container's top corners - its
worst-case impact zones - to absorb high stresses and deformation without
additional lid strengthening.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>A novel design of integral stacking post spreads the loads imposed by
stacking the 12 tonne boxes. A folded channel section down the centre of each
6mm steel side gives the required strength and rigidity and importantly reduces
the amount of welding required. This is particularly beneficial during
fabrication as it minimises the extent of distortion to which thin stainless
steel is otherwise prone.</P>
<H3>Background Information</H3>
<P>This is the second type of intermediate-level waste container for the
packaging and disposal of radioactive waste which has been tested by Nirex. Last
year Nirex completed a series of punishing tests on 500 litre stainless steel
drums to demonstrate their robustness under impact accident conditions.</P>
<P>Stress analysis work on the 3m<SUP>3</SUP> boxes is being carried out by
consulting engineer Ove Arup and Partners using its OASYS-DYNA3D finite element
system. This has a strain softening feature which accurately models the
behaviour of cement-immobilised contents during impact. Without that feature the
computer would overpredict accelerations and underpredict deformation and impact
duration. Other complex behaviours the system can model include buckling of
sheet metal, twisting and distortion, bolt shearing and weld failure. Welded
joints in the boxes have been minimised by design ingenuity.</P>
<P>The boxes are manufactured by Gralum Engineering Limited of Nelson,
Lancashire, which also produce a range of 500-litre drums for the nuclear
industry.</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>Nirex is currently investigating Longlands Farm, near Sellafield as a
potential repository site/or intermediate-level and some Iow~lewl radioactive
wastes. The next major step in this ongoing mutli-million pound research
programme is to build a rock laboratory to increase fuirther Nirex's knowledge
of the site.</I></LI></UL>
<P><IMG
SRC="images/box50.gif" ALT="3 cubic metre intermediate-level waste box in the final stages of manufacture" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" WIDTH="356" HEIGHT="366"><CITE>A
Nirex 3m<SUP>3</SUP> intermediate-level waste box in the final stages of
manufacture
</CITE></P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"><BR></P>
<P><CITE>NX 30/96  31 October 1996  </CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)    01900
817045 (home)  
</P>
