<HEAD>
<TITLE>Radioactive Waste Data - A Hit On CD? NX27/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Radioactive Waste Data - A Hit On CD?</H3>
<P>A compact disc containing the latest information on radioactive waste
arisings in the UK is now being sent to government, industry and research
organisations.</P>
<P>The new <I>United Kingdom Radioactive Waste Inventory </I>was published in
October 1996 on CD-ROM, and in bound volumes. It has been prepared for Nirex and
the Department of the Environment by Electrowatt Engineering Services (EWI)
using information provided by the producers of radioactive waste in the UK
including Amersham International plc, BNFL, Nuclear Electric plc (now Magnox
Electric plc and Nuclear Electric Ltd), Scottish Nuclear Ltd, UKAEA, the
Ministry of Defence and URENCO.</P>
<P>Francis Brown, Radioactive Waste Management Section Leader for Nirex, said: &quot;This
is the first time the Inventory has been distributed on CD-ROM. We chose this
method because all the data can be stored on one disk and interrogated with
ease. Virtually every user will have access to a computer with a CD-ROM reader.
This supplements the paper copy of almost 3.900 pages.</P>
<P>Britain is one of the few countries where such information is made publicly
available. Organisations involved with the UK nuclear industry, and leading
environmental groups, will get a free copy for research purposes. Copies will
also be lodged with the British Library, for general access, and with the Nirex
libraries at Harwell, Oxfordshire and Greengarth Hall, near Sellafield, in
Cumbria. Other organisations can obtain copies of the report and CD ROM from
EWI.</P>
<H3>BACKGROUND INFORMATION</H3>
<P>A national Inventory of radioactive waste has been compiled on a regular
basis since the early 1980's.</P>
<P>The published documents consist of:</P>
<UL>
<LI><I>The 1994 United Kingdom Radioactive Waste Inventory</I></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><I>The Radionuclide Content of UK Radioactive Waste</I></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><I>The Physical and Chemical Characteristics of UK Radioactive Waste</I></LI></UL>
<UL>
<LI><I>A Review of the Processes Contributing to Radioactive Waste in the UK</I></LI></UL>
<P><IMG
SRC="images/wasteinv.jpg" ALT="Francis Brown, Radioactive Waste Management Section Leader, with the CD-ROM and printed versions of the latest UK Radioactive Waste Inventory" ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="5" WIDTH="390" HEIGHT="348"><CITE>Francis
Brown, Radioactive Waste Management Section Leader for Nirex, with the CD-ROM
and printed versions of the lastest UK Radioactive Waste Inventory. It has been
published on CD-ROM, for the first time, to make data more accessible to
industry, government, research organisations and other interested bodies</CITE></P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"><BR></P>
<H3>A Summary Report (available in paper copy only)</H3>
<P>This latest Inventory gives a snapshot as at 1 April 1994. It describes all
stocks of waste held in the UK at that date, together with predictions of wastes
arising into the future. In addition, disposals of low-level waste are itemised
for each of the previous three years since the last Inventory was prepared.</P>
<P>The Inventory took two years to compile, assess and quality-assure the data
on 1,066 different waste streams. The total volume of waste reported in the
Inventory is 2,200,000 m3 after conditioning, of which 40% will arise by 2060.
Base information came from an official survey covering the major producers of
radioactive waste in the UK. Compiling the information and supporting the
production of the Inventory represents a major commitment by all the
participants. Figures from minor producers such as educational and research
establishments, health authorities and industrial companies are also included.</P>
<P>Nirex needs this information to plan the transport and disposal of
intermediate-level and low-level waste to a deep underground repository. In
addition, the Inventory data contributes to consideration by Government
departments and agencies of strategies for the management, regulation and
disposal of all levels of radioactive waste. On the world scene the Inventory
provides information for the International Atomic Energy Authority and European
Commission.</P>
<P><BR><BR></P>
<P><CITE>NX 27/96 10th October 1996</CITE></P>
