<H3>Briefing Material for Technical Journalists:</H3>
<H3>Nirex Scientific Research and Engineering Development</H3>
<P>Much Nirex work is at the forefront of science and technology.  The Company
and its contractors apply numerous and sometimes unlikely disciplines to find
and validate methods for the safe disposal of intermediate-level and long-lived
low-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>Press information covering technically interesting and important aspects of
this work is issued regularly in line with Nirex's policy to make the results of
its research widely available.</P>
<P>If you have missed any of this information, or would like to revisit a
specific subject, attached is a list of recent titles under general headings,
together with a pr&eacute;cis of contents.</P>
<P><CITE>NX 26/96  23rd September 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)    01900
817045 (home)  
</P>
<P><BR><B>Articles marked (www) are also available, with illustrations where
applicable, on world wide web: http://www.nirex.co.uk</B><BR></P>
<P><B>TUNNELLING RESEARCH</B></P>
<P><B>Tin Mine Tests Teach Nirex New Techniques (NX 7/96: 15.3.96: www)</B><BR>The
UK's oldest working tin mine is used to test rock monitoring instruments and
develop new techniques that could play a key role at Nirex's proposed deep rock
laboratory.<BR><B>Illustration:  Installing test equipment 732 metres deep in
tin mine.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Tunnelling Tests Create a Helpful Disturbance (NX 33/95: 20.12.95)</B><BR>'Zone
of Excavation Disturbance Experiments' carried out in Sweden provide valuable
information on the measurement and analysis of very small movements in rock
structures.<BR><B>Illustration:  Diagram of acoustic emission source
locations.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Blasting Trials to be Carried out by Nirex (NX 18/95: 7.6.95)</B><BR>Small-scale
blasting trials at Nirex investigation site in West Cumbria confirm that
wildlife and people will not be disrupted by shaft construction for proposed
rock laboratory.<BR><B>No illustration.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Takes Swedish Lessons (NX29/94: 3.11.94)</B><BR>Tunnelling
experiments in Sweden to find out how to measure the disturbance to rock
structures caused by different construction methods:  tunnel boring machine,
smooth blasting and normal blasting.<BR><B>Illustration:  Tunnel boring
machine at &Auml;sp&ouml; Hard Rock Laboratory, Sweden.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>DEVELOPMENT &amp; TRANSPORT OF RADIOACTIVE WASTE CONTAINERS</B></P>
<P><B>New Reusable Transport Container for Radioactive Waste (NX 14/96:
6.6.96:  www)</B><BR>Nirex develops a range of new reusable shielded containers
for transporting intermediate-level radioactive waste safely by road and rail. 
Four drums in each container will be robotically loaded and unloaded at each end
of journey.<BR><B>Illustration:  Cut-away showing construction of Nirex's
heaviest transport container.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Cooks Nuclear Waste (NX 2/96: 26.1.96)</B><BR>'Flame grilling'
and 'oven baking' super-compacted drums of low-level radioactive waste at up to
1000&#183;C to find out if radionuclides can escape during fire accidents.<BR><B>No
illustration.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Planning Next Century's Radioactive Waste Transport (NX 25/95: 24.8.95)</B><BR>Using
LOGCOST, a computer-based logistics and cost model, to simulate &#151; to the
minute &#151; next century's movement by road and rail of radioactive waste
packages from 30 sites around Britain to a deep repository.<BR><B>Illustration:
 VDU view of LOGCOST in operation.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Drops Nuclear Transport Containers (NX 2/95: 25.1.95)</B><BR>One-third
scale models of forged steel transport containers &#151; designed to hold four
500-litre drums &#151; are drop tested at different angles to prove their impact
strength and robustness.<BR><B>Illustration:  Drop testing in action.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Finite Element Impact Analysis Accurately Match Physical Tests (NX
35/94: 18.11.94)</B><BR>Computer simulations of impact damage to 500-litre
drums &#151; designed to hold radioactive waste immobilised in cement &#151;
match accurately the results of full scale drop tests.  This demonstrates the
drum's robustness and safety, as well as helping to validate the computer
modelling software.<BR><B>Illustration:  Impact damage to drum compared with
computer-generated model.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>GEOLOGICAL &amp; HYDROLOGICAL INVESTIGATIONS</B></P>
<P><B>World-wide Queue for Proposed Rocklab (NX 17/96: 26.7.96: www)</B><BR>Scientists
across the world wait to use the results of hydrogeological experiments which
Nirex will carry out if it gets permission to build a rock laboratory in West
Cumbria.  This work is part of an international project to study the
interactions between the hydraulic properties of natural rock and
mechanical/thermal changes.<BR><B>Illustration:  Schematic of proposed Rock
Laboratory.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>3D Modelling Hits New Heights at 2000 Metres Depth (NX 11/96: 10.5.96:
www)</B><BR>Nirex makes important advances in three-dimensional computer
modelling of geological structures, using a system that will accurately
represent a 2km cube of rock and zoom-in to details just a few centimetres
across.<BR><B>Illustration:  Three-dimensional computer model of strata
beneath Sellafield.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Radar Reveals Sellafield Secrets (NX 26/95: 19.9.95)</B><BR>Ground-probing
radar is used to investigate near-surface structure of drift material deposited
in West Cumbria during and after the last ice age of the Quaternary Period. 
Models of ice movement will be developed from the results of this survey, and
potential pathways for water flow will be identified.<BR><B>Illustration:  Six
radar facies from Sellafield area.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>UK's Largest Electromagnetic Induction Survey Completed (NX 13/95:
24.3.95)</B><BR>Using Controlled Source Audio-frequency Magnetotellurics on the
surface to identify changes in rock type and salinity at 2000 metres beneath
West Cumbria.<BR><B>No illustration.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Stops drilling at Longlands to Carry Out Major Experiment (NX
3/95: 24.1.95)</B><BR></P>
<P>Water pressure tests carried out between a number of boreholes at 900 metres
beneath West Cumbria to determine if fractures in rock structure are connected.<BR><B>No
illustration.</B></P>
<P><B>Nirex Inclines to the Boring (NX 38/94: 2.12.94)</B><BR>New inclined
drilling rig can bore holes to 3000 metres depth at angles up to 45 degrees to
investigate rock structures in many different directions from a single site.<BR><B>Illustration:
 New drilling rig in action.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>BIOSPHERE RESEARCH</B></P>
<P><B>Sowing the Seeds of Successful Research (NX 15/96: 13.9.96: www)</B><BR>Fossil
pollen dug up in France is helping scientists to determine what trees and shrubs
flourished in West Cumbria between the last two ice ages.  Nirex scientists
consider that similar species are likely to return in the future after the next
ice age.<BR><B>No illustration.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Cumbria Aids Water Quest in Arid Area (NX 13/96: 24.5.96: www)</B><BR>Research
into groundwater flow in West Cumbria will help validate the SHETRAN 4
hydrological modelling system.  This computer model will prove a valuable tool
for water companies and international agencies involved in water resources
management and land irrigation projects.<BR><B>Illustration: Cut-away view of
valley showing water flows modelled by SHETRAN.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Grass Crops Sow World-wide Knowledge (NX 5/96: 5.3.96: www)</B><BR>Scientists
using different computer systems in six countries try to predict how ryegrass
grown in lysimeters at a Berkshire research station is affected by groundwater
deliberately dosed with radioactive tracers.<BR><B>Illustration:  Scientists
from around the world examine crops at research station.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Britain's Climate &#151; Blowing Hot and Cold (NX 22/95: 17.7.95)</B><BR>Assessing
the range of climates which Britain may expect over the next million years,
based on evidence of previous climatic patterns and trends from glacial deposits
and fossils, modified with additional data on the greenhouse effect.<BR><B>Illustration:
 St Bees Head, West Cumbria, was a desert are 200 million years ago.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex System Looks at Mediterranean Climate (NX 14/95: 28.4.95)</B><BR>SHETRAN-UK
computer modelling system helps determine how climatic and man-induced changes
may affect the Mediterranean landscape and agriculture over the next 50 years.<BR><B>Illustration:
 Processes represented in SHETRAN.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Cultivates Greens (NX 11/95: 17.2.95)</B><BR>Investigating the
possible effects on food crops of radionuclides from a repository returning to
the surface in groundwater after many thousands of years.<BR><B>Illustration: 
Monitoring crop growth in a lysimeter.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>MATERIALS RESEARCH</B></P>
<P><B>Nirex Seeks Patent for Innovative Grout (NX 1/95: 5.1.95)</B><BR>New
cement grout developed for backfill of repository will keep alkali conditions at
pH 10.5 for many thousands of years and retail its porosity and physical
strength within closely set limits.<BR><B>Illustration:  Grout sample after
simulated 100,000 years of water flow.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
<P><B>Nirex Cement Slows Steel Corrosion (NX 44/94: 23.12.95)</B><BR>Research
shows that stainless steel drums in a deep repository will take 100,000 years to
corrode by one millimetre when surrounded by special cement grout developed by
Nirex.<BR><B>No illustration.</B></P>
<P><BR></P>
