<HEAD>
<TITLE>Weather Watching in West Cumbria. NX25a/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Weather Watching in West Cumbria</H3> 
<P>A specially commissioned network of automatic weather stations in the
mountains of West Cumbria will help Nirex assess the suitability of a coastal
area near Sellafield as a potential site for a deep repository for intermediate
and low-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>State of the art meteorological equipment has been installed at six exposed
sites to form one of the first high-altitude monitoring networks in the UK. It
will collect data for a minimum of five years.</P>
<P>Anna Littleboy, Nirex Manager for Hydrogeological Studies, said: &quot;We
need frequent and accurate measurements of meteorological conditions, river
flows and groundwater levels to enable us to calculate water balances and help
calibrate our computer model of the near surface hydrogeology in the local
sandstone units.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Meteorological data is also used in Nirex's biosphere research, which
studies surface<I> </I>processes, vegetation and soils, and their interactions
with groundwater. Understanding the sources and movement of groundwater is an
integral part of our site assessment programme.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Hydrometeorological and climatological data from Nirex's weather stations is
combined with Meteorological Office information from four monitoring sites to
give the detailed coverage needed for the region which contains a range of
geographical environments.</P>
<P>Shallow groundwater levels are regularly recorded in 10 boreholes (to 65
metres below ground level) drilled by Nirex in 1995 to characterise the
Quaternary geology of the area. These boreholes will soon be augmented by the
monitoring of a further 13 Quaternary boreholes drilled during this summer.</P>
<P>Deeper groundwater flow is monitored by Nirex at 21 boreholes in the
Sellafield area. This data is added to measurements collected by the former
National Rivers Authority from 70 tube wells to present a wider regional view.
Nirex also monitors the flow of three local rivers and selected springs to
ascertain surface water drainage from specific catchment areas.</P>
<P>Explained Anna Littleboy: &quot;Spot measurements of spring flows under a
range of weather conditions help us to identify locations, volumes and the
nature of groundwater discharge.&quot;</P>
<P>&#183; The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is the proposed
development of an underground rock laboratory (or 'Rock Characterisation
Facility') at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, to improve further the Company's
understanding of local geology and hydroegeology. The Inspector's report from a
recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application to construct the laboratory is
expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State for the Environment by the
end of October 1996.</P>
<H3>Technical information</H3>
<P>Nirex's meteorological monitoring network consists of two hill weather
stations and four precipitation gauging stations.</P>
<P>Because the sites are highly exposed, at altitudes between 260 and 605
metres above Ordnance Datum, the equipment has been designed to work accurately
at wind speeds in excess of 100 knots (52 metres per second) and rain fall rates
of over 100mm per hour.</P>
<P>Each weather station has a heated tipping bucket rain gauge, set to tip at
0.2mm increments, plus a heated volumetric rain gauge for checking purposes. Net
precipitation is recorded by an unheated tipping bucket covered with an
artificial surface. Soil and air temperatures are also recorded. The two rain
gauges are heated to melt snow and ice so the volume of water can be measured.</P>
<P>In addition to the above, each of the two comprehensive weather stations
includes instruments for recording climatic conditions such as solar radiation,
wind speed and direction, wet and dry bulb air temperature, and soil heat flux.</P>
<P>All meteorological instruments are interrogated by an on-site logging unit
every 60 seconds. The average or total value of each parameter is automatically
recorded in a storage module every 15 minutes. Raw data stored at each site is
downloaded monthly to a portable computer for statistical analysis by Nirex
scientists.</P>
<P>The six meteorological stations were built and installed for Nirex by Didcot
Instruments to designs produced by Entec Ltd.</P>
<P><CITE>NX  25a/96 9th October 1996</CITE></P>
