<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cementing a Relationship with the Rocks. NX24/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Cementing a Relationship with the Rocks</H3>
<P>Scientists at Nirex are trying to find out how high-aIkali cement will
influence the geological barrier of an underground repository system over many
thousands of years.</P>
<P>They are studying the chemical reactions which occur when cement leachates
interact with natural rock. The results are being used to test the validity of
computer models.</P>
<P>This work is important because the safe disposal of intermediate-level
radioactive waste in a deep rock repository depends on the satisfactory
performance of physical, chemical and geological barriers. The chemical barrier
is a specially developed (and patented) cementitious grout called Nirex
Reference Vault Backfill. This will keep water in its porous structure at above
pH10 for at least one million years to inhibit the escape of key radionuclides</P>
<P>Nirex manager of geosphere research, Les Knight, said: &quot;We need to know
how high-pH groundwater from the grout will affect the natural geological
barrier surrounding a repository. For example, will it dissolve rock to create
new or larger paths for groundwater?  Or, conversely, will new materials be
deposited to block the flow?&quot;</P>
<P>Close examination of springs at Maqarin, Jordan, has given a clue to the
mineralogy involved. This unusual site is a natural analogue of repository
conditions. It contains groundwater at pH12.5 which has become hyper-alkaline by
passing through deposits of naturally formed portlandite - a key mineral
constituent of cement. For many centuries cement leachates in the spring water
have reacted with host rock to seal up fractures with newly formed minerals
including ettringite-thaumasite, calcium-silicate-hydrates and zeolites.</P>
<P>If similar reactions occur in a repository, the local groundwater pathways
will eventually be blocked with these minerals which will prevent the escape of
any remaining radionuclides.</P>
<P>Laboratory experiments to investigate this natural phenomenon have been
carried out at Keyworth, Nottingham by the British Geological Survey with
funding from Nirex, the Environment Agency, Nagra (Switzerland) and SKB (Sweden)
The findings are being used to test the capabilities of coupled chemistry/flow
computer models developed to predict the composition of solids and fluids
produced with time by alkaline action in a repository, and how these change the
properties of the rocks.</P>
<P>The experiments reacted four different powdered minerals with simplified
synthetic cement leachates in 300mm long columns at 70 Degrees Celsius. Analysis
of thin sections of the resin-set columns showed how leachates diffused through
compressed powder and identified the distribution of the new minerals formed at
specific times.</P>
<P>Les Knight continued: &quot;The next stage in this world-leading scientific
investigation is to carry out full-scale experiments underground in rock strata
where a repository may be built.&quot;</P>
<P>This work is part of an ongoing multi-million pound research programme to
assess the suitability of Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a potential site
for a deep repository for intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive
wastes. Nirex has applied for permission to build a rock laboratory (or 'Rock
Characterisation Facility') at Longlands Farm to increase further its
understanding of the site.</P>
<P>The Inspector's report from a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application
to build such a facility is expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State
for the Environment by the end of October 1996.</P>
<H4>Technical Notes on Barriers</H4>
<P>The safety of an underground repository for intermediate-level radioactive
waste depends on the satisfactory performance of physical, chemical and
geological barriers.</P>
<P>Intermediate-level waste is typically immobilised in cement in stainless
steel drums which arc expected to provide a very high level of containment for
at least 1,000 years. During this time, around 99% of the radioactivity will
have decayed away.</P>
<P>Nirex Reference Vault Backfill will be packed around the drums, so that the
conditions inside the repository will remain alkaline. This is intended to
ensure that most long-lived radionuclides, e.g. plutonium-239, dissolve only to
a very low degree and so are chemically contained while they continue to decay.
After one million years, more than 99.99% of the original radioactivity will
have decayed.</P>
<P>So, of the initial radioactivity in waste, almost all is expected to decay
in situ, and only a very small proportion might eventually enter the natural
geological barrier of rock strata about 700 metres below ground level.
Retardation and dilution in the geological environment can then control to
acceptable levels the concentrations of those remaining radionuclides and their
consequent radiological impact.</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="images/lab50a.jpg" ALT="Joint Nirex/SKB/Nagra study, carried out by the British Geological Survey at Nottingham." ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="5" WIDTH="375" HEIGHT="337"><CITE>Joint
Nirex/SKB/Nagra study, carried out by the British Geological Survey at
Nottingham, of the reaction of highly alkaline fluids with various minerals.
These experiments will determine the reaction, if any, between vault backfill
and the surrounding rock of a proposed repository.</CITE></P>
<P></P>
<P><BR><BR CLEAR="left"></P>
<P><BR><BR></P>
<P><CITE>NX  24/96 11th September 1996</CITE></P>
