<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cautious Blasting for Rock Laboratory Shafts. NX23/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Cautious Blasting for Rock Laboratory Shafts</H3>
<P>Explosives experts working for Nirex have designed a range of blast patterns
to sink two vertical shafts to depths of up to 1020 metres through the sandstone
and volcanic rock of West Cumbria. The technique will create circular shafts of
five metres finished diameter with negligible disturbance to the rock structure
more than a few tens of centimetres beyond the shaft walls.</P>
<P>To achieve this, Nirex has specified a 'cautious blasting' technique - also
known as 'smooth blasting'. The skill lies in fragmenting the excavated rock to
a spoil size that is easy to handle and transport to the surface, while at the
same time accurately contouring the outer perimeter to a firm surface which will
support a concrete liner of five metres internal diameter through the
sandstones.</P>
<P>Before opting for a drill and blast technique, Nirex's mining engineers and
geologists thoroughly examined the potential of shaft boring machines. This
method was rejected because the depth and vertical accuracy needed by Nirex are
at the limits of world-wide machine-boring experience.</P>
<P>The two shafts are for the rock laboratory or 'Rock Characterisation
Facility' which Nirex has proposed to increase further its understanding of the
geology and hydrogeology at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield. The laboratory is
the next stage of a multi-million pound research project to assess the
suitability of Longlands Farm as a potential site for a deep repository for
intermediate and some low-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>The Inspector's report from the recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's
application to construct a rock laboratory is expected to be submitted to the
Secretary of State for the Environment by the end of October 1996.</P>
<P><B>Technical Details</B></P>
<P>The scheme uses four concentric rings of blastholes drilled in the shaft
floor (see diagram) with holes in the outer two rings sited close together.
Small decoupled explosives charges - <I>ie, </I>of less diameter than the holes
- are placed in the blastholes nearest the shaft perimeter and also in the
penultimate ring of 'cushion' holes. This large number of closely spaced
'contour' holes with decoupled charges provides the required smooth bore shaft
surface with minimum damage to the host rock mass.</P>
<P>Charges in the two inner rings of 'production' holes provide the main blast
to achieve the most efficient breakage and advance through the rock structure.</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="blast.gif" ALT="Schematic plan view illustrating a shaft blast pattern"><BR><CITE>Schematic
plan view illustrating a shaft blast pattern</CITE></P>
<P>Within the innermost ring of production blastholes is the cut zone - where
the first detonations take place. This shape of charges holes, empty 'relief'
holes and 'easer'' holes is the heart of the excavation blast. Sequential
detonation of the cut hole charges, typically with l00ms delays, creates an
initial opening by ejecting rock fragments into the relief holes. The easer
holes of the expanded cut are then fired in swift sequence to produce a void for
the rings of production hole charges to break into. Finally, the many small
charges in the cushioning and perimeter holes give the shaft its accurate
contour. A complete round will take several seconds to fire across the full
face.</P>
<P>Nirex estimates that sinking the two shafts will take about three and a half
years, with geological and hydrogeological monitoring and investigations being
carried out constantly as work progresses.</P>
<P>Nirex carried out<B> </B>small scale blasting trials at the site in June
1995 to confirm its calculations of noise, shockwave and vibration levels.</P>
<P><CITE>NX  23/96 20th August 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)    01900
817045 (home)  
</P>
