<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nirex Offers Geoscience Maps to Universities. NX21/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Offers Geoscience Maps to Universities</H3>
<P>Nirex, the radioactive waste disposal company, is offering sets of
geoscience maps, drawings and sections free to universities in the UK and
Ireland for use as teaching aids.</P>
<P>The sets were produced as part of the Company's ongoing multi-million pound
research programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm near Sellafield
as a potential site for a deep underground repository for intermediate and some
low-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>Geologically speaking, the Sellafield area is one of the most intensely
studied parts of Europe. Many techniques have been used over the past seven
years to provide a comprehensive picture of its geology and hydrology. These
include tests in boreholes up to 2000 metres deep and a range of geophysical
surveys such as seismic, electromagnetic and gravity surveys.</P>
<P>Nirex Scientific Liaison Manager, Bruce Alderman said, &quot;We hope that
our offer, which is entirely free of charge, will be taken up by the
universities. These sets of high-quality maps are surplus to our needs and we
would be delighted if they can be put to good use by teaching staff and students
in university geoscience departments.&quot;</P>
<P>The next major step is for Nirex to build a rock laboratory at Longlands
Farm to increase further its knowledge of the site. The Inspector's report from
a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application for a rock laboratory is
expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State for the Environment by the
end of October 1996.</P>
<P>Note to editors:<BR>Any UK or Irish University interested in receiving one
of the sets should contact:</P>
<P>Bruce Alderman, Scientific Liaison Manager,<BR> Curie Avenue, Harwell,
Didcot, Oxon, OX11 0RH<BR>Email: 
<A METHODS="POST" HREF="mailto:bruce.alderman@nirex.co.uk"><I>bruce.alderman@nirex.co.uk</I>.</A></P>
<P><CITE>NX  21/96 14th August 1996</CITE></P>
