<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nirex Issues Invitations to Tender. NX19/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Issues Invitations to Tender</H3>
<P>Nirex the radioactive waste disposal company, has issued invitations to
tender for the first<I> </I>stage of a Rock Laboratory (or<I> </I>'Rock
Characterisation Facility' ) at Longlands Farm, near Sellafield in west Cumbria,
subject to the Company obtaining planning permission for the development.</P>
<P>Dr Colin Bayliss,. Technical and Engineering Director, said: &quot;Putting a
major contract such as this in place takes many months. Therefore, it is
important that we invite<I> </I>tenders now, especially for the detailed design
elements of the work, so that we are in a position to move forward in a timely
way when and if the Secretary of State gives planning permission for the Rock
Laboratory, and not before&quot;.</P>
<P>The invitation to tender is for Phase 1 of the Rock Laboratory which
comprises two shafts 5 metres in diameter sunk to a depth of between 650m and
900m bOD, connected at the bottom by a tunnel. There are also some minor inset
galleries.</P>
<P>Three consortia have been invited to tender. They are:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Trafalgar House Construction International/Cementation (Africa Contracts)
</LI>
<LI> Balfour Beatty Construction/Deilmann-Haniel
</LI>
<LI> Amco Corporation/Shaft Sinkers/Tarmac/Taylor-Woodrow 
</LI></UL>
<P>The tender return date is 14 October 1996.</P>
<UL>
<LI> A public inquiry into the Nirex proposals for a Rock Laboratory ended on 1
 February 1996 and the Inspector's report is expected by the end of October. It
will  then be passed to the Secretary of State for the Environment for a
decision.</LI></UL>
<P><I>Notes for Editors:</I></P>
<P>Phase 1: is as outlined above and will take just under 4 years.</P>
<P>Phase 2: comprises the construction of 3 main galleries, each about 150
metres long at a depth currently planned to be about 753 metres below the
surface and is planned<I> </I>to take 2 years.</P>
<P>Phase 3: Two of the Phase 2 galleries will be extended up to 375 metres and
600 metres and three further galleries up to 200 metres will he constructed.
This will take up to 4 years.</P>
<P>The three Phases of the Rock Laboratory are estimated at a total cost of &#163;124m
for construction with a further &#163;71m for scientific research at 1995
prices.</P>
<P>A decision to apply for planning permission for a deep waste repository for
radioactive waste could be taken after Phase 1</P>
<P><CITE>NX  19/96 30th July 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)    01900
817045 (home)  
