<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nirex Pushes ahead with Quaternary Investigations. NX18-96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Nirex Pushes Ahead With Quaternary Investigations</H3>
<P>Nirex is testing static cone penetration - an alternative to borehole
drilling - at five<I> </I>sites in west Cumbria this summer. It is part of
the Company's intensive study of the Quaternary deposits of the area - the
unconsolidated materials left on top of the region's bedrock during and
after the last Ice Age.</P>
<P>Instead of erecting a drilling rig to bore a slim test well down to 50
metres depth, Cone Penetrometer Testing (CPT) has a probe containing
monitoring instruments which is pushed down through soft ground at
2Omm/second by hydraulic jacks on a specially equipped six-wheel drive
truck.</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG
SRC="images/truck1.jpg" ALT="Image of Drilling Truck" WIDTH="242" HEIGHT="150"><CITE>CPT
Truck in jack-up position.</CITE></P>
<P>The resistance to penetration provides information on the geotechnical
properties of the unconsolidated deposits. Specialised probes can also
provide data on groundwater pressures and chemistry. If this method proves
a success it could be used again by Nirex in the future</P>
<P>Nirex geologist Richard Heath said: &quot;CPT is a quick and economical
way to investigate near-surface conditions in unconsolidated deposits. We
will try this method along the 10km stretch of coastal flood plain between
High Sellafield and the River Irt estuary to calibrate sets of geophysical
data we acquired last year.&quot;</P>
<P>Last year, Nirex drilled and tested the Quaternary sequence at 12 sites
and this year plans to drill at 8 further sites.</P>
<P>Nirex's Quaternary investigations are part of its ongoing multi-million
pound research programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm near
Sellafield as a potential site for a deep underground repository for
intermediate and some low-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>Geologically speaking, the Sellafield area is one of the most intensely
studied pans of Europe. Many techniques have been used over the past six
years to provide a comprehensive picture of its geology and hydrology.
These include tests in boreholes up to 2000 metres deep and a range of
geophysical surveys such as seismic, electromagnetic and magnetotelluric
surveys.</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG
SRC="images/truck2.jpg" ALT="JPEG underside of truck showing 
penetrating cone." WIDTH="242" HEIGHT="150"><CITE>Underside of truck showing 
penetrating cone.</CITE></P>

<H3>TECHNICAL INFORMATION</H3>
<P>The CPT programme will be carried out at selected sites where the stone
content of the Quaternary deposits is sufficiently low to give clear
penetration to 30 or 40 metres depth. To test the CPT equipment and
calibrate its data, the truck-mounted system will first be used alongside a
fully cored and geophysically logged borehole produced by normal drilling
methods.</P>
<P>At two other sites, a grid of CPT investigations with an electrical
cone will be carried out over a 100 metre square area to measure the
conductivity/resistivity of the Quaternary deposits at depths down to 30
metres. This work will rapidly provide information to calibrate existing
three-dimensional soundings derived from electrical resistivity surveys
over a much larger area.</P>
<P>Piezometers will be installed as deep as possible at the two remaining
CPT sites. These will enable Nirex to monitor groundwater pressure on a
long-term basis and improve the regional spread of near-surface
hydrogeological data. Push-in well screens will also be fitted so that
groundwater can be regularly sampled for chemical analysis. This will
determine whether there is saline water discharge in the area.</P>
<P>Water strikes will be recorded during each CPT operation and in-situ
permeability tests will be carried out at each site.</P>
<P>Between May and August 1996, the Company also plans to carry out
wire-line logging and install standpipe piezometers at six other Quaternary
investigation sites using standard near-surface drilling techniques.</P>
<UL>
<LI>The next major step is for Nirex to build a rock laboratory at
Longlands Farm to  increase further its knowledge of the site. The
Inspector's report from a recent Public  Inquiry into Nirex's application
for a rock laboratory is expected to be submitted to  the Secretary of
State for the Environment by the end of October 1996.</LI></UL>
<P><CITE>NX  18/96 29th July 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)   
01900 817045 (home)  
</P>
