<HEAD>
<TITLE>World-wide Queue for Proposed Rocldab.../2</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>World-wide Queue for Proposed Rocklab</H3>
<P>Scientists across the world are waiting to use results of
hydrogeological experiments that Nirex will carry out if it gets permission
to build a rock laboratory near Sellafield, in West Cumbria. It is Nirex's
policy to make the findings of its research work available to the
scientific community.</P>
<P>Ten organisations concerned with the management and regulation of
radioactive waste disposal are participating in an international project
called DECOVALEX  Development of Coupled Models and their Evaluation
Against Experiments. They come from Canada, France, Japan, Spain, Sweden
and the UK.</P>
<P>DECOVALEX is studying the interactions between the hydraulic properties
of natural rock structures at depth and the mechanical and thermal changes
that may result from waste disposal. This is important to designers of
underground repositories, who need to understand the extent to which slight
disturbances of the rock due to the presence of a repository could alter
groundwater flow.</P>
<P>Each of the participating groups has computer models to simulate and
predict the physical changes which might occur underground. They need
realistic conditions to test and verify the accuracy of their models.</P>
<P>Nirex Manager of Geosphere Research, Dr Les Knight, said. &quot;Phase 1
of DECOVALEX was mainly concerned with predicting the results of small
scale experiments in surface facilities and existing rock laboratories. A
second phase, which has just started, is focused on large scale
predictions.</P>
<P>&quot;If our rock laboratory proceeds, Nirex will first provide seven
of the DECOVALEX participants with relevant base data so they can use their
models to make 'blind' predictions of results. Subsequently, we will
monitor any mechanical and hydraulic changes which occur during shaft
sinking so that real and modelled results can be compared.&quot;</P>
<P>DECOVALEX Phase 2 is also investigating thermo-hydro-mechanical
responses to simulated heat-emitting high-level waste buried in granite at
Kamaishi mine in Japan.</P>
<P>Nirex believes that a rock laboratory is the next logical step in its
ongoing multi-million pound research programme to assess the suitability of
Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a potential site for a deep underground
repository for intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>&#183; The Inspector's report from the recent Public Inquiry into
Nirex's application to build the rock laboratory is expected to be
submitted to the Secretary of State for the Environment by the end of
October 1996.</P>
<P><CITE>NX  17/96 26th July 1996</CITE></P>
<P><I>Media Enquiries:</I>
</P>
<P>Taryn Rock:	     019467 24880 (office)    0385 336091 (mobile)    01900
827174 (home)
</P>
<P>Nigel Monckton:   019467 24885 (office)    0836 387584 (mobile)   
01900 817045 (home)  
