<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Sowing the Seeds of Successful Research</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Sowing the Seeds of Successful Research</H3>      
<P>
Fossil pollen dug up in France is helping scientists to understand the range of
plants that could grow in west Cumbria in tens of thousands of years time. 
</P>
<P>
Nirex wants to know what trees and shrubs flourished in the Sellafield area
between the last two ice ages (18,000 and 65,000 years ago) because similar
species are likely to return in the future during the next periglacial period
(after the next ice-age).<BR> 
</P>
<P>
Vegetation history can be reconstructed by drilling into the geological record
of the past and extracting sedimentary core samples. Botanists can tell what
plants flourished at different times by examining preserved pollens in the
cores. The family, genus and even species of a plant can be identified from the
outer coat of a single pollen grain. 
</P>
<P>
Core samples, to a depth of two metres, from HalIsenna Moor - a Site of Special
Scientific Interest, in west Cumbria - have provided a detailed record of
vegetation types up to 12,000 years BC. In order to get a record of vegetation
before the last ice-age, core samples up to 20 metres deep have been collected
and analysed from Dinge, in Brittany. These have provided a detailed record for
the period 16,000 - 85000 years BC.
</P>
<P>
Dinge is an excellent analogue of Sellafield.  It is on a rocky western
extremity of the same continental land mass at approximately the same longitude.
 But, being 700km further south, Dinge was unaffected by glaciers, which stopped
at the Bristol Channel. 
</P>
<P>
Knowledge of the density and root structure of vegetation that will cover
Sellafield after the next ice age is important to Nirex. These factors influence
the movement of near-surface groundwater in the environment.
</P>
<P>
Understanding the movement of groundwater is a vital part of Nirex's
multi-million pound programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm near
Sellafield as a potential site for a deep underground repository for
intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive waste.<BR> 
</P>
<P>
&quot;We are investigating the possible consequences of a few very long-lived
radionuclides from wastes sealed deep underground reaching the surface through
groundwater flow after many thousands of years,&quot; said Martin Broderick,
Nirex Biosphere Research and Assessment Manager. &quot;We need to be able to
evaluate each scenario in our safety assessments.&quot;
</P>
<P>
Pollen analysis by the British Geological Survey, the University of Wales and by
the Laboratoire Botanique at the University of Marseilles has given Nirex
sufficient evidence to evaluate possible future vegetation conditions in the
periods under examination. The Dinge cores were also analysed for beetles
(Coleoptera) which provided further detail on the temperature and rainfall in
the period 125,000 - 500,000 years BC.
</P>
<P>
Martin Broderick said: &quot;We are confident that vegetation in west Cumbria
during the next periglacial period will be similar to the grasses and shrubs
which we identified at Dinge.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
The next major step in Nirex's assessment programme is to construct an
underground laboratory (Rock Characterisation Facility) at Longlands Farm to
improve further the company's understanding of local geology and hydrogeology.
The Inspector's report from a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application to
construct the rock laboratory is expected to be submitted to the Secretary of
State for the Environment by the end of October 1996. 
</P>
<P><CITE>NX  15/96 13th June 1996</CITE></P>
