<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nirex and BGS Research Available</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>New Reusable Transport Container For Radioactive Waste</H3>
<P>A range of new reusable shielded containers developed by Nirex will safely
transport intermediate-level radioactive waste to a deep repository by rail and
road next century. This follows careful design development which led to two
alternative concepts.</P>
<P>These two concepts were tested as one-third scale models to prove their
robustness, impact strength and sealing efficiency. The tests were carried out
to meet IAEA Regulations for Safe Transport of Radioactive Materials. The
Regulations include a requirement for the containers to retain their contents
safely after a nine metre drop onto an unyielding surface, followed by a 30
minute, 8000C, fully engulfing hydrocarbon fire.</P>
<P>Nirex Transportation Development Manager, Iain Gray, said: &quot;Severely
punishing physical tests combined with detailed finite element analyses showed
little to choose between the two concepts of Reusable Shielded Transport
Container (RSTC). Both met the IAEA Regulations.</P>
<P>&quot;In the final evaluation, with safety requirements met, we were able to
make a choice on capital cost and operational grounds. The winner was less
costly to manufacture and considered easier to load/unload and simpler to
maintain.&quot;</P>
<P>
Each RSTC holds four 500-litre stainless steel drums of intermediate-level waste
immobilised in cement, or a single drum/box of three cubic metres. Drums are
loaded into transport containers at a waste producer&#146;s site.  They are not
removed until the RSTC is deep underground in the repository.  After being
checked, the RSTCs are ready for reuse.
</P>
<P>Up to 120 of these containers will be needed to handle the flow of
intermediate-level waste from power plants, medical sources, general industry,
research laboratories and defence establishments.</P>
<H4>Technical Details</H4>
<P>The RSTCs will be produced with various wall thicknesses from 70mm to 285mm
to carry a range of packaged intermediate-level waste. The 70mrn version weighs
15 tonnes unloaded and can be safely transported by lorry, but at 47 tonnes the
285mm model will be primarily transported by rail.</P>
<P>The containers are likely to be made from forged steel, as were the
one-third scale models already tested. However, ductile cast iron and cast steel
are being investigated to find if they offer production advantages without
compromising integrity. 
</P>
<P>The RSTC incorporates four massive, integral, steel shock absorbers to
provide protection during accidents involving impacts in which a top edge of the
containers hits the ground first. The thick steel lid is covered with a heavy
wooden shock absorbent layer to protect against direct top-down impact.</P>
<P>Ease of loading/unloading played a vital part in the selection process
because these operations will be carried out robotically. Lid-to-body mating and
sealing must therefore be foolproof. Also the lock mechanisms and seal
energising bolts must be robust and secure to withstand damage, yet swift to
release using remotely-controlled equipment.</P>
<P>Technical and Engineering Director; Dr Colin Bayliss, said; &quot;The next
step is to prepare a full scale mock-up of the lid arrangement. This will be
used in operability trials, and to ensure that the design is fully compatible
with the remote-handling equipment used on nuclear sites.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Before the container is finally accepted, it must be approved by the UK
Department of Transport. Further detailed design and test work is now being
carried out so Nirex can submit its application next year.</P>
<P><CITE>NX  14/96 6th June 1996</CITE></P>
