<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nirex and BGS Research Available</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>Cumbria Aids Water Quest In Arid Areas</H3>
<P>Nirex research into groundwater flow in west Cumbria is set to help arid
regions to exploit efficiently their natural water resources.</P>
<P>Validation of SHETRAN Version 4, a hydrological modelling system, is
expected to provide a valuable tool for water companies and international
agencies involved in water resources management and land irrigation projects. An
earlier SHETRAN version was used in the European Community&#146;s Medalus
Projcct to discover how Mediterranean landscapes are likely to react to climatic
and man-induced changes over the next 50 years.</P>
<P>Three years of field studies in west Cumbria will investigate the quantities
and sources of groundwater discharging into river channels through surface
seepage, artesian boreholes and springs.  Much of the work will be completed by
two post-graduate Ph.D. students funded by Nirex.  One will study the hydrology
and chemistry of groundwater while the other carries out computer modelling.</P>
<P>Black Beck, a small river which crosses Cumbria's coastal plain outside the
Lake District National Park, was selected for this research project because
substantial groundwater discharge continued throughout the severe drought of
summer 1995.</P>
<P>Water table levels and river flow will be logged constantly, together with
site weather  conditions including rainfall. Seepage meters are to be buried in
the river bed to monitor the quantity of groundwater rising into the flowing
stream. Instruments in shallow boreholes, springs and wells will complete the
picture.
</P>
<P>Regular chemical analyses of sarnples from all these outlets are designed to
identify the different origins of water. Nirex is particularly interested in
tracing groundwater which has migrated through rocks over thousands of years
from the site which is being assessed as a potential deep repository for
intermediate and low level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>Says Martin Broderick, Nirex Manager of Biosphere Research &amp; Assessment;
 &quot;This work will help validate the new Variably-Saturated Subsurface flow
module in SHETRAN Version 4, and provide valuable information on groundwater
movement in the Sellafield area.</P>
<P>&quot;The seepage metering technique for river beds was originally developed
by the US Geological Survey. This is the first time it will be used in Britain.</P>
<P>&quot;Equipment for our experiments has been designed by the Water Resources
System Research Unit at the University of Newcastle-upon-Tyne, which is managing
the research programme on our  behalf.&quot;</P>
<H4>Technical Background </H4>
<P>SHETRAN was built around the SHE &#151; Syst&egrave;me Hydrologique Europ&eacute;en
&#151; flow simulation system to create models of combined water flow, sediment
transport and contamination migration through a catchment to streams and
vegetation. Development work was carried out for Nirex at the University of
Newcastle-upon-Tyne with input by the University of Lancaster's Centre for
Research on Environmental Systems.</P>
<P>The system divides a catchment into five zones: i) saturated, where
groundwater pressure is greater than atmospheric;  ii) unsaturated, (above the
saturated zone) with water pressure lower than atmospheric;  iii) ground surface
and stream channels;   iv) vegetation canopy; and,  v) banks of streams which
form narrow strips of saturated and unsaturated zones.
</P>
<P>Very fine details of water, sediment and contaminant movement are modelled
by dividing a catchment into more than 10,000 compartments, This enables the
varying size and complex shapes of zones to be simulated accurately, and zone
materials of different physical properties to be included together with the rate
of contaminant transfer between them.</P>
<P>The latest development of SHETRAN Version 4, contains a three-dimensional
Variably Saturated Subsurface (VSS) flow component to simulate groundwater
migration in areas of  highly complex geology where the water table is likely to
drop or rise many metres. Typically this involves flow pathways through
Quaternary deposits to the surface. The ability to simulate seamlessly the
results of rapidly rising and falling water tables is important in areas of
regular drought or flood.</P>
<P>SHETRAN plays a vital role in Nirex&#146;s multi-million pound research
project to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a site
for a deep repository for intermediate and low-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>The next stage of Nirex's site characterisation programme is to construct a
rock laboratory &#151; Rock Characterisation Facility &#151; to increase further
its understanding of the site's geology and hydrogeology. The Inspector&#146;s
report from the recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application to construct the
rock laboratory is expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State for the
Environment by the end of October 1996. </P>
<P><CITE>NX  13/96 24th May 1996</CITE></P>
