<H3>
Jobs Boost from Rock Lab</H3>
<P>Nirex has announced  that  construction of a proposed underground rock
laboratory in  west Cumbria would lead to the creation of  up to 170 jobs.</P>
<P>
  Approximately 120 people would be needed during the construction phase and
around 50 scientific staff would be employed to carry out experiments during the
life of  the laboratory. 
</P>
<P>June Isherwood, Human Resources Manager at Nirex, said: &quot;The jobs which
would result from  the proposed Rock Laboratory would be of  real benefit  to
the local  economy.  They  would be created against a background of recent job
losses in west Cumbria.&quot;  
</P>
<P>The extent of local employment in the contractor labour force is expected to
be higher in the 'site establishment' activities.  At that stage there would be
a need for carpenters, brick-layers, fitters, electricians and steel fixers.
There would also be work for general labourers and machine operators.  
</P>
<P>
Shaft sinking, gallery construction and the scientific and technical programme
will require specialised skills and the extent of local recruitment will be
maximised by early identification of need and the adoption of suitable
recruitment and training policies.  
</P>
<P>Ms Isherwood added: &quot;In the construction area Nirex is doing as much as
is possible in preparation for the work prior to planning approval, and much
more than many developers would consider appropriate in a competitive market.&quot;

</P> 
<UL><LI>Nirex currently sponsors three Cumbrian geology students at university
and a post-graduate research fellowship at the Westlakes Science and Technology
Park in Whitehaven.   
</LI>
<LI>A 66-day Public Inquiry into the Company's plans ended on February 1.  The
Inspector will submit his recommendations to the Secretary of State by the end
of October. 
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX  12/96 20th May 1996</CITE></P>
