<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nirex and BGS Research Available</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>
3D Modelling Hits New Heights At 2000 Metres Depth</H3>
<P>Geologists at Nirex are making important advances in three-dimensional 
computer modelling of geological structures.
</P>
<P>
 Their computer models of strata beneath Sellafield in West Cumbria, will  zoom
from a screen view of a two kilometre rock cube, compiled from  millions of data
points, down to a five metre cube to focus on individual  fractures. Structural
details just a few centimetres across, and intersected by  boreholes, may be
clearly defined and located.
</P>
<P>This is achieved by running a large scale computer graphics suite, as used
in  oil exploration, in parallel with a highly detailed system for mapping thin 
seams, as used in mineral mining. Results are processed by a spatial checking 
system to confirm each model fits together exactly when viewed from any 
perspective.
</P>
<P>Accurate characterisation is a vital aspect of Nirex's ongoing multi-million
 pound research programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm near 
Sellafield as a potential site for a deep underground repository for 
intermediate-level and some low-level radioactive waste.
</P>
<H4>Technical Details</H4>
<P>Many techniques are used to produce a comprehensive picture of local geology
and hydrogeology. So far 29 boreholes have been drilled to depths approaching
2,000 metres and extensive programmes of down-hole tests carried out. These,
together with seismic reflection and numerous other geophysical surveys -
including magnetic, gravity, radiometric and resistivity investigations - make
the area one of the most closely studied in the world.</P>
<P>Nirex runs its three-dimensional geological models under Unix on a Silicon 
Graphics workstation. This gives the computational speed and high quality 
graphics which are essential for the task. All large geological features are 
handled by EarthVision software developed by <A HREF="http://www.dgi.com/">Dynamic
Graphics Inc.
</A></P>
<P>Borehole data from Nirex's drilling sites across 50 square kilometres of
West  Cumbria are combined with results of other large scale surveys to 
characterise the overall geological structure of the area on EarthVision.
</P>
<P>Said Nirex Senior Geologist, Andrew Bowden: &quot;EarthVision is
exceptionally  good at modelling rock properties within the geological
framework. For small  scale details of faults and intersections we bring
<A HREF="http://www.maptek.com.au">Maptek</A>'s Vulcan software  into play,
with some intermediate levels of data introduced to both systems.&quot;
</P>
<P>Geological, geophysical and hydrogeological data are collected in the field
in  digital form. This eases data analysis and processing. Geological
interpretation is carried out by Nirex's Geological Integration Team, comprising
leading consultants including the British Geological Survey. The resulting
geological interpretations are input to Vulcan or EarthVision for the
construction of three-dimensional models.
</P>
<P>When each new compilation of data is introduced, the upgraded geological 
models are transferred to <A HREF="http://www.MidlandValley.com">3D-Move</A>
software for spatial verification. This  unfolds and tests the fault structures
modelled by EarthVision and Vulcan to  prove they are geologically sound.
</P>
<P>Any anomaly discovered by 3D-Move is referred to the Geological Integration 
Team. They apply their expertise to analyse the problem and produce a  revised
interpretation for reintegration with the existing three-dimensional  models.
</P>
<P>
Every new set of verified data improves the detail and precision of these vast 
models, and their value to Nirex.
</P>
<P>The next stage of Nirex's site characterisation programme is to construct a 
rock laboratory (Rock Characterisation Facility) to increase further its 
understanding of the site's geology and hydrogeology. The Inspector's report 
from a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application to construct the rock 
laboratory is expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State for the 
Environment by the end of October 1996.
</P>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX  11/96 14th May 1996</CITE></P>
