<HR>
<H3>
Nirex and BGS Make Dounreay Research Available</H3>
<P>The British Geological Survey, acting for Nirex, is making details of  the
geological investigations at Dounreay available to other  companies. The
information could be  relevant to oil exploration  onshore and offshore around
the north of Scotland. 
</P>
<P>Dr Bob Chaplow, Nirex Manager for Site Characterisation said: &quot;In our 
investigations between 1989 and 1991, Nirex gathered a huge quantity  of high
quality data on the geology of northern Scotland and offshore.  We have always
believed that our data may have commercial value and we  are now offering this
information on the open market.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Included are detailed studies of the two deep boreholes drilled at  Dounreay
in Caithness and data from geophysical surveys that tie in  with published
information from offshore seismic surveys and  boreholes. 
</P>
<P>Dr Chaplow continued: &quot;The information could be useful to oil 
prospecting companies. It will enable them, for example, to check  their
understanding of the geology of the West Orkney Basin against  information from
our boreholes and  detailed seismic surveys.&quot;   </P>
<UL><LI>In 1989, Nirex commenced investigation of  Dounreay and Sellafield, 
in West Cumbria, as potential sites for a deep underground repository  for
radioactive wastes.  In 1991 the Company decided to concentrate  its
investigations at the Sellafield site.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P><CITE>NX  9/96 29 April 1996</CITE></P>
