<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Press Release 4/4/96</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>SUBSTANTIAL SUPPORT AMONG CUMBRIANS FOR ROCK LAB
</H3>
<P>
There has been a substantial jump in the number of residents in  Cumbria who are
in favour of the Nirex Rock Laboratory once they know  it is to be used solely
as a research facility.</P>
<P>Almost two-thirds (64%) of residents who are aware of the proposed  Rock
Lab, support the project on that basis, according to a new  independent opinion
poll conducted by Gallup. The figure is up from  52% in November 1994, when
Nirex last conducted opinion research in  Cumbria. In Copeland, 67% are in
favour compared to 68% in 1994.</P>
<P>
 Support for a repository is also increasing in Cumbria with 45% in  favour (36%
in 1994), whilst the percentage who totally oppose it has  fallen from 19% to
15%. A further 28% tend to oppose the project but  might accept it if assured
about safety.  In Copeland, support has  remained constant at 56% whilst total
opposition has fallen from 14%  to 11%.  With assurances about safety, a further
26% might accept the  repository. 
</P>
<P>In 1994, almost four out of five people believed the Rock Laboratory  was to
be used for the disposal of radioactive waste. This has now  fallen to 35%. 
</P>
<P>Tom Curtin, Nirex Head of Corporate Communications, said: &quot;These 
results are very encouraging. People seem to have a greater depth of  knowledge
about our proposals. Understanding of the role of the Rock  Laboratory has
increased, we obviously have more work to do in  explaining the project and the
role of Nirex.&quot;</P>
<P>In Copeland, 31% believe the Rock Laboratory will be used for testing 
rocks, whilst in Cumbria, this figure is only 17%.</P>
<P>Overall, three in five Cumbrians favour the disposal of radioactive  wastes
deep underground as against 15% who prefer surface storage.  These figures are
in line with the 1994 poll. More than half of  Cumbrians still believe it is a
bad idea to transport radioactive  wastes through the county from Sellafield to
another location, with  only 14% believing this to be a good idea.</P>
<P>The poll also found that unemployment was the main issue of concern  among
Cumbrians (23%), followed by &quot;peace and quiet&quot; (18%) and the 
environment (11%), law and order (7%) and nuclear power (4%). 	 </P>
<P>A 66-day planning inquiry on the Rock Laboratory proposals finished in
February.  The Inspector will submit his report to The Secretary of State for
the Environment by the end of October.</P>
<P>NX 8/96	   3rd April 1996 	</P>
<P><A HREF="nirnews.htm">Back to news page</A></P></BODY></HTML>
