<DOCNO>WT05-B15-148</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000826-B012-185</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.nirex.co.uk:80/tinmine.htm 194.159.250.213 19970119082520 text/html 4184
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 08:25:18 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.14
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 4012
Last-modified: Tue, 02 Apr 1996 10:05:14 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>press release 12/12/95</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><P><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3><STRONG>Tin mine tests teach Nirex new techniques</STRONG></H3>
<P>    Scientists have used the UK's oldest working tin mine to test
instruments that could play a key role at Nirex's proposed deep rock laboratory.

</P>
<P>Rock mechanics monitoring equipment was installed in granite 732 metres
underground on the 400 fathom level at South Crofty Mine, between Camborne and
Redruth, Cornwall. The old seafaring measurement of depth is still used in
Cornish mines.</P>
<P>
 South Crofty was chosen because its depth and working environment, 33&#176;C
ambient temperature and almost 100 per cent humidity, are comparable to those of
the planned rock laboratory (RCF or Rock Characterisation Facility) at Longlands
Farm near Sellafield, West Cumbria.</P>
<P>Dr David Mellor, Nirex RCF Science Manager, said: &quot;These trials will
help Nirex select the most appropriate equipment and develop techniques for use
in the RCF. We have already tested underground mapping methods, and surveying
and rock imaging techniques in Cornish and Cumbrian mines.&quot;</P>
<P>At South Crofty, a team of geotechnical experts from contractors
<A HREF="http://www.demon.co.uk/geosci/geonuc.html">GeoScience</A> and SubTerra
Engineering helped Nirex to take rock measurements with a Bof-ex borehole
fracture extensometer and CSIRO strain cell.  
</P>
<P>This work will form part of Nirex's ongoing multi-million pound research
programme to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, as a
potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and some low-level
radioactive waste. </P>
<P>The next major step for Nirex will be to build a rock laboratory (Rock
Characterisation Facility) at Longlands Farm to increase further its knowledge
of the site. The Inspector's report from a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's
application to build the rock laboratory is expected to be submitted to the
Secretary of State for the Environment by the end of October 1996.  
</P>
<H3>TECHNICAL INFORMATION
</H3>
<P>The Bof-ex extensometer measures small excavation-induced displacements
across naturally occurring fractures in rock. It was originally developed by
Atomic Energy of Canada Ltd for use at the Manitoba rock laboratory, but is now
commercially available. This is the first time it has been used in the UK. 
</P>
<P>Before installing Bof-ex equipment in a borehole, the core from the borehole
must be fracture-logged to select downhole measuring locations. Mechanical
anchors are then accurately located and fixed in place. Transducers fitted
between the anchors measure any change in the distance between the anchor points
caused by rock movement during excavation.</P>
<P>The CSIRO strain cell was developed in Australia by the Commonwealth
Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation to measures stresses and
pressures in rock structures. The cell is glued into a slim bore hole and
initial strain readings are taken. A tube of rock containing the cell is then
removed by overcoring with a large diameter hollow drill bit.  
</P>
<P>Strain gauge readings are taken continuously as rock is cut away. Releasing
the natural rock pressure on the tube allows it to expand very slightly. This
change is measured to calculate the original stress condition.</P>
<P>During the tests, Carnon Contracting of South Crofty drilled a series of
cored holes up to 15 metres long and demonstrated the installation of borehole
packers that allow sections of a hole to be isolated for hydraulic tests.</P>

<IMG SRC="images/tinmine.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 

<P><I>Bof-ex extensometer is installed in its borehole 732 metres below the surface at South Crofty Mine,
Cornwall, as part of instrument tests carried out by Nirex.     
</I></P>
<P><A HREF="nirnews.htm">Back to news page</A>
</P>
