<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>press release 12/12/95</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><P><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H3>GRASS CROPS SOW WORLDWIDE KNOWLEDGE 
</H3>
<P>Ryegrass grown at a Berkshire research station in soil from West Cumbria is
the focus of an international research project. Scientists using different
computer systems in six countries are trying to predict how the grass is
affected by groundwater deliberately dosed with radioactive tracers.</P>
<P>It is part of the BIOMOVS II (Biosphere modelling validation studies, part
2) project to test models that calculate the transfer and build-up of
radionuclides in the biosphere - the part of Earth's surface and atmosphere that
supports life.</P>
<IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pr1.gif" VSPACE="20" HSPACE="15" WIDTH="200">
<P><CITE>Scientists from around the world examine crops being grown in
Nirex-funded lysimeters at Ascot.</CITE></P>
<P></P>
<P>Ryegrass is grown for Nirex under carefully controlled experimental
conditions at the Centre for Analytical Research in the Environment, run by
Imperial College of Science, Technology &amp; Medicine at Silwood Park, Ascot.
Eight lysimeters - large outdoor concrete tanks - filled with soil from West
Cumbria are fed from beneath with water containing accurately measured traces of
seven radionuclides. Natural rainfall, soil conditions and other factors
affecting plant growth are monitored throughout the season.</P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT">Samples of the grass are analysed in a laboratory at
different stages of growth to discover if it has taken up any radioactivity.</P>
<P>Precise details of growing conditions are issued to BIOMOVS II participants
throughout the world. From these they predict the upward migration of
radionuclides through the soil and into the crop. The accuracy of their
different modelling techniques will be revealed when Nirex releases its test
results this year.</P>
<P>This exercise in international co-operation allows scientists to refine and
validate their theoretical models using well-documented practical results.
Contaminated rain and other sources of radioactive pollution are also being
investigated in BIOMOVS II.</P>
<P>Martin Broderick, Nirex Manager of Biosphere Research and Assessment, said: &quot;Nirex-funded
work is an important source of accurate data for experiments in which pollutants
reach the crop from below. We are probably the world leaders in this field and
are happy to share our knowledge through the BIOMOVS forum.&quot; 
</P>
<P>Scientists from Canada, France, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and USA are
participating in this part of the project. It began in late 1994 and will last
two years. So far four crops of ryegrass have been harvested and analysed.</P>
<P>This work will help Nirex to assess the suitability of Longlands Farm, near
Sellafield, as a potential site for a deep repository for intermediate and some
low-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>An important aspect of site characterisation is to investigate the
possibility of radioactive material from waste getting into groundwater and
reaching the surface after many thousands of years. The vast majority of any
radionuclides in groundwater at a repository will have become harmless through
radioactive decay long before they reach the surface. But Nirex needs to know if
there is the remotest chance that some might be taken up by plants and enter the
food chain.</P>
<P>The next major step in Nirex's ongoing multi-million pound research
programme is to build a rock laboratory (Rock Characterisation Facility) at
Longlands Farm to increase further its knowledge of the site. The Inspector's
report from a recent Public Inquiry into Nirex's application to build the rock
laboratory is expected to be submitted to the Secretary of State for the
Environment by the end of October 1996.</P>
<P>Nirex Press Release Ref. NX 5/96  5 March 1996   
<P>     
</P>
