<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nirex - the facts</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex Logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<H1>THE FACTS</H1>
<H3>A guide to the safe disposal of radioactive waste.</H3> 
<H3>What we do...</H3> 
<IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic16.gif" ALT="Image of the Nirex Investigation Site" HSPACE="15" HEIGHT="200">
<P ALIGN="LEFT">United Kingdom Nirex Limited is a company owned by the nuclear
industry and set up to dispose of intermediate and some low-level radioactive
waste.  The Company has no plans to import foreign wastes and has no
responsibility for high-level radioactive waste.  The preferred disposal route
is in chambers excavated in a deep geological repository.  Most of the
radioactive waste planned for disposal in the repository will be
intermediate-level wastes such as:<BR> 
</P>
<UL><LI>claddings separated from spent nuclear fuel;</LI>
<LI>filters and other wastes from effluent treatments;
</LI>
<LI>worn-out plant and equipment;
</LI>
<LI>isotopes used in medical treatments;</LI>
<LI>radioactive materials used in industry and defence.
</LI></UL>
<P>Low-level waste includes rubble and steelwork from decommissioning.  Most of
this waste is currently disposed of at the Drigg site in Cumbria operated by
British Nuclear Fuels.  That site is expected to have capacity well into the
21st century.</P> 
<P><A HREF="nirfx2.htm">About Nirex</A></P>
<P><A HREF="nirfxall.htm">Return to section menu</A></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT05-B15-175</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000826-B015-80</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.nirex.co.uk:80/nirfx2.htm 194.159.250.213 19970119083510 text/html 1073
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 08:35:07 GMT
