<DOCNO>WT05-B15-176</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000826-B015-121</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.nirex.co.uk:80/nirfx3.htm 194.159.250.213 19970119083542 text/html 1665
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 1997 08:35:31 GMT
Server: Apache/0.8.14
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 1493
Last-modified: Tue, 02 Apr 1996 10:05:14 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Where does the waste come from</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H3>Where does the waste come from?</H3>
<P>Nearly all of man's activities produce waste.  The cars we drive....  the
clothes we wear....  the electricity that lights our homes.  For each of these,
there are useless by-products - waste.  <BR>More than one quarter of the UK's
electricity comes from nuclear power.  Our hospitals use radioactivity in the
treatment of cancers.  And defence, industry and research establishments make
use of radioactive materials.  Naturally, there are waste products.</P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic31crp.gif" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" HEIGHT="150">
<CITE>More than one quarter of the UK's electricity comes from nuclear power.</CITE></P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"></P>   
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG
ALIGN="RIGHT" SRC="images/pic3.gif" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" HEIGHT="150"><CITE><BR>
Industry benefits from the use of radioactive materials, for example where x-ray
sources are used in inspecting welds or detecting cracks.</CITE><BR CLEAR="YES"></P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><B>As a responsible society, it is our duty to dispose
carefully of wastes so that they cannot harm either this generation or, equally
importantly, our children, grandchildren or any future generation.</B> </P>
<P><A HREF="nirfx4.htm">How much waste is there?</A></P>
<P><A HREF="nirfxall.htm">Return to section menu</A></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
