<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Why bury the waste?</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<IMG SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H3>Why bury the waste?</H3>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic7.gif" HSPACE="15" HEIGHT="150">This
generation has exploited nuclear technology - nuclear power stations, for
example, have supplied electricity to our homes and industry for nearly 40
years.  It is only right that we should dispose responsibly and safely of all
the wastes we have created.  The waste exists now and more will be produced.  At
the moment, this is stored at a number of sites throughout the UK.  It could be
kept safely like this for many more years.  But this is not the final answer. 
Societies can change and change quickly.  Only 50 years ago, there was general
war in Europe.   The industrial revolution is just 200 years old.  And the
glories of Rome were followed by the centuries of the Dark Ages.  <BR><BR><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic29.gif" HSPACE="15" HEIGHT="200">The
rocks beneath an area near Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, were formed more
than 450,000,000 years ago - the human presence in the area is but a blink in
time.  Unlike the toxicity in many other wastes, radioactivity fades with time. 
But some kinds demand the right containment for many thousands of years.</P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>A repository in deep rock is the preferred responsible
solution for intermediate-level radioactive wastes.</P>
<P><A HREF="nirfx6.htm">Containing the radioactivity</A></P>
<P><A HREF="nirfxall.htm">Return to section menu</A></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT05-B15-179</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA047-000826-B015-222</DOCOLDNO>
