<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Containing the radioactivity</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex Logo" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<HR>
<H3>Containing the radioactivity</H3>
<P>When a material is radioactive, it means that it gives out rays or tiny
particles.  Unless contained, these could be harmful.  However, radioactive
emissions can be blocked by suitable barriers.  (Note how radiologists go behind
a screen when taking an x-ray - the principle is the same.)  Radioactivity fades
or decays with time - in many cases, relatively soon.  However, certain
materials can remain significantly radioactive for many thousands of years.  To
help contain the radioactivity and in preparation for disposal, the waste is
packed in stainless steel drums (or boxes), with a cement mixture poured almost
to the brim.  About 3,000 cubic metres has already been packaged and is stored
at Sellafield and other sites.  The waste, in its special packaging, can be kept
safely in interim storage for decades if necessary.  But to maintain safety over
many thousands of years, the waste containers will be placed in rock caverns
deep underground.  More cement will be poured around the gaps and the repository
will be sealed.  So there is not just one but a number of barriers:
</P>
<OL SEQNUM="1">
<LI>the solid waste form;</LI>
<LI>the cement in the drums</LI>
<LI>the stainless steel drums</LI>
<LI>the backfill material poured around the drums</LI>
<LI>for a potential repository at Sellafield, about half a mile of overlying
rocks</LI>
</OL>
<P></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic36a.gif" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="10"><CITE>Intermediate
level waste will be immobilised in cement in stainless steel drums or boxes.</CITE><BR
CLEAR="left"></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic36b.gif" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="10"><CITE>Four
drums will be placed in a <I>stillage</I> (or frame).</CITE><BR CLEAR="left"></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic36c.gif" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="10"><CITE>The
frames will be stacked in caverns excavated in hard rock.</CITE><BR CLEAR="left"></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic36d.gif" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="10"><CITE>Cement
backfill will be pumped around the stillages.</CITE></P>
<P></P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"><A HREF="nirfx7.htm">The rock
laboratory</A></P>
<P><A HREF="nirfxall.htm">Return to section menu</A></P>
</BODY></HTML>
