<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>How other countries tackle disposal</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG
SRC="images/nirsmlog.gif" ALIGN="TOP">
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="How">How other countries tackle disposal</A></H3>
<P>The UK is not alone in its plans to develop an underground repository as the
responsible and environmentally-friendly way to tackle the disposal of
radioactive wastes. At Forsmark in Sweden, an underground repository is already
in operation for shorted-lived intermediate wastes. The Swedes are now planning
a rock laboratory to explore locations for a deep disposal site. In France, four
sites have been selected as potential sites for deep rock laboratories - one of
which may eventually become the repository site. in the United States,
exploratory excavations are under way at Yucca mountain in Nevada. The situation
is similar in Belgium, Canada, Germany, Japan, Spain and Switzerland: in fact,
every OECD country with a substantial nuclear power programme is planning for
deep disposal. 
</P> 
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic24.gif" ALT="Disposal of Nuclear waste in Swedish repository." HEIGHT="200"><CITE>Disposal
of Nuclear waste in Swedish repository.</CITE></P>
<P><BR CLEAR="LEFT"></P>
<P><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="images/pic2.gif" ALT="Imgae of NAGRA's rock laboratory at Grimsel." VSPACE="30" HSPACE="15" HEIGHT="230"><BR><BR><CITE>Site
of NAGRA's Underground Rock Laboratory at Grimsel, Switzerland.</CITE></P>
