    <tr>
        <td valign="top" width="23%" height="24"><b>Subject:</b></td>
        <td colspan="2" width="77%" height="24">NIREX 97</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>I set out below my thoughts as an input to our decisions on
where next with Nirex 97:</p>

<blockquote>
    <p>1. A successful end-point for Nirex 97 can be
    characterised as follows:</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> regional models (which
        underpin the more local scale models to be used to<br>
        predict the impacts of RCF shaft sinking) able to
        reproduce key characteristics<br>
        of the site (e.g. heads and salinities);</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> the published Nirex 97
        report realistically demonstrates that a repository at<br>
        Sellafield can meet the risk target on the basis of our
        current knowledge;</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> a better insight of the
        key discriminators of site suitability and an
        understanding<br>
        of how we can take that insight forward through the RCF,
        interpretation and<br>
        modelling programmes to resolve those discriminating
        factors.</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>2. Our time constraint is fixed in respect of needing
    published predictions in advance of<br>
    the start of RCF shaft sinking on 1 September but there may
    be some flexibility about<br>
    the scope of those published predictions. Also, we must
    present a nominally final<br>
    report to the March Board: our flexibility lies in
    identifying additional packages of work<br>
    which may run on past March and are required as a result of
    initial calculations. </p>
    <p>3. If we need extra budget for 1996-97, I need to know now
    so that I can make the case<br>
    to Michael.</p>
    <p>4. In respect of the groundwater pathway, I am sure that
    most of the issues have already<br>
    been raised, hence the following thoughts are possibly not
    new:</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> we need to look hard at
        the BVG permeability to see if we can justify a lower<br>
        central value (if not, I have the feeling that we may
        struggle to make a case for<br>
        the site);</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> we need to revisit the
        properties for the ZRAPs and, in particular, to use both<br>
        input and output model data as a means to constrain
        feasible values;</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> there are obviously
        strong feelings amongst the Site Characterisation Team
        that<br>
        our treatment of heterogeneity, particular more local
        scale heterogeneity, as for<br>
        the ZRAPs, may be creating problems that are not real
        (the road-blocked super<br>
        highway). While it seems that the proper treatment of
        heterogeneity may not be<br>
        feasible on the timescale for Nirex 97, some exploration
        of the impacts of<br>
        heterogeneity may be helpful. We should not just rely on
        Peter's reassurances<br>
        about the veracity of his analytical treatments;</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> we need to decide which
        of the 2-D or 3-D models is ultimately used to<br>
        generate the risk calculations. Perhaps now we have a
        feel for the key<br>
        parameter sensitivities from the imposed head and
        salinity model, we could use<br>
        a more physically realistic coupled model to explore
        those sensitivities as the<br>
        basis for revised MASCOT calculations when we come to
        generate the<br>
        &quot;definitive&quot; risk numbers for Nirex 97.</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>5. In respect of wells, we will need to update them in
    line with whatever hydrogeological<br>
    model we end up with. Given the potential beneficial impact
    of physical containment<br>
    that should be considered for the wells.</p>
    <p>6. I agree with Graham's analysis that the gas pathway has
    been approached in a<br>
    particularly flat-footed way. We need to generate a report
    which calculates what we<br>
    actually think would happen rather than what we think would
    not happen but which<br>
    would be a problem if it did.</p>
    <p>7. Currently the bias audit falls short of what I had
    expected, i.e. a semi quantitative<br>
    analysis of both in-model and out-of-model factors that could
    significantly change the<br>
    answer. I think that this is a second order priority compared
    to getting the<br>
    groundwater pathway right but nonetheless I would suggest
    that we give some thought<br>
    to whether this aspect of Nirex&nbsp;97 can be taken further
    in the time available.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>A couple of further thoughts arising from an observation that
there is still a gap between the<br>
modellers and the hydrogeologists:</p>

<blockquote>
    <p>1. From hereon the hydrogeologists and modellers must work
    very closely together to<br>
    complete Nirex&nbsp;97 and the RCF predictions. This includes
    taking decisions on<br>
    parameters, model variants, etc. We cannot afford for Peter
    to take something away<br>
    and bring it back a few weeks later when it is done. Which
    members of the Site<br>
    Characterisation Team (Nirex or contractors) should we plug
    into the core team to<br>
    drive this forward? Is there are additional expertise that we
    should be bringing to bear?</p>
    <p>2. I was concerned that after £200M the modellers are
    saying that we are short of<br>
    datapoints by a factor of 10x or 100x. We need to get to the
    bottom of this - it seems<br>
    more fundamental than just the number of hydrogeological
    units we are using. Options<br>
    would seem to be:</p>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> more site
        characterisation</p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> a different approach to
        modelling</p>
        <p><font face="Symbol">·</font> we conclude that a BUSC
        type site is inherently not characterisable to the<br>
        requisite level.</p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>

<p>It is essential that the proposed way forward on the
groundwater pathway, when formulated, is<br>
circulated to myself, Bob, Anna and Graham for comment. Is the
appropriate mechanism for<br>
steering subsequent activities the NHMT? A successful outcome is
obviously critical to the<br>
Company's programme and must be a top priority for all of us.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>John Holmes</p>

<p>Director for Science</p>

