<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nirex Report No. SA/96/004</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<P><IMG SRC="../../images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex logo" ALIGN="TOP"></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="+2"><B>ROCK CHARACTERISATION FACILITY:<BR>BASELINE
GROUNDWATER PRESSURES AND HYDROCHEMISTRY<BR>SUMMARY REPORT</B></FONT></P>
<P><BR><BR></P>
<H2>Preface</H2>
<P>The United Kingdom has significant quantities of radioactive waste, which
have arisen primarily from the nuclear power programme since the 1950s.  More
will arise over the lives of existing nuclear plants and any developed in
future.</P>
<P>Nirex is responsible for providing and managing facilities for the safe
disposal of intermediate and certain low-level radioactive waste (ILW and LLW
respectively).  Government policy, in line with international expert opinion, is
that the preferred disposal route for such wastes is the excavated caverns of a
deep geological repository.  In 1991, Nirex chose an area near Sellafield, West
Cumbria, as the focus for further investigations, following preliminary
geological investigations undertaken there and at Dounreay in Scotland from
1989.  The deep disposal concept aims to use a combination of natural and
engineered barriers to achieve the necessary degree of long-term isolation and
containment of the radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>Most of the radioactive waste planned for disposal in the repository will be
intermediate-level wastes such as:</P>
<UL>
<LI>claddings separated from spent nuclear fuel</LI>
<LI>filters and other wastes from effluent treatments</LI>
<LI>worn-out plant and equipment</LI>
<LI>isotopes used in medical treatments</LI>
<LI>radioactive materials used in industry and defence.</LI></UL>
<P>ILW and LLW are produced at a number of locations throughout the United
Kingdom.  The largest quantities arise from the generation of electrical power,
production of nuclear fuel and reprocessing, and from defence establishments,
research and development, and radioisotope manufacture.  In addition, many other
medical, industrial and educational establishments produce small quantities of
radioactive wastes.</P>
<P>Most LLW produced in the UK is currently disposed of at the Drigg site in
Cumbria operated by British Nuclear Fuels plc (BNFL).  That site is expected to
have capacity for LLW arisings well into the next century.</P>
<P>Nirex has no responsibility for high-level radioactive waste.</P>
<P>Nirex has carried out extensive investigations in West Cumbria to help
determine whether a site around Longlands Farm, near Sellafield, could be
suitable for a deep repository.  Some 60% of the ILW expected to be presented
for deep disposal during the 50-year operational period of the repository arises
from BNFL operations at Sellafield.</P>
<P>By the autumn of 1996, 27 deep boreholes had been drilled in the Sellafield
region as part of the Company's science programme.  They provide information to
construct a three-dimensional picture of the rocks in the area and their
hydrogeology - the nature and quantity of water present and the way it moves.</P>
<P>In common with other countries investigating potential sites for deep
geological disposal, Nirex proposes to build an underground rock laboratory, or
Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF), to obtain a more detailed picture of the
geology and hydrogeology of the area.  During 1995/96, a public inquiry was held
into the Company's proposals to construct an RCF at Longlands Farm.</P>
<P>'Baseline' is the description which is generally applied to the conditions
in a system, e.g. a groundwater system, prior to some form of induced
perturbation.  The undisturbed conditions incorporate the effects of natural
features and processes which account for spatial and/or temporal variability in
the system.  Prior to construction of the RCF, baseline conditions for
groundwater pressures and geochemical conditions need to be established. 
Sufficient information needs to have been acquired so that:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured with confidence and used
to test and develop models of the site; and</LI>
<LI>there is a sufficient database on undisturbed conditions that the
properties of the Potential Repository Zone can be interpreted within the
context of regional groundwater flow and hydrochemical models.</LI></UL>
<P>In order to meet assurances given at the RCF Public Inquiry, a report on the
Baseline Groundwater Pressures and Hydrochemical Conditions [1] was produced by
Nirex, in association with Golder Associates (UK) Ltd, and subjected to
independent peer review.</P>
<P>This report summarises the detailed information on baseline conditions as
presented in Nirex Report SA/96/006 [1] and reports the results of the
independent peer review carried out.  The detailed report compiles and discusses
the data available to describe the baseline conditions for the groundwater
system at Sellafield, and concludes that there is adequate knowledge of the
baseline conditions for groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry in the RCF
location.  This conclusion has been supported by independent peer review.</P>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50">1.</TD>
<TD>INTRODUCTION</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>2.</TD>
<TD>PEER REVIEW</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>3.</TD>
<TD>GROUNDWATER PRESSURES</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>4.</TD>
<TD>HYDROCHEMISTRY</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>5.</TD>
<TD>NIREX'S CONCLUSIONS</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>6.</TD>
<TD>REVIEW GROUP'S CONCLUSIONS</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>7.</TD>
<TD>NIREX'S RESPONSES TO THE REVIEW GROUP</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>8.</TD>
<TD>REFERENCES</TD></TR></TABLE>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
<P>The construction of a Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF) is proposed by UK
Nirex Ltd (Nirex) at Longlands Farm, West Cumbria as an integral part of
characterisation of the Sellafield area, leading to assessment of the long-term
safety of a potential deep waste repository near Sellafield.  The construction
of the RCF is subject to a decision by the Secretary of State for the
Environment, following a planning inquiry, and all statements relating to the
RCF in this report are subject to that condition.</P>
<P>A report [1] has been produced pursuant to an assurance given by Nirex in
February 1996 to supply to the Environment Agency a peer-reviewed report on
baseline conditions for both groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry at the
proposed RCF location, within the Potential Repository Zone, prior to the
commencement of shaft sinking.  This report [1], prepared in association with
Golder Associates (UK) Ltd, compiles and discusses the data available to
describe the baseline conditions for the groundwater system at Sellafield, and
concludes that there is adequate knowledge of the baseline conditions for
groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry in the RCF location.</P>
<P>'Baseline' is the description which is generally applied to the conditions
in a system, e.g. a groundwater system, prior to some form of induced
perturbation.  The undisturbed conditions incorporate the effects of natural
features and processes which account for spatial and/or temporal variability in
the system.  Prior to construction of the RCF, baseline conditions for
groundwater pressures and hydrochemical conditions need to be established. 
Sufficient information needs to have been acquired so that:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured with confidence and used
to test and develop models of the site; and</LI>
<LI>there is a sufficient database on undisturbed conditions that the
properties of the Potential Repository Zone can be interpreted within the
context of regional groundwater flow and hydrochemical models.</LI></UL>
<P>This report provides a summary of the detailed baseline report [1], presents
the report of the independent peer review group (Attachment A) and provides
Nirex's response to the findings of the peer review.</P>
<P>Section 2 summarises the composition of the peer review group and the manner
in which they conducted the review of the baseline report [1].  Sections 3 to 5
are executive summaries of Nirex's baseline report [1] on groundwater pressures,
hydrochemistry and the conclusions reached on the establishment of baseline. 
Section 6 summarises the conclusions of the peer review group and Section 7
presents Nirex's response to these conclusions.</P>
<H2>Peer Review</H2>
<P>In accordance with the assurance given by Nirex at the close of the RCF
Public Inquiry in February 1996, the report on baseline conditions [1] has been
subjected to independent peer review.</P>
<P>Nirex convened an independent Review Group in June 1996 to carry out the
peer review.  The Terms of Reference for the Group were to examine critically
baseline information presented by Nirex and to express opinions on the
following:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>the appropriateness of the definition of baseline as adopted by Nirex in
relation to the purpose for which Nirex will use the information; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>the sufficiency of the information obtained in relation to establishing
baseline, in accordance with the established definition, prior to the
commencement of RCF shaft construction.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The Terms of Reference required the Review Group to assess the technical
adequacy of the baseline work and data, and the adequacy of the reporting.</P>
<P>Nirex also requested that the Review Group gave consideration as to whether
there were any other data sets not included in the baseline reporting, that may
be required for the assessment of repository performance and may be perturbed by
the RCF construction such that they would need to be obtained before RCF
construction.</P>
<P>The Review Group membership consisted of:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Dr Andreas Gautschi, NAGRA, Switzerland</LI>
<LI>Professor Gunnar Gustafson, Chalmers University of Technology, Sweden</LI>
<LI>Professor Peter Fritz, Umweltforschungszentrum Liepzig-Halle GmbH, Germany</LI>
<LI>Professor John Lloyd, University of Birmingham.</LI></UL>
<P>All members were professionally independent of Nirex.  Professor Lloyd is a
member of the independent Nirex Review Panel.  For Review Group activities Nirex
paid Group members reasonable professional fees and expenses.</P>
<P>The Review Group consisted of highly qualified scientists who have extensive
international experience in the interpretation of shallow and deep groundwater
flow systems, both in terms of groundwater pressure distributions and in terms
of hydrochemical processes and evolution.</P>
<P>Their report includes details of the background to the review, the
composition of the group (including their curricula vitae), their method of
working and programme, the issues they raised and their conclusions.</P>
<P>The Review Group identified two issues not addressed in the report [1]. 
These were that fall outside the baseline requirements, namely in situ stresses
and environmental isotopes.  Nirex provided evidence that these issues are
addressed elsewhere and this was accepted by the Review Group [2, 3].</P>
<P>The Review Group accepted that the data sets presented in Report SA/96/006
[1] are comprehensive in respect of baseline but indicated the desirability of a
presentation of tritium concentration data for the shallow groundwaters.  A
report presenting this data is in preparation [4].  The Review Group were
satisfied with this approach.</P>
<H2>Groundwater Pressures </H2>
<P>Data for groundwater pressures are used in the modelling of groundwater
flow. Numerical models of groundwater flow generally calculate groundwater
pressure as an output parameter (except at model boundaries, where pressures may
be specified as inputs).  The model outputs may then be compared with measured
pressures to assess the validity of the model.  The groundwater pressure data at
Sellafield are being used in support of groundwater flow modelling of
undisturbed and disturbed conditions.  Both types of modelling have the same
overall objective, namely to gain an improved understanding of the hydrogeology
of the Potential Repository Zone and its surroundings, in order to improve
confidence in the models that will be used to predict groundwater flow and
radionuclide transport in safety assessments for a deep waste repository.</P>
<P>Groundwater pressures in the Sellafield area have been measured with
increasing density and frequency of measurements since 1974.  The early
measurements were in boreholes  less than 90 metres deep, drilled to investigate
the groundwater resources in the area.  By 1986, there were eleven regularly
monitored boreholes of this type within the Sellafield 'Site' area subsequently
chosen by Nirex for deep borehole investigation.  Within 2.5 km of the planned
RCF shafts, seven of these boreholes are still being monitored, three of which
have hydrographs exceeding twenty-two years' duration.  Since 1989, Nirex have
drilled and tested a series of deep boreholes in the Site area, including eleven
new deep boreholes in the Potential Repository Zone.  These have been
instrumented progressively with multi-packer equipment for long-term monitoring
of groundwater pressures, with the greatest density of monitoring close to the
planned RCF.  </P>
<P>The first use of the full Long-Term Monitoring System was to record pressure
responses to the various phases of the Borehole RCF 3 Pump Test in late 1994 and
the first half of 1995.  This provided an invaluable 'testing ground' for future
monitoring and interpretation of the pressure responses to RCF construction
(especially shaft sinking), although the drawdowns and flow rates associated
with the Borehole RCF3 Pump Test were much smaller than those to be expected for
RCF construction.  </P>
<P>The installation of the Long-Term Monitoring System commenced in late 1992. 
The instrumentation comprising the network was progressively installed during
the subsequent two years such that by 1 January 1995 the network was complete
apart from Borehole PRZ2, in which the instrumentation became operational on 22
January 1995.  The Borehole RCF 3 Pump Test was the last significant
perturbation caused to the groundwater pressures by the surface based
investigations.  This test was completed in July 1995.  The earliest date that
Nirex expect to be able to commence RCF shaft sinking is September 1997.  Thus,
when shaft sinking starts the Long-Term Monitoring System data set will
comprise:</P>
<UL>
<LI>up to 4 years 9 months, and at least 2 years 7 months of data records; and</LI>
<LI>at least 2 years 1 month of data records (end July 1995 to end August 1997)
since completion of the Borehole RCF3 Pump Test.</LI></UL>
<P>The Long-Term Monitoring System has provided time series data with sampling
intervals generally ranging from 2 to 30 minutes.</P>
<P>Data from the Long-Term Monitoring System are supplemented by data from
Environmental Pressure Measurements made in all the Nirex deep boreholes during
pauses in drilling.  Groundwater pressures in the shallow Sherwood Sandstone
Group and Quaternary drift deposits come from a variety of sources, including
Environment Agency and observation boreholes drilled by British Nuclear Fuels
plc, Nirex 'Quaternary' boreholes and new shallow hydrogeological boreholes
recently installed by Nirex around the planned RCF shafts.  These direct
groundwater pressure measurements are supported by an extensive network of
meteorological and surface hydrometric monitoring installations within the
Sellafield area.</P>
<P>The number of Environmental Pressure Measurement locations exceeds the
number of Long-Term Monitoring System zones, and the Environmental Pressure
Measurement data add valuable detail to the Long-Term Monitoring System baseline
groundwater pressures, which can be used to test models of the undisturbed
system.  Environmental Pressure Measurement data have already been used to
evaluate such flow models [5]. For intervals where both Environmental Pressure
Measurements and Long-Term Monitoring System measurements are available, the
Environmental Pressure Measurement data are confirmed by averaged Long-Term
Monitoring System data for the 'quiet' period(s) preceding or following the
Borehole RCF3 Pump Test.</P>
<P>Time series monitoring of groundwater pressures, using the Long-Term
Monitoring System and the shallow boreholes, provides a series of data sets
containing information covering time scales of a few minutes to over twenty
years.  These data have permitted the natural (e.g. tidal barometric and
recharge related) and anthropogenic fluctuations in baseline groundwater
pressures to be observed and their likely influences quantified.  In the
Potential Repository Zone, the largest of these fluctuations are those in the
Sherwood Sandstone Group resulting from natural seasonal variations in
groundwater recharge.  These are generally less than 3 metre head changes
although the drought of 1995 caused groundwater heads in near surface monitoring
points in Boreholes RCM1 and RCM2 to fall by up to 5.5 metres.  For locations
with the largest seasonal fluctuations (in the shallow Sherwood Sandstone Group
in 'interfluve' settings), the hydrographs within the Potential Repository Zone
are well correlated with hydrographs in similar settings more remote from the
Potential Repository Zone, where no perturbation by the RCF is expected.  At
greater depths (in the Borrowdale Volcanic Group), natural fluctuations in
groundwater pressures are much less, and so detection of perturbations due to
the RCF should be straightforward, as was detection of perturbations in the
Borehole RCF 3 Pump Test. </P>
<P>In summary, it is shown that the temporal fluctuations in groundwater
pressures are sufficiently well characterised and understood that they will not
interfere with the ability to detect future perturbations caused by RCF
construction and they can be understood within the context of regional
groundwater flow at Sellafield.</P>
<P>The areal extent of the perturbations in groundwater pressures that could
potentially be caused by the RCF has been derived using scoping calculations.  A
nominal 10 kPa (1 metre head) drawdown has been used to define the limit to the
perturbations.  The most useful information on perturbations of groundwater
pressures (for modelling purposes) is expected to come from the shaft sinking
phase of RCF development.  During this period, which will last approximately 3.5
years, drawdowns exceeding 10 kPa (1 metre head) in the Borrowdale Volcanic
Group of rocks are not expected to extend more than 2 km from the shafts.  Thus,
pressure measurements in the Borrowdale Volcanic Group of rocks in boreholes
remote from the RCF (especially Boreholes 11A and 14) should remain unperturbed
during shaft sinking.  It is quite possible that these remote locations in the
Borrowdale Volcanic Group of rocks will also remain unperturbed throughout the
10 year operational lifetime of the RCF.</P>
<P>The Long-Term Monitoring System zones are located to monitor both specific
features (section of the boreholes containing zones of interest based on an
assessment of geological and hydrogeological information), and sections of the
boreholes which do not contain such features.  The distribution and density of
the monitoring zones to provide both baseline data and to permit monitoring of
future perturbations caused by the RCF is demonstrated by:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the distribution of monitoring zones cover areas where calculations show
that responses from the RCF are likely to be detected and areas where responses
are unlikely to be detected;</LI>
<LI>the monitoring points cover all major lithological and structural features
encountered in the vicinity of the RCF; and</LI>
<LI>the density of the monitoring points, as demonstrated by the Borehole RCF 3
Pump Test, is more than adequate to define the distance-drawdown relationships
in the three major geological formations (Sherwood Sandstone Group, Brockram and
Borrowdale Volcanic Group of rocks).</LI></UL>
<H2>Hydrochemistry</H2>
<P>Hydrochemical data are generally used in a more qualitative way in support
of groundwater modelling than are pressure data.  Hydrochemical parameters which
are not influenced by geochemical reactions, for example chloride, are used to
infer directions of groundwater flow and mixing proportions.  Chloride
concentrations also directly influence the potential for groundwater flow
because of the relationship between salinity and density.  Other hydrochemical
data are interpreted in terms of the evolution of the groundwater system and the
geochemical processes which occur in the undisturbed system,</P>
<P>Future hydrochemical disturbance by the RCF will occur over a smaller
spatial scale than perturbations to groundwater pressures and will introduce
localised temporal changes on a timescale which can be contrasted with the long
timescales over which natural changes occur.  On the timescale of the operation
of the RCF, the plausible causes of chemical perturbation in the deep subsurface
are:</P>
<UL>
<LI>mass flux (either by bulk groundwater flow or by diffusion) of chemical
species towards or away from the RCF; or </LI>
<LI>changes in the temperature/pressure regime causing chemical reaction or
outgassing.  </LI></UL>
<P>The mass flux might include the movement of contaminants introduced by the
excavation or by construction activities, such as blasting or grouting
chemicals, or introduction of atmospheric oxygen.  Diffusion of oxygen from the
RCF atmosphere into the excavation disturbed zone and beyond could occur over a
small scale during RCF operation.  Confidence in the hydrochemical baseline
conditions with respect to detecting and using these perturbations comes from
the quantity of data drawn from locations close to the future RCF, and from
demonstration that the spatial variations at the small scale are sufficiently
well characterised and consistent with regional patterns.</P>
<P>In the Borehole RCF 3 Pump Test, there were no significant changes in the
salinity of the water pumped from any of the tested intervals.  This reflects
the small volumes extracted and the relatively small length scale of mass flow
(required for a hydrochemical perturbation) which is typically two orders of
magnitude less than that of pressure perturbation.  The expected radius of
influence for hydrochemical perturbation around the planned RCF is thus much
smaller than for pressure perturbations.  For this and practical reasons related
to the feasibility of time-series sampling, monitoring for hydrochemical
perturbations will be made from the RCF itself (via short sampling boreholes
drilled from the RCF), rather than from the previously sampled locations in deep
and shallow boreholes.  </P>
<P>Although chloride is the most sensitive tracer of groundwater movement where
there is a salinity contrast (especially in the vicinity of the Saline
Transition Zone between fresh/brackish waters and underlying saline waters),
other hydrochemical parameters can potentially be used to detect mass flows of
groundwater and to distinguish the sources of groundwater flow.  These include
nitrate, which is a tracer for shallow fresh groundwater, and potassium, which
has a distinctive profile with depth in the saline groundwaters.  Sulphate is of
interest because of the possibility of air introduced through the RCF causing
oxidation of sulphide minerals (chiefly pyrite) within the rock formations. 
Increasing concentration of dissolved sulphate would be a tracer of this
process.</P>
<P>Groundwater compositions in the Potential Repository Zone from surface down
to -400 m aOD are represented by 16 Discrete Extraction Test samples plus 11
samples taken during Environmental Pressure Measurement tests.  The Discrete
Extraction Tests are predominantly from the Sherwood Sandstone Group, with 3
derived from tests in the Brockram formation and 2 from the Borrowdale Volcanic
Group.  Below this there is a fairly even distribution of 14 Discrete Extraction
Test samples, 4 post-drilling Discrete Extraction Tests and 7 Environmental
Pressure Measurement samples from depths in the range -400 to -1000 m aOD.  This
includes the zone of Borrowdale Volcanic Group of rocks in which the RCF
galleries will be located.  There are also samples from 5 tests in the deeper
Borrowdale Volcanic Group of rocks  (below -1000 m aOD) which were taken in
Borehole 2.  In summary, groundwater samples have been taken at 57 hydrochemical
test locations in a volume of less than a cubic kilometre within the Potential
Repository Zone.  The distribution of samples has been determined by the
practicalities of groundwater sampling in deep boreholes.</P>
<P>Hydrochemical data from the 8 sampled deep boreholes within the Potential
Repository Zone have been combined to form a single composite depth profile,
with no evidence of significant systematic lateral variations in composition
within the area of the Potential Repository Zone, except within the Saline
Transition Zone.  As the RCF galleries will be well below the Saline Transition
Zone, perturbations of the Saline Transition Zone will be monitored from the
shafts.  The position of the Saline Transition Zone above the RCF location has
been identified by sampling and geophysical logging in the South Shaft
centre-line Borehole RCF3 and in the boreholes immediately surrounding it (RCM1,
RCM2).</P>
<P>Shallow groundwaters in the region have been characterised by additional
hydrochemical data from boreholes, wells and springs, largely from the
Environment Agency (formerly National Rivers Authority) archives, plus
hydrochemical data collected by Nirex from two pre-existing moderately deep
boreholes in the Potential Repository Zone, depth sampling of Environment Agency
boreholes, a survey of springs, sampling in mines, rainfall sampling sites and
river baseflow surveys.</P>
<P>An additional function of the RCF will be to obtain relatively unperturbed
data for unstable hydrochemical parameters, especially pH and indicators of
redox conditions, which are difficult to obtain reliably by sampling from deep
boreholes.  It is proposed that these measurements will be made early in the RCF
programme in order to minimise the effect of perturbation by construction. 
There will then be the opportunity for longer-term monitoring of these
parameters.</P>
<H2>Nirex's Conclusions</H2>
<P>Baseline conditions have been established if sufficient information has been
acquired so that:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured with confidence and used
to test and develop models of the site; and</LI>
<LI>there is a sufficient database on undisturbed conditions that the
properties of the Potential Repository Zone can be interpreted within the
context of regional groundwater flow and hydrochemical models.</LI></UL>
<P>The scale of the perturbations to groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry
likely to be caused by the RCF has been established in the Nirex Report [1] and
objective evidence has been presented to demonstrate that they can be detected
by the established monitoring systems and by the measurements to be made within
the RCF.  The range and scale of the natural and other anthropogenic
fluctuations are also identified and described [1].  The magnitudes of these
fluctuations are small in comparison to those likely to be induced by the RCF
and objective evidence has been presented to demonstrate that these fluctuations
can be distinguished from those likely to be caused by the RCF.  The monitoring
network is designed to obtain data from outside the zone of influence of the
RCF, thus permitting background fluctuations to be monitored at the same time as
the RCF is proceeding.  Correlations have been established between these
fluctuations occurring within the Potential Repository Zone and those more
remote to provide confidence that fluctuations caused by factors unconnected
with the RCF can be predicted with confidence within the Potential Repository
Zone and hence separated from the RCF-induced effects.</P>
<P>The first of the criteria for establishment of baseline has thus been
satisfied.</P>
<P>The level of understanding of the hydrogeological and hydrochemical
conditions within the Potential Repository Zone and the database of information
that underpins this understanding has been demonstrated by the interpretations
and modelling already reported and tested against observations.  The datasets
for groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry have achieved very good levels of
spatial and temporal coverage, reliability and interpretability.  Significant
refinements to these datasets cannot be achieved from further surface-based
investigations.</P>
<P>The second criterion for establishment of baseline has thus been achieved.</P>
<P>The baseline dataset satisfies a reasonable and realistic assessment of its
adequacy in relation to the two established criteria.  The conclusion is,
therefore, that baseline has been established for groundwater pressures and
hydrochemistry.</P>
<H2>Review Group's Conclusions</H2>
<P>The Review Group reached the following conclusions (see Attachment A for the
full report of the Review Group):</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50">i.</TD>
<TD>Nirex Report SA/96/006 [1] had been designed to demonstrate that the
groundwater pressure and hydrochemical data were sufficiently well understood so
that construction of the RCF may commence without jeopardy to the scientific
interpretation of the Sellafield area for a potential radioactive waste
repository.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>ii.</TD>
<TD>Two primary criteria have been adopted to determine the adequacy of the
baseline conditions (see Section 1).  These criteria have been set within the
context of the eventual use of the data, firstly, as a baseline against which
the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured, and secondly, as a baseline
that will allow the interpretation of the undisturbed properties of the
Potential Repository Zone.  The Group considered that the two criteria are sound
and objective within the requirements of the Sellafield studies.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>iii.</TD>
<TD>With respect to groundwater pressure data the Group considered that Nirex
has established sufficient data and understanding to constitute a baseline that
adequately defines the extent, range and scale of natural and anthropogenic
fluctuations.  The Group also considered that Nirex has in place a monitoring
network that will adequately record pressure perturbations created by the RCF
and continue to record pressure data outside the RCF response area.  The Group
drew attention to the fact that the extensive pressure data base collated in
Nirex Report SA/96/006 [1] up to end October 1996 will be extended for
approximately a further 10 months prior to the commencement of RCF shaft
construction (on the assumptions that planning permission for the RCF is
received and that shaft construction proceeds in accordance with Nirex's
planning base programme with shaft excavation commencing on 1 September 1997).</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>iv.</TD>
<TD>The Group supported the approach adopted by Nirex to represent the
hydrochemical data and believes that sufficient data have been collected to
define baseline conditions in terms of hydrochemical parameters and their
distribution.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>v.</TD>
<TD>The Group concurred with the view that for further realistic understanding
of the hydrogeological conditions the most effective means of obtaining data,
particularly hydrochemical data, is through an RCF scientific investigation
programme.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>vi.</TD>
<TD>In conclusion the Group stated to state that it believes that Nirex has
satisfied the criteria set for baseline conditions and fulfilled the commitment
given at the Public Inquiry.  The Group unequivocally supported the Nirex
conclusions that baseline conditions have been established.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<H2>Nirex's Responses to the Review Group's Conclusions</H2>
<P>The conclusions reached by the Review Group support the statements made by
Nirex at the RCF Public Inquiry that baseline conditions have been established. 
Nirex accepts the findings of the Review Group.</P>
