<P><B>1.   INTRODUCTION</B></P>
<P><B>1.1 Background</B></P>
<P>During the Sellafield Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF) Public Inquiry
the question was raised as to whether adequate baseline hydrogeological data
would be acquired by Nirex prior to the RCF construction so that the
construction disturbance created would not irrevocably destroy data that could
not be indirectly represented through other Nirex data sources or future Nirex
investigations.</P>
<P>In order to establish the extent of baseline data requirements the context
in which the data are to be eventually applied has to be defined.  For the
Sellafield study it is considered that sufficient information needs to have been
acquired prior to construction so that:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>(i)</TD>
<TD>the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured with confidence and used
to test and develop models of the site, and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>(ii)</TD>
<TD>there is sufficient database on undisturbed conditions that the properties
of the potential repository zone (PRZ) can be interpreted within the context of
regional groundwater flow and hydrochemical models.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>To address the baseline data issue Nirex stated in their Closing Statement
at the Public Inquiry that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;Nirex work to extend and refine information about baseline conditions
continues.  A further independent peer review of the available data, considering
both groundwater pressures and hydrochemistry is planned  to be carried out by
the end of 1996.  Nirex intends that, to provide the Environment Agency with an
opportunity to give a view prior to the start of underground characterisation, a
peer-reviewed baseline report will be supplied to, and discussed with, the
Agency prior to the commencement of the RCF shaft sinking.  The Company will
take due account of views expressed by the Agency before shaft sinking begins. 
The Company intends that the peer-reviewed submission which is put to the
Environment Agency will be published.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>In order to demonstrate the extent of the stipulated baseline data Nirex
commissioned Golder Associates as Contractor, to compile and report on the
groundwater pressure and hydrochemical database and to explain the data in the
context of its adequacy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The final baseline compilation was published in December 1996 in Nirex
Report  SA/96/006 entitled:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="100"><FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD>Rock Characterisation Facility</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Longlands Farm, West Cumbria:</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Report on Baseline Groundwater</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Pressures and Hydrochemistry</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The Report is a Nirex Science Report and forms part of the Sellafield
Geological and Hydrogeological Investigations.</P>
<P><B>1.2 Review Group</B></P>
<P>To meet the peer review commitment given at the Public Inquiry, Nirex
convened an independent international Review Group in June 1996.  The Terms of
Reference for the Group were to critically examine baseline information
presented by Nirex and to express opinions on the following:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>(i)</TD>
<TD>the appropriateness of the definition of baseline as adopted by Nirex in
relation to the purposes for which Nirex will use the information, and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>(ii)</TD>
<TD>the sufficiency of the information obtained in relation to establishing
baseline, in accordance with the established definition, prior to the
commencement of RCF shaft construction.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The Terms required that the Group were to assess the technical adequacy of
the baseline work and data, and the adequacy of the reporting. Nirex also
requested that the Group gave consideration as to whether there were any other
data sets not included in the baseline reporting, that may be required for the
assessment of a repository performance and may be perturbed by the RCF
construction such that they would need to be obtained before RCF construction.</P>
<P><B>1.3 Scope of Work</B></P>
<P>The scope of work of the Review Group was to review the baseline reporting
in the context of the Group's Terms of Reference and to advise Nirex on issues
as the reporting process progressed.</P>
<P><B>2. REVIEW GROUP MEMBERSHIP</B></P>
<P>The Review Group membership consisted of:</P>
<P>Professor Peter Fritz, Umweltforschungszentrum Leipzig-Halle GmbH, Germany<BR>Dr
Andreas Gautschi, Nagra,  Switzerland<BR>Professor Gunnar Gustafson, Chalmers
University of Technology, Sweden<BR>Professor John Lloyd, University of
Birmingham, United Kingdom</P>
<P>All members were professionally independent of Nirex.  Professor Lloyd is a
member of the independent Nirex  Review Panel.  For Review Group activities
Nirex paid Group members reasonable professional fees and expenses. 
</P>
<P>The Group consisted of highly qualified scientists who have extensive
international experience in the interpretation of shallow and deep groundwater
flow systems, both in terms of groundwater pressure distributions and in terms
of hydrochemical processes and evolution.  All of the Group members have
experience in underground radioactive waste assessment programmes.   The <I>curriculum
vitae </I>of the members are given in Appendix I.</P>
<P><B>3. GROUP METHOD OF WORKING AND PROGRAMME</B></P>
<P><B>3.1 Information Process</B></P>
<P>As part of the reporting process two draft versions of Nirex Report
SA/96/006 were prepared and issued to the Review Group for appraisal, prior to
the final published version of the report in December 1996.</P>
<P>The reporting sequence was:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>Contractor Approved Report</TD>
<TD>issued to Group</TD>
<TD>2 September 1996</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD>Nirex Draft Report</TD>
<TD> issued to Group</TD>
<TD>14 November 1996</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Prior to the production of the Contractor Approved Report the Group met with
Nirex representatives (10 July 1996) to be briefed on the baseline requirements
and to endorse the approach being adopted.  Subsequent to receipt of that Report
meetings were held on 5 September 1996 and 11 October 1996 to discuss issues
raised by the Group, agree the overall Nirex approach and monitor progress.</P>
<P>On 4 and 5 November 1996 the Group made a familiarisation visit to
Sellafield where site conditions were explained by Nirex staff.</P>
<P>Following receipt and review of the Nirex Draft Report the Group met with
Nirex representatives on 22 November 1996 to discuss the resolution of
outstanding issues prior to publication of the final report.</P>
<P>The Group received the final report on 4 December 1996.  The conclusions of
the Group given in Section 5 of this Report are based upon the final version of
Nirex Report SA/96/006.</P>
<P><B>3.2 Review  Process</B></P>
<P>Throughout the preparation of Nirex Report No. SA/96/006 the Group had
access to the Nirex baseline data and was able to actively and critically review
both the data and the context of the reporting of the data.</P>
<P>Each Group member reviewed completely each of the draft reports and the
final report.  All other Nirex reports requested by  Group members for
background information were made available.  </P>
<P>The average time spent by each of the Group members at meetings and carrying
out independent reviews was 15 days.</P>
<P><B>4. ISSUES RAISED BY GROUP</B></P>
<P><B>4.1 Procedure Adopted</B></P>
<P>As a consequence of the review process a number of issues covering a broad
range of subjects were raised by Group members.  These were collated and
discussed with Nirex staff at the meetings noted in Section 3.1.  A procedure of
Issue Tracking Forms was used, whereby an issue was recorded by the Group and a
response elicited from Nirex.  The procedure was carried out  throughout the
reporting process so that, as applicable, modifications were made to the report
subsequent to an issue being raised, or the Group accepted that an issue was not
relevant in the baseline context.</P>
<P><B>4.2 Details of Issues</B></P>
<P>The details of the issues raised by the Review  Group and the responses
received from Nirex are given as Issue Tracking Forms in Appendix III.</P>
<P>Issue Tracking Forms Nos. 1-26 relate to issues that proved pertinent to the
baseline reporting, while Forms Nos. S1 and S2 concern issues that fall outside
of the baseline requirements, but have been addressed by Nirex.</P>
<P>The Group did not identify any data sets that it considers should have been
included in Report No. SA/96/006, with the exception of tritium concentration
data for the shallow groundwaters.  This issue was addressed by Nirex in Issue
Tracking Form 17, (Appendix III), and the response was accepted by the Group.</P>
<P>The Group raised the question as to whether <I>in situ</I> stress, and
possible changes to environmental isotope concentrations, isotopic ratios and
soil gases as a consequence of the construction of the RCF should be included in
the baseline definition (see Issue Tracking Forms S1 and S2,  Appendix III).  In
discussions with Nirex, the  Group agreed that such information should not be
included in that it was reported elsewhere.</P>
<P>In all cases the responses in their final form, as given in Appendix III,
were accepted by the Group.  The Issue Tracking Forms were all signed  by
Professor J W Lloyd by agreement with all Group members.</P>
<P><B>5. CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P>The following statements have the agreement of all members of the Review
Group.</P>
<P>Nirex Report No. SA/96/006 has been designed to demonstrate that the
groundwater pressure and hydrochemical data are sufficiently well understood so
that construction of the RCF may commence without jeopardy to the scientific
interpretation of the Sellafield area for a potential radioactive waste
repository.</P>
<P>Two primary criteria have been adopted to determine the adequacy of the
baseline conditions (see Section 1.1).  These criteria have been set within the
context of the eventual use of the data, firstly, as a baseline against which
the disturbance created by the RCF can be measured, and secondly, as a baseline
that will allow the interpretation of the undisturbed properties of the PRZ. 
The Group considers that the two criteria are sound and objective within the
requirements of the Sellafield studies.</P>
<P>With respect to groundwater pressure data the Group considers that Nirex has
established sufficient data, spatial correlation and understanding to constitute
a baseline that adequately defines the extent, range and scale of natural and
anthropogenic fluctuations.  The Group also considers that Nirex has in place a
monitoring network that will adequately record pressure perturbations created by
the RCF and continue to record pressure data outside of the RCF response area. 
The Group draws attention to the fact that the extensive pressure data base
collated up to the end of October 1996 in Report SA/96/006 will be extended for
approximately a further 10 months prior to the commencement of RCF construction
(on the assumption that planning permission for the RCF is received and that
shaft construction proceeds in accordance with Nirex's planning base programme
with shaft excavation commencing on 1 September 1997).</P>
<P>The Group supports the approach adopted by Nirex to represent the
hydrochemical data and believes that sufficient data have been collected to
define baseline conditions in terms of hydrochemical parameters and their
distribution.</P>
<P>The Group concurs with the view that for further realistic understanding of
the hydrogeological conditions the most effective means of obtaining data,
particularly hydrochemical data, is through an RCF scientific investigation
programme.</P>
<P>In conclusion the Group wishes to state that it believes that Nirex has
satisfied the criteria set for baseline conditions and fulfilled the commitment
given at the Public Inquiry.  The Group unequivocally supports the Nirex
conclusions that baseline conditions have been established.</P>
