<P><B>ANTHONY JEFFREY SMITH will say:</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am the Managing Partner of Wardell Armstrong, a long established
consultancy Partnership specialising in mining, minerals, engineering and
environmental matters.</P>
<P>1.2 I hold a degree in Mining Engineering from the University of Newcastle
Upon Tyne.  I am a Chartered Engineer, a Fellow of the Institution of Mining
Engineers and was a Branch President of that Institution for 1993/1994.</P>
<P>1.3 I head the Firm's mining project team and have been responsible for
managing various mining projects involving both feasibility and design studies
and a wide range of mine engineering work.</P>
<P>1.4 On the Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF) project, I am responsible
for managing all the feasibility, design and other supporting technical work
undertaken to date by Wardell Armstrong.  The scope of that work has included
both surface and underground design and the related construction and
environmental issues.           
</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2. SUMMARY</B></P>
<P><B> Introduction</B></P>
<P>2.1 This summary describes the surface works required for the RCF.  It does
not address underground construction or the environmental effects of the
development.  These topics will be addressed by other witnesses.</P>
<P><B>Design Changes</B></P>
<P>2.2 The underground layout of the RCF will be planned and managed in
response to an iterative and adaptive approach to the programme of scientific
work.  It follows, therefore, that the RCF does not have a fixed underground
layout which will be constructed without change.  This is addressed in Dr
Mellor's evidence.  </P>
<P>2.3 Since the submission of the Planning Application [COR/102]<SUP>2 </SUP>and
Environmental Statement [COR/101]<SUP>3 </SUP>in July 1994, a number of changes
have been made to the RCF design which have an effect on the surface works. 
These are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>a proposal to construct both shafts to 680 metres below Ordnance Datum
(bOD) and to develop the galleries at the 650 metres bOD horizon.  This option,
termed the Central Case, replaces that submitted with the Planning Application
and is a more limited development than that assessed in the Environmental
Statement; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>a variant on the Central Case, which is an option to construct both shafts
to 935 metres bOD (including the shaft sump).  This option, termed the Variant
Case, supports gallery development at 900 metres bOD, which is the deepest
horizon at which Phase 2 and Phase 3 of the Science Programme would be
undertaken.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.4 The Central Case and the Variant Case, therefore, define the limits of
the underground development required to support the Science Programme. Hence,
gallery development could occur at any level between 650 metres bOD and 900
metres bOD, and a decision on this will be made during shaft construction.</P>
<P>2.5 If the Variant Case were adopted, the principal effects at the surface,
relative to the Central Case, would be:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>an extension of Phase 1 Construction by about 4 months; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>an increase of up to around 15% in the volume of spoil arising and,
therefore, a corresponding increase in the size of the Spoil Disposal Area, as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.6 A number of changes have been made to the surface land areas within the
Appeal Site area as a result of consultations with statutory and other bodies. 
These include:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>a minor relocation of the Spoil Disposal Area to maintain badger foraging
routes and an increase in size to accommodate the additional spoil that would
arise from the adoption of the Variant Case; and </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>the exclusion of 4.6 hectares of unused land from the Surface Site.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.7 Taking these and other minor changes into account, leads to a reduction
in the  Surface Site from about 74 hectares, as shown on the Planning
Application, to about 72 hectares.</P>
<P>2.8 Other design changes are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>an adjustment of the route of the surface water drain to Newmill Beck and
the effluent pipeline to the Sellafield Works to avoid disturbance to Bluebell
Wood, in response to concerns expressed by the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology;
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>reduction in the size of the surface water drain headwall structure at
Newmill Beck, together with a corresponding reduction in the pipe diameter of
the surface water drain, in response to concerns expressed by the National
Rivers Authority (NRA); </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>a reduction in the tree planting area on the soil storage mounds, in
response to concerns expressed by the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and
Food (MAFF); </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>the deletion of the pumping station and manholes for the effluent pipeline,
as a result of adopting a pressure system; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(v)</TD>
<TD>the adoption of grouting instead of ground freezing as the preferred form
of ground treatment to control groundwater inflow during shaft construction. 
This is based upon current geological and hydrogeological information.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B> Land Use</B></P>
<P>2.9 <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figures 5.2</A> and
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.3">5.3</A> provide further information about the
land areas that comprise the Appeal Site as a result of the proposed changes. 
</P>
<P>2.10 Whilst the Surface Site will be about 38 hectares, only about 10
hectares of this will be developed for the Access Road, Platform Site,
earthworks, soil storage areas, site roads, and Longlands Farm Buildings.  In
addition, the Spoil Disposal Area to the west of the Surface Site will occupy up
to 8 hectares before it is progressively restored to agricultural pasture.</P>
<P>2.11 The existing Borehole RCF2 platform, about 1 hectare, will be used
during the construction period to support the RCF development and will provide
parking facilities throughout the life of the RCF for the workforce and
visitors.
</P>
<P>2.12 As part of the landscape proposals, 4.85 hectares of new woodland will
be planted, 2.46 hectares of which will be lost during the earthworks operation
as part of Restoration. However, the restoration proposals incorporate an
additional 2.21 hectares of new woodland planting, giving a final total new
woodland area of 4.6 hectares at the end of Restoration.  Landscape proposals
are addressed by Mrs Wilson in her evidence.</P>
<P><B>Services Corridors</B></P>
<P>2.13 The Services Corridors, occupying about 34 hectares, will accommodate
the effluent pipeline, the surface water drain and possibly, depending upon
commercial agreements, the electrical power supplies from the Sellafield Works
to the Platform Site.  The actual area occupied by the services within the
Service Corridors will be considerably less than the 34 hectares identified.
Once the installation of the services is complete, early in the programme, the
land will be returned to agricultural pasture.</P>
<P><B>Platform Site Level</B></P>
<P>2.14 At the proposed location, the Platform Site area of 4 hectares could
have been established at any level between 80 metres above Ordnance Datum (aOD)
and 84.5 metres aOD and still achieve a cut/fill earthworks balance [COR/101]<SUP>7</SUP>.
</P>
<P>2.15 The Platform Site on which the shafts and supporting surface facilities
will be constructed takes into account the proximity of inhabited buildings and
the A595(T), the preservation of trees and hedgerows, and the need to achieve a
cut/fill balance in the earthworks operation to form the Platform Site.</P>
<P>2.16 However, the 84.5 metres aOD level relates better to the natural
topography, field pattern and existing buildings at Longlands Farm, and enables
the valley to the south-west of the Platform Site to be retained largely intact.
 It also allows the retention of most of the mature trees, reduces the amount
and duration of earthworks operations, and allows Restoration to be more easily
achieved [COR/101]<SUP>9</SUP>.</P>
<P>2.17 Following consultations in 1993, Cumbria County Council accepted the
benefits of forming the Platform Site at 84.5 metres aOD (refer to the
correspondence in  Appendix A1).   
</P>
<P><B>Site Access</B></P>
<P>2.18 The Access Road to the Surface Site will commence at the existing new
junction with the A595(T), and its route is indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure8.1">Figure 8.1</A>.  The Access Road will form the
spine to which all the other internal roads will connect in order to provide
access to all areas of the Surface Site and the eastern end of the Services
Corridors.</P>
<P><B>Earthworks</B>
</P>
<P>2.19 Topsoil will be stripped from an area of about 5 hectares, comprising
the Access Road, site roads and the extension of the existing platform for
Boreholes RCF3 and RCF4 in order to form the Platform Site.  The soil will be
moved to the east side of the Platform Site, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A>, where it will be stored for
eventual re-use.  Any existing soil storage mounds disturbed by the construction
work will also be moved to this new storage area.</P>
<P>2.20 The Platform Site will be formed by extending Boreholes RCF3 and RCF4
platform, cutting into the side of the valley and the Borehole RCF2 platform to
the north and extending into the valley along the south-western boundary using
the newly excavated material as fill [COR/101]<SUP>12</SUP>. If mechanical
ripping proves impracticable, some low intensity blasting of the rock may be
required to form the 84.5 metres aOD level.
</P>
<P>2.21 Subsoil will be placed on the face of the new embankment to support
tree planting.</P>
<P><B>Drainage</B></P>
<P>2.22 During the early stages of construction, cut-off drains will be
installed around the perimeter of the Platform Site, at the crest of the cut
slope and the toe of the embankment, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure10.1">Figure 10.1</A>, to intercept and control
surface water and sub-surface water flows [COR/101]<SUP>13</SUP>.</P>
<P>2.23 The cut-off drainage will flow into a lined pond for settlement prior
to discharge into an intermittently flowing rill which enters the southern
tributary of Newmill Beck. Prior to the placement of the fill, a drain and
drainage blanket will be installed to maintain flow in, and sub-surface drainage
to the rill [COR/101]<SUP>14</SUP>.  </P>
<P>2.24 Surface water run-off from the completed Platform Site and Access Road
will be collected via grease trap gullies and oil interceptor chambers and will
discharge into a concrete drainage channel, installed around the perimeter of
the Platform Site, as indicated in Figure 6.2 [COR/101]<SUP>18</SUP>.  After
passing through a settlement tank, the surface water will discharge to Newmill
Beck, via the surface water drain.</P>
<P>2.25 Foul water arising from sanitary facilities during initial construction
will drain to sealed tanks and will be disposed of by tanker off-site at a
disposal point approved by North West Water plc. </P>
<P>2.26 During operation of the RCF, foul water will be collected within the
foul drainage system and will be treated by an on-site sewage treatment plant. 
The treated effluent will then be discharged, along with settled underground
water and other minor arisings, through the effluent pipeline.</P>
<P><B>Electrical Power</B></P>
<P>2.27 Electrical power will be required on the Surface Site from the
beginning of Site Establishment and throughout the life of the RCF.  A secure
supply is required and this will be achieved by the use of duplicate incoming
electrical supplies.</P>
<P>2.28 The two options [COR/101]<SUP>22</SUP>for the supply of electrical
power are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>routeing two power supplies between the BNFL Sellafield distribution system
and the RCF.  A possible route is indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure
6.3</A>; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>taking the supplies from the Grid.  With this option it is not possible at
present to identify the route of the duplicate supplies.  For illustration, one
of the two supplies could be via a short connection to the existing 33 kV
overhead power supply line passing the south-east corner of the Surface Site as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.29 During the early stages of construction, should either of these
electrical power supplies not be available, temporary generators would be used,
together with the provision of a limited capacity temporary electrical supply
[COR/101]<SUP>23</SUP>.</P>
<P><B>Water Supply</B></P>
<P>2.30 The water supply will be via a connection to the existing public water
mains along the A595(T). North West Water plc will determine the optimum means
of connection.</P>
<P><B>Surface Lighting</B></P>
<P>2.31 Security lighting will be installed around the perimeter fence to
provide  illumination levels between 5 and 20 lux [COR/101]<SUP>25</SUP>. The
gatehouse on  the Access Road will require up to 150 lux of illumination
[COR/101]<SUP>26</SUP>.
</P>
<P>2.32 Levels and locations of temporary lighting during initial construction
works will vary depending on the particular construction activities underway at
any particular stage during the initial 15 month construction period. 
Illumination levels between 100 and 300 lux will be required.  Only those areas
which need to be illuminated for safety and operational reasons will be
illuminated during this period. </P>
<P>2.33 For operational lighting, the levels of illumination will  be in the
range of 20 to 50 lux [COR/101]<SUP>28</SUP>.
</P>
<P>2.34 Particular care will be taken in the specification and siting of all
the surface lighting to minimise light spillage without compromising safety and
security.</P>
<P><B>Surface Structures</B></P>
<P>2.35 The surface facilities required to support the construction and
operation of the RCF are shown in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A>
and comprise principally the headgear and heapstead buildings, spoil conveyor
and hopper, fan house, winder houses, office block, workshop and stores,
substations, explosives store and a concrete batching plant. </P>
<P>2.36 The buildings will generally comprise steel portal frames, either clad
in proprietary plastic coated metal cladding and/or brick, or be of a
pre-fabricated modular construction.  The colour will be dealt with through
planning conditions, by agreement with the Planning Authority.</P>
<P>Headgear </P>
<P>2.37 Construction headgear will be supplied by the shaft sinking contractor
and will vary in design according to the contractor's method of working. Since a
shaft sinking contractor has not yet been selected, details of the construction
headgear to be used for the RCF are not yet known.  However, a typical height
would be of the order of 25 to 30 metres, as illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.1">Figure 12.1</A>.</P>
<P>2.38 The height of the operational headgear will be 29.2 metres.  The figure
is derived by taking into account statutory safety and operational requirements.
  </P>
<P>2.39 The visual effects of the headgear are addressed by Mrs Wilson in her
evidence.</P>
<P>Longlands Farm Buildings</P>
<P>2.40 The Longlands Farm Buildings will be converted to a visitor reception
area and offices in accordance with a planning permission granted by Copeland
Borough Council on October 13 1994 (Ref No. 4/94/0617/0), a copy of which is
included in Appendix A2.</P>
<P><B>Spoil Handling and Disposal</B></P>
<P>2.41 During Phase 1 Construction, rock spoil will be brought to the surface
in kibbles (large buckets) and tipped on to the ground adjacent to each shaft. 
From there, it will be loaded into dump trucks and taken to the Spoil Disposal
Area.  The kibble discharge and spoil stockpile area will be screened to
minimise noise and dust.  </P>
<P>2.42 During Phase 2 Construction and Phase 3 Construction, spoil will be
brought to the surface through the North Shaft in rail-mounted vehicles which
will be emptied within the enclosed heapstead building and the spoil conveyed to
a 150 tonne capacity hopper.  The spoil will then be loaded into dump trucks for
transportation to the Spoil Disposal Area.</P>
<P>2.43 The Spoil Disposal Area has been designed to accommodate the maximum
volume of spoil which would arise from adoption of the Variant Case, estimated
to be about 160,000 m<SUP>3</SUP>.  </P>
<P>2.44 Prior to placement of the spoil, topsoil and subsoil will be stripped
from the initial areas and formed into noise mitigation bunds along the
south-west side of the Spoil Disposal Area in order to protect the nearby
buildings of Newton Manor and Saddlebank.</P>
<P>2.45 Throughout its life, the Spoil Disposal Area will be worked and
restored progressively to agricultural pasture, using subsoil and topsoil
recovered from the existing field.  The spoil mound will be profiled to blend in
with the surrounding landform and will not exceed 4 metres in depth.  
</P>
<P><B>Programme</B></P>
<P>2.46 Since the submission of the Planning Application and Environmental
Statement, there have been a number of changes.  Of these changes, the most
significant to the programme is the change in the assumed start date for the RCF
project from   September 1995 to the date currently assumed for internal Nirex
planning purposes of  July 1996.  This programme change is shown in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure14.1">Figure 14.1</A>.
</P>
<P>2.47 Overall, the construction of the RCF will take place over a period of 6
&#190; years, with most of the surface facilities being completed in the first
12 months.  At the end of construction will be the Phase 3 Science Programme
during which only minor excavations will be required underground depending upon
the scientists' requirements.  At any point up to the end of Phase 3, the
scientific work may show that the Sellafield site is unsuitable for a
repository. Under these circumstances, restoration works would commence.  </P>
<P><B>Closure and Restoration</B></P>
<P>2.48 Restoration will take about 2&#189; years to complete.  The work will
comprise the removal of machinery and equipment from underground, backfilling
and capping the shafts, demolition and removal of all surface structures,
hardstandings and road surfaces, and re-contouring some areas of the Surface
Site, together with some additional tree planting works in order to return the
land to agricultural pasture [NRX/1/1]<SUP>32</SUP>.
</P>
<P>2.49 At the end of Restoration, 4.6 hectares of new woodland planting will
remain. The landscape aspects of the restoration proposals are addressed by Mrs
Wilson in her evidence.</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. INTRODUCTION AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE
</B></P>
<P>3.1 This evidence describes the surface works required for the RCF, proposed
for construction at Longlands Farm.</P>
<P>3.2 It has been prepared in response to the refusal of Planning Permission
by Cumbria County Council and addresses the issues relevant to the scope of this
evidence referred to in their Statement of Case dated March 1995.  </P>
<P>3.3 The evidence does not address underground construction or the
environmental effects of the development.  These topics will be addressed by
other witnesses.</P>
<P><A NAME="AppealSite"></A><B>4. APPEAL SITE</B></P>
<P>4.1 The Appeal Site, which is approximately 222 hectares, lies to the
south-west of the A595(T), some 16 km south of Whitehaven in West Cumbria.  The
nearest settlement is the village of Gosforth, about 1 km to the east.  The BNFL
Sellafield Works are situated some 2 km to the west, beyond which lies the sea.
The Lake District National Park is to the north-east of the A595(T).  The Appeal
Site includes the Surface Site, the Platform Site and the Services Corridors.
The Surface Site and Services Corridors encompass approximately 72 hectares and
represent the maximum extent of the surface land take, as shown in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>.  Further information on the
Appeal Site and local area is given in [COR/112]<SUP>1</SUP>.</P>
<P><A NAME="DesignChanges"></A><B>5. DESIGN CHANGES</B></P>
<P><B>Central Case and Variant Case
</B></P>
<P>5.1 The underground layout of the RCF will be planned and managed in
response to an iterative and adaptive approach to the programme of scientific
work.   It follows, therefore, that the RCF does not have a fixed underground
layout which will be constructed without change.  This is addressed in Dr
Mellor's evidence.  </P>
<P>5.2 Since the submission of the Planning Application [COR/102]<SUP>2 </SUP>and
the Environmental Statement [COR/101]<SUP>3  </SUP>in July 1994, a number of
changes have been made to the RCF design which have an effect on the surface
works.  These are: </P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>a proposal to construct both shafts to 680 metres bOD and to develop the
galleries at the 650 metres bOD horizon.  This option, termed the Central Case,
replaces the proposal submitted with the Planning Application to construct the
South Shaft to 835 metres bOD and the North Shaft to 705 metres bOD, with a
limit on the maximum depth of both shafts of 900 metres bOD.  The Central Case
is, therefore, a more limited development than that assessed in the
Environmental Statement, given that both shafts are not as deep as originally
proposed, and provides only the development necessary to support the Science
Programme at the currently preferred repository horizon of 650 metres bOD; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>a variant on the Central Case, which is an option to construct both shafts
to 935 metres bOD (including the shaft sump).  This option, termed the Variant
Case, supports gallery development at 900 metres bOD, which is the deepest
horizon at which Phase 2 and Phase 3 of the Science Programme would be
undertaken. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.3 The Central Case and the Variant Case, therefore, define the limits of
the underground development to support the Science Programme. Hence, gallery
development could occur at any level between 650 metres bOD and 900 metres bOD,
and a decision on this will be made during shaft construction.
</P>
<P>5.4 If the Variant Case were adopted, the principal effects at the surface,
relative to the Central Case, would be:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>an extension of Phase 1 Construction by about 4 months; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>an increase of up to around 15% in the volume of spoil arising and,
therefore, a corresponding increase in the size of the Spoil Disposal Area, as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Changes in Surface Land Area Within the Appeal Site Area </B></P>
<P>5.5 A number of changes have been made to the surface land areas within the
Appeal Site area, following consultations with statutory and other bodies. 
These are summarised as:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>the Spoil Disposal Area has been relocated slightly in order to maintain
badger foraging routes and has been increased in size to accommodate the
additional spoil that would arise from the adoption of the Variant Case. In
addition, following review, the soil storage mounds associated with the Spoil
Disposal Area have been moved to provide improved noise protection to the nearby
buildings of Newton Manor and Saddlebank.  These changes result in an increased
land take requirement of about 3.2 hectares to the Surface Site area, whilst
still remaining within the Appeal Site;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>the opportunity was taken to exclude 4 parcels of unused land from the
Surface Site, which account for an area of about 4.6 hectares;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>a proposal to relocate topsoil storage mounds, stripped as part of the
formation of the platforms for the RCF/RCM Boreholes, when the area currently
occupied by that topsoil is needed for the RCF development;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>a correction has been made to the total area of planting.  The figures
quoted in the Planning Application did not take account of the planted areas
which will be removed to accommodate the earthworks required as part of
Restoration; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(v)</TD>
<TD>the land area for the Services Corridors was checked and adjusted from 33.1
hectares to 34 hectares, whilst still remaining within the Appeal Site.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.6 Taking all the changes into account, leads to reduction in the surface
land area requirement within the Appeal Site area from about 74 hectares, as
shown on the  Planning Application, to about 72 hectares.</P>
<P>5.7 <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figures 5.2</A> and
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.3">5.3</A> provide further information about the
land areas that comprise the Appeal Site as a result of the proposed design
changes. </P>
<P><B>Design Changes Arising From Consultations
</B></P>
<P>5.8<B> </B>In addition to those changes already described, a number of
detailed design changes have been made and these are summarised as:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>changes to the route of the surface water drain to Newmill Beck and the
effluent pipeline to the Sellafield Works to follow part of the existing access
road between Boreholes 2 and 5, in order to avoid disturbance of Bluebell Wood.
This was in response to concerns expressed by the Institute of Terrestrial
Ecology;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>a reduction in the size of the surface water drain headwall structure at
Newmill Beck, together with a corresponding reduction in the pipe diameter of
the surface water drain, in response to concerns expressed by the NRA;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>the planting scheme has been revised to take into account the concerns
expressed by MAFF, resulting in a reduction in tree planting area on the soil
storage mounds.  This topic is addressed by Mr Short in his evidence;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>adoption of a pressure system for the effluent pipeline, removing the need
for a pumping station and manholes along its route, although some air valves and
washout chambers will be required instead; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(v)</TD>
<TD>the adoption of grouting instead of ground freezing as the preferred form
of ground treatment to control groundwater inflow during shaft construction. 
This is based upon current geological and hydrogeological information.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.9 A number of changes in timing have also been adopted in the RCF
Programme and these are described in Section 14 of this evidence.</P>
<P><A NAME="LandUse"></A><B>6. LAND USE</B></P>
<P><B>Surface Site</B></P>
<P>6.1 The Surface Site, shown in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A>,
is approximately 38 hectares and is centred on Longlands Farm which is currently
the site of borehole development associated with the RCF. </P>
<P>6.2 Within the Surface Site,  about 10 hectares of land will be developed
for the RCF, comprising the Access Road, the Platform Site, earthworks, soil
storage areas, site roads and Longlands Farm Buildings.   A further 7 hectares
on the west side of the Surface Site will be used as the Spoil Disposal Area for
spoil from the underground development.  If the Variant Case was adopted, there
would be a proportional increase in the size of the Spoil Disposal Area to about
8 hectares in order to accommodate the increased volume of spoil arising.</P>
<P>6.3 The existing Borehole RCF2 platform, about 1 hectare, will be used
during the construction period to support the RCF development and will provide
parking facilities throughout the life of the RCF for the workforce and
visitors.  For those visiting the Longlands Farm visitors centre, separate
parking will be provided adjacent to the farm. Woodland planting areas
associated with the RCF/RCM/ PRZ Borehole sites will remain.
</P>
<P>6.4 A total of 4.85 hectares of new woodland will be planted on the Surface
Site as part of the landscape proposals.  Of this, 2.46 hectares will be lost
during the earthworks operation as part of Restoration.  However, the loss will
compensated by an additional 2.21 hectares of new woodland, planted as part of
Restoration, to give a final total new woodland area of 4.6 hectares.  Landscape
proposals are addressed by Mrs Wilson in her evidence.</P>
<P><B>Platform Site</B></P>
<P>6.5 The 4 hectare Platform Site will be developed from the existing 1.3
hectare platform for Boreholes RCF3 and RCF4 and is the engineered, levelled
surface created for the proposed shaft entrances, the headgear, winder houses
and related structures such as offices, workshops and stores [COR/101]<SUP>4</SUP>.
 The Platform Site layout is shown in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure
6.2</A>.</P>
<P><B>Environmental Considerations
</B></P>
<P>6.6  The Surface Site for the RCF development at Longlands Farm: </P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>does not affect ecologically sensitive areas. This is addressed by Dr
Bayfield in his evidence;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>minimises the number of trees and hedgerows lost in order to reduce visual
intrusion and for the preservation of habitats.  This is addressed by Mrs Wilson
in her evidence;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>achieves a cut and fill balance with the topography of the Platform Site,
thereby avoiding the need to import fill material and thus reducing off-site
traffic, noise and dust; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>places the Platform Site as far away as reasonably practicable from
inhabited buildings and from the A595(T)</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Services Corridors</B></P>
<P>6.7 The Services Corridors, occupying approximately 34 hectares, are the
surface areas within which the service connections to the RCF for electrical
power supply,  treated foul water, underground water and other minor arisings,
surface water drainage and possibly telecommunications links (within Services
Corridor B), will be constructed.  The corridors extend approximately 2 km
westwards from the Platform Site to the Sellafield Works across agricultural
land as indicated in Figure 6.3 [COR/101]<SUP>5</SUP>.</P>
<P>6.8 The actual area occupied by the services within the Service Corridors
will be considerably less than the 34 hectares identified. Once the installation
of the services is complete, early in the programme, the land will be returned
to agricultural pasture. </P>
<P><A NAME="PlatformSite"></A><B>7. PLATFORM SITE LEVEL </B></P>
<P>7.1 The design adopted for the earthworks layout is dictated by the location
of the shafts and the topography of the area around the shafts. A steep-sided
valley runs in a general north-south direction approximately 70 metres to the
south-west of the shaft locations.  The level of the valley bottom in this area
is approximately 70 metres aOD [COR/101]<SUP>6</SUP>.</P>
<P>7.2 The proximity of this valley provides the opportunity to design the
Platform Site by balancing the volume of cut material around the shafts with the
volume of fill material which will be required to raise the valley bottom to the
same level as the cut platform. In this way, the required Platform Site area of
approximately 4 hectares can be created at any level between 80 metres and 84.5
metres aOD. Levels outside this range do not achieve a balance of cut and fill,
necessitating either the import of fill material or the off-site disposal of cut
material [COR/101]<SUP>7</SUP>. </P>
<P>7.3 A Platform Site level of 80 metres aOD was proposed in the RCF
Consultative document [COR/504]<SUP>8</SUP>.  This was reviewed in 1993 and,
following consultations with Cumbria County Council, the 84.5 metres aOD
Platform Site level was selected instead, for the following reasons [COR/101]<SUP>9</SUP>:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>it relates better to the natural topography, the field pattern and the
existing buildings at Longlands Farm, than the previous proposal.  In
particular, the 84.5 metres aOD Platform Site level will enable the existing
valley to the south-west of the Platform Site to remain largely intact and
retains the majority of the mature trees in the area.  The final restoration
scheme will also be achieved in a shorter period of time as less earth moving is
required; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>adoption of the 84.5 metres aOD Platform Site level reduces the volume of
material to be excavated and placed as part of the cut/fill operation to  form
the Platform Site.  This, in turn, shortens the period of earthworks operations
by an estimated 11 weeks compared to forming the Platform Site at the 80 metres
aOD level.  Since the earthworks operations will generate noise and dust
emissions from heavy vehicle movements, the shorter programme time and reduced
volume of material to be excavated and placed to form the 84.5 metres aOD
Platform Site level will lead to a reduction in these emissions; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>7.4 The environmental benefits of forming the Platform Site at the 84.5
metres aOD level outweigh any resulting increase in visual intrusion.  This has
been accepted by Cumbria County Council (refer to correspondence in Appendix
A1). The visual effects of the development are addressed by Mrs Wilson in her
evidence. </P>
<P><A NAME="SiteAccess"></A><B>8. SITE ACCESS</B></P>
<P><B>Access Road</B></P>
<P>8.1 The Access Road to the Surface Site will commence at the existing new
junction with the A595(T) and will initially follow the existing Longlands Farm
access road in a south-westerly direction, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure8.1">Figure 8.1</A>. There  will be a lay-by on the
left hand side for vehicles to pull into prior to entering the Surface Site. 
</P>
<P>8.2  A gatehouse will be located in the centre of the road to control
vehicle movements on to and off the Surface Site.  Beyond this, there will be a
lay-by on the right hand side for vehicles to pull into prior to leaving the
site. </P>
<P><B> Internal Road Network</B></P>
<P>8.3 The Access Road will form the spine to which all the other internal
roads will connect in order to provide access to all areas of the Surface Site
and the eastern end of the Services Corridors. </P>
<P>8.4 The internal road system is designed to segregate cars and light goods
vehicles (LGVs) from heavy goods vehicles (HGVs) and dump trucks removing spoil
to the Spoil Disposal Area.  The road layout will also provide access to all
areas of the Platform Site for emergency vehicles.</P>
<P>8.5 The roads that will connect to the Access Road are as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>the access (east of the gatehouse) to Longlands Farm Buildings;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>the access to Borehole RCF2  platform for the car park and borehole
monitoring</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>the Platform Site roads;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>the access to Borehole RCF1, via the Platform Site roads, for borehole
monitoring;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(v)</TD>
<TD>Explosives Store access road; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(vi)</TD>
<TD>the Spoil Disposal Area access road.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Long-Term Farm Access</B></P>
<P>8.6 At Restoration, all the Platform Site and access roads will be removed,
with the exception of the initial 200 metres of the Access Road from the A595(T)
that connects with the access road to the Longlands Farm Buildings.  This will
remain to provide long term access from the A595(T) to these buildings.</P>
<P><B>On-Site Traffic</B></P>
<P>8.7 The majority of cars and LGVs on-site will arise from the movement of
the labour force to and from work.  The  main parking areas for these and
visitors' vehicles will be on the Borehole RCF2 platform (236 spaces) with a
limited area on the Platform Site adjacent to the office block (64 spaces). 
There will also be 24 parking spaces outside Longlands Farm Buildings for the
visitor centre.</P>
<P>8.8 The number of available parking spaces on the Borehole RCF2 platform
reduces during scientific monitoring periods when space for access and working
must be allowed.
</P>
<P>8.9 Peak periods for the combined effects of heavy vehicles and construction
and operational vehicles will occur during Site Establishment when the Platform
Site will be formed and also during Restoration. HGVs will enter and move around
within the Surface Site and Services Corridors, delivering items of plant,
machinery and construction materials, as and when required [COR/101]<SUP>10</SUP>.</P>
<P>8.10 Construction and operational vehicles will comprise earth moving and
compaction plant, dump trucks, concrete trucks, mobile cranes, etc.  These will
carry out the bulk earthworks operations and subsequent construction of surface
buildings and infrastructure. The earthmoving plant and associated dump trucks
will continue to operate after Site Establishment and throughout the
construction period, disposing of spoil in the Spoil Disposal Area.</P>
<P>8.11 Once the Surface Site infrastructure is complete, the numbers of
operational plant and HGVs will be considerably less. These vehicles will be
segregated from the majority of light vehicles and will  move freely around the
internal road system and hardstanding areas [COR/101]<SUP>11</SUP>.</P>
<P><B>Off-Site Traffic</B></P>
<P>8.12 The traffic generated by the RCF development will vary according to the
construction activities at any one time.  Traffic effects are addressed by Mr
Purcell in his evidence.</P>
<P><A NAME="Earthworks"></A><B>9. EARTHWORKS</B></P>
<P><B>Topsoil and Subsoil</B></P>
<P>9.1 Initially, approximately 16,000 m<SUP>3</SUP> of topsoil will be
stripped from an area of about 5 hectares, comprising the Access Road, site
roads and extension to the Platform Site.  The topsoil will be moved to the east
side of the Platform Site where it will be stored for eventual re-use, as
indicated in Figure 6.2 [COR/101]<SUP>12</SUP>.</P>
<P>9.2 Topsoil previously stripped and stored as part of the formation of the
RCF/RCM Borehole platforms will be relocated to the east side of the Platform
Site when the area currently occupied by that topsoil is needed for the RCF
development.</P>
<P>9.3 Subsoil will be stripped and placed on the fill embankment of the
Platform Site to support tree planting.</P>
<P>9.4 All soils will be stored for eventual re-use and during storage will
provide visual and noise screening for the RCF.</P>
<P><B>Platform Site</B></P>
<P>9.5 The Platform Site will be formed by extending Boreholes RCF3 and RCF4
platform, cutting into the side of the valley and the Borehole RCF2 platform to
the north and extending into the valley along the south-western boundary
[COR/101]<SUP>12</SUP>.</P>
<P>9.6 Excavated material, including that previously stockpiled from the
excavation of the RCF/RCM Borehole platforms, will be placed within the valley
to create an embankment retaining the Platform Site.  The cut and fill slopes
will be formed at stable angles and sown and planted to blend in with the
surrounding landscape.  A cut/fill line is indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure9.1">Figure 9.1</A>.</P>
<P>9.7 The majority of the rock will be excavated using a ripper and hydraulic
breaker, although it may be necessary to use low intensity blasting as well. 
</P>
<P>9.8 The excavated volume of cut material, including material from existing
stockpiles, comprising boulder clay and varied states of weathered sandstone, is
estimated to be about 86,000 m<SUP>3</SUP>. This will bulk upon excavation and,
together with the volume of material excavated for the structures on the
Platform Site, will be equivalent to about 103,000 m<SUP>3
</SUP>of fill when re-compacted.</P>
<P><A NAME="Drainage"></A><B>10. DRAINAGE</B></P>
<P><B>Pre-Earthworks Drainage</B></P>
<P>10.1 Cut-off and subsoil drainage will be installed around the perimeter of
the Platform Site, at the crest of the cut slope and the toe of the embankment
during the early stages of the earthworks to allow existing surface and
sub-surface flows from the catchment area to be effectively controlled and
diverted.  The design capacity of this system is 100 litres per second (l/s)
[COR/101]<SUP>13</SUP>.</P>
<P>10.2 Existing soakaways not disturbed by the earthworks, which are protected
by oil interceptors and which were installed for the RCF/RCM Borehole platforms
will continue to be used to drain local areas of the Surface Site.</P>
<P>10.3 An intermittently flowing rill runs through the Surface Site in a
north-south direction and enters the southern tributary of Newmill Beck. Flows
from its catchment area will be catered for by the provision of a drain and
drainage blanket under the fill on the line of the rill with a design capacity
of 121 l/s [COR/101]<SUP>14</SUP>.</P>
<P>10.4 Surface water run-off from the embankment, forming the south-western
boundary of the Platform Site, will be contained and collected by a herringbone
system of french drains [COR/101]<SUP>15</SUP>.</P>
<P>10.5 The cut-off drainage will flow by gravity to an area south of the
Platform Site outside the limit of earthworks and on the line of the existing
rill.  In accordance with advice from the NRA, a lined settlement pond
incorporating an oil interceptor, a scum board and other associated structures
will be constructed at this point downstream of the Platform Site to protect the
watercourse from contamination. Discharge from the settlement pond to the
existing rill will be via a spillway [COR/101]<SUP>16</SUP>.</P>
<P>10.6 <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure10.1">Figure 10.1</A> provides further
information about the pre-earthworks drainage.</P>
<P>10.7 Upon completion of the earthworks and establishment of landscaping, the
oil interception structure and settlement pond may be removed, subject to
approval by the NRA, and the land reinstated to a condition suitable for
agricultural use [COR/101]<SUP>17</SUP>.</P>
<P><B>Surface Water (Completed Site)</B></P>
<P>10.8 The surface water run-off from the completed Platform Site and Access
Road will be collected, via grease trap gullies and oil interceptor chambers and
will discharge into a concrete drainage channel, installed around the perimeter
of the Platform Site, as indicated in Figure 6.2 [COR/101]<SUP>18</SUP>.  </P>
<P>10.9 The channel will connect into a multi-bay settlement tank and from
there the surface water will discharge to Newmill Beck, via the surface water
drain,  approximately 1.2 km long.  The route of the drain, shown in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>, will follow part of the route
of the effluent pipeline carrying treated foul water, underground water and
other minor arisings to the Sellafield Works along Services Corridor B.</P>
<P>10.10 Additions to surface water run-off will come from the washing down of
plant and from the use of water bowsers for dust suppression, both of which will
use domestic water. The latter will only be utilised during dry weather and
will, therefore, not contribute to wet weather flows.  Recycling of water will
be employed where practicable.</P>
<P>10.11 Sampling of the surface water will be carried out and the water will
only be discharged to Newmill Beck in accordance with the following discharge
consent criteria [COR/101]<SUP>19</SUP>:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>the rate of discharge to Newmill Beck shall not exceed 600 l/s;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>suspended solids shall not exceed 50mg/l; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>no visible oils or greases.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>10.12 Following discussions with the NRA, the surface water drain headwall
structure at Newmill Beck has been reduced in size to reduce its visual
intrusion. This has also brought about a corresponding reduction in the pipe
diameter of the surface water drain from a maximum of 675mm to 300mm. 
</P>
<P>10.13 Following closure of the RCF, the Surface Site will be restored to a
condition suitable for agricultural use.  Surface water will then be directed to
the rill flowing into the southern tributary of Newmill Beck via field drains.
</P>
<P><B>Foul Water</B></P>
<P>10.14 During the initial part of Site Establishment, foul water will arise
from the portable toilet and washing facilities provided by the contractor.  It
will be stored in appropriately designed tanks, prior to disposal  off-site by
tanker at an approved disposal point.</P>
<P>10.15 Foul water will be generated from offices, workshops, winder houses,
gatehouse and from portable facilities installed underground.</P>
<P>Disposal Options</P>
<P>10.16 Following discussion with officers of North West Water plc, the option
of discharging untreated foul water from the development, by means of a pumping
main and gravity sewer to Gosforth Sewage Treatment Works, was considered
undesirable for the following reasons:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>there would be insufficient capacity at the existing works to cater  for
the  flows without major extension; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>the existing works could not receive other aqueous emissions from the
development, such as groundwater, and therefore another separate site outfall in
Services Corridor B  would have been required.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>10.17 Foul water will be collected within the foul drainage system and will
gravitate at approved falls to the inflow control chamber of an on-site sewage
treatment plant.   The plant will be designed to meet the following discharge
consent criteria [COR/101]<SUP>20</SUP>:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>Biochemical Oxygen Demand (BOD) (5 days) shall not exceed  30mg/l;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>suspended solids shall not exceed 45 mg/l; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>the rate of discharge shall not exceed 9 l/s. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">10.18 The treated foul water from the sewage
treatment plant, together with settled underground water and other minor
arisings such as cement washings, will discharge into the effluent pipeline, 3.5
km long, which will connect to the Calder Interceptor Sewer within the
Sellafield Works and then discharge into the sea [COR/101]<SUP>21</SUP>.
</FONT>
</P>
<P><B>Surface Discharge of Water from Underground</B></P>
<P>10.19 During construction and operation of the RCF, water will arise from:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>inflow of groundwater into the excavations; and  </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>drill flushing, dust suppression and cleaning (process water).</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>10.20 The volumes of groundwater arising are expected to be variable, being
dependent upon the nature of the strata through which the shafts and galleries
are constructed.  Inflows will be controlled by in-shaft pumping and grouting 
of certain zones ahead of the shaft excavation.   </P>
<P>10.21 During construction, there is the potential for water pumped from
underground  to  include suspended solids and traces of oil.  These contaminants
will be controlled by surface settlement ponds and oil interceptors before
disposal.  </P>
<P>10.22 The effluent pipeline will not be commissioned in time to handle water
pumped from underground during the construction of the South Shaft foreshaft. 
Therefore, the water will be disposed of by tanker off-site at an approved
disposal point.   </P>
<P>10.23 Water pumped from underground from all subsequent construction and
operational phases will be disposed of via the effluent pipeline to the Calder
Interceptor Sewer. </P>
<P><A NAME="Services"></A><B>11. SERVICES</B></P>
<P><B>Electrical Power</B></P>
<P>11.1 Electrical power will be required on the Surface Site from the
beginning of Site Establishment.  There will be a continuing demand for
electricity for the duration of the development to provide power for the shaft
winders, the ventilation equipment and all general activities, including
heating, lighting and transport on the surface and underground.</P>
<P>11.2 It is important that interruptions to the electrical supply to the
shaft winders are minimised  in order to facilitate access and egress from the
RCF at all times. The secure supply must also be available to all safety-related
equipment. This will be achieved by the use of duplicate incoming electrical
supplies. There are two  options for the supply of electrical power to the RCF
both of which will be duplicate [COR/101]<SUP>22</SUP>:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>Option 1 - 11 kV Supply from the BNFL Sellafield Distribution  System.<BR><BR>This
would involve laying two power cables in trenches or on overhead lines between
the BNFL Sellafield distribution system and the RCF.  A possible cable route
would be approximately 3.4 km long and is indicated within Services Corridor A
in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>Option 2 - 33 kV Supply from the Grid<BR><BR>It is not possible at
present to identify the route of the duplicate supplies from the Grid to the
Surface Site.  One supply could be via a short connection to the existing 33 kV
overhead power supply line passing the south-east corner of the Surface Site, as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>. Both supplies will
be stepped down by two 33 kV to 11 kV transformers and associated switching
equipment, installed on the Platform Site</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>11.3 During the early construction stages, should either of these electrical
power supplies not be available, temporary generators would be used, together
with the provision of a limited capacity temporary electrical supply [COR/101]<SUP>23</SUP>.
</P>
<P><B>Domestic Water</B></P>
<P>11.4 Domestic water will be required for the following operations:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>drinking water and sanitation;
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>concrete and grout mixing;
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>ashing down of plant; </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iv)</TD>
<TD>surface dust suppression; </TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(v)</TD>
<TD>wheel washing;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(vi)</TD>
<TD>fire fighting use;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(vii)</TD>
<TD>flushing of underground drills;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(viii)</TD>
<TD>underground dust suppression; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(ix)</TD>
<TD>watering of planted and other landscaped areas.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>11.5 The water supply will be connected into the existing public water mains
along the A595(T). North West Water plc. will determine the optimum means of
connection.
</P>
<P>11.6 The maximum water supply requirement on the Surface Site has been
estimated at about 200 m<SUP>3</SUP>/day.  This excludes water required for
surface dust suppression and wheel washing, which can be met largely from water
recycled from the surface water settlement tanks.</P>
<P>11.7 The water supply to the Surface Site will be adequate to meet fire
fighting requirements.  Additional water will also be available for fire
fighting purposes from the water tank situated on the Platform Site.</P>
<P>11.8 The supply will be fitted with a meter to enable water usage to be
monitored.</P>
<P><B>Surface Lighting</B></P>
<P>11.9 The lighting of the surface works will be considered in three different
sub-sections [COR/101]<SUP>24</SUP>:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>Security Lighting;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>Temporary Lighting; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>Operational Lighting.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Security Lighting</P>
<P>11.10 The perimeter fence will be illuminated by high pressure sodium vapour
lights fitted on up to 6 metre high columns set at 30 metre intervals.  Light
spillage will be kept at a low level, due to the low mounting height and low
power of the lights, whilst maintaining an adequate illumination level. Typical
levels of illumination will be between 5 lux and 20 lux [COR/101]<SUP>25</SUP>.</P>
<P>11.11 At the gatehouse on the Access Road, illumination levels of up to 150
lux will be required [COR/101]<SUP>26</SUP>.
</P>
<P>Temporary Lighting</P>
<P>11.12 For safety reasons, high overall levels of illumination are necessary
during the initial construction period, with typical levels of illumination
between 100 lux and 300 lux.  This is a temporary situation with a duration of
about 15 months.</P>
<P>11.13 The amount of light spillage will be kept low by ensuring that the
number of high level light sources is kept to a minimum and greater use is made,
where practicable, of lower mounting heights and an increased number of fittings
[COR/101]<SUP>27</SUP>.</P>
<P>Operational Lighting</P>
<P>11.14 For operational lighting, the levels of illumination will be between
20 lux and 50 lux and will be much lower than for the temporary installation
[COR/101]<SUP>28</SUP>.
</P>
<P>11.15 The main design aim will be to provide satisfactory illumination with
low levels of glare where there are moving vehicles or pedestrians. Maximum use
will be made of<B> </B>high pressure sodium vapour, flat glass type luminaires,
which provide full cut-off distribution of light. Care will be taken to ensure
that the lamp support and plan arrangement are such that economy of operation
and maintenance is kept to acceptable levels whilst still ensuring minimal light
spillage into the surrounding area [COR/101]<SUP>29</SUP>.</P>
<P>11.16 During operation, lighting will be maintained at the lowest
practicable illumination level consistent with the safety and security of
personnel using or visiting the RCF.</P>
<P><A NAME="SurfaceStructures"></A><B>12. SURFACE STRUCTURES</B></P>
<P><B>General</B></P>
<P>12.1 The structures to be built on the Platform Site are shown in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A> and will comprise buildings
directly associated with the underground construction and operation. These will
comprise construction headgear, operational headgear, shaft top buildings
(heapsteads), winder houses, fan house, spoil conveyor and  enclosed hopper to
retain excavated spoil, prior to transfer to the Spoil Disposal Area by dump
trucks.</P>
<P>12.2 In addition, major service buildings will include an office block and a
workshop and stores. A series of smaller structures will include electrical
substations, weighbridge, wheelwash, gatehouse and a water tank for underground
process water and fire fighting.</P>
<P>12.3 An explosives store (one store for explosives and one for detonators,
but licensed as a single Division E store) will be located to the north-west of
the Platform Site. </P>
<P>12.4 A concrete batching plant will be in operation during most of the
construction period.</P>
<P>12.5 The colour of the buildings will be dealt with through planning
conditions, by agreement with the Planning Authority. </P>
<P><B>Headgear</B></P>
<P>Construction Headgear</P>
<P>12.6 The construction headgear will be supplied by the shaft sinking
contractor. Their height will vary depending on which contractor is appointed
since it is a function of the contractor's method of working.  Typically, a
construction headgear would be of the order of  25 metres to 30 metres in height
and is illustrated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.1">Figure 12.1</A>.</P>
<P>Operational Headgear</P>
<P>12.7 The operational headgear will be 29.2 metres overall in height and will
be the tallest operational structures on the site.  This figure is derived by
taking safety and operational requirements into account. It meets the statutory
requirements to cater for accidental overwinds, and the necessary detaching
mechanism and cage retaining catches that would operate in the event of an
overwound conveyance.  The arrangement also provides for clearances for
personnel access to various parts of the headgear structure for routine
maintenance and adjustment. There is the means to sling large or long materials
and equipment from the underside of the cage, known as the slinging allowance. 
This feature of the headgear arrangement  permits plant or equipment which will
not fit into the shaft conveyance to be taken underground, for example the
traction unit of an underground spoil loader. </P>
<P><B>Description of Surface Structures</B></P>
<P>North Shaft Heapstead Building</P>
<P>12.8 The North Shaft heapstead building will be a steel framed structure, 12
metres high, clad in proprietary plastic coated profiled metal sheet.  Its
overall plan dimensions are 50 metres by 13 metres approximately, which would
include the plan dimensions of the North Shaft operational headgear.
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.2">Figure 12.2</A> gives typical details. The
foundations will be reinforced concrete pad or raft foundations.  </P>
<P>12.9 Within the North Shaft heapstead building, there will be the materials
handling equipment (mine car systems) for the transfer of the excavated spoil
from the galleries to the spoil disposal conveyor system. There will also be
safety equipment associated with controlling shaft conveyances during loading
and unloading operations.</P>
<P>North Shaft Operational Headgear
</P>
<P>12.10 The North Shaft operational headgear will be a steel framed structure,
which will be 29.2 metres high and will be clad in a proprietary plastic coated
profiled metal sheet. Overall plan dimensions for the structure are 12 metres by
8 metres approximately.</P>
<P>North Shaft Spoil Disposal Conveyor
</P>
<P>12.11 The North Shaft spoil disposal conveyor structure forms part of the
North Shaft heapstead building and houses the conveyor systems for moving the
underground spoil from the shaft top to the storage hopper.  The conveyor will
be a steel framed structure, clad in proprietary plastic coated profiled metal
sheet, and will be supported on conveyor trestles and reinforced concrete
foundations. However, where the conveyor system leaves the North Shaft heapstead
building, the conveyor system will run in a reinforced concrete box structure
until the conveyor rises above ground level. The conveyor will discharge the
spoil into a storage hopper, for subsequent loading into dump trucks and
transportation to the Spoil Disposal Area.</P>
<P>South Shaft Heapstead Building</P>
<P>12.12 The South Shaft heapstead building will be a brick clad steel framed,
or brickwork, structure with a screeded concrete roof decking, finished with an
asphalt surface, as indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.3">Figure 12.3</A>.
 Its overall plan dimensions are 39 metres by 9 metres approximately, which
would include the plan dimensions of the South Shaft operational headgear,
whilst its height will be about 10 metres. Foundations will be reinforced
concrete pad or raft foundations.</P>
<P>12.13 Within the South Shaft heapstead building, there will be mechanical
and electrical equipment for signalling and communication associated with the
loading and unloading of the shaft conveyances.</P>
<P>South Shaft Operational Headgear
</P>
<P>12.14 The South Shaft operational headgear will be a steel framed structure,
29.2 metres high, clad in a proprietary plastic coated profiled metal sheet.</P>
<P>Fan House</P>
<P>12.15 The fan house will consist of brick walls with a steel and concrete
frame, and shall have a screeded precast concrete roof with asphalt finish, as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.4">Figure 12.4</A>. The building
will be constructed adjacent to the South Shaft, and will incorporate fan
equipment and ducting. 
</P>
<P>12.16 Winder Houses</P>
<P> The North Shaft and South Shaft winder houses will be constructed from
steel portal frames and will be clad in proprietary plastic coated profiled
metal sheet.  The plan dimensions are approximately 21 metres by 21 metres and
the height is approximately 10.5 metres, as illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.5">Figure 12.5</A>.</P>
<P>12.17 The winders and associated gearboxes and motors will be located on a
reinforced concrete ground floor slab with supporting foundations in reinforced
concrete set below ground level.</P>
<P>Office Block</P>
<P>12.18 The office block will be a 2 storey prefabricated building utilising
modular construction, which will have a tank room located on the roof.  The
overall plan dimensions are 39 metres by 24 metres approximately, and the
maximum height of the building is 10.5 metres, as illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.6">Figure 12.6</A>.
</P>
<P>12.19 The ground floor of the office block will house the changing
facilities, laboratories, mess room, maintenance and records room, switchroom,
control room, medical room, rescue room and reception area. The first floor will
be occupied by offices, meetings and conference rooms, telemetry room and staff
mess room.</P>
<P>Workshop and Stores</P>
<P>12.20 The workshop and stores will be a steel framed structure clad in
proprietary plastic coated profiled metal sheet, having overall approximate plan
dimensions of 57 metres by 17 metres and a height of about 8 metres, as
indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.7">Figure 12.7</A>.  The building
will be divided into distinct areas; plant repair workshop, welding shop,
mechanical workshop, electrical workshop and stores.  Above the workshop areas
there will be an overhead gantry crane to facilitate the lifting and moving of
equipment and plant. The stores area will be subdivided to provide pallet
storage on the ground floor, for heavy items, but will have a mezzanine floor
for storage of lighter items.  An area will be provided on the ground floor for
the storage of oil.</P>
<P>Weighbridge and Wheelwash</P>
<P>12.21 A wheelwash will be located at the exit from the Spoil Disposal Area
with a second wheelwash on the Platform Site operating for the duration of the
earthworks activities.  A weighbridge will be located on the Platform Site.</P>
<P>Longlands Farm Buildings </P>
<P>12.22 The Longlands Farm Buildings will be converted for use partly as a
reception area, for specialist visitors such as scientists and engineers and for
agreed parties of the general public, and partly as offices. No reception
facilities for the general public will be provided at the Surface Site [COR/101]<SUP>30</SUP>.
</P>
<P>12.23 This change of use, which is the subject of a planning permission
granted on October 13 1994 (Ref No. 4/94/0617/0) by Copeland Borough Council,
will involve the refurbishment of the interior, but no major internal changes
will be made.  No changes to the external structure of the buildings will be
made, other than for general repair and maintenance. A path will be constructed
across the land to the south-west of the farm to an informal viewing area,
overlooking the Platform Site.  The planning permission includes for the
provision of 24 parking spaces for visitors.  A copy of the planning permission
is included in Appendix A2.</P>
<P><A NAME="Spoil"></A><B>13. SPOIL</B></P>
<P>Spoil Handling During Phase 1 Construction
</P>
<P>13.1 Within each construction headgear, there will be a kibble tipping chute
to discharge rock spoil excavated from underground to a stockpile beside the
headgear.  The spoil will be loaded into dump trucks and taken to the Spoil
Disposal Area.</P>
<P>Spoil Handling System During Phase 2 and Phase 3 Construction </P>
<P>13.2 During Phase 2 Construction and Phase 3 Construction, spoil will be
brought to the surface through the North Shaft in rail mounted vehicles which
will emptied by a tippler.  The tippler will discharge the spoil from the
vehicles on to a conveyor feeding a 150 tonne capacity hopper, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure12.2">Figure 12.2</A>, for loading lorries and dump
trucks.</P>
<P>13.3 Wherever practicable, the hopper, mineral transfer and conveying
facilities will be enclosed to control the spread of dust.  Noise emissions will
also be reduced from these facilities due to their enclosure, and the use of
rubber lined chutes and minimised fall heights for the loading of lorries and
dump trucks.</P>
<P>Spoil Disposal Area </P>
<P>13.4 Spoil excavated during construction of the RCF, amounting to a bulked
volume of about 140,000 m<SUP>3</SUP> from the shafts and galleries for the
Central Case, will be taken to the Spoil Disposal Area.</P>
<P>13.5 Over its life of approximately 6&#189; years, the Spoil Disposal Area
will be worked in transverse areas.  Prior to spoil emplacement in the first
area, topsoil from the first and second areas together with subsoil from the
first area will be formed into noise mitigation bunds along the south-west side.
</P>
<P>13.6 The spoil will be spread to a maximum depth of 4 metres and will be
blended into the original ground contours around its periphery, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</P>
<P>13.7 The Spoil Disposal Area will, as it is formed, be restored
progressively to agricultural pasture, using the topsoil and subsoil recovered
from the existing field. On completion of spoil disposal, the topsoil and
subsoil in the noise mitigation bunds will be spread over the spoil placed in
the final two areas.</P>
<P>13.8 For the Variant Case, the volume of spoil will amount to a bulked
figure of about 160,000 m<SUP>3</SUP>.  In order to restrict the maximum depth
of spoil to 4 metres, the area over which the spoil would be placed increases
from about 7 hectares (Central Case) to about 8 hectares, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</P>
<P>Testing of BVG Bulk Sample </P>
<P>13.9 A bulk sample of BVG (Borrowdale Volcanic Group), up to 15,000 tonnes,
may be removed from site to evaluate its potential use as an aggregate or fill
material [COR/101]<SUP>31</SUP>.  The effects of the generated traffic on the
local road network are addressed by Mr Purcell in his evidence. 
</P>
<P><A NAME="Programme"></A><B>14. PROGRAMME</B></P>
<P><B>Revisions to Programme</B></P>
<P>14.1 Since the submission of the Planning Application and Environmental
Statement, there have been a number of changes to the RCF Programme.  The most
significant change is a revised start date for the RCF project from September
1995 to the date currently assumed for internal Nirex planning purposes of July
1996,   as a consequence of the refusal of the Planning Application.  This
programme change is shown in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure14.1">Figure 14.1</A>.</P>
<P>14.2 Other changes which affect the phasing of activities within the
programme are:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>a change from ground freezing to grouting as the preferred means of
controlling groundwater inflows during shaft construction; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>the construction of the North Shaft is now scheduled to commence 3 months
later than the start of the South Shaft construction.  </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>14.3 The decision to adopt grouting instead of ground freezing as the
preferred method of ground treatment during shaft construction means that
construction of the South Shaft and North Shaft collars and foreshafts can start
earlier in the programme (previously, the collar and foreshaft construction
could not commence until the drilling and furnishing of the freeze holes had
been completed). </P>
<P>14.4 An earlier start to shaft construction in the programme means that some
surface activities will also start earlier in the programme than originally
planned.  These include the commissioning of the foul and surface water drainage
systems, the provision of the water supply and water tank, the erection and
commissioning of the concrete batching plant, and the installation of the
wheelwash and weighbridge.  The construction of the South Shaft and North Shaft
winder houses and their foundations have also been brought forward.</P>
<P>14.5 Other elements such as the heapsteads and operational headgear remain
programmed to occur after construction of the shafts and are broadly within the
same relative stage as in the Planning Application programme.</P>
<P>14.6 The effect of the changes is to increase the overall RCF construction
period by about 3 months, from 6&#189; years (given in the Environmental
Statement) to 6&#190; years for the Central Case. </P>
<P><B>Phasing of Surface Works</B></P>
<P>14.7 Construction will initially concentrate on the topsoil strip and cut
and fill earthworks operations to form the Platform Site.  As part of the
Platform Site formation, pre-earthworks drainage, the cut-off drain and
settlement pond will be installed to control surface and sub-surface flows.  The
Platform Site earthworks will not be complete when the shaft sinking contractor
is mobilised. Hence, initial activities such as the construction and
commissioning of the concrete batching plant and the tower crane for the shafts,
which will be undertaken by the shaft sinking contractor, will run concurrently
with Site Establishment.</P>
<P>14.8 The Access Road will be constructed concurrently with the development
of the Platform Site.  The existing access road to the RCF/RCM Boreholes will be
maintained to provide access to the Platform Site until the Access Road is made
available to the shaft sinking contractor.  This will ensure that the shaft
sinking contractor is guaranteed access at all times.  Once the Access Road is
open the existing road will be removed and the area returned to grassland.</P>
<P>14.9 In addition to the construction of the Platform Site and Access Road,
the shaft sinking contractor will require a number of essential services to be
installed prior to construction of the South Shaft foreshaft.  To enable
foreshaft construction to commence at the earliest practicable opportunity, some
of these will be provided on a temporary basis until the permanent facilities
can be commissioned.</P>
<P>14.10 The permanent electrical power supply will not be available for
foreshaft construction and so electricity demand will be met in part by the
provision of a limited capacity temporary electrical supply with the remainder
being satisfied by on-site generators.  Substation foundations, cable ducting
and drawpits will be installed during the construction of the Platform Site to
ensure minimal disruption to the installation of the substations and cabling.</P>
<P>14.11 A piped water supply will be installed alongside the Access Road
during its construction.  The water supply and the water storage tank on the
Platform Site will be in place at the start of construction of the foreshaft to
supply process water for underground drilling and for use in the concrete
batching plant.</P>
<P>14.12 The foul and surface water infrastructure will be partially in place
but will not be commissioned until after foreshaft construction has commenced. 
The Platform Site drainage and concrete drainage channel will be in place at the
start of foreshaft construction but the effluent pipeline, surface water drain,
sewage treatment plant and settlement tank will not be completed.  Until these
are made available the foul water will be tankered off the site to an approved
disposal point and the surface water will either be discharged into the
settlement pond or the existing RCF/RCM Boreholes site drainage system.</P>
<P>14.13 Construction of the surface structures will initially concentrate on
the winder houses and their foundations.  Other surface structures such as the
office block, the workshop and stores, and the gatehouse are not in close
proximity to the foreshafts and will be constructed after foreshaft construction
has commenced.  The exception to this is the explosives store which will be
installed prior to commencement of the foreshafts.  </P>
<P>14.14 There are also a number of the surface structures that will not be
constructed until after the shafts have been completed namely the operational
headgear, the heapsteads and the fan house.</P>
<P>14.15 Construction of the Access Road to the Spoil Disposal Area will follow
the completion of the main access road and, along with the wheelwash and the
weighbridge, will be commissioned prior to commencement of the foreshaft
construction.  Completion of the other site roads including the internal road
network are less critical and these will follow construction of the Spoil
Disposal Area access road.</P>
<P>14.16 The security of the site will be maintained by utilising the existing
site fencing and extending and adapting this to fit the development of the
Surface Site as construction progresses.</P>
<P><A NAME="Closure"></A><B>15. CLOSURE AND RESTORATION</B></P>
<P>15.1 At any point up to the end of Phase 3, the Science Programme in the RCF
may show that the Sellafield site is unsuitable for a repository. Under these
circumstances, restoration works would commence. </P>
<P>15.2 The objective for the restoration of the RCF is to remove surface
structures and return the site to a condition capable of supporting agricultural
land uses, similar to those existing prior to the development.  It is intended
that, at the end of any appropriate aftercare period, the site could be returned
to normal agricultural use without further monitoring or maintenance.</P>
<P>15.3 The closure and restoration of the RCF will involve three main stages,
as follows [NRX/1/1]<SUP>32</SUP>:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>underground salvage;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>dismantling and demolition of surface buildings; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>restoration of the landscape, soil management and re-vegetation.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Underground Salvage</B></P>
<P>15.4 On completion of the underground construction phases, mobile plant will
be brought to the surface for re-sale, scrap or return to the lessor.  The only
mobile plant then in operation underground will be that required for the Science
Programme; this plant will be removed prior to closure and sealing of the
facility [NRX/1/1]<SUP>33</SUP>.</P>
<P>Fixed Plant and Services</P>
<P>15.5 Fixed plant will comprise rail track, ventilation fans and pumps. 
Underground services will include electrical systems, communications networks
and pipework for water.  Plant and services not required during the Phase 3
Science Programme will be removed for re-sale or scrap, or return to the lessor
[NRX/1/1]<SUP>34</SUP>.</P>
<P>15.6 Following removal of plant and equipment, essential services including
water, electricity, ventilation and communication systems will be down-rated to
the level required in order that final closure operations may be undertaken. 
Removal of plant and equipment is expected to take about 5 months [NRX/1/1]<SUP>34</SUP>.
</P>
<P>Shafts</P>
<P>15.7 Following closure of the RCF, it will be necessary to secure the shafts
to avoid potential hazards [NRX/1/1]<SUP>35</SUP> such as:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="0">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>danger to the public through accidental entry;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" WIDTH="50">(ii)</TD>
<TD>ground subsidence; and</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">(iii)</TD>
<TD>pollution of the groundwater due to unauthorised dumping of waste materials
or other causes.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>15.8 It is anticipated that after removal of shaft furnishings the shafts
will be completely filled, generally in accordance with the National Coal Board
(NCB) guidelines [NRX/1/1] <SUP>36</SUP>, as indicated in
<A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure15.1">Figure 15.1</A>.  </P>
<P>15.9 Prior to backfilling, the shafts and the main gallery entrances will be
sealed with concrete plugs at their junctions with the shaft. This will retain
the fill in the shafts and prevent it from moving into the galleries.  Insets
will not be plugged as they will be filled with granular material during the
shaft filling operation [NRX/1/1]<SUP>37</SUP>.  Final details of the shaft
seals will be established prior to backfilling.</P>
<P>15.10 The material used to backfill the shafts must be clean and inert,
appropriately sized, and must possess sufficient strength to resist crushing and
degradation after placement.  The shafts could be filled with the spoil
excavated during construction but by the time closure and restoration is being
considered, the Spoil Disposal Area will have re-vegetated and will be back in
agricultural use.  Excavation of this restored area to remove, crush and process
the spoil may have unacceptable environmental effects.  </P>
<P>15.11 There are a number of hard rock quarries in Cumbria from where
suitable material could be obtained.  Limestone is frequently used to backfill
coal mine shafts and this is presently available within about 50 km of the
Surface Site.  Assuming locally available rock was used, filling the shafts
would take about 4 to 5 months.</P>
<P>15.12 When the shafts have been filled to their full depth, permanent
reinforced concrete caps will be constructed at rockhead to seal the entries
completely, as indicated in <A HREF="nrx1fig.htm#Figure15.2">Figure 15.2</A>.
The shaft caps will be constructed following the demolition and removal of the
headgear and heapstead buildings. Capping of the shafts is expected to take
about 1 month [NRX/1/1]<SUP>38</SUP>.
</P>
<P>15.13 Since the shafts will be backfilled and capped,  no  ground subsidence
will occur.  </P>
<P><B>Dismantling and Demolition of Surface Buildings</B></P>
<P>15.14 Removal of most of the surface buildings, plant and infrastructure
will only fully begin following closure of the RCF and completion of the
underground salvage operation.
</P>
<P>Removal of Plant</P>
<P>15.15 All plant and machinery, either mobile or fixed will be prepared in
the same way as described for the underground plant [NRX/1/1]<SUP>39</SUP>.</P>
<P>Infrastructure</P>
<P>15.16 Dismantling and demolition of infrastructure and services will be done
largely at the same time as the demolition of the buildings.  However, essential
services will be removed in the later stages of the closure when they are no
longer required [NRX/1/1]<SUP>40</SUP>. </P>
<P>15.17 Longlands Farm will be returned to agricultural use and access from
the A595(T) will be retained via the Access Road and the access road to the
Longlands Farm Buildings.</P>
<P><B>Restoration of the Landscape
</B></P>
<P>15.18 Following removal of the surface buildings and infrastructure, the
Platform Site will be regraded to reflect the original valley form. The new
landscape will be capable of sustaining agricultural use similar to that of the
surrounding area and a range of appropriate wildlife habitats.
</P>
<P>15.19 Approximately 60,000 m<SUP>3</SUP> of material will be re-distributed
to enable the original field structure and the valley area to be re-instated. 
This will consist primarily of removal of the sandstone fill embankment used to
create the Platform Site [NRX/1/1]<SUP>41</SUP>.  It is envisaged that it will
take about 3 months to complete the earthworks.</P>
<P>15.20 The earthworks will necessitate the removal of about 2.46 hectares of
immature planting.  This will be felled and shredded to be utilised as mulch
material for new planting areas within the valley. However, new planting during
Restoration will compensate for the majority of this loss and will provide a
more logical landscape structure, resulting in a net gain of about 4.6 hectares
of new woodland at the end of Restoration. </P>
<P>15.21 Planting and landscape management will be addressed by Mrs Wilson in
her evidence.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>16. CONCLUSIONS  </B></P>
<P>16.1 The proposed surface works described in this evidence are necessary for
the safe and efficient construction and operation of the RCF.</P>
<P>16.2 The facilities are necessary to support the RCF Science Programme. 
</P>
<P>16.3 Of the total land take of 222 hectares, identified as the Appeal Site,
only about 17 to 18 hectares will be developed at the surface and of this, 7 to
8 hectares of the Spoil Disposal Area will be progressively restored and
returned to agriculture use.</P>
<P>16.4 Most of the surface construction  activity will be completed in the
first 12 months.  However, vehicle movements associated with shaft construction
and underground development will continue over a period of about 6<SUP>3</SUP>/<SUB>4
 </SUB>years.</P>
<P>16.5 The restoration proposals aim to reinstate the landscape to reflect the
existing features.  The Platform Site will be regraded to reflect the original
valley form.  At the end of Restoration a total area of 4.6 hectares of new
woodland will remain.   
</P>
