<P><A NAME="Acronyms"></A><B>18. ACRONYMS AND ABBREVIATIONS
</B></P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Aggregate:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Granular material either
processed from natural materials such as rock, gravel or sand, or manufactured,
such as slag.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">aOD</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Above Ordnance Datum.
Ordnance Datum being mean sea level at Newlyn.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Appeal Site:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The terrestrial area
which is the subject of a request for Planning Permission.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Biochemical Oxygen
Demand:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">A measure of the amount
of material present in water which can be readily oxidised by micro organisms. 
A measure of the ability of a material to take up oxygen in water.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">bOD</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Below Ordnance Datum.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Borehole:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The void left by the
action of drilling a hole, usually through rock.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Borrowdale Volcanic
Group:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The name given to a
sequence of rocks of volcanic origin found in the Lake District.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Boulder Clay:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Glacial clay, generally
containing a variety of boulders or pebbles.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Bund</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Low Embankment</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Catchpit/Interceptor
Chamber:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Sump or well below
ground level immediately beneath a tank or tanks that contain liquid, to contain
leakage or spillage.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Cement grout:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">A fluid mixture of water
and cement.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Cladding:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">External vertical or
near-vertical non load bearing covering to a structure.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Conventional shaft
sinking:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">See &quot;conventional
drill and blast&quot; &quot;normal sinking cycle&quot;.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Conventional drill and
blast:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The generic name given
to methods of underground excavation involving the drilling of holes in the rock
to be excavated, the use of explosives in these holes to blast and fragment the
rock and the physical removal of the blasted rock, usually performed as separate
and distinct stages.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Conveyances:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Cages or containers for
the carriage of persons or materials through the shafts.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Cut and fill operation:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Earthworks formed partly
of cutting and partly of embankments.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Drainage blanket:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Drainage layer placed
near the base of an embankment.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Falls:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Difference in level
between a higher and lower point of a slope.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Fan drift:</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="301"><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">An airway leading from a
shaft, or airway, to a fan.</FONT>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Fascia:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Covering board fixed to a rafter-end
wall plate, or wall face at eaves.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Fill:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Material used for the raising the
level of the ground.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Foreshaft:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Initial shaft excavation of
sufficient depth to enable installation of the sinking platform and associated
equipment.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">French Drain;</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Drain formed by excavating a trench
and backfilling it with granular material within which may be laid a porous or
perforated pipe.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Galleries:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Any underground passage driven and
maintained to provide access for haulage or ventilation purposes, or for
personnel to travel.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Graded filter material:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Filter material that consists of
layers of coarse gravel, or sand and fine gravel or sand, so designed that the
fine material will not clog the coarse material.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Ground freezing techniques:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">A method of consolidating
water-bearing strata, to prepare it for shaft sinking, in which a freezing agent
(usually brine) is circulated through suitably disposed Boreholes drilled into
the strata around the site of the shaft.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Grouting:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The process of injecting cement or
other material to improve the strength of strata or to retard or prevent the
passage of liquids or gases.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Headgear:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The structure at the top of a shaft
on which the winding pulley or sheaves are mounted.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Headwall:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Retaining wall at the end of a
culvert or pipe.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Heapstead buildings:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Buildings surrounding the shaft top
and headgear structures.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Hectare (ha):</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">One hectare (2.471 acres) is 10,000
square metres.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Herringbone: </FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">System of laying pipes at
alternative diagonals on a centre pipe run.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Hopper:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Open container the bottom of which
is in the shape of an inverted pyramid or cone, for storing loose material
released through an outlet at the bottom.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Horizon/s:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">A system of (usually horizontal)
galleries at an identified level.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Hydrogeology</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The study of geology pertinent to
the character and movement of ground water.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Infrastructure:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The organisational and material
resources supporting an activity.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Ingress:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The means provided to facilitate
entry to underground.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Interceptor Chamber:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Chamber to prevent the passage of
foul air from a sewer into a drain.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Kibble/s:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Large steel bucket used to remove
debris and to transport men and materials in  shaft sinking, and in special
circumstances to facilitate an examination of a shaft.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Light spillage:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Amount of light falling outside its
designated area.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Luminaires:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Apparatus that distributes, filters
and transforms light.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">MAFF</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries
and Food.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Mulch Material:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Material formed from organic
material.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">NRA:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">National Rivers Authority.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Oil Interceptor:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">One or more chambers arranged to
prevent the ingress of oil to a drain or sewer, then retain the collected oil
for later removal.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Outfall:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Structure through which water is
discharged into a watercourse or body of water.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Potential Repository Zone (PRZ):</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">That section of the BVG currently
considered to be the most likely site for the future repository.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Shaft collar:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The ring of initial foundations
forming the mouth of a shaft.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Spillway:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Structure over which or through
which excess water is discharged from a reservoir or channel.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Spoil:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Waste material, arising from
excavations.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Subsidence:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Downward movement of the ground
surface that results from collapse, removal or displacement of the underlying
material.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Sump:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The part of a shaft below the lowest
winding level.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Substation:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">An area where electrical
transformers and switchgear are situated.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Suspended solids:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Solid material suspended in liquid.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Switchroom:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Room housing electrical switchgear.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Tippler:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">A mechanical arrangement for tipping
mine cars to discharge contents.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Topsoil:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Surface layer of fertile soil.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Water Flush (drilling):</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Introduction of water to the drill
bit to help remove cuttings, reduce production of airborne dust and cool the
bit.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Winder houses:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Buildings containing the machines
which power the conveyances through the shafts.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Winder/s:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Winding engines used to raise or
lower a conveyance in a shaft via a rope.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">Winding:</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Times New Roman">The act of raising or lowering
through a shaft.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P></P>
<P><A NAME="AppendixA1"></A><B><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">APPENDIX A1</FONT></B></P>
<P><FONT FACE="Times New Roman"><B>Letter from Cumbria County Council</B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Nirex Liaison Group - RCF Platform Level</FONT></P>
<P><BR></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="500"><BR>14 September 1993<BR>Your ref<BR> Our
ref:	JGH/MGF/A125/3<BR>Enq to:		JG Hetherington<BR>Direct Line:	     (0539)
814376<BR>Minicom Tel No:				0228 812381			 							</TD>
<TD><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>Planning<BR>County Offices, Kendal,<BR>Cumbria,
LA9 4RQ<BR>Telephone:	(0539) 814203<BR>	Fax:	(0539) 726276 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Mr P Zyda<BR> Solicitor, Director (Cumbria)<BR> UK Nirex Ltd<BR> Cumbria
Directorate<BR> Buttermere Pavilion<BR> Westlakes Science Park<BR> Moor Row<BR>
Cumbria<BR>	CA24 3JZ<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>  Dear Mr Zyda<BR><BR>  	</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>NIREX LIAISON GROUP - RCF PLATFORM LEVEL</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>With the postponement of the NLG Sub Group (on the ES), I thought I should
write setting out further views on the specific issues of the revised RCF
platform level, before matters progress too far.  It was not left clear, nor
have I been informed subsequently, whether the design is proceeding to the
higher level and new orientation.  Perhaps you could confirm the current
intention?<BR><BR> Notwithstanding, my landscape architect has carefully
considered the documents presented at the 17th June Sub Group and, as a result
we have a number of points to make which you would be advised to take into
account in finalising/preparing the ES and application documents.  I had hoped
these matters may have been discussed before now through the NLG process.<BR><BR>Despite
what was said and minuted with regard to the revised platform height,
particularly in relation to the perceived change of approach from that set out
in the original RCF consultation, our provisional view is that the revised
orientation and relation to natural landform offers some advantages over the
original proposal.  We are concerned that the documentation produced to justify
the change may focus on less significant aspects, such as the view envelope, at
the expense of making clear the more immediate near impacts.  I set out more
fully below some of our specific comments and concerns, in the hope that when we
do manage to meet you will have had time to consider their implications.</P>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">1.</TD>
<TD>It is accepted that the proposed new orientation relates better to the
natural topography, the field pattern and existing buildings at Longlands Farm
than that of the previous proposal.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">2.</TD>
<TD>The proposed development would cover less area and be less disruptive of
the natural landform.  It would allow most of the attractive small valley on the
south side to be retained intact rather than be plugged by a substantial
embankment.  It should be less damaging to existing vegetation.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">3.</TD>
<TD>Eventual restoration of the natural topography of the RCF site would be
correspondingly easier.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">4.</TD>
<TD>However, the fact that the area of the visual envelope would increase by
less than 1% is scarcely a meaningful statistic.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">5.</TD>
<TD>The main impact of the proposed development on the senses would be the mere
fact of its presence as an alien structure in open countryside.  An additional
4.5 metres of elevation is not unduly significant in this reasoning.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">6.</TD>
<TD>Considering the visual impact more clinically, a 1% increase in the area
from which the development could be seen could be significant if that 1%
included new, highly critical, close viewpoints.  (The small scale and quality
of reproduction of the map reductions to hand does not allow this to be
assessed.)  However it seems unlikely that there would be significant new
viewpoints normally accessible to the general public.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">7.</TD>
<TD>The development would have a greater visual impact if raising its elevation
revealed a greater horizontal extent of its lower buildings or opened up sight
of ground level clutter and activity.  This appears not to be the case from the
eastern side.  The `study' does not address this issue from other directions -
the ES should.  Are we to assume that the stockyard, for example, re-sited near
the south-western boundary, will not be visible at the higher elevation from
critical viewpoints on that side ?  Mass car parking could be a highly
conspicuous element.  A car park is shown near the south-west boundary of the 80
metre RCF platform.  No provision for parking is shown in the revised proposals.<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">8.</TD>
<TD>Perspective would rapidly reduce the scale of the 4.5 metre apparent
additional height of the buildings as distance from the site increases.  The
difference between previous and present proposals would only be perceptible from
the closer view points.  We would expect close, critical viewpoints to have been
identified already in relation to the previous proposal - have they?  The
documentation to hand does not recognise any.  The photomontages appear to have
been chosen to represent various distances rather than critical viewpoints.  All
three photomontages are taken from the east or south-east of the site.  Are
there no critical views from other directions (eg Seascale and the south-west)?<BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">9.</TD>
<TD>Only the Red Admiral Inn could be considered close (400m).  This is
presumably the most critical viewpoint.  The focal length of the camera lens is
not stated.  (A focal length of about 50mm is usually considered to be
equivalent to the human eye.)  Nevertheless the photomontage gives a credible
impression of the visual impact.  The effect of the raised elevation is apparent
on the montage with a greater area of all the buildings visible (except that the
unnamed building between the mineral shaft and the conveyor at 80.0m level is
not present in the new design at the 84.5m level).  This view of the site would,
however, be readily screened by the block of woodland planting (as proposed)
alongside the A595 road.  The additional visual impact of the raised elevation
would not appear to be significant from Boonwood (1 km) and certainly not from
the caravan site (2.5 km).<BR></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>To sum up, taking these considerations into account, our view is that there
are benefits in raising the elevation of the platform to 84.5 metres OD which
could well outweigh the disadvantages.  However the summary document available
(UKN/PD/PR/031) leaves several questions unanswered and concentrates on
unhelpful argument, leaving the critical questions of the impact from a variety
of near views, and the role of landscaping, inadequately specified to be sure
that the view expressed here is indeed the case.<BR><BR>  I look forward to
hearing your response and discussing the implications in due course.  I have
copied this letter to Copeland Borough Council, and Peter Radmell of ERM.<BR><BR>Yours
sincerely<BR><BR><BR><BR>  for County Planning Officer
</P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P><A NAME="AppendixA2"></A><B><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">APPENDIX A2</FONT></B></P>
<P><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Conversion of Longlands Farm Buildings</FONT></P>
<P><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Notice of Grant of Planning Permission 
</FONT></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="6">COPELAND BOROUGH COUNCIL</FONT><BR> Catherine Street,
Whitehaven, Cumbria CA28 7NY<BR> 
</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT">App No 4/94/0617/</P>
<P><BR> Town and Country Planning Act 1990.<BR>
<BR> NOTICE OF GRANT OF PLANNING PERMISSION<BR>
<BR> MR D BROWN - UK NIREX LIMITED<BR> BUTTERMERE PAVILION<BR> WESTLAKES
SCIENCE PARK<BR> MOOR ROW<BR> CUMBRIA           	CA24 3JZ
</P>
<P><BR></P>
<P>CONVERSION OF FARM BUILDINGS FOR USE AS A VISITOR<BR> RECEPTION AREA AND
OFFICES, CONSTRUCTION OF A<BR> VIEWING PLATFORM AND ACCESS TO THE SAME AND<BR>
CONSTRUCTION OF 24 PARKING SPACES<BR> LONGLANDS FARM, GOSFORTH.<BR> UNITED
KINGDOM NIREX LIMITED
</P>
<P><BR><BR></P>
<P>The above application dated 01/08/94 has been considered by the Council in
pursuance of its powers under the above mentioned Act and PLANNING PERMISSION
HAS BEEN GRANTED subject to the following conditions :</P>
<P><BR></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="10">1.</TD>
<TD>The development hereby permitted shall be commenced within FIVE years from
the date hereof.<BR><BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="10">2.</TD>
<TD>This permission shall not be implemented unless and until such time as
permission may be granted for the Rock Characterisation Facility which is the
subject of a separate planning application to Cumbria County Council under
reference 4/94/9011.<BR><BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="10">3.</TD>
<TD>Should consent for the Rock Characterisation Facility be granted and this
approval implemented in respect of Longlands Farm buildings then the use now
authorised shall cease concurrently upon completion of the Rock Characterisation
Facility.<BR><BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="10">4.</TD>
<TD>Access for disabled people shall be provided to the satisfaction of the
Local Planning Authority, details of which shall be submitted to and approved by
the Local Planning Authority before development commences.<BR><BR></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="10">5.</TD>
<TD>Full details of both foul and surface water drainage, including proposals
for surface water run-off from the car parking area, shall be submitted to and
approved by the Local Planning Authority before any development commences on
site.<BR></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The reasons for the above conditions are:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>For the avoidance of doubt.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Local Planning Authority wish to be able to review the matter at the end
of the limited period stated.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
