<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PE/NRX/1/S1 - SURFACE WORKS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG SRC="../../images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex Logo">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B><FONT SIZE="5">PE/NRX/1/S1</FONT></B><BR></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="2">Appellant Ref: DB/CD 8.5.1</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">LPA
Ref: 4/94/9011</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">DOE Ref: APP/HO900/A/94/247019</FONT><BR><BR></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">UNITED KINGDOM NIREX LIMITED</FONT><BR></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Rock Characterisation Facility</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="4">Longlands Farm, Gosforth, Cumbria</FONT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">SUPPLEMENTARY</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PROOF OF EVIDENCE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">OF</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Mr A J SMITH</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="4">BSc, CEng, FIMinE</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">SURFACE WORKS</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">(Design Changes)</FONT></B><BR><BR></CENTER>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD><A HREF="../nrx1ix.htm">Back to NRX1 Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../poe.htm">Back to POE Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. Introduction
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1 Following a review of the principal points of concern arising in various
opposition proofs of evidence, a number of changes to the surface works are
proposed in order to address these concerns. 
</P>
<P><B>2. Principal Points of Concern and Proposed Changes </B>
</P>
<P><B>Security Fencing</B></P>
<P>2.1 The security fencing for the RCF has been criticised as being too
extensive and giving the site an industrialised appearance. 
</P>
<P>2.2 Following a review of the security fence line it would be possible to
reduce the extent of fencing and still maintain a secure site.
</P>
<P>2.3 The security fencing proposed in the Planning Application is illustrated
in Figure 1. The new security fencing would be confined to only the operational
areas of the RCF - the Platform Site, car park, explosive store and gate house -
as shown in Figure 2. The borehole sites which were previously to be 'absorbed'
within the single security fence line would now be left fenced separately. The
internal access roads would only be fenced with traditional stockproof fencing,
about 1m high. This has the effect of breaking up a single large fenced area
into a number of smaller discrete areas.
</P>
<P>2.4 In addition, the fence line originally proposed along the top of the 2m
high screening bund on the fill embankment forming the south western boundary of
the Platform Site would be re-routed along the toe of the embankment, resulting
in a significant reduction in its visibility.
</P>
<P>2.5 The net result of these changes would be a reduction of about 20% in the
length of security fencing to that originally proposed in the Planning
Application and about 20% less than the length of fencing already in use at the
site.
</P>
<P><B>Lighting
</B>
</P>
<P>2.6 Concern has been expressed that the type and extent of the lighting
proposed for the RCF will have a significant visual impact on the surrounding
area, particularly as the site is currently unlit at night.
</P>
<P>Temporary Lighting</P>
<P>2.7 The temporary lighting is necessary for construction personnel to be
able to work safely on the site. Although it is likely that planning
restrictions will constrain the hours of working (on the surface) to 0700 - 1900
hrs Monday to Friday and 0700 -1300 hrs on a Saturday, during the winter months
there will be times during these working hours when artificial lighting will be
needed to allow personnel to work safely.</P>
<P>2.8 The design level of lighting is 100 - 300 lux, which is typical of the
industry standard on civil engineering sites for craft work (refer to
<A HREF="#Table1">Table 1</A> - Schedule of Recommended Illuminance Levels for
Building and Civil Engineering Sites).
</P>
<P>2.9 It is concluded that any reduction in the proposed temporary lighting
levels would compromise site safety. It should be noted that the temporary
lighting is, by definition, only used during the initial site establishment
phase of the work - about 2 years and, more importantly, will not be used after
1900 hrs.
</P>
<P>Security Lighting
</P>
<P>2.10 The function of the security lighting is to provide a sufficient level
of lighting at night to enable the CCTV cameras to function and to provide
security personnel with enough light to detect potential intruders outside the
security fence, particularly on regular patrols around the site. This can be
achieved with a relatively low degree of illumination.
</P>
<P>2.11 The lights will be mounted on 6m high columns which will be spaced at
30m centres. The design level of illumination will provide an absolute minimum
level of 1 lux and, typically, will be in the range 5 to 20 lux. This is
consistent with industry recommendations (see <A HREF="#Table1">Table 1</A>).
</P>
<P>2.12 The amount of security fence lighting would be reduced as a result of
the re-design of the fence line described previously. It is proposed only to
light the security fence around the Platform Site, car park, gate house and
explosives store, as indicated in Figure 2. This reduces the illuminated length
of fence line by about 30% from that proposed in the Planning Application.
</P>
<P>2.13 Care will be taken in the specification of the general lighting system
- type, height, intensity and spacing of the lights - to minimise light
spillage.
</P>
<P><B>Explosives store
</B>
</P>
<P>2.14 Concern has been expressed at the perceived close proximity of the
explosives store to dwellings and its storage capacity. 
</P>
<P>2.15 Because of the nature of shaft sinking work, it is not possible to
predict accurately when explosives will be required for blasting. It is
necessary to have an operational buffer stock on site in order to ensure that
explosives are available when required so that costly delays in shaft
construction are avoided.
</P>
<P>2.16 With regard to the quantity explosives of explosives to be stored, it
is proposed that the explosives store be licensed as a Division E store, capable
of holding up to 1800kg of explosives. This is sufficient for continuous shaft
sinking and is normal practice in mining operations. 
</P>
<P>2.17 Although it is permissible - and common practice - to store detonators
within the main explosives store, two separate stores adjacent to each other to
allow detonators to be stored in a separate building is now proposed and
requires an amendment to the Application. However, it would still be licensed as
a single Class E store subject to the 1800kg limit.
</P>
<P>2.18 The next smallest store which could be licensed is a Class D store for
up to 900kg. This is half the size of the Class E store and would be
impracticable for this project.
</P>
<P>2.19 The explosives stores has been located in a position which complies
with the statutory distances from the highway, houses and the RCF itself. This
is shown in Figure 3. This in accordance with the requirements laid down in the
Stores for Explosives Order, 1951.
</P>
<P>2.20 Explosive stores are specially designed and manufactured against
intruders. Additionally, the RCF store will be alarmed and under camera
surveillance and security patrols.
</P>
<CENTER><A NAME="Table1"></A>TABLE 1 - SCHEDULE OF RECOMMENDED ILLUMINANCE
LEVELS FOR BUILDING</CENTER>
