<P><B>SUSAN ROSEMARY WILSON will say:</B><BR>
</P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1  PERSONAL DETAILS
</B></P>
<P>1.1  I am a Bachelor of Arts with Honours in Geography, from the University
of  Birmingham, with a Diploma in Landscape Design from the University of 
Manchester.  I became an Associate of the Landscape Institute in 1975, and was
elected a Fellow of the Landscape Institute in 1993.</P>
<P>1.2  From 1973 to 1989 I was employed by Brian Clouston and Partners, an
International Group of Landscape Architects, Architects and Planners which was
established in 1965.  I became a Director of this Company in January 1980.  In
1989 Brian Clouston and Partners merged with Rural Planning Services plc,
whereupon I became a Director of RPS Clouston, part of the RPS Group.</P>
<P>1.3  In 1991 W J Cairns and Partners became a wholly owned subsidiary of the
RPS Group, and I became the Landscape Principal of the RPS Cairns Offices in
Edinburgh and Belfast, in accordance with the requirements of the Landscape
Institute.  My evidence is based on the landscape assessments carried out to
date by my consultancy in connection with the proposed RCF development at
Longlands Farm.</P>
<P>1.4  My personal experience covers the landscape planning, design,
implementation and subsequent management of a wide range of projects for the
public and private sectors, including a number of new trunk road schemes, major
landfill and flood alleviation schemes, mineral applications for opencast coal,
hardrock and fuller's earth, and large scale commercial developments.  I have
also been involved in the preparation of environmental impact assessments and
environmental statements, for all forms of development, and have given evidence
in a number of public inquiries on behalf of both private and public sector
clients.</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2  SUMMARY
</B></P>
<P>Background Scope of Evidence
</P>
<P>2.1  My evidence outlines the background to the landscape assessments
leading to the Rock Characterisation Facility (`RCF') Environmental Statement
published in 1994, describes the landscape proposals, and addresses the effects
of the proposed development on the landscape, including the visual effects on
residential properties, users of public roads, rights of way and amenity areas,
and on the people living and working within this area.</P>
<P>2.2  My evidence also considers the effect of the proposed development on
the adjoining countryside and the present characteristics and qualities of the
Lake District National Park.</P>
<P><B>The Baseline Landscape
</B></P>
<P>2.3  A series of landscape and visual assessments have been carried out for
the proposed development. The methodology for these assessments is set out in
full in the &quot;Sellafield Baseline Information Report&quot; 1990 [COR/701](1)
, the &quot;Approach to Landscape Assessment&quot;, [COR/702](2) and the RCF
Environmental Statement (1994) [COR/101](3).</P>
<P>2.4  The existing landscape character and quality of the Appeal Site and
surrounding areas is described with reference to
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>.  This illustrates the broad
topography of the area which rises from the coastal plain in the west to the
high fells in the east, and the landscape character zone 16 Lingbank/Longlands,
identified in the Sellafield Baseline Information Report. [COR/701](1).</P>
<P>2.5  The Lingbank/Longlands landscape character zone lies between the Calder
Valley and Gosforth, and straddles the A595(T), thereby extending into the
National Park.  The landscape quality of the eastern part of this zone was
upgraded in the VRM assessment due to its location within the National Park,
while the quality of the western part of the zone remained low due to the
adverse visual influence of Sellafield.</P>
<P>2.6  A county wide landscape assessment was subsequently carried out by
Cumbria County Council and the site of the proposed development lies within the
main coastal strip identified in that study.  Within this broad area of
countryside, there are a number of settlements and modern man-made structures
including masts, electricity pylons, other overhead lines, examples of which are
indicated on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>.  However it is the
Sellafield Works which forms the predominant man-made feature, as illustrated in
Photograph 3.10.32. in the Environmental Statement.</P>
<P>2.7  A series of exploratory boreholes were developed in and around the
Platform Site of the proposed development.  The location of the current
boreholes sites is shown in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.3">Figure 4.3</A>.
These give rise to some visual intrusion arising from the earthworks.  This
varies according to the stage of development and proximity of the view to each
borehole site, but is not considered to be significant in the context of the
character of the existing landscape.</P>
<P>2.8  Although the scenery of the Lake District National Park to the east can
be enjoyed from the area west of the A595(T), the landscape of the Appeal Site
and its immediate surroundings is of average scenic quality, lacking any
especially attractive features. This is particularly so when compared with the
coastal zones to the north and to the south of the Appeal Site, which lie within
a County Landscape and the Lake District National Park respectively.</P>
<P>2.9  The Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan [COR/302](4)
recognises the wide variety and generally high quality of the landscapes within
the County and this is reflected in the high proportion of the land that is
afforded special protection through designation as National Park or County
Landscape.</P>
<P>2.10  It is therefore significant within this broader context of high
landscape quality that the site and its immediate surroundings are not subject
to any special designation in the Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan
[COR/302](4) or The Copeland Borough Council Local Plan. [COR/305](5). The
landscape quality of the wider area of the coastal strip is in fact relatively
mundane, lacking any distinctive qualities or character.  The Sellafield Works
and associated development also detract from the quality of  the landscape
although this is locally mitigated by mature deciduous woodlands and
shelterbelts.</P>
<P><B>Description of the Proposals</B></P>
<P>2.11  The landscape proposals as illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figures 5.1</A> to 5.3, are described, in
addition to those features which are of specific concern, or which will have a
particular visual effect.</P>
<P>2.12  The landscape proposals during the operational life of the proposed
development are shown on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.  The
proposals have been designed to integrate the development into the surrounding
countryside, to avoid wherever possible adverse visual effects on the
environment, and to ensure any potential adverse environmental effects are
minimised or mitigated.
</P>
<P>2.13  The level of the proposed Platform Site was determined at 84.5 metres
aOD to achieve the optimum balance between visibility of the proposed
structures, and the effect on the existing topography - with the retention of
most of an adjacent valley, and the existing mature woodlands.  Longlands Farm
will also be retained.</P>
<P>2.14  A 2 metre high screen bund will be formed around the south- west
periphery of the Platform Site to screen low level activity and features on the
site.  Topsoil storage mounds stored to the east of the Platform Site will
perform a similar screening function in views from the east.</P>
<P>2.15  As the earthworks are completed they will be progressively soiled and
seeded to prevent erosion, the undesirable growth of weeds, contamination of the
stored soil and to improve their appearance.  The borehole platforms and
associated earthworks of Nirex Deep Boreholes (&quot;Boreholes&quot;) 2, 4 and 5
and RCF1 will also be seeded with a herb rich grass seed mix to improve their
appearance and nature conservation potential until the borehole sites are fully
restored.</P>
<P>2.16  The landscape proposals have been designed in accordance with the
principles of design agreed with officers of Cumbria County Council, including
the County Landscape Architect and in consultation with the Forestry Commission
to:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>provide visual screening for the development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>integrate the proposals within the existing landscape and vegetation
structure of the surrounding countryside;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>improve the landscape character and visual amenity of the local area
through the creation of new indigenous broadleaved woodlands;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>mitigate any potential effects of the proposed development on existing
local fauna; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v)</TD>
<TD>provide indigenous wildlife habitats to increase the ecological resource
for local flora and fauna.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.17  Accordingly the landscape proposals include in total some 4.85
hectares of permanent new woodland under a Forestry Commission Woodland Grant
Scheme, similar to that in operation for the 1994-95 RCF Borehole Planting.  The
Scheme will also include new hedgerow planting and infilling of existing
hedgerows, which will be maintained at a minimum height of 2 metres in order
that they may contribute to low level screening of the Platform Site from
adjacent views.</P>
<P>2.18  The planting proposals will be implemented in a phased programme to
accommodate the extensive earthworks programme, and is illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>. This also indicates the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole planting, the majority of which was carried out in the
Spring of 1994.</P>
<P>2.19  The Planting Phase 1 comprises 1.74 hectares of woodland trees and
shrubs to be implemented in the first planting season, including temporary
planting on soil storage mounds; the Planting Phase 2 comprises 3.11 hectares of
woodland including temporary planting on the southern embankment of the Platform
Site which will be removed during the restoration proposals.  The temporary
planting which will be removed during the restoration earthworks and
subsequently replaced as part of the restoration proposals is also indicated on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A>.</P>
<P>2.20  The planting proposals which form part of the proposed development,
combined with the extensive woodland planting undertaken by Nirex on land
adjacent to the site, will completely surround the proposed development with
woodland.</P>
<P>2.21  The variations to the initial landscape proposals, which were included
in the application , have arisen following consultations.  These are also
indicated on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>, as follows:
omission of planting on soil storage mounds to the north of Wetwood, and to the
south-east of the Platform Site; omission of planting along Services Corridor B
through proposed woodland on the embankment west of the Platform Site; the
additional area of the Spoil Disposal Area and noise bunds associated with the
variant design down to 935 metres bOD.</P>
<P>2.22  The variations have been assessed and I consider that the minor
modifications to the planting proposals and storage of topsoil and subsoil
mounds, in response to consultations with MAFF, will not give rise to any
discernible changes in the effects of the proposed development.  Should the
shafts be driven to a depth below 650 metres bOD the additional spoil would be
accommodated within the proposed Spoil Disposal Area without further increasing
the overall height of the new landform. This is indicated on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>.  The delay in the commencement
of the RCF (compared with the programme in the application) will also have a
beneficial effect arising from the extended growing period for the existing
immature tree planting, which will increase its size and screening potential.</P>
<P>2.23  The most significant of the built structures, in respect of their
impact on the landscape and visual amenity of the area, are the tower crane at
35 metres high, the construction headgear at 25-30 metres high, and the
subsequent operational headgear at a height of 29.2 metres.  All the structures
will be temporary in nature and vary in duration from 11 months for the tower
crane to up to 7 years for the operational headgear.
</P>
<P>2.24  The layout of the Platform Site and underground services has been
designed to avoid direct impact on adjacent landscape features and areas of
ecological significance and interest.</P>
<P>2.25  The design and location of the security fencing will be carefully set
out to ensure that it is not visually prominent within views from public areas.</P>
<P>2.26  The colour of paintwork or cladding of the proposed buildings and
other structures will be dealt with through planning conditions, by agreement
with the Planning Authority.  However, it is intended that a range of
unobtrusive colours will be used to reduce the visibility of the development
within the landscape.</P>
<P>2.27  The period of most intense lighting of the Platform Site would occur
during the early construction phase, of approximately 15 months, when temporary
high level lighting will be required. The number of high level light sources
will however be minimised and lighting only activated when needed. During the
operation of the proposed development, lighting will be maintained at the lowest
practicable illumination level consistent with the safety and security of
personnel using or visiting the RCF.</P>
<P>2.28  The Restoration Proposals are illustrated on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A>. These have been designed to
reinstate the landscape to reflect the existing features and land uses.  A
further 2.21 hectares of woodland planting is proposed to give a final total of
permanent new woodland associated with the proposed development of 4.6 hectares.
 Nature conservation features beneficial to both fauna and flora of the locality
include herb rich grassland, a wetland area in the base of the restored valley,
scrub vegetation on the woodland edge and a varied woodland structure.</P>
<P><B>Effects on the Landscape</B></P>
<P>2.29 The physical and visual effects of the proposed development on the
landscape has been assessed using the methodology described in the RCF
Environmental Statement paragraphs 3.10.23 to 38. [COR/101](6).
</P>
<P>2.30 Subsequent work has been carried out to assess the effects of proposed
variations in the design of the proposed development, following consultation on
the application, by reference to the seven criteria used by the County Council
to assess the quality of the County Landscape outside the National Park.
</P>
<P>2.31 The main physical effects of the development giving rise to temporary
changes in the landscape will be confined within the Appeal Site. These are
related to landform, vegetation cover and built structures as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>the effect on the local topography of the temporary but extensive
earthworks associated with the creation of the Platform Site;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>the creation of a new landform by disposal of excavated spoil;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>the temporary noise and visual screen bunds;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>the introduction of temporary hardstandings, buildings, cranes, shafts and
access roads, into the landscape of the Surface Site; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v)</TD>
<TD>the loss of some 15 trees and some 450 metres of hedgerows and scrub within
the valley.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.32 There are no cultural features of significance within the Appeal Site,
and no Scheduled Monuments, Listed Buildings, Conservation Areas, Parks or
Gardens of Special Historic Interest directly affected by the proposed
development. A site of very minor archaeological significance will be lost to
the proposed development and this is discussed in Dr. Ralston's evidence. [<A
HREF="../nrx8/nrx8.htm"><B>PE/NRX/8</B></A>].
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para2.33"></A>2.33 The development has been located and designed
to minimise any adverse physical effects on the surrounding area. In addition it
should be noted that all structures are programmed to remain on site for the
minimum period necessary for their operation. All buildings and hardstandings
will be removed when the site is restored to create no long term effects. The
proposed Spoil Disposal Area and planting are designed to reflect and integrate
with existing features of the landscape and vegetation of the immediate
surroundings.
</P>
<P>2.34  The effects of the proposed development will thus be localised and
mitigated through the design of the new landforms, temporary earthworks, and new
planting and by the existing topography and woodlands. After the restoration is
completed the permanent changes to the landform and more particularly the new
planting will give rise to minor localised changes to the general landscape
character of the Surface Site and the immediately adjacent area. There will
however, be no long term diminution in the quality of the landscape. The
proposed development should not, therefore, in my view, lead to any change in
the County Council's assessment of landscape quality of the Appeal Site and
surrounding area based on the criteria set out in Assessment of County
Landscapes - Structure Plan, Technical Paper No. 4. [COR/304](7).
</P>
<P>2.35 Although the permanent changes to the landform within the site will not
affect the character of the immediately surrounding landscape, the proposed
planting will make a long term beneficial contribution to its existing landscape
character. The addition of these substantial new woodlands, and improved
hedgerows will extend the benefits of the existing mature woodlands, and enrich
the landscape character and quality of the area to the east, south and
south-west of the Platform Site.
</P>
<P>2.36 The effect on the landscape character of the wider countryside within
which the proposed development is located is not considered to be significant.
The open countryside of the main coastal strip within which the site lies is
characterised by a greater density of development than adjacent areas within the
areas of County Landscape and the National Park. It has already been affected by
large scale development, especially the Sellafield Works, and is consequently
less sensitive to further changes. I therefore consider that the countryside of
the main coastal strip can accommodate the proposed RCF development without
changing the existing character of the surrounding landscape.
</P>
<P>2.37 Although the proposed development has been designed, wherever possible,
to reduce and mitigate its adverse visual effects, the proposals will give rise
to some visual intrusion, due largely to the height and scale of the tower crane
and the headgear.
</P>
<P>2.38 The RCF Environmental Statement concluded that the proposed development
would not give rise to significant visual effects other than for a small number
of properties and viewpoints in relatively close proximity to the Surface Site.
The assessment of visual effects found that the development proposals would give
rise to visual intrusion but would not give rise to any visual obstruction.
However, it is recognised that the new woodland planting implemented as part of
the RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development will, as it matures, obscure views to the
west, including those of the proposed RCF development from the adjacent stretch
of the A595(T) and the Red Admiral Hotel. This will assist in integrating the
proposals within the existing landscape and vegetation structure of the
surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>2.39 The visual effect of the proposed development has been assessed in
relation to the extent of its visibility, the degree of its visual intrusion,
and its effect on the visual amenity experienced from settlements and dwellings,
centres of employment, the transport infrastructure, public rights of way, areas
of recreational amenity, and features of Cultural Heritage. The visual
assessment was carried out from public viewpoints. It sought also to assess the
effect on private amenity from points of public access adjacent to private
property. The extent of visibility of the RCF (from all potential viewpoints
both public and private) was initially identified through a series of Visual
Envelope Maps (VEMs) which were prepared for the various phases of the
development as indicated in Figures 3.10.20 to 3.10.24 of the Environmental
Statement.
</P>
<P>2.40 The information shown on a Visual Envelope Map represents a compromise
between precision in reflecting the complex detail of the visual effects and the
ability of a computer to process a large data set. It is therefore only an
indicative illustration of areas which may have a view of the proposed
development. Observations on the ground have confirmed that the VEMs present
very much a &quot;worst case image&quot;. The screening effect of existing
mature woodland and topography at 5 metres contour intervals was taken into
account. In reality this would be significantly augmented by minor landscape
features which are below the resolution of the computer model. These include
minor changes in landform, hedges, industrial buildings or walls, and small
groups of trees and shrubs which singly or in combination serve to obstruct or
filter views.
</P>
<P>2.41 The Longlands Farm buildings and extensive mature woodlands around the
site, as shown on Figure 3.10.36 in the Environmental Statement, will provide
some visual containment and screening of the Platform Site and lower buildings
from adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>2.42 Similarly the RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole planting carried out in 1994 and 95
will develop to form a very effective screen to the proposed development,
particularly in views from the A595(T) in the vicinity of the Red Admiral Hotel,
and the hamlet of New Mill. An assessment of the predicted height of this
planting, based on current growth rates and Forestry Commission prescribed
growth rates for the area has been carried out, in order that these may be taken
into account in the assessment of visual effects on the proposed development.
</P>
<P>2.43 The most intrusive features, comprising the tower crane, (on site for a
total of some 11 months), the construction headgear (on site for some 39
months), and the operational headgear, (on site for the remainder of the
operational programme of about 6.5- 7 years), will be most visible within the
immediate surroundings of the Platform Site.
</P>
<P>2.44 The significance of visual effects on settlements and dwellings is set
out in Table 3.10.3 of the Environmental Statement. This has been updated and
expanded in my <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> to indicate the
effect on the visual amenity of residents. A number of properties lying beyond a
1.5 kilometres radius from the headgear, from which noticeable adverse visual
effects may be experienced have been included in this table. Properties included
in Table 3.10.3 of the Environmental Statement which will not have a view of the
proposed development are indicated accordingly. The properties identified in the
schedule and potential degree of change in visual amenity is illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A>.
</P>
<P>2.45 The Schedule in my <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>
indicates that the headgear will be visible from a total of 17 properties within
a 1.5 kilometre radius of the surface site with potential views possible from 5
additional properties available from upper storey windows and/or at oblique
angles of view. The occupiers of the 17 properties affected would experience a
change in visual amenity following implementation of the proposals, of differing
levels. The visual amenity of the 5 properties with barely discernible views
would not change.
</P>
<P>2.46 Substantial adverse effects will be experienced in the vicinity of
Sides Bungalow. A view of the proposed Platform Site from a point approximately
500 metres to the west of Sides Bungalow is illustrated in photograph in Figure
3.10.35 of the Environmental Statement. A photomontage in Figure 3.10.13 of the
Environmental Statement illustrates the proposed development from the same
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>2.47 Moderate to substantial adverse effects will be experienced initially
in the vicinity of the Red Admiral Hotel due to the proximity of the
development. However, this effect will be significantly reduced within 5 to 7
years as the existing immature woodland increases in height, as illustrated in
the Photograph in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>. The &quot;existing&quot;
view from the Red Admiral Hotel was shown in Figure 3.10.36 in the Environmental
Statement; a more recent view is illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure
6.3</A>.
</P>
<P>2.48 The proposed development will also have a moderate adverse effect on
visual amenity in the vicinity of Brownbank 1.7 kilometres to the south, due to
the perceived contrast with the uncluttered topography of the Cumbrian Fells,
which forms the backdrop to the view and which has few intrusive man made
features. A similar view from a point further south is illustrated in the
Photomontage in Figure 3.10.11 in the Environmental Statement. However, in time,
the intervening Moss Wood Plantation, combined with the tree tops currently
filtering views of the site, will obscure the development in views from the
property.
</P>
<P>2.49 Similarly moderate adverse effects will be experienced from the
vicinity of Ponsonby Old Hall 1 kilometre to the north, due to the prominence of
the development protruding above the horizon, as shown in the Photomontage in
3.10.17 of the Environmental Statement of a view taken from the nearby public
footpath.
</P>
<P>2.50 Slight to moderate adverse effects on visual amenity will also be
experienced at Gibb House and Gibb Hill Farm, the vicinity of Broom, The Moors
and Ennerdale.
</P>
<P>2.51 A slight adverse effect on visual amenity will be experienced where the
observer is sited either at a sufficient distance from the proposals, where
vegetation significantly filters views, or when the Sellafield Works is dominant
in views of the development, as at Tarn How, Fleming Hall, and Haverigg
Moorside.
</P>
<P>2.52 Where the development would be visible but cause no discernible
deterioration in the visual amenity an assessment of no change is recorded. This
level of no change may be due to distance, the small extent of the proposed
development which will be visible, where the view embraces other major
structures, or where the Sellafield Works is visually dominant.
</P>
<P>2.53 The only settlement affected will be the eastern edge of Seascale. The
view from the eastern edge of Seascale adjacent to the B5344 is illustrated in
the Photomontage in Figure 3.10.7 of the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>2.54 The lengths of footpaths, bridleways and byways from which the proposed
development may be visible are indicated in Table 3.10.5 in the Environmental
Statement. These figures indicate that pedestrians on only short sections of
these rights of way will experience views of the development, as views are
frequently constrained by hedgerows, walls and similar features. Such views may
give rise to short term, moderate or locally substantial adverse effects on the
visual amenity of footpath users, due to the nature of the view, which is
dependent on the direction of movement, and also fragmented by intervening
vegetation and structures. The adverse effect on the visual amenity of users of
the railway, roads, and areas of recreational amenity will be slight other than
for a few locations in close proximity to the site, on Sides Lane, the A595(T),
and from nearby elevated viewpoints to the east.
</P>
<P>2.55 This is illustrated in the Photomontage in Figure 3.10.10 of the
Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>2.56 The proposed development will be visible from parts of Seascale Golf
Course against the backdrop of Cumbrian Fells. This will have an adverse effect
on this particular view, offset to some degree by the ameliorating effect of
distance, as shown in the Photomontage in Figure 3.10.14(a) of the Environmental
Statement. However within the wider context of the landscape setting of the Golf
Course, the proposed development would not change the visual amenity of users of
the Golf Course.
</P>
<P>2.57 Although the tallest structures, the tower crane and headgear, may be
visible from the surrounding area, there are few locations in the area where
views of the proposal would not also include the Sellafield Works which, because
of its scale and impact, would reduce the visual significance of the proposal.
</P>
<P>2.58 The assessment of the night time effect of the lighting associated with
the RCF indicated that the design of the lighting scheme and the use of high
pressure sodium, and light control lanterns will minimise the extent of visual
intrusion arising from the lighting. The resulting pink/white &quot;haze&quot;
will appear subdued and give rise to only slight levels of intrusion when
perceived in the context of the bright orange light and widespread glow of the
Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>2.59 The most intrusive elements would be the 20 metres high columns
required during the construction period but these will be in limited use and of
a relatively short duration. The higher levels of lighting required at the
security gate may also be visually intrusive. However this will be a localised
effect and, due to the proximity to the A595(T), will lie within a broad
corridor also affected by vehicle headlights. The proposed lighting should not,
therefore give rise to significant overall levels of visual intrusion.
</P>
<P>2.60 In order to assess fully the significance of any visual effects of the
proposed RCF development these must be considered in the context of the visual
prominence and adverse visual influence of the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>2.61 A VEM of the Sellafield Works has therefore been produced to identify
the extent of visibility and the potential area within which the Sellafield
Works has a detracting or adverse influence on the scenic quality of views
within the landscape. The VEM was produced using the same base topographical and
vegetation data used for the VEMs of the proposed RCF, illustrated in Figures
3.10.20-24 of the Environmental Statement. From this a composite VEM of the
proposed RCF headgear, and the cooling towers and chimneys of the Sellafield
Works has been produced and is illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure
6.2</A>. This shows the extent of potential visibility of any part of the
Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>2.62 A comparison of VEMs indicates that the Sellafield Works has a much
more extensive VEM and potential field of visual influence and that, apart from
a few localised exceptions, all areas of visibility of the RCF coincide with
areas of visibility of the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>2.63 The cumulative visual effect of the proposed RCF development and the
existing Sellafield Works is not considered to be significant in the
Environmental Assessment, as the overall visual intrusion of the development is
low. In addition the existing woodland and topography will create a natural
barrier between the proposed RCF development and the Sellafield Works which will
ensure that the two developments are perceived as separate from one another.
Where there will be open views of the proposed RCF from the south-west,
including Sides Lane, such views will not encompass Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>2.64 I therefore consider that in view of the relatively low overall level
of visibility of the proposed development, the existing landscape context which
contains other man made features and the limited impact it will have on the
visual amenity of the area, the features of the proposed RCF could be
accommodated within this part of the countryside without significant adverse
effects.
</P>
<P><B>The Effect on the Lake District National Park
</B></P>
<P>2.65 Concern has been expressed by Cumbria County Council at the effect of
the proposed development on the character and qualities of the Lake District
National Park. However the proposals lie to the west of the A595(T) which forms
the National Park Boundary and will not therefore directly affect the landscape
of the Park.
</P>
<P>2.66 Although dissociated from the Sellafield Works by the intervening
countryside and substantial blocks of woodland, most views of the proposed RCF
development from the Lake District National Park and adjacent areas will also
encompass or lie within the broader context of views of the Sellafield Works.
The extensive and highly complex development at Sellafield is the predominant
man-made feature in the area. Whenever the Sellafield Works is encompassed
within a view, the complex arrangement of towers draws the eye away from other,
lesser structures which become insignificant by comparison, and therefore of no
consequence within the view. Thus in the panoramic views from the National Park
which contain Sellafield, the visual significance of the proposed RCF
development will be small.
</P>
<P>2.67 The area of the Lake District National Park which lies close to the
site is affected by other intrusive features such as the A595(T) and the
associated traffic. It is therefore less vulnerable and susceptible to changes
arising from new development than more remote areas, with the special landscape
character and scenic quality more typified by or generally associated with the
Lake District.
</P>
<P>2.68 In the wider context of the western fells the character of this part of
the National Park, which is degraded by the detracting effects of the A595(T)
and open views towards the Sellafield Works, is in marked contrast to the
adjacent minor valleys, and more particularly nearby Wasdale, Eskdale and
Butterdale which do have the attractive scenic qualities and characteristics
typical of the Lake District. It is also notable that the County Assessment did
not consider the area west of the A595(T) and adjacent to the National Park
boundary to be sufficiently attractive or distinctive to justify its designation
as a County Landscape, even though it adjoins the National Park.
</P>
<P>2.69 Although the proposed development will be visible from the National
Park, I consider that it will not be prominent, and will not affect the
appearance or special characteristics and qualities particularly associated with
the landscape of the National Park.
</P>
<P>2.70 At distances over 1.5 kilometres the surface details of the development
will not be discernible and, although visible in part, it will not appear as an
alien element out of scale or character within its landscape context. This is in
stark contrast to the Sellafield Works which does not sit easily within the
landscape.
</P>
<P>2.71 Significant viewpoints within the Lake District National Park within
the VEM of the proposed development include:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>the elevated moorland including Cat Bields/Nether Wasdale Common, Stone
Pike/Wheel Fell and Cold Fell at distances of between 5 to 10 kilometres. The
development will also be visible from Irton Pike and in filtered views between
the trees on Irton Fell, at a distance of some 6.5 kilometres as illustrated in
Photomontage 3.10.18 in the Environmental Statement.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>The elevated access roads, bridleways and footpaths below the moorland from
which intermittent views can be obtained such as those from Gibb Hill Farm and
Hurlbarrow. This type of view is generally from a distance of 1.5 kilometres or
more, and is illustrated by Photomontage 3.10.16 in the Environmental Statement.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>Localised views will be obtained from isolated properties within 1.5
kilometres of the development at Ponsonby and adjacent to the western boundary
of the National Park at New Mill, Boonwood and including the Red Admiral Hotel.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.72 The visual assessment of the proposed development presented in the
Environmental Statement indicates that the visual effect of the proposals on the
Lake District National Park will be small. I therefore consider that the
proposed RCF development will have no significant effect on either the character
or landscape quality of the Lake District National Park, neither will it have
any discernable effect upon the visual or recreational amenity of the National
Park.
</P>
<P><B>Consultations
</B></P>
<P>2.73 Prior to the submission of the Planning Application and Environmental
Statement regular Consultations were held with Cumbria County Council, and their
consultant advisors, Copeland Borough Council, and the Lake District Special
Planning Board through the Nirex Liaison Group. In particular, consultations
have been held and the agreement of the local authorities has been obtained, to
the landscape design principles, the methodology of the landscape assessments,
and the planting details and final draft of the Landscape Management Plan.
</P>
<P>2.74 During the consultation period following submission of the planning
application the County Council received many representations from interested
organisations and individuals.
</P>
<P>2.75 The proposed development addresses the concerns expressed by members of
the public, raised during the consultation period, in achieving the optimum
environmental scheme, and through the measures designed to reduce and mitigate
potential adverse effects of the development on the landscape of the open
countryside and Lake District National Park.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusions
</B></P>
<P>2.76 I consider that the proposed development will not have a significant
adverse effect on the character and quality of the surrounding open countryside.
The proposed development through the extensive new woodlands and landscape
proposals would on the contrary, enhance the quality of the landscape of the
Appeal Site and surrounding area in the longer term. Similarly, although the
proposed development lies close to the boundary of the Lake District National
Park it will not be detrimental to the landscape characteristics and quality of
the National Park.
</P>
<P>2.77 It is accepted and acknowledged by Cumbria County Council that the
scheme has been designed as far as practicable to reduce the effect of the
proposed development on the landscape. The design will continue to be refined as
the details are developed. The proposed development has sought and continues to
seek a balance between the interests of ecology, archaeology, agriculture and
effects on the landscape, and the operational needs of the development. In
particular the potential physical and visual effects on the landscape character
and quality of the surrounding area have been limited and will be reduced over
time as the new and proposed woodland planting becomes established and matures.
</P>
<P>2.78 I therefore conclude that, although the proposed development would give
rise to some visual intrusion and localised physical change, this would be
either temporary or would in the long term be offset by the beneficial effects
of new woodlands and enriched vegetation cover in and around the Appeal Site.
The proposed development would not therefore give rise to any long term
demonstrable harm to the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. BACKGROUND AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE
</B></P>
<P>3.1 My Evidence will describe the baseline landscape of the Appeal Site and
its surroundings, and is based upon the assessments carried out to support the
planning application and described in the RCF Environmental Statement
[COR/101](3). I will develop those assessments in order to describe the effect
of the proposed development upon the landscape and local residents.
</P>
<P>3.2 The &quot;Approach to Landscape Assessment&quot; [COR/702](2) was agreed
with Cumbria County Council in February 1993. A composite of two established
Landscape Assessment methods was adopted for the baseline assessment, detailed
in the Sellafield Baseline Information Report, [COR/701](1). These were: &quot;Landscape
Assessment : A Countryside Commission Approach&quot;, CCD 18 (1987)
[COR/703](8), and the USA Bureau of Land Management &quot;Visual Resources
Management (VRM) Program&quot;. The primary objective of the assessments was to
assess the quality and sensitivity of the landscape in the study area in order
to identify areas that would be least sensitive to development. The assessments
are described in detail in the Sellafield Baseline Information Report, Nirex
Report 94. [COR/701](1).
</P>
<P>3.3 The Landscape Survey was both qualitative and quantitative, with an
overall assessment and detailed inventory of features. Sources of information
for the survey included the following:</P>
<UL>
<LI>a general site survey on foot including record photographs;</LI>
<LI>an oblique aerial photographs;</LI>
<LI>a detailed site levels and features survey; and</LI>
<LI>a tree and hedgerow survey
</LI></UL>
<P>3.4 The landscape baseline study indicated that Longlands Farm lies within a
landscape character zone which straddles the A595(T), extending into the Lake
District National Park. The landscape evaluation classified the study area into
a number of Visual Resource Management (VRM) classes based on the 5 rating
factors of Scenic Quality, User Reaction, Population Density, Sensitivity Level,
and Distance Zone, for which each character zone was given a grade of High,
Medium or Low. On the basis of the evaluation undertaken for the Sellafield
Baseline Information Report the Lingbank Plantation - Longlands Area (Character
Zone 16) was placed in Class 4 out of a total of 5 (where Class 1 is high
quality).</P>
<P>3.5 The evaluation was then modified to take account of special
circumstances, relating to national landscape designations in respect of
scientific interest or scenic quality, and planning policies, legislation, and
guidelines. As a result that part of the Lingbank/Longlands Farm zone within the
National Park, although similar to the rest of this zone in all other respects
was elevated to VRM Class 2, and the adjacent central portion, including the
wooded area around Longlands Farm elevated to Class 3. The less attractive and
less visible area overlooking the Sellafield Works remained in Class 4.
</P>
<P>3.6 An assessment was carried out of the effects of the proposed development
on this landscape and recommendations made for preliminary mitigation measures.
</P>
<P>3.7 The subsequent detailed visual assessment was carried out to identify
all the potential visual effects of the proposed development, which could then
advise and inform the detailed mitigation proposals. As the development was not
expected to cause visual obstruction, the assessment of visual effects
concentrated on an assessment of visual intrusion. This was assessed in terms
of:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="LEFT">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>the degree of intrusion i.e. the contrast between the development and its
surroundings using the final part of the VRM method;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>the extent of visibility, i.e. the potential visibility of the development
at different phases, determined using computer- generated Visual Envelope Maps
(VEMs). These are an indication of the potential areas from which a view of part
of the development may be gained. The computer generated model was supported by
on- site survey; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>the significance of intrusion, based on the number of people or user groups
affected, by reference to various populations, transport and other data.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>3.8 The detailed mitigation measures were based on a series of principles
for landscape design developed following discussions with Cumbria County Council
and Copeland Borough Council, and appended to the &quot;Approach to Landscape
Assessment&quot; [COR/702](2), and formed the basis of the approach to the
design of the landscape proposals for the proposed RCF development.
</P>
<P>3.9 The significance of the effects was assessed in relation to settlements
and dwellings, centres of employment, the transport infrastructure, public
rights of way, visitors and recreation, cultural heritage, landscape quality and
the Lake District National Park.
</P>
<P>3.10 The assessments concluded that:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1200">the proposed development would not cause visual obstruction
and consequently effects on landscape would be limited to visual intrusion;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>measures to minimise the adverse effects would significantly reduce the
degree of visual intrusion and the extent of visibility of the Platform Site. As
a result, visual intrusion was found to be low when considered in terms of the
effects on people, except for a few locations in close proximity to the site;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>the overall effects on the Lake District National Park and surrounding
areas was considered to be minor, and the cumulative visual effect of the
proposed development and the existing Sellafield Works was not considered to be
significant; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>in the longer term, site restoration and measures such as tree planting
would enhance the scenic quality of the Longlands Farm area.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The methodology and results of the assessments are detailed in Section 3
Chapter 10, &quot;Landscape&quot;, of the RCF Environmental Statement.
[COR/101](10).
</P>
<P>3.11 My evidence will address the effects of the proposed development on the
landscape, including the visual effects on residential properties, users of
public roads and rights of way, amenity areas and on the people living and
working within the area. I will explain the significance of the visual effects
of the proposed development on visual amenity, by reference to photographs and
photomontages.
</P>
<P>3.12 I will also describe the landscape proposals and outline minor proposed
variations since the preparation of the Environmental Statement, and consider
their effects on the landscape. These include minor changes to the construction
details and the development programme.
</P>
<P>3.13 My evidence will address the effect of the proposed development on the
countryside, including:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the relationship of the proposed development to existing developed areas in
terms of siting, scale and design within the open countryside, and</LI>
<LI>the extent to which the proposed development would enhance the quality and
setting of the existing environment, and the degree of integration into the
existing pattern of surrounding land uses that will be achieved.
</LI></UL>
<P> 3.14 I will also consider the effect of the Platform Site on the present
characteristics and qualities of the Lake District National Park and demonstrate
that although the site lies close to the boundary of the National Park it would
not be detrimental to those characteristics and qualities.
</P>
<P>3.15 I will refer to Figures and Tables including plans, drawings,
photographs and photomontages, and to the figures and tables incorporated in the
RCF Environmental Statement. [COR/101](3).</P>
<P><A NAME="Baseline"></A><B>4. THE BASELINE LANDSCAPE
</B></P>
<P><B>Landscape Character of the Appeal Site and Surroundings
</B></P>
<P>The Landscape Context is illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figures
4.1</A> and <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.2">4.2</A>.
</P>
<P>4.1 The existing landscape character of the Appeal Site and its surroundings
is assessed and described in Section 3, Chapter 10 of the RCF Environmental
Statement.[COR/101](10). This assessment was carried out assuming a `green field
site' in view of the temporary nature of the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes development
which commenced in 1993. The description of the character of the landscape of
the site and its surroundings, set out in the RCF Environmental Statement, and
is summarised in the following section.
</P>
<P>4.2 The Appeal Site lies within the Lingbank/Longlands Landscape Character
Zone (16) which extends from Gosforth to the Calder Valley, within which the
landscape comprises low lying, rolling farmland typical of the Cumbrian Coastal
area. To the east of the A595(T) the land rises to the lower fells of the Lake
District National Park, with open pastures between steep sided well-wooded
valleys. The topography of the area is indicated on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>.
</P>
<P>4.3 The Appeal Site falls in a south-west direction from a high point of
approximately 110 metres aOD adjacent to the A595(T) to a low point of
approximately 65 metres aOD to the south. There is a small steep sided valley
beginning south-west of the farm buildings and meandering south beyond the
Surface Site. At its head it is divided by a steep sided drumlin. The valley
floor is damp and marshy in places, and is drained by an intermittently flowing
rill that enters the southern tributary of Newmill Beck. Sections AA and BB in
Figure 2.11 of the Environmental Statement illustrate the general fall of the
land to the south-west.
</P>
<P>4.4 The gently undulating topography of the agricultural landscape, within
which the site lies, consists predominantly of rectangular pasture fields,
generally larger to the west and north and becoming smaller in size towards the
east. The fields are bounded by hedges on raised dykes, typical of this part of
Cumbria, and woodlands, ranging from small copses to larger more rectangular
plantations and shelterbelts, which decrease in frequency towards the more
exposed coast. The topography becomes more undulating towards the north, but
flatter beyond Seascale to the south.</P>
<P> 4.5 Immediately east of the Appeal Site and adjacent to the A595(T), higher
pastures create a transition between the intensively farmed lowlands and the
moorlands of the Lake District, with the higher fells climbing steeply above to
dominate the skyline and creating a strong, west facing aspect to the landscape.
As the ground rises the hedgerow field boundaries gradually give way to stone
walls, and the fields become more open in character.
</P>
<P>4.6 The landscape within the Lingbank/Longlands Area is varied and, although
exposed to the west, is afforded enclosure by the undulating topography, raised
field boundaries and woodland areas. Views of adjacent lower ground from the
many winding lanes, tracks and footpaths are generally restricted by the high
enclosing banks and hedgerows or walls. However, higher ground may often be
visible above the hedgerows and trees, and substantial panoramas are often
available from elevated viewpoints, where the landscape is locally more open in
character. The Photograph in Fig. 3.10.29 of the Environmental Statement
illustrates the landscape from a point to the south-west of the Appeal Site.
</P>
<P>4.7 The immediate locality of the Appeal Site is sparsely populated with a
number of scattered farms and cottages and the Red Admiral Hotel adjacent to the
A595(T). The nearest settlements are Gosforth less than 1 kilometre to the
south-east and the hamlet of New Mill which lies on the eastern boundary of the
Appeal Site. A line of electricity pylons extends south-east from Sellafield
running parallel to the coastline to the west, while masts and telegraph posts,
carrying 33 kV overhead lines and minor electrical cables, also punctuate the
view. Modern farm buildings such as silos and large scale outbuildings which are
locally intrusive, are located on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>.
The temporary RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole structures also create an element of visual
intrusion. However the predominant man made feature is the Sellafield Works, the
towers of which dominate the coastal landscape between Saltcoats to the south
and Thornhill to the north. This is illustrated in the Photograph in Fig.
3.10.32 of the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P><B>Landscape Quality
</B></P>
<P>4.8 Although located close to the boundary of the Lake District National
Park, the Appeal site and adjacent areas west of the A595(T) do not lie within
any designated landscape areas, including those of the existing Areas of Great
Landscape Value and the proposed County Landscape Areas.
</P>
<P>4.9 The assessment of landscape quality, carried out as part of the work to
support the planning application, is summarised in the Environmental Statement
paragraphs 3.10.54 - 55. This assessment concluded that the area around
Longlands Farm and the Lingbank Plantation is of average scenic quality.
</P>
<P>4.10 The area's lack of any special landscape quality was confirmed in a
recent countywide assessment carried out by Cumbria County Council. This
assessment was based on the guidelines published by the Countryside Commission
(CCD 18,1987) [COR/703](8) and identified a number of attributes, against which
the landscape was assessed. These are set out in Technical Paper No. 4
[COR/304](7) as follows:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(1)</TD>
<TD><U>Landform</U> : particularly striking, prominent or unusual;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(2)</TD>
<TD><U>Land cover</U> : rich or varied patterns, normally including a
proportion of semi-natural vegetation cover;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(3)</TD>
<TD><U>Natural or built features</U> : groupings of natural or built features
of visual interest including settlements, individual buildings, groups of trees,
lakes or tarns, wildlife and historic features;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(4)</TD>
<TD><U>Cultural features</U> : historic field patterns and hedgerows or stone
walls, parkland, earthworks or historic associations;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(5)</TD>
<TD><U>Detractors</U> : an absence of intrusive development or other
discordant elements. These may be major roads, quarries, industrial or farm
buildings, power lines or edges of housing development; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(6)</TD>
<TD><U>Views</U> : interesting, extensive or striking views.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="2">In addition to the attributes listed above County Landscapes
must evoke:-</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(7)</TD>
<TD><U>Strong sensory response</U> : definable in terms tending to be either
positive or extreme in character. (Other areas will tend to have a less clearly
defined image with a greater spread of descriptive terms often of a more neutral
or negative character).
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.11 The area within which the site lies was identified in the County
Council Assessment as part of the more extensive `main coastal strip', which is
described as follows:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>This type comprises a lower and less distinctive coastal landscape
found south of Sellafield towards Drigg and extending inland and northwards to
include the western outskirts of Egremont and farmland west of the A595. The two
sample sites revealed the area to be predominantly flat or undulating
agricultural land divided into large fields tending to be square in shape, with
either shelterbelts near the coast or fair hedges. The Sellafield complex and
associated developments detract from many views. The area contains attractive
blocks of deciduous woodland which to some extent mitigate the general
impression of a rather intensively managed bland landscape. However it does not
project the distinctive character which would justify its inclusion as a County
Landscape.</I>&quot; (paragraph 3.5 page 32)
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.12 This assessment was carried out against a background of growing
pressures on land for development, the desire to conserve and protect the
landscape and to identify those rural areas of Cumbria which, although not of
national importance, have a landscape quality of County importance. The
assessment was published as Technical Paper No. 4 [COR/304](7) in support of the
Joint Structure Plan.
</P>
<P>4.13 Although the scenery of the Lake District to the east can be enjoyed
from the area west of the A595(T), the landscape of the Appeal Site and its
immediate surroundings is of average scenic quality, lacking any especially
attractive features. This is particularly so when compared with the coastal
zones to the north and to the south of the Appeal Site, which lie within a
County Landscape and the National Park respectively.
</P>
<P>4.14 This overall impression is locally mitigated by the mature deciduous
woodlands and shelter belts, developed in the character of an &quot;Estate&quot;
landscape around Newton Manor, combined with the varied topography associated
with the valley of Newmill Beck and its southern tributary. These features also
create localised screening of many areas from the adverse visual influence of
the Sellafield Works which further reduces the landscape quality of the area.
</P>
<P><B>Deep Borehole Development
</B></P>
<P>4.15 The RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development is discussed in Dr Chaplow's
evidence. [<A HREF="../nrx14/nrx14.htm"><B>PE/NRX/14</B></A>]. The borehole
locations are indicated on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.3">Figure 4.3</A>.</P>
<P>4.16 The exploratory boreholes in and around the site are a temporary
development which forms part of a more extensive programme of investigation by
Nirex into the existing site conditions, and the regional geological and
hydrological setting of the site. Some 22 boreholes have been established, all
but two of which have been located outside the National Park.
</P>
<P>4.17 Within the immediate area of the proposed Rock Characterisation
Facility a series of 9 boreholes have been drilled comprising Boreholes RCF1,
RCF2, RCF3, RCM1, RCM2 and RCM3, and PRZ1, PRZ2 and PRZ3, to characterise parts
of the Potential Repository Zone. Two existing borehole sites, Boonwood and
Holmrook 13 are also being used for monitoring purposes.
</P>
<P>4.18 The sites for Boreholes RCF1 and RCF2, within the Appeal Site, will
remain to allow access to boreholes for monitoring, but the remainder are
temporary and will be restored to the original land use, generally grassland,
upon completion of the drilling works. Any adverse effects caused by the visual
impact of the drilling rigs and the disturbed surface area would, therefore, be
of short duration. The earthworks and bare soil, associated with the Borehole
sites when in use, give rise to a degree of adverse visual intrusion for
adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>4.19 In general terms the programme for restoration of the borehole sites
which pre-date the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes is well advanced. On completion of the
drilling and preliminary investigations, the well-head will be protected and
borehole sites will be restored to their original land use, generally grassland,
in accordance with individual site schemes to the approval of Cumbria County
Council.
</P>
<P>4.20 Currently earthworks restoration of Borehole 14 is complete and the
site has been returned to agriculture, while site restoration of Boreholes 8, 12
and 13 is in hand, and should be completed during the summer of 1995. Where
restoration proposals have been implemented such as in the case of Borehole 14
the residual visual effects are negligible.
</P>
<P>4.21 The boreholes rigs within the Surface Site have recently been
dismantled, but the Borehole platforms and earthworks are visible. The
earthworks associated with the boreholes currently cause localised visual
intrusion as their mass, geometric shape and bare sandstone rock or soil
surfaces contrast with the rolling topography and green pasture and do not
readily fit into the local landscape. The overall height of the earth mounding
has been restricted so that they are only visible, and therefore intrusive, at
relatively close proximity.
</P>
<P><B>The Surface Site Landscape Character and Quality
</B></P>
<P>4.22 The Baseline Landscape of the Appeal Site is illustrated in Figure 2.11
of the Environmental Statement. The landscape character and quality of the
Surface Site is described in the RCF Environmental Statement paragraphs 3.10.45
- 53, and is summarised below. It is also shown in the aerial photograph in
Figure 3.10.30 of the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>4.23 A realigned access from the A595(T) was constructed in 1993 to service
the sites of RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes, Boreholes 2, 4 and 5 and Longlands Farm
Buildings. The former narrow unsurfaced access to Longlands Farm Buildings is
now disused. In addition there is a short track leading north-west from the farm
and an open track winding across the head of the valley pasture to the
south-west. Two electricity supply lines carried on wooden poles cross parts of
the Surface Site, one leading to the farm buildings.
</P>
<P>4.24 There is a large area of dense tree cover to the west of the Surface
Site at Lingbank Plantation, including Lingbank Moor, and the Larches. Smaller
blocks of trees or shelter belts immediately adjacent to the site but lying
outside the boundary include Wet Wood and Bluebell Wood to the south and
Longwood and the Roundel further north. There are also a number of small groups
or copses of individual mature sycamore and ash trees in the valley and around
the farm buildings. New woodland shelter belts were planted as part of the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole development, early in 1994, north and east of the site
adjacent to the A595(T) and towards the south of the site. The planting of a
small woodland, north of Sides Bungalow, which was delayed pending
archaeological investigations which have now been completed, will be carried out
during the 1995-1996 planting season.
</P>
<P>4.25 Many of the hedgerows which border the fields on, or surrounding the
Surface Site are overgrown with gaps in places, and range from 3 to 7 metres in
height. There are no significant hedgerow trees. The ley pasture and arable
fields are located mainly in the more gently sloping land adjacent to the
A595(T), whilst the pasture is predominantly found around the steeper slopes of
the valley.
</P>
<P>4.26 The landscape of the Surface Site is rather more attractive than the
immediately adjacent land to the south and west, as indicated in the
Environmental Statement, paragraph 3.10.54. This is largely due to a combination
of the varied topography associated with the valley of Newmill Beck and its
southern tributary and the visual interest provided by the woodlands of the
former Newton Manor Estate, located in and around the site. These also create a
visual barrier between the Appeal Site and the detracting influence of the
Sellafield Works, and thereby mitigate the adverse effect of Sellafield on many
views from within and of the Surface Site.</P>
<P><A NAME="Description"></A><B>5. DESCRIPTION OF THE PROPOSALS
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction</B>
</P>
<P>5.1 The landscape proposals illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figures
5.1</A> to 5.3 incorporate the minor proposed amendments to the application
scheme and was considered in the Environmental Statement, and in the cross
sections in Figures 3.10.2 to 3.10.5 of the Environmental Statement. A detailed
description of the structures and phasing of the proposed development is set out
in Mr Smith's Evidence [<A HREF="../nrx1/nrx1.htm"><B>PE/NRX/1</B></A>]  I
will therefore limit my description to the landscape proposals and those
features which will have a visual effect.
</P>
<P>5.2 The landscape proposals have been designed to ensure the proposed
development can be integrated into the surrounding countryside and that any
potential adverse environmental effects have been avoided or ameliorated
wherever practicable.
</P>
<P><B>Earthworks</B>
</P>
<P>5.3 The design of the earthworks is dictated by the location of the shafts
which lie close to the steep sided valley crossing the site. The proximity of
this valley provides the opportunity to achieve a cut and fill balance in the
design of the Platform Site, by using the excavated material to raise the valley
bottom to the same level as the cut platform.
</P>
<P>5.4 During the design process for the RCF the alternative options of a
Platform Site level at 80 metres aOD and at 84.5 metres aOD were assessed to
derive the optimum base height for the Platform Site. To assist in this process
Visual Envelope Maps (VEMs) of both options were produced.
</P>
<P>5.5 A comparison of these two sets of VEMs indicated that the area of
visibility of the base platform and headgear at 84.5 metres aOD was in the order
of 1% greater than at 80 metres aOD. It was considered that the greater height
would not result in any change in the visual effect on the sensitive receptors
including settlements, residential properties, roads and areas of cultural
heritage.
</P>
<P>5.6 The 84.5 metres aOD level also offered a number of environmental
benefits over the 80 metres aOD level. The proposed landform at a level of 84.5
metres aOD level allows optimum integration to be achieved with the natural
topography, the field pattern and the existing buildings at Longlands Farm. In
particular the 84.5 metres platform level will enable the existing valley to the
south-west of the Platform Site to remain largely intact and retains the
majority of the mature trees in this area. The final restoration scheme will
also be achieved in a shorter period of time as less earth moving is required.
</P>
<P>5.7 The shorter establishment programme of the 84.5 metres aOD option will
also reduce the period during which there are potential noise and dust
emissions.
</P>
<P>5.8 It was therefore concluded that the benefits to the landscape of the
84.5 metres aOD Platform level far outweighed the resulting increase in the
visual intrusion. Following consultations with Cumbria County Council in June
1993 the 84.5 metres aOD level was selected for the Platform Site.
</P>
<P>5.9 The Platform Site will be formed by extending the existing Boreholes
RCF3 and RCF4 platform, and cutting into the side of the valley and Borehole
RCF2 platform to the north. The excavated material, including that previously
stockpiled from the excavation of the RCF/RCM Borehole platforms, will be placed
within the valley to retain the Platform Site on its south-western periphery. A
2 metre high screening bund will be formed around the south-west periphery of
the Platform Site, to screen some of the low level activity and features
associated with the development operations. This visual &quot;clutter&quot; is
often the most visually intrusive part of any development. All slopes will be
formed at stable angles, grass seeded and planted to blend in with the
surrounding landscape. The cut slopes will be formed to a depth of 3 metres in
superficial materials at a gradient of 1 in 2, above weathered sandstone at a
gradient of 1 in 1.
</P>
<P>5.10 The topsoil will be stored on the east side of the Platform Site for
eventual re-use, and provide temporary visual screening of the proposed
development from the east.
</P>
<P>5.11 Underground spoil will be disposed of within an existing field to the
west of the Platform Site, to create a new landform. This will increase the
level of the field by approximately 4 metres above existing ground level, and
will be married into the existing peripheral contours. Should the shaft be
driven below 650 metres bOD the additional spoil generated would be accommodated
within the proposed Spoil Disposal Area without increasing the overall height of
the new landform, as indicated on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>.
</P>
<P>5.12 The Spoil Disposal Area has been designed to reflect existing
topographical features and to blend with the existing landforms.
</P>
<P>5.13 Topsoil and subsoil will be formed into noise mitigation bunds along
the south-west side of the new landform, and will also serve to provide a visual
screen from nearby properties. The Spoil Disposal Area will, as it is formed, be
restored progressively for agricultural use, using the subsoil and topsoil
recovered from the existing field. The noise bund material will be spread over
the penultimate and final areas.
</P>
<P>5.14 As the earthworks including soil storage mounds and new permanent
landforms are created, they will be topsoiled as appropriate, cultivated and
grass seeded. This will stabilise the soils, thereby preventing erosion, prevent
weed contamination of the soil stockpiles and rapidly improve the appearance of
the site. Where rock outcrops are exposed they will also be seeded to mitigate
any potential visual impact an exposed rock scar would create.
</P>
<P><B>Landscape Proposals</B>
</P>
<P>5.15 A detailed description of the programme and phasing of the earthworks
is set out in Chapter 2 of the Environmental Statement, and is dealt with by Mr
Smith in his evidence to the Inquiry .
</P>
<P>5.16 The landscape proposals were designed in accordance with the principles
of design agreed with officers of Cumbria County Council, including the County
Landscape Architect and in consultation with the Forestry Commission,
incorporating their recommendations and requirements.
</P>
<P>The landscape proposals are designed to:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>provide visual screening for the development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>integrate the proposals with the existing landscape and vegetation
structure of the surrounding countryside;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>improve the landscape character and visual amenity of the local area,
through the creation of new indigenous woodlands; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>provide indigenous wildlife habitats to increase the ecological resource
for local flora and fauna.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.17 The landscape proposals, which include in total some 4.85 hectares of
new woodland planting, will be implemented in a phased programme to accommodate
the extensive earthworks programme. This is illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>. Planting Phase 1 comprises some
1.74 hectares of woodland trees and shrubs, and will be implemented during the
first planting season, to create new infill woodland blocks south of the site,
between the site access road and Borehole RCF2 platform. This will complete a
band of woodland around the site extending south-east from the access road to
Longlands Farm buildings, and from the Farm to the south and west of the site to
link with the existing mature woodland of Lingbank Moor. Planting Phase 1 also
includes temporary planting along the east and northern edge of Borehole RCF1
platform, and along the eastern edge of Borehole RCF2 platform, which will be
used as a car park for the proposed development.
</P>
<P>5.18
</P>
<P>Planting Phase 2 will be implemented on completion of the Site Establishment
earthworks and comprise a further 3.11 hectares of woodland planting around the
Platform Site, with substantial blocks of planting to the north-west, east and
south-west of the Platform Site to establish a complete woodland barrier around
the site.
</P>
<P><A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A> indicates the temporary
planting on soil storage mounds, and temporary earthworks.
</P>
<P>5.19 Also illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A> are
variations in the design arising from consultations which include a number of
minor changes to the planting proposals. The variations are largely in response
to MAFF's concern that planting should not be carried out on soil stockpiles.
Accordingly, in order to minimise any potential conflict between the need for
planting to provide medium and long term screening to mitigate the visual
effects of the development, and Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food's
concerns, a number of the stockpiles have been relocated to avoid important
planting areas. In visually sensitive areas where the stockpiles and planting
form a valuable combined screening function, the stockpiles could not be
relocated, and the requirement to retain the planting has taken precedence. The
following modifications have now been incorporated in the proposals:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>In phase 1 the proposed planting along the north-east side of Wet Wood has
been reduced to a small triangular area to link the recent block of woodland
planting south of the Borehole RCF1 site and Wet Wood. This will ensure the
woodland perimeter to the site is retained, with Wet Wood continuing to screen
the development from the south;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>A small block of Planting Phase 2 to the west of Borehole RCF1 and
south-east of the Platform Site has been omitted to leave soil storage mounds
free of planting as requested by MAFF. The planting screen around the south and
eastern periphery of the Surface Site will however be maintained by existing and
proposed planting;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>The Services in Corridor B have been located in the existing track to avoid
Bluebell Wood. To the south-west of the Platform Site a narrow north-south gap
will be created at the northern end of the extensive planting proposed on the
embankment. The alignment and location of the Services Corridor will not in any
way reduce the potential of this planting for mitigation of the visual effects
of the development; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>The additional spoil area required for material which would be generated by
a shaft depth between 650 metres and 935 metres bOD and temporary noise soil
storage mounds, designed to act as noise bunds, are also indicated.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.20 Where overhead power lines and underground service corridors cross new
planting areas, it is intended to create a woodland edge type habitat. This will
create attractive open spaces, similar to glades or rides, within the woodlands
and allow a herb rich ground cover to develop. These areas would prevent
interference with potential overhead lines while also increasing the ecological
diversity of the woodland and forming a habitat attractive to birds, small
mammals and insects.
</P>
<P>5.21 In addition it is also proposed to temporarily seed the platforms of
Boreholes 2, 4 &amp; 5, and RCF1 with a herb rich grass seed mix to soften their
appearance and create a nature conservation resource until the platforms are
fully restored.
</P>
<P>5.22 Approximately 15 trees, some 450 metres of hedgerow and some gorse
scrub within the valley will be lost as a result of the proposals, particularly
in the area of the south-west embankment to the Platform Site.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>5.23 However, approximately 4.85 hectares of woodland will be planted in
total as part of the proposals comprising mainly broadleaved species indigenous
to the area, including oak, ash, alder and birch. A small conifer and evergreen
component will be included in the planting to reinforce the screening potential
of the new woodlands during the winter months, comprising holly, pine and
spruce.
</P>
<P>5.24 The planting will be carried out in accordance with a Forestry
Commission Woodland Grant Scheme similar to that in operation for the new
planting carried out in Spring 1994. The establishment of new planting stock
will be helped by tree tubes or guards and protected by stock proof fencing,
with stiles to allow access for maintenance. Details of the proposed planting
are included in Nirex Landscape Planting and Management Plan in Report DCTT24
[COR/704](9).
</P>
<P>5.25 The hedgerow structure in and around the site will also be reinforced,
by infilling gaps in existing hedges and through the creation of new hedgerows.
The predominant species will include hawthorn, blackthorn, holly and dog rose.
Where necessary the traditional stone banks will be repaired and fencing in poor
condition replaced to protect the new planting from stock grazing the adjacent
fields. Existing and new hedgerows, when established, will be managed to
maintain a minimum height of 2 metres, in order that they can contribute to the
screening of the proposed development from adjacent roads.
</P>
<P><B>Surface Structures and Security Fencing
</B></P>
<P>5.26 The built structures on the site will include short term temporary
structures such as the tower crane with a potential height of 35 metres, the
construction headgear at a height of 25 to 30 metres, and contractor's site
accommodation. The crane will be present for a period of approximately 11
months, and may subsequently be required for the construction of the operational
headgear; the construction headgear will be present for a period of
approximately 39 months, after which they will be replaced by the operational
headgear. There will be a short duration of overlap of approximately 6 months
between the construction and operational headgear. RCF structures will include
the two operational headgear with an overall height of 29.2 metres and
associated heapsteads and winder houses, a hopper at a height of 19 metres, two
storey offices, workshop and stores and a number of minor buildings, all of
which will be on site for the remainder of the RCF Construction and Science
Programme. (Approximately 7 years in total).
</P>
<P>5.27 The design and location of the security fencing will be carefully set
out to ensure that it is not visually prominent within views from public areas.
</P>
<P>5.28 The colour of paintwork or cladding of the proposed buildings and other
structures will be dealt with through planning conditions, and by agreement with
the Planning Authority, but it is intended that a range of unobtrusive colours
will be used to minimise the visibility of the development within the landscape.
</P>
<P><B>Lighting</B>
</P>
<P>5.29 Lighting is a major concern of local residents and the local
authorities as a potentially intrusive and urbanising influence within this
rural area.
</P>
<P>5.30 The period of most intense lighting would occur over a period of 12-15
months, during the early construction period when temporary high level lighting
will be required. The number of light sources will, however, be minimised to
reduce the overall impact of the lights and opportunities will be sought to
balance lower mounting heights with the consequent increase in the number of
fittings. The lighting will be activated only when needed and be sufficient for
its purpose. However, due both to the intensity of the lighting and height of
the lanterns, the lighting will be visually significant during this period.
</P>
<P>5.31 During the operational phase of the proposed development, lighting will
be maintained at the lowest practicable illumination level consistent with the
safety and security of personnel using or visiting the RCF.
</P>
<P>5.32 Security lighting will comprise lighting to the perimeter fence which
will be illuminated with a relatively low lighting level. However at the
gatehouse on the access road higher levels of illumination will be required for
security purposes.
</P>
<P>5.33 In order to minimise the potential visual intrusion of the lighting
maximum use will be made of high pressure sodium vapour lights, which give a
softer more natural white light, and flat glass light control lanterns or &quot;spill
shields&quot;. These reduce the visibility of the light source and provide full
cut-off of the distribution of light, thereby minimising lateral and upward
light spillage.
</P>
<P><B>The Restoration Proposals
</B></P>
<P>The Restoration Proposals are illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A>.
</P>
<P>5.34 The restoration proposals aim to reinstate the landscape to reflect the
existing features, and to contribute to the nature conservation resource for the
area.
</P>
<P>5.35 The Platform Site will be regraded to reflect the original valley form,
and include steep sides to the valley with more gentle slopes rising towards
Longlands Farm Buildings. All screen bunds will be removed. The stored topsoils
and subsoils will be used to restore the Surface Site for agricultural pasture.
</P>
<P>5.36 Some temporary planting, carried out to provide mitigation of the
visual effects of the Platform Site earthworks, will be removed during the
regrading carried out as part of the restoration. This will include the planting
of the topsoil mounds along the north-west sides of the Borehole RCF1 and RCF2
Sites and that on the large embankment which extended south-west into the
existing valley. Some of the latter planting will be replaced as part of the
restoration proposals. The restoration scheme of the valley has been designed to
reflect the original slopes and existing vegetation pattern. The reuse of the
soil stock piles during restoration will result in the removal of 2.46 hectares
of immature woodland planting carried out as part of the proposed RCF
development.
</P>
<P>5.37 However the restoration proposals incorporate 2.21 hectares of woodland
planting to give a final total new woodland area of 4.6 hectares. This will link
the established woodlands, and create a more appropriate woodland framework for
the restored landform and future land use. New species rich hedgerows will also
be created on the lines of original field boundaries, in accordance with the
local style to create traditional Cumberland dykes.
</P>
<P>5.38 Nature conservation features will include herb rich grasslands. wetland
habitats, including a wet area in the base of the restored valley, scrub
vegetation on the woodland edge and a varied woodland structure, beneficial to
both flora and fauna.
</P>
<P><B>Landscape Management
</B></P>
<P>5.39 A Management Plan has been prepared to support the planning
application, which is incorporated in the Nirex Report DCTT 24 [COR/704](9) and
which was submitted for consultation to Cumbria County Council in February 1994.
The principal aim of the Management Plan is to achieve a diverse landscape
structure which is sustainable in the long term. This has been based on the
existing woodland management agreement with the Forestry Commission for the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole Planting, which also incorporates the existing woodlands
around and within the site in BNFL ownership.
</P>
<P>5.40 The Plan will also be extended to include hedgerows and scrub in
addition to new planting within a comprehensive programme.
</P>
<P>5.41 The aim of the Management Plan is to establish new planted areas which
are visually attractive, functional, of interest and value to wildlife and
sustainable in the long term, and to ensure the long term future of the existing
woodlands. The Management Plan will thus incorporate both short and long term
objectives to ensure successful establishment of the new planting.
</P>
<P>5.42 Maintenance of the new planting during the first five years following
planting is particularly important and will determine the long term success of
the new woodlands and associated habitats. The principal operations required
during this period include weed control, pruning dead or damaged material,
watering and fertiliser application as necessary, and replacement of stock which
fails within 3 years. All existing and new woodlands and hedgerows will be
protected by stock proof fencing, in order that grassland within the Surface
Site can be retained under an agricultural grazing regime wherever possible.
Grassland within the security fencing will not be available for grazing due to
operational security requirements. However these areas will be managed as herb
rich meadows to increase their nature conservation potential and interest.
</P>
<P><A NAME="EffectOnLandscape"></A><B>6. EFFECT ON THE LANDSCAPE
</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction</B>
</P>
<P>6.1 The effect of the proposed development on the landscape has been
assessed using the methodology described in Chapter 10 of the RCF Environmental
Statement [COR/101](10), which is summarised as follows.</P>
<UL>
<LI>The existing landscape in and around the Surface Site was surveyed, and
recorded;</LI>
<LI>The extent and visual nature of the development was examined at each phase
of the proposed development;</LI>
<LI>The extent of visibility of the development was determined using VEMs, for
each phase of the development; and</LI>
<LI>The area surrounding the proposed development was surveyed in order to
establish the degree and significance of the visual effects of the successive
phases of proposed development compared with a green field site.
</LI></UL>
<P>6.2 Subsequent work to assess the effects of the proposals has been carried
out, using the same methodology, to take into account design variations and to
update the earlier assessments where necessary. I have reviewed the methodology
in order to be able to make a fuller assessment of the significance of landscape
and visual effects and to consider the capacity of the countryside within which
the Appeal Site is located, to accommodate the proposed development. To achieve
this I have considered the development of the Appeal Site against the seven
criteria used by the County Council to assess the quality of the landscape,
namely landform, landcover (or vegetation cover), natural or built features,
cultural features, detractors, views and the sensory response evoked by
landscape, within which the Appeal Site lies. The first five criteria are
considered in the section on Landscape effects and the last two addressed in the
section on visual effects.
</P>
<P>6.3 The Environmental Statement concluded that the visual effects of this
development would be confined to visual intrusion, with visual obstruction not
being an important issue in this instance (Environmental Statement paragraph
3.10.25). My more recent surveys support this conclusion and my evidence will
therefore concentrate on visual intrusion. However, it should be noted that the
new woodland planting adjacent to the A595(T) will, as it matures, obstruct
existing views to the west from the A595(T) and adjacent properties. In view of
this prospect the planting was designed following local consultation and
incorporates a reduced density of trees adjacent to the A595(T), directly in
front of the Red Admiral Hotel, which will create a more open character to the
woodland at this point.
</P>
<P><B>Landscape Effects
</B></P>
<P>6.4 The effects of the development giving rise to physical changes in the
landscape will be confined within the Surface Site and comprise essentially
those effects related to landform, vegetation cover and built structures and
cultural features as follows.</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>The temporary but extensive earthworks associated with the creation of the
Platform Site; these include the filling of part of the northern section of the
small steep-sided valley required to create the south west boundary of the
Platform Site. This would result in the excavation of cut slopes up to 10 metres
deep on the north and east sides of the platform. These will however be soiled
in conjunction with the use of a Geomembrane and hydroseeded to reduce their
visual impact, and to avoid erosion. The Platform Site and valley area will
subsequently be restored, to reflect the existing landforms on completion of the
Phase 3 Science Programme, with no long term adverse effects on the landscape.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>The creation of a new landform through the disposal of excavated spoil,
which is designed to reflect a drumlin landform The new landform will thus
reflect existing topographical features, and will also be visually contained by
the surrounding mature woodlands during construction. After restoration the
proposed development would not, therefore, significantly alter the nature of the
landform characteristics of the area.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>Temporary noise and visual screen bunds designed to mitigate noise and
visual intrusion on nearby properties, such as Saddlebank and Newton Manor which
lie to the west of the Spoil Disposal Area, and further soil storage mounds
located around the Platform Site. These will be removed on completion of the
Phase 3 Science Programme, when the site is restored, to result in no long term
effect on the landscape.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>Changes in Land Cover: approximately 15 trees, 450 metres of hedgerow and
gorse scrub within the valley would be lost as a result of the development. Due
to the extent of existing areas of shelterbelts and hedgerows which would remain
undisturbed in the area, this loss is not significant. The loss would also be
compensated by the extensive new woodland planting to be carried out as part of
the proposed development, and when the valley landscape is restored on
completion of the Phase 3 Science Programme, the restoration of existing
hedgerows and the creation of new wetlands and species-rich grasslands of
potential nature conservation value. The increased variety of landcover will
thus enrich the land cover quality of the landscape in the vicinity of the site,
both in the short and long term.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v)</TD>
<TD>The structures, buildings and hardstanding areas, including a car park and
the access roads required during the Platform Site construction and operation
would introduce a significant development into the landscape of the Surface Site
for the duration of the works, and thereby substantially change its appearance
and character. However all structures are programmed to remain on site for the
minimum period necessary for their operation. All buildings and hardstandings
except for the access to Longlands Farm Buildings will be removed when the site
is restored to give no long term effects on the landscape.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>vi)</TD>
<TD>Cultural Features There are no Scheduled Monuments, Listed Buildings,
Conservation Areas, parks or gardens of special historic interest which would be
affected by the development. A small area of poorly preserved, vestigial remains
of ridge and furrow cultivation will be lost to the development, but this is of
very minor archaeological significance. This is discussed in Dr Ralston's
evidence.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>6.5 The development has been located and designed to minimise any adverse
effects on the landscape and surrounding area, with the retention of existing
mature woodland and much of the existing valley crossing the site as it extends
to the south-west. Longlands Farm Buildings will also be retained.
</P>
<P>6.6 The proposed RCF development including Surface Site restoration will
have on balance a beneficial long term effect on the landcover on the Surface
Site. The proposed planting of approximately 4.6 hectares of permanent new
woodland will make a significant, long term, contribution to the woodland which
currently enriches the landscape in the vicinity of the Appeal Site. The new
planting will also enhance the structural diversity of the woodland within the
Lingbank/Longlands area and ensure a continuity of woodland cover. The
management proposals also incorporate proposals for infilling gaps in existing
previously over-mature and neglected hedgerows and repairing hedgerow banks and
walls.
</P>
<P><B>Visual Effects
</B></P>
<P>6.7 The proposals have been designed wherever possible to mitigate adverse
visual effects caused by the Platform Site, including the buildings and
structures associated with the proposed development, using the beneficial
screening effects of the existing woodland, topography and buildings of
Longlands Farm. Nevertheless the proposals will give rise to visual intrusion,
which will be significant in a few locations due to close proximity to the
proposed development or where unimpeded views will be obtained of the
development.
</P>
<P>6.8 The assessment of the visual effect of the proposed development was
based on a detailed appraisal of the existing landscape, an examination of the
extent and degree of visual intrusion which the development will have and the
significance of these visual effects experienced from settlements and dwellings,
centres of employment, the transport infrastructure, public rights of way, and
areas of recreational amenity, which I will address in the following section of
my evidence. The effects on areas of Cultural Heritage and the Lake District
National Park are addressed in Section 7.0.
</P>
<P><B>Extent of Visibility
</B></P>
<P>6.9 The extent of visibility of the RCF was identified through a series of
Visual Envelope Maps (VEMs) prepared for the various phases of the development.
These are illustrated in Figures 3.10.20 to 3.10.24 of the Environmental
Statement. The information shown by a VEM represents a compromise between
precision in reflecting the complex detail of the visual effects and the ability
of the computer to process a large data set, and is therefore only an indicative
illustration of the potential areas from which any part of the proposed
development may be seen. Observation on the ground has confirmed that the VEMs
present very much a &quot;worst case&quot; image.
</P>
<P>6.10 In reality the screening effect of the topography (at 5 metres contour
intervals), and woodland included in the computer model is significantly
augmented by minor landscape features which are below the resolution of the
computer models. These include minor changes in landform, hedges, individual
buildings or walls, and small groups of trees and shrubs, which singly or in
combination serve to obstruct or filter views.
</P>
<P>6.11 In addition to the existing woodlands, the Platform Site will also be
partially obscured from the A595(T) in the vicinity of the Red Admiral Hotel and
the hamlet of New Mill by the immature tree planting to the west of the road, as
illustrated in the Photograph in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>.
</P>
<P>6.12 It is expected that during the next few years this planting, which is
mixed deciduous and coniferous, will develop to form a very effective screen to
the proposed development and ultimately an attractive woodland adjacent to the
road. However, within the approximately 12 year life of the development, the
planting will not form a complete screen of all structures on the site in more
elevated views from the east. An assessment of the predicted height of this
planting based on current rates of growth and Forestry Commission predicted
growth rates for the area has been carried out, in order that these may be taken
into account in the assessment of visual effects of the proposed development.
</P>
<P>6.13 A comparison of the Visual Envelope Maps indicates that, within a 5
kilometre radius, the main areas from which the proposed development will be
seen are to the south, including the B5344 and Seascale, and the higher ground
to the north-east, including Bleng Fell, Ponsonby Fell, and Cold Fell. The
taller structures of the tower crane and construction headgear will be visible
over a much wider area; the crane visible over 56% of the area within a radius
of 1 to 5 kilometres and 25% of the area between 1.5 and 5 kilometres, while the
operational headgear will be visible over 50% of the area within a radius of 1.5
kilometres and up to 23% of the area between 1.5 and 5 kilometres. The
structures will be particularly visible in the immediate surroundings of the
Platform Site including the edge of the Lake District National Park, adjacent to
the A595(T) and higher ground to the north-east and south-east.
</P>
<P><B>Degree of Intrusion
</B></P>
<P>6.14 The degree of visual intrusion is derived from the extent to which an
object is viewed within the landscape, and the perceived contrast or integration
with the existing landscape features and characteristics, in terms of its form,
line, colour, texture, and scale.
</P>
<P>6.15 The Environmental Statement concluded that the Platform Site earthworks
prior to restoration will contrast with the existing landform of the Surface
Site and surroundings, and thereby contribute to the overall visual intrusion of
the proposed development. However, following restoration the regraded landform
will reflect and be integrated into the existing landscape, with no residual
intrusion.
</P>
<P>6.16 The proposed planting will be complementary to and reflect the existing
vegetation within the existing landscape and will not therefore give rise to any
visual intrusion. As the vegetation matures it will screen the proposed
development and thereby alter existing views. However it is considered that this
effect will enhance the landscape quality of the Appeal Site and thereby benefit
the visual amenity of the Appeal Site and adjacent countryside.
</P>
<P>6.17 The main source of intrusion will be the new structures on the Platform
Site. The most intrusive features will be the tower crane at approximately 35
metres high, which will be on site for some 11 months, and more significantly
the construction headgear at 25 to 30 metres high (39 months) and subsequently
the operational headgear at 29.2 metres high (for approximately 7 years to
restoration). The operational headgear are illustrated in the photomontages of
the proposed development in the RCF Environmental Statement. [COR/101](3). These
will be tall, relatively large scale, man-made features in the Landscape, and
therefore visible over a wide area, as indicated by the VEM in Figure 3.10.24 of
the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>6.18 The tower crane, the headgear and associated larger buildings will
introduce new built structures into the landscape of the coastal strip, which
will be visually prominent from some viewpoints. Where seen, the structures will
contrast with the adjacent features of the site and the surrounding landscape,
in terms of form, line and texture, particularly when viewed against the back
cloth of rolling agricultural pasture and woodland. The contrast will however be
greatly reduced when the proposed development is viewed against the backdrop or
in the context of the considerably taller and more extensive Sellafield Works.
The Photomontage in Figure 3.10.8 of the Environmental Statement illustrates a
view of the proposed development in the context of the farm silo and large scale
farm building, with a number of poles carrying overhead cables in the adjacent
field and Sellafield in the distance to the right.
</P>
<P>6.19 There will be similarities in perceived height between the proposed
structures and the existing overhead line supports, the grain silo and the
headgear and in the mass of the proposed support RCF buildings and the large
scale farm building. However, the scale of the group of structures and built
features of the proposed development will be considerably larger than any
adjacent existing groups of buildings in the vicinity of the Surface Site. In
all views of the proposed development, however, within the wider landscape
context of the coastal strip, it will be perceived as a very much smaller
feature than the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>6.20 The scale and nature of the proposed development is such that it is
most appropriately located away from existing generally attractive villages, and
larger settlements, as is the case for most mineral operations. The existing
topography and vegetation also creates a substantial visual barrier between the
proposed development and the nearest village of Gosforth. The proposed
development therefore avoids any potential adverse effects arising from the
disparity in scale or character of the development with nearby settlements.
</P>
<P>6.21 The final design of the materials, and colour of the buildings and
other structures within the Platform Site will be agreed with the County Council
to achieve an acceptable solution. It is intended to use a range of unobtrusive
colours to mitigate the potential intrusiveness of the proposed development.
However, the colour of the proposed structures may also contrast with the
surrounding landscape, at times and from some viewpoints.
</P>
<P><B>Significance of Visual Effects
</B></P>
<P>6.22 The detailed assessment of properties was carried out within a 1.5
kilometre radius of the Platform Site as the environmental assessment found
that, beyond 1.5 kilometres, the visual intrusion would be noticeable but not
significant. The significance of the visual effects is largely related to the
potential for the development to affect views experienced and enjoyed by people
from the areas they frequent or value, including residential property and areas
of public access. The significance of any visual intrusion will also be
determined by the nature of the existing view, distance of the viewpoint,
duration of the effect, and perception of the viewer, and can be measured by the
resulting effect or change that would arise in visual amenity.
</P>
<P>6.23 The change in visual amenity may be adverse resulting from a
deterioration in the existing view or beneficial, arising from an improvement in
the existing view, and is categorised as follows:</P>
<UL>
<LI>substantial - where a significant change will occur in the view;
</LI>
<LI>moderate - where a noticeable change will occur;</LI>
<LI>slight - where a barely perceptible change will occur; and</LI>
<LI>no change - where no discernible deterioration or improvement will be
experienced in the existing view.
</LI></UL>
<P>6.24 The following section of my evidence considers the visibility of the
proposed development in the context of the existing landscape and proposed new
planting, and identifies the resulting change in visual amenity. The detailed
assessment was conducted during the environmental assessment of the scheme and
is reported in detail in the Environmental Statement. I have subsequently
verified and updated that original assessment, using the same methodology, and
expanded and quantified, where possible, the visual effects which will be
experienced from properties and key viewpoints accessible by the public around
the Surface Site.
</P>
<P>6.25 The significance of visual effects on settlements and dwellings is set
out in Table 3.10.3 of the Environmental Statement. This has been updated and
expanded in my <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>, to indicate the
effect on the visual amenity of residents. A number of properties lying outside
the 1.5 to 5 kilometres radius, from which noticeable adverse visual effects may
be experienced have been included in the schedule. Properties included in Table
3.10.3 of the Environmental Statement which will not have a view of the proposed
development are indicated accordingly. The properties identified in the schedule
and potential degree of change in visual amenity are illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A>.</P>
<P>6.26 The Schedule in my  <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>
indicates the headgear would be visible from a total of 17 properties within a
1.5 kilometre radius of the Surface Site with potential views possible from 5
additional properties available from upper storey windows and/or at oblique
angles of view. The occupiers of the 17 properties affected would experience a
change in visual amenity following implementation of the proposals, of differing
levels. The visual amenity of the 5 properties with barely discernible views
would not change.
</P>
<P>6.27 The adverse effects giving rise to a deterioration in visual amenity
will vary from substantial adverse to slight adverse depending on the nature and
duration of the view. The adverse visual effects will be reduced where the
effects of distance, and filtering from vegetation are more pronounced and also
where the views include a range of modern man-made artifacts or structures which
have a detracting influence on the existing view, and character of the scene
within the view.
</P>
<P>6.28 Substantial adverse effects will be experienced from Sides Lane in the
vicinity of Sides Bungalow. The proposed development will be visible 500 metres
from the Platform Site and although intervening vegetation will provide some
screening of the new RCF structures, they will be visible against the sky, in
silhouette. A photomontage in Figure 3.10.13 of the Environmental Statement
illustrates the proposed development from a point approximately 500 metres west
of Sides Bungalow on Sides Lane. The Sellafield Works are not visible from this
viewpoint and although the Works have an influence on the visual amenity of the
adjacent area, they will not, therefore, have a detracting influence on the view
towards the proposed development, which is shown in the Photograph in Figure
3.10.35 of the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>6.29 Substantial to moderate adverse effects will be experienced initially
in the vicinity of the Red Admiral Hotel due to the proximity of the
development. However, this effect will be significantly reduced within 5 to 7
years as the existing immature woodland increases in height, and as illustrated
in the Photomontage in Figure 3.10.9 in the Environmental Statement. The &quot;existing&quot;
view from the Red Admiral Hotel was shown in Figure 3.10.36 of the Environmental
Statement; a more recent view is illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure
6.3</A>.</P>
<P>6.30 The proposed development will also have an initially moderate adverse
effect, on visual amenity in the vicinity of Brownbank 1.7 kilometre to the
south, due to the visibility of the proposed development and the perceived
contrast with the uncluttered topography of the Cumbrian Fells, which forms the
backdrop to the view and which has few intrusive man made features. A similar
view from a point further south is illustrated in Photomontage 3.10.11 of the
Environmental Statement. However, I consider that, in time, the intervening Moss
Wood Plantation will obscure the proposed development in views from the
property, combined with the tree tops currently filtering views of the site.
</P>
<P>6.31 Similarly moderate adverse effects will be experienced from the
vicinity of Sella and Ponsonby Old Hall 1 kilometre to the north, due to the
prominence of the proposed development protruding above the horizon as shown in
the Photomontage in 3.10.17 of the Environmental Statement of a view taken from
the nearby public footpath. Sellafield is visible in the wider panoramic view
from this area, however its detracting effect is limited due to its distance
from the proposed development, and the visual separation caused by the woodland
lying between the Works and the proposed development.
</P>
<P>6.32 Moderate and slight adverse effects will be experienced at Gibb House
and Gibb Hill Farm approximately 1.5 kilometres to the north of the site. The
proposed development will be visible against the coastal plain and the Irish Sea
from this elevation. However, intervening trees and garden vegetation will
provide screening and filtering of the view particularly in the summer months.
Slight to moderate adverse effects will also be experienced from the vicinity of
Broom, where the partial screening by intervening vegetation will limit views,
although where visible the proposed development will appear in silhouette.
</P>
<P>6.33 Residents of The Moors and Ennerdale approximately 1.5 kilometres to
the south of the development will also experience a moderate and slight to
moderate effect, as the ameliorating effect of distance will be offset by the
nature of the view of the proposed development, which will be viewed against the
back drop of the Cumbrian Fells.
</P>
<P>6.34 A slight adverse effect on visual amenity will be experienced where the
observer is sited either at a sufficient distance from the proposals, where
vegetation significantly filters views, or when the Sellafield Works is dominant
in views of the proposed development.
</P>
<P>6.35 Slight adverse effects will thus be experienced at Tarn How which,
although situated at a distance of 1.7 kilometres to the south-east will
experience views of the proposed development against the skyline. Similarly
slight adverse effects will be experienced in the vicinity of Fleming Hall 0.9
kilometres to the south-west, where the distance from the proposed development
is less but the majority of the structure is obscured by landform. Haverigg
Moorside, 1.4 kilometres to the south-east will experience a slight adverse
visual effect, with a view of the top of the proposed structures on the skyline
softened by intervening vegetation.
</P>
<P>6.36 Where the proposed development would be visible but cause no
discernible deterioration in the visual amenity an assessment of no change is
recorded. This level of no change may be due to distance, the small extent of
the proposed development which will be visible, where the view embraces other
major structures, or where the Sellafield Works is visually dominant.
</P>
<P>6.37 Properties where no change in visual amenity is recorded include High
Bridge Petton, 1.6 kilometres to the south-east, which is not orientated towards
the proposed development and the effect of distance, filtering and the presence
of Sellafield in the view will result in no change to the visual amenity. Low
Boonwood, although lying only 1 kilometre to the north-east, is oriented away
from the proposed development, and will be extensively screened from the
proposed development by intervening landform, buildings and trees, with only a
small proportion of the proposed development potentially visible. Similarly
views of the majority of the proposed development will be screened by
intervening landform from Calder Town End House 1.5 kilometres to the west, with
no discernible deterioration in the overall view, and no change in visual
amenity.
</P>
<P>6.38 Seascale, approximately 2 kilometres to the south-west, will be the
only settlement affected with occasional views available of the proposed
development, from a few properties on the north and eastern edges of the
settlement. Visual effects would generally be slight to no change due to the
distance from the Surface Site and the filtering effect of intervening
vegetation, and buildings. The view from the eastern edge of Seascale adjacent
to the B5344 is illustrated in the Photomontage in Figure 3.10.7 of the
Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>6.39 The development would be visible from very few centres of employment,
the main one being the Sellafield Works situated about 2 kilometres west of the
Surface Site. However, due to a combination of distance, the character of the
Works, intervening vegetation, buildings and topography it is considered the
proposed development will give rise to no change in visual amenity for
employees.
</P>
<P>6.40 The Red Admiral Hotel and the Boonwood Garden Centre are located
adjacent to the Surface Site and employees would initially experience moderate
adverse effects in visual amenity. This will reduce through time as the immature
planting adjacent to the A595(T) increases in height, to obscure all views of
the proposed development.
</P>
<P>6.41 Views of the taller structures may be available from the top floor of
the Westlakes Hotel; however these will be perceived in the context of the
Sellafield Works and give rise to no change in visual amenity for employees, or
for guests at the Hotel.
</P>
<P>6.42 The Table at 3.10.4 in Environmental Statement indicates the potential
lengths of road and railway within 5 kilometres of the proposed development as
indicated on the V.E.Ms. However this table does not take into account
hedgerows, incidental vegetation, or structures and is considered to be an over
estimate of the potential visibility of the proposed development. The effects on
the visual amenity of travellers will also be reduced by the limited duration of
any view, and the often fragmented views that will be possible due to roadside
vegetation or structures, the changing angles of view due to the road alignment
and direction of travel.
</P>
<P>6.43 The structures and Platform Site earthworks will be visible to
northbound motorists along parts of the section of the A595(T) adjacent to the
Surface Site and from parts of an elevated section of this road some 2
kilometres to the south. The headgear and tower cranes will be visible from
sections of the A595(T) within the 1.5 kilometres and 5 kilometres radii, and
from the more elevated sections of road up to 7 or 8 kilometres to the north and
south. Beyond 5 kilometres the proposed development will have no discernible
effect on the visual amenity of motorists.
</P>
<P>6.44 The most significant effect on the visual amenity of motorists will
only occur to the south of Thornbank, where the proposed RCF structures would
become noticeable, near Bridge Petton and adjacent to the Surface Site, where
moderate adverse effects will be experienced. This will reduce adjacent to the
Surface Site as the adjacent immature planting increases in height to screen all
views from the adjacent section of road. The view from the A595(T) south of
Thornbank is illustrated in Photomontage in Figure 3.10.10 of the Environmental
Statement.
</P>
<P>6.45 The more open aspect and elevated character of the B5344 would also
make available open views of the more visually exposed southern part of the
proposed development, between woodlands and plantations. However, the adverse
effect will in part be mitigated by distance to give a slight to moderate
adverse effect on the visual amenity of motorists.
</P>
<P>6.46 The proposed development will also be visible from some minor roads and
the Sellafield Works access road, although generally over relatively short
lengths. The greatest effect of the visual amenity on motorists will be
experienced from Sides Lane as open views of the proposed development will give
rise to substantial visual intrusion.
</P>
<P>6.47 The Cumbria Coast Line railway passes over 3 kilometres from the
proposed development but at this distance there would be no discernible change
to visual amenity.
</P>
<P>6.48 The lengths of footpaths, bridleways and byways from which the proposed
development may be visible are indicated in Table 3.10.5 in the Environmental
Statement. These figures indicate that pedestrians on only short sections of
these rights of way will experience views of the proposed development, as views
are frequently constrained by hedgerows, walls and similar features. Such views
of the proposed development from occasional view points on these paths may give
rise to short term moderate or substantial adverse effects on the visual amenity
of footpath users due to the nature of the view, which is dependant on the
direction of movement, and also fragmented by intervening vegetation and
structures.
</P>
<P>6.49 Travellers on the bridleway alongside Sides Lane will thus experience
substantial adverse effects due to the proximity of the Platform Site and the
silhouetting of the proposed headgear and associated buildings against the
skyline. Travellers on the stretch of public footpath immediately to the north
of Ponsonby Old Hall will also experience moderate adverse effects on their
visual amenity, over that section of footpath with open views of the proposed
development.
</P>
<P>6.50 The proposed development will be visible from parts of Seascale Golf
Course against the backdrop of Cumbrian Fells. This will have an adverse effect
on this particular view, offset to some degree by the ameliorating effect of
distance, as shown in Photomontage in Figure 3.10.14(a) of the Environmental
Statement. However within the wider context of the landscape setting of the Golf
Course, the proposed development would not change the visual amenity of users of
the Golf Course.
</P>
<P>6.51 Similarly the proposed development would occasionally be seen by
visitors and users of the Cumbrian Cycleway, recreational footpaths and areas of
public access on the western edge of the Lake District National Park. However in
most cases this would give rise to only a slight deterioration in the view and
would not therefore significantly harm the visual amenity of these areas.
</P>
<P>6.52 Users of Ponsonby Farm Park, a recent attraction developed at Ponsonby
Old Hall, would be able to see the taller structures in filtered views between
the existing vegetation; these may have a slight adverse effect on the visual
amenity of the views but would not impinge on the appreciation or enjoyment of
the Farm Park.
</P>
<P>6.53 The visual assessment indicates that the visual intrusion and effect on
visual amenity would generally not be significant apart from a few locations in
close proximity to the site. Similarly the visual effects of the proposed
development on facilities such as playing fields, visitor attractions, the
cycleway and recreational footpaths would not detract from the appreciation or
enjoyment of these activities.
</P>
<P><B>Night time Effects of Lighting
</B></P>
<P>6.54 Lighting within and around the site is to be maintained at the lowest
practicable illumination level consistent with the safety and security of
personnel using or visiting the RCF.
</P>
<P>6.55 The use of high pressure sodium vapour light, and flat glass, full
cut-off light control lanterns or baffles will also minimise the light spillage
and generally obscure from view the light source from all but the high mast and
headgear lights. High pressure sodium lights also produce a pinkish white light
which has a more natural colour, similar in character and colour to moonlight
and domestic lighting.
</P>
<P>6.56 Some lighting particularly during the early construction period will be
visible from the A595(T) and residential properties in the vicinity of the
Surface Site, and highlight the presence of the proposed RCF development within
this rural area. However, the extent of visual intrusion arising from the
proposed lighting is likely to be limited and of relatively short duration.
</P>
<P>6.57 The potential visual intrusion of the lighting at night should however
be considered in the context of the existing background light, sources and more
particularly widespread impact of light emanating from the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>6.58 The lighting at the Sellafield Works is different in nature to the
general lighting of the coastal strip in two respects. Firstly the Sellafield
Works appears as the single biggest illuminated area along this part of the
coast, and secondly the concentration and intensity of light at the Works is
unlike anything else in the area and draws the eye away from all other features.
The colour of the lighting is also generally in contrast with that used in the
locality, being of an orange colour rather than the &quot;domestic&quot; white
light which predominates elsewhere within the countryside.
</P>
<P>6.59 In night time views of the Sellafield Works, from the open fells to the
east of the proposed development, the Sellafield Works appears to have an even
greater concentration of lighting than a town such as Whitehaven, which can also
be seen from these locations.
</P>
<P>6.60 Within this context, the permanent lighting of the proposed RCF
development will be relatively subdued with only significant local effects on
properties such as the Red Admiral Hotel, Sides Bungalow and Brownbank which are
close to the proposed development. Properties with open views of the site access
could also experience an effect due to the higher levels of lighting required at
the gatehouse. Sides Lane and properties on the B5344 to the south of the
proposed development, although more distant from the Platform Site, will
experience effects since these locations have the clearest views of the proposed
development yet have no, or limited, views of the Sellafield Works save for the
orange glow in the sky at night.
</P>
<P><B>Visual Effects of Traffic
</B></P>
<P>6.61 The proposed development will give rise to some increase in traffic on
the A595(T) and as the traffic enters the Surface Site and follows the site
access road, which will have a visual effect in localised views of these roads.
On the A595(T), the RCF traffic will comprise an intensification of the existing
traffic on the road which is, at busy times, already visually intrusive. However
this is unlikely to change the degree of visual intrusion caused by traffic on
the A595(T) to any discernable extent. On the access road the traffic may give
rise to some minor visual intrusion to residents and users of footpaths with a
view of the road. However, the new planting along the A595(T) and adjacent to
the access road, reinforced by the proposed new planting, will screen all cars
and much of the Heavy Goods Vehicles within 5 to 7 years and thereby mitigate
any adverse visual effects.
</P>
<P>6.62 The effect of the traffic is likely to be more noticeable during the
dark or dim winter mornings and afternoons, when the loom of car headlights
above the level of hedgerows, the earthmounds and the woodland planting will
draw attention to its presence.
</P>
<P><B>Visual Influence of The Sellafield Works
</B></P>
<P>6.63 In order to assess fully the significance of any visual effects of the
proposed RCF development these must be considered in the context of the visual
prominence and adverse visual influence of the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>6.64 A VEM of the Sellafield Works towers and chimneys has been produced to
identify the extent of visibility and the potential area within which the
Sellafield Works has a detracting or adverse influence on the scenic quality of
views within the landscape. The VEM was produced using the same base
topographical and vegetation data used for the VEMs of the RCF, and illustrated
in Figures 3.10.20 - 24 of the Environmental Statement. From this a composite
VEM has been produced which illustrates the extent of potential visibility of
any part of the Sellafield Works cooling towers and chimneys only, the area of
overlap between these features and any part of the proposed RCF headgear, and
the areas of potential visibility of the proposed RCF headgear where the
Sellafield features are not visible. This is illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A>. As previously noted the Visual
Envelope Map is a broad indication and generally presents the worse case.
</P>
<P>6.65 A comparison of the VEMs indicates that the Sellafield Works has a much
broader VEM and potential field of visual influence, and that, apart from a few
localised exceptions, all areas of visibility of the RCF coincide with areas of
visibility of the Sellafield Works.
</P>
<P>6.66 Both the Sellafield Works and the proposed RCF would be viewed from a
number of areas within the two distinct landscape zones of the undulating
farmland of the coastal strip, and the open fells of the Lake District National
Park to the east of the Surface Site.
</P>
<P>6.67 Within the main coastal strip with which both the Sellafield Works and
the proposed RCF are located, there is considerable variation in the detailed
character of the landscape, which is reflected in the variation in topography
from 0 metres aOD at the coast to 120 metres aOD east of Thornhill where the
area abuts the lower fells. (This is illustrated in
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>).
</P>
<P>6.68 The lower lying land below 30 metres aOD along the coast, within which
the Sellafield Works is located, is more open with relatively little woodland or
tree cover, and small, or relatively gentle variations in landform.
Notwithstanding the great height of the cooling towers and chimneys, within this
area the great scale and bulk of the Works and associated power lines have a
high level of visibility in both near and distant viewpoints.
</P>
<P>6.69 In contrast the proposed development lies within a localised area of
considerably more varied topography ranging from 60 to 120 metres aOD, with a
higher proportion of woodland and tree cover than most of the main coastal
strip. The detailed landforms, woodlands, and incidental tree groups in and
around the Surface Site will provide screening and visual containment of much of
the proposed RCF development. Where potential viewpoints could occur, views are
often restricted as a result of localised features, such as sunken lanes and
roads, walls, and hedgerows.
</P>
<P>6.70 Where locations do afford open views of the proposed RCF development
the buildings, headgear and other structures will generally be perceived against
or in the context of the adjacent woodlands, which also comprise a large scale
feature in the landscape.
</P>
<P>6.71 In addition the majority of views of the proposed development also
encompass the Sellafield Works. Where locations do afford open views to the
proposed development, the viewer can almost invariably see the Sellafield Works.
In these instances it is the greater mass of the Sellafield Works rather than
the proposed development which will catch the eye. One of the few exceptions is
the area immediately to the south of the Platform Site from the B5344 and Sides
Lane. In this area direct views to the Sellafield Works are screened by the
local topography, whilst there are direct views towards the proposed
development. As one travels west along Sides Lane towards Fleming Hall and along
the B5344 towards Brownbank, clear views of the Sellafield Works once again
dominate the skyline.
</P>
<P>6.72 Views from the open fells begin at about 5 kilometres from the Platform
Site, at which point the whole coastal strip becomes visible. At this distance
the proposed RCF development would not generally be more noticeable or visually
significant, than other relatively large scale or visually significant features
within the main coastal strip, and would become one more man made feature
amongst many within this landscape. The Sellafield Works, which covers an area
several times greater in area than the proposed development, and which contains
buildings and structures considerably greater, in both number and scale, than
the proposed RCF development, would continue to be the visually dominant feature
within this part of the main coastal strip.
</P>
<P><B>Summary of Effects
</B></P>
<P>6.73 The physical effects of the proposed development, will be localised to
the landscape of the Surface Site, and mitigated through the design of the new
landforms and temporary earthworks, and by the existing and proposed planting.
After the restoration is completed the permanent changes to the landform and
more particularly the new planting will give rise to minor localised changes,
some of which are beneficial, in the general landscape character of the Surface
Site and immediately adjacent area. There will thus be no long term diminution
in the quality of the landscape as a result of the proposed development.
</P>
<P>6.74 However, the large scale on-site structures would be temporary, with a
limited life in total of about 12 years. They will not therefore, in the long
term, be detrimental to the general visual amenity of the area.
</P>
<P>6.75 The effect on the landscape character of the wider countryside of the
main coastal strip within which the development will be located, will not be
significant. The landscape character of the main coastal strip is influenced by
ongoing change and development which in this area includes:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>the growth of villages and towns for residential and employment purposes,
and associated number and density of services such as overhead lines;</LI>
<LI>incidental development appropriate to or requiring an open countryside
location, or development which might not be deemed appropriate within a
designated landscape such as the Lake District National Park, or County
Landscapes;</LI>
<LI>development which is subject to topographical constraints or a coastal
location such as the Sellafield Works with its associated electricity pylons and
the railway; and</LI>
<LI>the type of agriculture and farm management which is determined by land
quality and topography.
</LI></UL>
<P>6.76 The form, density and character of such land uses and development
within the countryside of the main coastal strip are generally quite different
to equivalent land uses, where they exist, within the adjacent areas designated
for their landscape quality, and afforded protection from development in the
National Park, and to a lesser degree the County Landscapes. These differences
serve to heighten the contrast in landscape character and scenic quality between
the coastal strip and the adjacent protected landscapes, in which the overall
rate and nature of change is constrained. The latter are also acknowledged to be
generally more sensitive to change, and therefore more susceptible to a
diminution in landscape quality as a result of change or development within
their landscapes.
</P>
<P>6.77 The open countryside of the main coastal strip is characterised by more
intensive patterns of land use and development, including the examples
illustrated in <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>, and thus less
sensitive to further changes arising from development. I therefore consider that
the countryside within which the Appeal Site lies could accommodate the change
that would arise with the proposed development, without any diminution of the
intrinsic character or quality of the surrounding landscape.
</P>
<P>6.78 The proposed development would not, in my view, lead to any change in
the County Council's assessment of landscape quality of the Appeal Site and
surrounding area based on the criteria set out in Technical Advice Note No. 4.
[COR/304](7).
</P>
<P><A NAME="EffectOnPark"></A><B>7. EFFECT ON THE LAKE DISTRICT NATIONAL PARK
</B></P>
<P>7.1 The County Council has expressed concern, in the grounds for refusal of
the Planning Application for the proposed RCF development, that the RCF Appeal
Site lies close to the Lake District National Park and considers that it would
be detrimental to the present characteristics and qualities of the National
Park. However I would endorse the conclusions of the assessment in the
Environmental Statement which states in paragraph 3.10.9 &quot;Overall effects
on the landscape and visual amenity of the Lake District National Park and
surrounding areas are considered to be minor&quot;. The Appeal Site is shown on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>.
</P>
<P>7.2 The natural beauty of the Lake District National Park is derived from
the great variety and unspoilt nature of the landscape, and the dramatic
contrasts that occur between the upland fells and mountainous screes, the lakes
and tarns, the wooded slopes and more extensively farmed pastures of the valley
bottoms.
</P>
<P>7.3 However, the intrinsic characteristics and qualities of the National
Park encompass more than scenic beauty. That the perception of the landscape is
not just a visual experience was recognised by the Countryside Commission in
their guidelines to Landscape Assessment (1987) which state:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>Perception itself is not simply a matter of seeing with the eye.
All the five senses are involved in an appreciation of landscape beauty</I>&quot;.
(Landscape Assessment, a Countryside Commission Approach 1987, CCD 18, para
3.7).
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.4 The ambience of a landscape, which may change according to the seasons
and weather conditions, and our emotional and intellectual response to the
landscape are thus equally important. In the context of modern urban life one of
the most valued characteristics and qualities of the Lake District Landscape is
its sense of remoteness or isolation and, beyond the villages and lower valleys,
appearance of unspoilt wilderness.
</P>
<P>7.5 It is this aggregated experience and appreciation of the particular
characteristics and qualities of the landscape of the Lake District which
rightly deserves the protection of the National Park - and which attracts the
numerous visitors on which the tourist industry of the Park is based.
</P>
<P>7.6 In the vicinity of the Appeal Site, the landscape at the margin of the
National Park comprises a fairly broad band of gently undulating agricultural
land, extending to the west of the A595(T), in which the Appeal Site is located,
and which flows across the National Park Boundary to form a transitional zone
between the characteristic landscape of the Lake District and the coastal plain.
</P>
<P>7.7 This transitional landscape was identified as a single character zone
(16 - Lingbank/Longlands area) in the baseline study carried out in 1990 and
encompasses a broad band between the valleys of the River Calder and Blengdale,
straddling the A595(T) where it forms the National Park boundary and extending
some 2 kilometres into the Park. This is indicated on
<A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A> of my Evidence, and illustrated
in photograph in Figure 3.10.33 of the Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>7.8 The physical and visual characteristics of the landscape within this
zone are those of the rolling farmland typical of the higher, eastern portion of
the &quot;main coastal strip&quot; identified in the Technical Paper No. 4
[COR/304](7) which was restricted to land outside the National Park. On both
sides of the National Park boundary the land is more intensively farmed than the
higher more open land to the east. The farms are similar in character on both
sides of the boundary with their associated land uses and outbuildings including
recent large scale units of modern materials and construction.
</P>
<P>7.9 In the context of the western fells the character of this part of the
National Park which is degraded by the detracting effects of the A595(T) and
open views towards Sellafield, is in marked contrast to the adjacent minor
valleys, and more particularly nearby Wasdale, Eskdale and Butterdale which have
the attractive scenic qualities and characteristics typical of the Lake
District. It is also notable that the County Assessment did not consider the
area west of the A595(T) and adjacent to the National Park boundary to be
sufficiently attractive or distinctive to justify its designation as a County
Landscape, even though an area of similar landscape east of the A595(T) lies
within the National Park.
</P>
<P>7.10 The Platform Site is centrally located within this transitional
landscape and will therefore be clearly associated with the characteristic
landscape of the main coastal strip and not that of the National Park, notable
for its scenic qualities, and quite special ambience.
</P>
<P>7.11 Wherever boundaries are drawn on a plan, one side of which is
designated as protected and of high value, and the other less so, it is
inevitable that views from the designated area - such as the National Park will
include less attractive landscape. They will also include views of developments
containing features and artifacts which may not be considered acceptable within
the designated area of higher landscape value, but which of necessity need to be
located within the locality and within the countryside. Such development should
of course be designed to respect and where appropriate enhance the local
countryside within which they are sited. However, the content and nature of
these views do not necessarily harm the character, quality and ambience of the
designated landscape.
</P>
<P>7.12 An example of a development which lies outside the National Park but
which is viewed from within the Park is that of the 15 wind turbines at Kirkby
Moor - Lowick High Common. At the time of the Planning Application the site lay
within an Area of Great Landscape Value which is now a County Landscape. In fact
the Inspector could find no marked difference in the quality of the landscape of
the development site, to the south of the A5092(T), which forms the boundary of
the National Park and that to the north, within the Park.
</P>
<P>7.13 In his letter of consent for the windfarm the Secretary of State
considered that</P>
<P> ... &quot;<I>although the site is close to the National Park and in
similar countryside, it is not situated in a nationally designated area of
landscape importance. The windfarm would be readily seen from part of the Park
but will not directly affect the Park's appearance or character&quot; ... &quot;it
is appropriate to consider the proposal therefore only as one situated in an
area designated by the County Structure Plan as one of Great Landscape Value</I>&quot;;</P>
<P>- which were considered to be potentially acceptable locations for
windfarms, while National Parks are not.
</P>
<P>7.14 Views from the National Park which incorporate the Appeal Site will
also encompass the coastal plain of the main coastal strip, in which the
Sellafield Works forms the predominant man made feature. The proposed
development will thus be seen in the context of this landscape setting, and will
therefore be perceived as a medium sized built element within a wide landscape
panorama along with other modern and relatively large-scale built elements
including farm storage buildings, silos, electricity pylons, and other overhead
lines which lie between the several settlements within the area. Examples of
such elements are indicated on <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>.
</P>
<P>7.15 At distances over 2.5 kilometres the surface details of the development
will not be discernible and, although visible in part, it will not appear as an
alien element out of scale or character within its landscape context. This is in
stark contrast to the Sellafield Works which does not sit easily within the
landscape, as illustrated in the photograph in Figure 3.10.32 of the
Environmental Statement.
</P>
<P>7.16 Significant viewpoints within the National Park include:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>the elevated moorland including Cat Bields/Nether Wasdale Common, Stone
Pike/Wheel Fell and Cold Fell at distances of between 5-10 kilometres. The
development will also be visible from Irton Pike and in filtered views between
the trees on Irton Fell, at a distance of some 6.5 kilometres and as illustrated
in Photomontage 3.10.18 in the Environmental Statement;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>The elevated access roads, bridleways and footpaths below the moorland,
from which intermittent views can be obtained, such as those from Gibb Hill Farm
and Hurlbarrow. The extent of the visibility of the development and its effect
on views from these locations is dependent upon intervening/obstructing features
such as buildings, walls, hedgerows or other vegetation and the angle of the
road and the direction of the traveller. This type of view is generally from a
distance of 1.5 kilometres or more, and is illustrated by the Photomontage in
Figure 3.10.16 of the Environmental Statement.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>Localised views will be obtained from isolated properties within 1.5
kilometres of the development at Ponsonby and adjacent to the western boundary
of the National Park at New Mill, Boonwood and including the Red Admiral Hotel.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>7.17 The visual assessment of the proposed development presented in the
Environmental Statement indicates that the visual effect of the proposals on the
National Park will be small. The main elements of the proposed development which
will be seen in views from the National Park are the upper portions of the tower
crane, the construction and subsequently the operational headgear. Much of the
Platform Site and smaller buildings will be screened by topography or existing
trees and woodland areas.
</P>
<P>7.18 The proposals will therefore give rise to some visual intrusion for
properties, footpaths and access roads on the western boundary of the National
Park. The relative scale and degree of this effect is lessened within the
context of existing adverse effects arising from the traffic on the A595(T) on
these properties. In addition any adverse visual effect arising from the
proposed development will be temporary, due to the limited life of the RCF which
will be completed and restored within some 12 years from commencement of work on
site.
</P>
<P>7.19 There will be panoramic views from the more elevated access roads,
footpaths and bridleways within the cultivated pastures between the A595(T) and
the fells. The proposed RCF structures will be more visible within these views,
although generally seen in the context of the existing mature woodland and
buildings at Longlands Farm, due to the closer proximity and lower elevation of
the viewpoints. Although there may be an adverse effect from specific
viewpoints, which have an open view directly towards the proposed development,
the overall effect on visual amenity will generally be slight, particularly
where such views encompass the visually prominent Sellafield Works. The effect
of the proposed development in views from more distant parts of the National
Park would give rise to no change in the visual amenity.
</P>
<P>7.20 Views of the National Park which will encompass the proposed RCF
development are restricted to those obtained from properties, roads and
footpaths to the south-west and west of the proposed development, where the RCF
will be seen with the Lakeland fells as a backdrop. Most views of the proposed
development from these locations will also be partly screened by the intervening
landform and belts of tree planting such as Moss Wood. In views from the B5344,
Brownbank, the outskirts of Seascale, and properties between Seascale and
Sellafield such as How Farm and Seascale Hall, only the upper portion of the
tower crane and headgear will be visible. In these views the proposed
development will appear relatively insignificant when seen against the dramatic
panorama of the high fells. Although the immediate local scenery within such
views may be adversely affected, this will not in any way affect the perceived
quality of the Lake District landscape. The change in visual amenity will
therefore be slight.
</P>
<P>7.21 Although the proposed development will be located near to the boundary
of the Lake District National Park, and will be visible from the National Park,
it will not be prominent, apart from a number of viewpoints in close proximity,
and will not directly affect the appearance or special characteristics and
qualities, particularly associated with the landscape of the National Park. I
therefore consider that the proposed RCF development will have no significant
effect on either the character or landscape quality of the National Park,
neither will it have any discernible effect upon the visual or recreational
amenity of the National Park.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Consultations"></A><B>8. CONSULTATIONS
</B></P>
<P>8.1 Prior to the submission of the Planning Application and Environmental
Statement regular Consultations were held with the Cumbria County Council, and
their consultant advisors, Copeland Borough Council, and the Lake District
Special Planning Board, through the Nirex Liaison Group.
</P>
<P>8.2 In particular, consultations have been held and the agreement of the
local authorities has been obtained, to the landscape design principles, the
methodology of the landscape assessments, and the planting details and final
draft of the Landscape Management Plan.
</P>
<P>8.3 During the consultation period following submission of the planning
application Cumbria County Council received many representations from interested
organisations and individuals.
</P>
<P>8.4 The representations which related solely to landscape and visual amenity
issues, or which made reference to them in addition to raising a number of other
points, were a relatively small proportion of the total number. Approximately 20
letters out of many hundreds received to date made specific reference to the
importance of the scenic quality of the Lake District and the potentially
adverse effect of the RCF proposal on this local resource, or expressed concern
about the close proximity of the proposed development to the National Park, and
the potential adverse impact on landscape and tourism.
</P>
<P>8.5 These letters were almost exclusively quite general in their concern
that the RCF was an unsuitable development to be located close to the Lake
District National Park. Only two letters expressed specific concerns about the
effect of the proposals on the visual amenity enjoyed by local residents.
</P>
<P>8.6 In many cases the concern for the effect of the RCF on the scenic
quality of the National Park is linked with the perception that the proposed
development could have an adverse effect on local tourism, and the reputation of
the Lake District as a holiday destination.
</P>
<P>8.7 The majority of correspondents concerned with landscape and visual
amenity were local residents. The Cumbria Tourist Board were principally
concerned over the visual impact of the proposed development and its effect on
tourism. One local small business was concerned about the adverse effect the
proposal would have on the tourist trade. One local resident expressed specific
concern over the visual impact of the security fencing and built structures
being an incongruous development within the landscape. There were no
representations clearly expressing specific concern about the impact of the
proposed development on the local landscape, as separate from the regional or
National Park landscape.
</P>
<P>8.8 The Friends of the Lake District considered that the design of the
buildings would be &quot;discordant and alien in the landscape&quot;, expressed
concern at the impact of lighting within this rural area, and considered the
proposed development would be inappropriate within this landscape. Concern was
also expressed at the adverse impact of the proposed development on the visual
amenity of public rights of way and it was noted that &quot;overhead power lines
would be visually intrusive&quot;.
</P>
<P>8.9 Although Gosforth Parish Council recommended refusal, if the proposed
development is approved the Council require conditions to be imposed to minimise
environmental impacts. Their additional requirement for a management plan and
control of weeds is addressed in the Management Plan [COR/704](9) which has
already been prepared for the Surface Site. Concerns expressed by the Parish
Council that lighting use should be controlled to maximise energy saving will be
addressed by the design and operational approach to the lighting of the site.
</P>
<P>8.10 The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (MAFF) have expressed
concern at the use of topsoil mounds as temporary planted mounds, to provide
screening of the proposed development and the practicality of removing these
trees after about 12 years without damage to the topsoil resource. The mounds
will serve a valuable function in mitigating the potential adverse visual
effects of the proposed development in giving greater immediate height to the
proposed screen planting. The planting is also required to provide vegetative
screening or masking of the mounds themselves. Where appropriate the mounds have
been redesigned or relocated to minimise the amount of stored topsoil which will
be temporarily planted.
</P>
<P>8.11 MAFF also requested clarification of which area will be managed for
quality agricultural pasture and which for rough grazing and nature conservation
interests. These areas are differentiated on my <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figures
5.1</A> and <A HREF="nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.3">5.3</A>.
</P>
<P>8.12 I have demonstrated in my evidence that the proposed development will
not have any significant effect on the Lake District National Park, although
some small areas within the Park will experience some visual intrusion from the
proposed development, nor will the proposed development adversely affect the
overall landscape character and quality of the surrounding countryside or the
National Park.
</P>
<P>8.13 Although the proposed buildings will be large in scale they will be
designed to minimise any visual intrusion, through the use of unobtrusive
colours, to harmonise and merge with the existing landscape when viewed from
some distance. The proposed buildings and other structures will also be
temporary in nature. 9
</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>9. CONCLUSIONS
</B></P>
<P>9.1 A series of landscape and visual assessments of the proposed development
have been carried out, which have been updated during the refinement and
development of the proposals. The methodology for these assessments is set out
in full in the &quot;Approach to Landscape Assessment&quot; (Nirex Report 375)
[COR/702](2) and the RCF Environmental Statement (1994). [COR/101](3).
</P>
<P>9.2 The Appeal Site lies within the undulating farmland of the coastal
strip, adjacent to the boundary of the National Park. The baseline studies
indicated that the site lies within a landscape character zone of rolling
farmland, between the Calder Valley and Gosforth, which straddles the A595(T),
and thus extends into the National Park. The quality of the eastern part of this
zone was upgraded in the VRM assessment due to its location within the National
Park, while the quality of the western part of the zone remained low due to the
adverse visual influence of Sellafield. The landscape of the central part of the
zone within which the Appeal Site is located is extremely varied and enclosed by
the topography, raised field boundaries and woodland areas which restrict views
within this area.
</P>
<P>9.3 The landscape and visual assessments carried out for the Environmental
Statement concluded that the long term effect of a temporary RCF development on
the surrounding landscape within this landscape character zone, would not be
significant.
</P>
<P>9.4 The RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes were developed in and around the Platform Site
of the proposed development, and have given rise to some visual intrusion
arising from the earthworks and the borehole rigs. The visual effects are
variable, according to the stage of development and proximity of the view to
each borehole site, but are not considered to be significant in the context of
the character of the existing landscape. The restoration of the Nirex Deep
Borehole Sites is now well advanced and the visual effects of these are further
diminishing as the restoration programme proceeds.
</P>
<P>9.5 The Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan recognises the wide
variety and generally high quality of the landscapes within the County and this
is reflected in the high proportion of the land that is afforded special
protection through designation as National Park, or County Landscape.
</P>
<P>9.6 It is therefore significant within this broader context of high
landscape quality that the Appeal Site and its immediate surroundings are not
subject to any special designation in the Cumbria and Lake District Joint
Structure Plan or The Copeland Local Plan. The landscape quality of the wider
area of the main coastal strip is in fact relatively mundane, lacking any
distinctive qualities or character. The Sellafield Works and other development
also detract from the quality of the landscape, although this is locally
mitigated in the vicinity of the Appeal Site by mature deciduous woodlands and
shelterbelts.
</P>
<P>9.7 The landscape effects of the proposed development of the RCF have been
assessed against the landscape attributes considered by the County Council, in
the review of the County Landscape carried out to identify those areas of
sufficient quality to be designated County Landscapes. This assessment
demonstrated that the proposed RCF development would have no overall adverse or
beneficial effect on the landscape assessment and should therefore result in no
change to the County Council's assessment of the quality of the landscape of
this area.
</P>
<P>9.8 Within the constraints of the Appeal Site and the engineering and the
operational requirements, the proposed development seeks to achieve an
environmentally acceptable scheme. The proposals include detailed measures to
minimise any adverse effects of the development on, and to integrate the
development into the surrounding landscape with the retention of local existing
features within the landscape, including the mature woodlands, and much of a
minor valley crossing the Surface Site and Longlands Farm.
</P>
<P>9.9 Accordingly the landscape proposals include in total some 4.6 hectares
of permanent new woodland to be planted in a phased programme under a Forestry
Commission Woodland Grant Scheme, similar to that in operation for the 1994-95
RCF/RCM/PRZ Borehole Planting. The Scheme will also include new hedgerow
planting and infilling of existing hedgerows, which will be maintained at a
minimum height of 2 metres in order that they may contribute to low level
screening of the site from adjacent views.
</P>
<P>9.10 Nirex have already undertaken extensive planting of new mixed deciduous
and evergreen woodland planting on land adjacent to the Surface Site. This,
along with the substantial new woodlands which form part of the RCF proposals,
will completely surround the proposed development with woodland to visually
contain the Platform Site. The woodland will also increasingly provide a
valuable ecological resource and habitat, both during the operations and
following the restoration of the Surface Site.
</P>
<P>9.11 Similarly the herb rich grassland, improved hedgerows and hedgebanks,
and wetland features which form part of the landscape proposals will have a
beneficial effect through the enrichment and extension of the ecological
potential of the area for wildlife, particularly after restoration of the
Surface Site, and help to integrate the proposals into the surrounding
landscape.
</P>
<P>9.12 The landscape proposals will be maintained and a Management Plan
executed to ensure an attractive, functional and diverse landscape structure is
achieved, that is of interest and value to wildlife and sustainable in the long
term.
</P>
<P>9.13 The variations to the proposed development have been assessed and I
consider that the minor modifications to the planting proposals and storage of
topsoil and subsoil mounds, in response to consultations with MAFF, will not
give rise to any discernible changes in the effects of the development on the
landscape. Any potential variation down to a depth of 935 metres bOD would give
rise to a greater volume of spoil but without a significant increase in the
effect on the landscape. The additional spoil created would be accommodated
within the Spoil Disposal Area which is sufficient to accommodate the full range
of spoil arisings that could be generated from any development between 650
metres bOD and 935 metres bOD. The delay in the overall programme will have a
beneficial effect arising from the extended growing period for the existing
immature tree planting, which will increase its size and screening potential.
</P>
<P>9.14 The proposals have been designed to mitigate the effect of the
development upon the topography of the Appeal Site and the visual effects of the
structures. The Surface Site layout also seeks to avoid where possible direct
impact on features of the landscape or areas of ecological interest, and has
been refined to mitigate indirect effects. The main physical effects of the
development on the landscape have been identified and include:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" ALIGN="CENTER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">i)</TD>
<TD>the effect on the local topography of the temporary but extensive
earthworks associated with the creation of the Platform Site;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>ii)</TD>
<TD>the creation of a new landform by disposal of excavated spoil;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iii)</TD>
<TD>the temporary noise and visual screen bunds;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>iv)</TD>
<TD>the introduction of temporary hardstandings, buildings, cranes, headgear,
and access roads, into the landscape; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>v)</TD>
<TD>the loss of some trees and hedgerows within the valley.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>9.15 Although the permanent changes to the landform will not affect the
character of the surrounding landscape, the proposed planting will increase the
area of woodland, thereby making a long term beneficial contribution to the
landscape character. The addition of these substantial new woodlands, and
improved hedgerows will extend the beneficial effects of the existing mature
woodlands, altering and enriching the landscape character of the area
immediately to the east, south and south-west of the Platform Site. The proposed
development will thus, in the longer term, enhance the quality and setting of
the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>9.16 The area of countryside within which the site lies also contains the
Sellafield Works, the railway and overhead power lines, and has already been
affected by development of a larger scale or &quot;industrial&quot; character,
to a greater extent than the rest of the coastal strip, beyond the boundaries of
the settlements of Egremont and Whitehaven. It could therefore, more easily
accommodate the proposed RCF development than other more open and less vegetated
parts of the countryside, where significant structures and large buildings may
be perceived to be inappropriate to the landscape character of the area.
</P>
<P>9.17 The visual effect of the proposed development has been assessed in
relation to the extent of visibility, the degree of visual intrusion, and its
significance in terms of the effect on the visual amenity experienced from
settlements and dwellings, centres of employment, the transport infrastructure,
public rights of way, areas of recreational amenity, and features of Cultural
Heritage. The most intrusive features will be the temporary structures
comprising the tower crane, the construction headgear and the operational
headgear, which will be most visible within the immediate surroundings of the
Platform Site.
</P>
<P>9.18  Of the 17 properties at which a deterioration in visual amenity will
be experienced, a significant deterioration was recorded for only 3, with a
noticeable deterioration recorded for 9 and a perceptible change recorded for a
further 5. The only settlement affected will be the eastern edge of Seascale.
The only centres of employment affected will be the Red Admiral Hotel and
Boonwood Garden Centre, where an initially moderate effect on visual amenity
will reduce as the development is increasingly screened from view by the
maturing tree planting adjacent to the A595(T).
</P>
<P>9.19 The adverse effect on the visual amenity of users of the railway,
roads, public footpaths and areas of recreational amenity will be slight other
than for a few locations in close proximity to the site, on Sides Lane, the
A595(T), and from nearby elevated viewpoints to the east. There will also be no
significant effect on the settings of any Ancient Monument or Listed Building,
due to the effect of topography and existing woodlands which screen all but the
top of the tallest structures.
</P>
<P>9.20 The Platform Site has been located to achieve a balance in minimising
disturbance to the existing landscape and maximising the screening effect of the
existing topography, the mature woodlands, and the buildings of Longlands Farm.
However the proposed development would introduce substantial features into the
countryside which would give rise to some visual intrusion. This would be of
limited duration and, apart from a few locations, in close proximity to the
Platform Site, the change in the visual amenity of the surrounding area would be
slight. These effects would decrease as the screening potential of the new
woodland and proposed planting becomes increasingly effective throughout the
life of the development.
</P>
<P>9.21 There are few locations in the area where views of the proposed
development would not also include the Sellafield Works which, because of its
scale and impact, would reduce the visual significance of the proposed RCF.
However the cumulative visual effect of the proposed RCF development and the
existing Sellafield Works is not considered to be significant as the overall
visual intrusion of the proposed development will be low. In addition the
existing woodland and topography will create a natural barrier between the
proposed RCF development and the Sellafield Works which will ensure that the two
developments are perceived as separate from one another. Where there will be
open views of the proposed development from the south-west, the existing views
do not encompass Sellafield.
</P>
<P>9.22 The assessment of the night time effect of the lighting associated with
the proposed development indicated that the design of the lighting scheme and
the use of high pressure sodium, light control lanterns will minimise the extent
of visual intrusion arising from the lighting. The resulting pink/white &quot;haze&quot;
will appear subdued and give rise to only slight levels of intrusion when
perceived in the context of the bright orange light and widespread glow of the
Sellafield Works. The most intrusive elements would be high level lighting
required during the construction period but this will be in limited use and of a
relatively short duration. The higher levels of lighting required at the
security gate may also be visually intrusive. However this will be a localised
effect and, due to the proximity to the A595(T), will lie within a broad
corridor also affected by vehicle headlights. The proposed lighting will
therefore not give rise to significant overall levels of visual intrusion.
</P>
<P>9.23 The proposed RCF structures, although dissimilar in use or detailed
character will, in distant views, relate in scale to other features in the
existing landscape. They will also be considerably smaller in scale than the
towers and chimneys at the Sellafield Works, which are visually dominant in most
views due to the west facing aspect of the landscape.
</P>
<P>9.24 I therefore consider that in view of the relatively low overall level
of visibility of the proposed development, the existing landscape context which
contains other man made features and the limited impact the proposed development
will have on the visual amenity of the area, the features of the proposed RCF
could be accommodated within this part of the countryside without significant
adverse impact, or harm to the character and quality of the overall landscape of
the main coastal strip.
</P>
<P>9.25 Concern has also been expressed at the effect of the proposed
development on the characteristics and qualities of the Lake District National
Park. However the proposals lie to the west of the A595(T) which forms the
National Park Boundary and will not therefore directly affect the landscape of
the National Park.
</P>
<P>9.26 Although dissociated from the Sellafield Works by the intervening
countryside and substantial blocks of woodland, most views of the proposed RCF
from the Lake District National Park and adjacent areas will also encompass or
lie within the broader context of views of the Sellafield Works, which is the
predominant man-made feature in the area. Whenever the Sellafield Works is
encompassed within a view, the complex arrangement of towers draws the eye away
from other lesser structures which become insignificant by comparison, and
therefore of no consequence within the view. Thus in the panoramic views from
the National Park which contain the Sellafield Works, the visual significance of
the proposed RCF development will be small.
</P>
<P>9.27 The area of the National Park which lies close to the site is affected
by other intrusive features such as the A595(T) and the associated traffic. It
is therefore less vulnerable and susceptible to changes arising from new
development than more remote areas, with the special landscape character and
quality more typified by or generally associated with the Lake District.
</P>
<P>9.28 Although the proposed development will be visible from the National
Park, it will not be prominent, except from viewpoints in close proximity, and
will not directly affect the appearance or special characteristics and
qualities, particularly associated with the landscape of the National Park. I
therefore consider that the proposed RCF development will have no discernible
effect on the visual or recreational amenity of the National Park.
</P>
<P>9.29 I consider that the proposed scheme addresses the concerns expressed by
members of the public, raised during the consultation period. It seeks to
achieve an acceptable environmental design, with measures to minimise any
adverse effects of the development on the landscape of the open countryside and
Lake District National Park.
</P>
<P>9.30 I also consider that the proposed development will not have a
significant adverse effect on the character and quality of the surrounding open
countryside. The beneficial effects of the extensive new woodlands will
eventually enhance the quality of the landscape of the Appeal Site and
surrounding area, and compensate for the small loss of vegetation resulting from
the proposed development. Similarly, although the proposed development lies
close to the boundary of the Lake District National Park it will not be
detrimental to the present landscape characteristics and quality of the National
Park.
</P>
<P>9.31 It is accepted and acknowledged by Cumbria County Council, that
considerable measures have been taken in the siting of the development and in
the design of the landscape proposals including earthmounding and new planting,
and that the scheme has been designed as far as practicable to minimise the
effect of the proposed development on the landscape. The design will continue to
be refined as the details are developed. The proposed development has sought and
continues to seek a balance between the interests of ecology, archaeology,
agriculture and effects on the landscape, and the operational needs of the
development. In particular the potential physical and visual effects on the
landscape character and quality of the surrounding area have been limited and
will be reduced over time as the new and proposed woodland planting becomes
established and matures.
</P>
<P>9.32 I therefore conclude that, although the proposed development would give
rise to some visual intrusion and localised adverse effects on the landscape,
these would be temporary and would in the long term be offset by the beneficial
effects on the landscape of the new woodlands and enriched vegetation cover in
and around the Appeal Site. The proposed development would not therefore
diminish the intrinsic character or quality of the surrounding landscape, or
give rise to any long term demonstrable harm to the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P><A NAME="References"></A><B>10. REFERENCES</B></P>
