<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD><A HREF="../nrx2ix.htm">Back to NRX2 Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../poe.htm">Back to POE Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. INTRODUCTION
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1 Six photomontages were prepared as supporting illustrations by P.
Radmall in his Proof of Evidence. I have examined these photomontages to verify
their accuracy as illustrations of the proposed Rock Characterisation Facility.</P>
<P>1.2 It was evident, during a site examination of the copy of the photographs
attached to the proof of evidence, that substantial alteration to the originals
had occurred during the creation of the photomontages reducing their quality,
definition and detail.
</P>
<P><B>2. ANALYSIS OF THE PHOTOMONTAGES
</B>
</P>
<P><B>2.1 Figure 4c - Predicted view from footpath north of Moss Wood
</B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD>This presents the proposed RCF structures on the skyline in front of
Longlands Farm and Wet Wood.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>a.</TD>
<TD>The image of the RCF is wrongly positioned in the horizontal plane being
located too far to the right and in front of Wet Wood.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>b.</TD>
<TD>The RCF structures are drawn larger than they should be.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>c.</TD>
<TD>A small block of woodland adjacent to Sides Lane and middle ground
vegetation has been obscured with &quot;green grassland.&quot;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>d.</TD>
<TD>Telegraph poles have been painted over or lost in the photograph.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.2 I consider that figure 4c does not accurately represent the potential
view of the proposed RCF and exaggerates the potential visibility and visual
impact of the proposed development as follows: 
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The RCF would appear smaller.
</LI>
<LI>The lower buildings would be screened from view by the proposed and
existing land-forms.
</LI>
<LI>The view of the proposed development would be mitigated by existing middle
ground vegetation.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>2.3 Figure 4d - Predicted view from access track to Tarn How.
</B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD>Figure 4d presents the proposed RCF development behind the site of borehole
2. Wet Wood appears on the skyline to the right of the proposals.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>a.</TD>
<TD>The image of the horizontal position of the RCF is slightly to the right
and the vertical position is elevated.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>b.</TD>
<TD>Due to the mislocation of the image of the RCF, structures other than the
headgear and hopper are shown breaking the sky line.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>c.</TD>
<TD>Telegraph poles in the locality of the RCF have been lost from the image.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>d.</TD>
<TD>The green colour illustrating grass and indicating the earthworks to the
platform site has been extended upwards too far and applied over sky and
background woodland.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.4 As with figure 4c I consider the potential view for the proposed RCF in
figure 4d has been exaggerated; only the top of the head gear and tip of the
hopper will be visible above the sky line, and would be seen in the context of
other man made features.
</P>
<P><B>2.5 Figure 4e - Predicted view from footpath north of Hurlbarrow farm</B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD>Figure 4e presents the proposed RCF development against a faded backdrop of
Seascale and adjacent area with the Sellafield works extending along the skyline
to the right.</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>a.</TD>
<TD>The image of the RCF has been wrongly positioned in the horizontal plane,
and is located too far to the right.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>b.</TD>
<TD>The RCF structures have been shown larger than they would appear.
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.6 The proposed RCF would be partially obscured by Longlands Farm buildings
and associated trees with the lower buildings screened by intervening land-form.
It would be seen against the backdrop of Seascale and adjacent area which is on
the horizon.
</P>
<P><B>2.7 Figure 4f - Predicted view from bridleway at Gallows Hill 
</B></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD>Figure 4f illustrates the proposed RCF shaft headgear and hopper on the
skyline, with the Sellafield Works filling the skyline to the left of The Cop
woodland. Gosforth forms the middledistance view to the right and to the east,
the location of the A595, can be identified by a white truck.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.8 At this distance over 2km any differences or errors become marginal.
Seen in the wider panoramic view from this viewpoint the tops of the structures
would be perceived within the relatively developed landscape of the coastal
strip.
</P>
<P><B>3 Summary
</B>
</P>
<P>3.1 All the images of the RCF in Photomontages 4c to 4e have been
exaggerated either in scale, vertical position or inaccurate placement in front
of intervening land-form. Horizontal positioning is also inaccurate.</P>
<P>In addition the landscape context in which the RCF is perceived and its
relationship to its manmade features is not adequately represented due to loss
of definition and detail in all the photomontages.</P>
<P><B>4. CONCLUSIONS
</B>
</P>
<P><A NAME="Para4.1"></A>4.1 In view of the inaccuracies in scale, location
and details shown, I believe that the illustrations shown in Mr Radmall's
figures 4c, 4d, and 4e should not be relied upon for the purpose of assessing
the nature and extent of the visibility of the proposed RCF structures.
</P>
<P><B>5. VISUAL ENVELOPE MAPS
</B>
</P>
<P><B> 5.1 Figure4a - Visual Envelope</B><BR><B>Figure 5a - Comparative
visual envelope of RCF and Sellafield Complex.
</B></P>
<P>5.2 The visual envelopes shown in Mr Radmall's figures 4a and 5a have a
number of differences to the visual envelopes in my figure 6.2. These are due in
part to the different computer model used but mainly to the difference in base
information.
</P>
<P>5.3 Mr Radmall's figures 4a and 5a are based on topography with no
consideration of the screening effect of the major blocks of vegetation, which
are taken into consideration in my figure 6.2. The information shown in figure
6.2 still presents a &quot;worst case&quot; but maybe used to indicate a general
potential area of visibility of any part of the RCF shaft headgear and the
cooling towers and piles of Sellafield.
</P>
<P>5.4 In reality the information used in the computer model is significantly
augmented by minor landscape features such as land-form, hedges, small groups of
trees or shrubs, individual or groups of buildings and walls, which singly or in
combination serve to obstruct or filter views.
</P>
<P>5.5 Furthermore the Sellafield visual envelope in Mr Radmall's evidence is
based on only one cooling tower. As the cooling towers are spread over a
distance of approximately 1km, the information in Mr Radmall's figure 5c will
give a distorted and significantly underestimated visual envelope compared with
my figure 6.2.
</P>
<P>5.6 I do not consider therefore the information in Mr Radmall's figures 4a
and 5a present an accurate or realistic indication of even a worst case visual
envelope of either a proposed RCF development or the Sellafield Works.</P>
<P></P>
