<HEAD>
<TITLE>PE/NRX/2/S2 - LANDSCAPE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG SRC="../../images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex Logo">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B><FONT SIZE="5">PE/NRX/2/S2</FONT></B><BR></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="2">Appellant Ref: DB/CD 8.5.1</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">LPA
Ref: 4/94/9011</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">DOE Ref: APP/HO900/A/94/247019</FONT><BR><BR></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">UNITED KINGDOM NIREX LIMITED</FONT><BR></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Rock Characterisation Facility</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="4">Longlands Farm, Gosforth, Cumbria</FONT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PROOF OF EVIDENCE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">OF</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Mrs S R WILSON</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="4">BA, Dip LD, FLI</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">LANDSCAPE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">EVALUATION OF</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">MR P RADMALL'S ORIGINAL</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PHOTOGRAPHY AND AMENDED</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PHOTOMONTAGES</FONT></B><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD><A HREF="../nrx2ix.htm">Back to NRX2 Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../poe.htm">Back to POE Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1. INTRODUCTION</B></P>
<P>1.1 At my request I have been provided with photocopies of the photographs
from which the photomontages 4c, 4d, and 4e were compiled. I shall refer to
those photographs as photographs 4C, 4D and 4E.</P>
<P>1.2 I have also been provided with copies of Mr Radmall's amended
photomontages 4c,4d, and 4e.</P>
<P>1.3 I have analysed the information in both the copies of the photographs
and the amended photomontages and make the following observations.</P>
<P><B>2. Photomontage 4c.</B></P>
<P>2.1 The amended photomontage locates the RCF structurces further to the
left. However the structures are still shown too far to the right.</P>
<P>2.2 The correct position of the South Shaft headgear can be clearly
identified by the drilling rig which was located on Borehole RCF3 and which is
just visible in photograph 4C immediately to the right of the woodland block
extending from the left hand side of the photograph. (Bluebell wood and The
Larches).</P>
<P>2.3 In my cross examination by Mr Drabble I agreed to his statement that
only the hopper and the two shaft headgear would be visible. The detailed
examination of photograph 4C indicates that this would not be true. If the South
Shaft headgear were located in the correct position the hopper would be hidden
behind Bluebell wood. This can be verified from the accompanying location plan
for photomontage 4c.</P>
<P>2.4 The correct horizontal location would also place the two shaft headgear
behind the intervening vegetation, which is illustrated as partially screening
the hopper in the amended photomontage 4c, and to the left of the position of
the hopper.</P>
<P>2.5 The intervening vegetation and landforms would thus screen all
buildings, save for the upper part of the two shaft headgear.</P>
<P>2.6 Mr Radmall, in paragraph 4.6 of his evidence refers to the illustration
of the proposed RCF in the original photomontage 4c as follows:-</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>(para. 4.6)   &quot;As one moves further south the major structures of the
RCF will remain a prominent skyline feature, screened intermittently by
vegetation and by undulating terrain&quot; (e.g. 3.10.11)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;It is more dramatic in our Figures 4c and 4d&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.7 However, I consider that a correct illustration of the proposed RCF,
from the viewpoint from which the photomontage is depicted, would appear less
visible than that illustrated in the Environmental Statement Figure 3.10.11, as
the hopper would not be visible and much of both shaft headgear would also be
screened from view. The RCF structures would therefore not appear more dramatic
than the illustration in Figure 3.10.11.</P>
<P>2.8 The proposed shaft headgear would have a localised visual effect and be
perceived in the locational context of the existing woodland and the
agricultural landscape of the coastal strip. To the left of the view lie the
farmhouse and large scale buildings of Fleming Hall farm.</P>
<P><B>3. Photomontage 4d</B></P>
<P>3.1 In the amended photomontage the horizontal location of the RCF
structures is unchanged. However the lower buildings have been located behind
the foreground ridge instead of being cut into the ridge.</P>
<P>3.2 The RCF structures are still located slightly too far to the right.</P>
<P>As with photomontage 4c the correct position of the shaft headgear can be
clearly identified in the photograph by the drilling rig which marks Borehole
RCF3. This is located at the position where the left edge of the winder house is
illustrated in the amended photomontage.</P>
<P>3.3 The unchanged location appears to place the RCF structures closer to the
viewpoint and therefore too high in the landscape. All the buildings save for
part of the shaft headgear and hopper would be obscured by intervening
vegetation including the hedge on top of the existing ridge and the adjacent new
planting (at an estimated height of 4 metres).</P>
<P>3.4 The Platform Site earthworks would be wholly obscured by the existing
topography and vegetation.</P>
<P>3.5 Considerably fewer of the RCF structures would thus be visible than
illustrated in Mr Radmall's original photomontages which he describes as &quot;more
dramatic&quot; than the Environmental Statement Figure 3.10.11.</P>
<P>3.6 Furthermore the RCF structures would be viewed in the context of the
characteristic features of the agricultural landscape of the coastal strip
including the numerous overhead lines, and on the distant skyline the Red
Admiral Hotel and traffic on the A595(T).</P>
<P><B>4. Photomontage 4e</B></P>
<P>4.1 In the amended photomontage the RCF structures appear to be in
approximately the correct horizontal position in relation to Longlands Farm
buildings, to the left of the original position.</P>
<P>4.2 However, the RCF structures have been shown too high in relation to the
Longlands Farm woodlands. These are at an elevation of approximately 91 to 100
metres aOD, and 11 to 18 metres high. This would give a top of canopy height of
111 metres aOD. The top of the RCF headgear would be 113.7 metres aOD. Thus the
trees would be a similar height to the RCF structures, and as they lie in front
of the RCF structures their relative height would appear higher. Similarly the
top of the shaft headgear would appear lower than the ridge of the Red Admiral
Hotel which is approximately 118 metres aOD.</P>
<P>The relative heights of the shaft headgear, Longlands Farm buildings and the
Red Admiral Hotel are illustrated in drawing number 008808.</P>
<P>4.3 None of lower buildings would be visible as depicted in the amended
photomontage.</P>
<P>4.4 The RCF structures would be largely screened in this view by the
Longlands Farm buildings and trees. That portion of the RCF structures which
could be visible would be lost against the backdrop of the built up area of
Seascale.</P>
<P>4.5 In the preparation of the photomontages the position of a development is
not a question of interpretation but should be accurately plotted by the
computer techniques adopted by Mr Radmall in his Appendix C, and checked or
plotted against an Ordnance Survey map. Thus if one draws a line on a plan
between the view point and the proposed development, the RCF is clearly found to
be in line with, and behind the Longlands Farm buildings.</P>
<P>4.6 The Longlands Farm buildings and associated vegetation can be readily
identified on site, if necessary with the aid of binoculars, and from this
location would obviously contribute to the screening of the proposed RCF.</P>
<P>4.7 In Mr Radmall's evidence he refers to the original photomontage 4e as
follows:-</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;...our figure 4e, in such views the RCF retains its prominence.
accentuated by its contrast with the rural foreground and by the possibility of
appearing in silhouette against the distant sea.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;4E also demonstrates the ability of the RCF to introduce a new focal
point into views which are channelled towards the site along valleys framed by
the surrounding terrain.&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>4.8 The partially screened RCF structures will not create the focal point
illustrated in 4e which appears to show not just the headgear and hopper but the
top of most of the lower buildings which would be obscured by the existing
landforrn into which the Platform Site is cut, and vegetation.</P>
<P>4.9 Even in Mr Radmall's 4e the RCF would be viewed against a backdrop of
the built up area Seascale of which lies on an elevated landform. The coastline
beyond is not evident, nor is the sea, in the photograph or photomontage.</P>
<P>4.10 The RCF in its correct position, screened by landforrn, with the taller
structures partially screened by the existing Longlands Farm building and tree
groups would not be prominent; there is no possibility from this viewpoint that
the RCF structures would appear in silhouette against the distant sea.</P>
<P><B>5. Conclusion</B></P>
<P>5.1 In view of the inaccuracies in Mr Radmall's amended photomontages I have
no reason to alter my conclusions in <A HREF="nrx2s1.htm#Para4.1">paragraph 4.1</A>
of my Supplementary evidence
<B>PE/NRX/2/S1</B>.</P>
<P></P>
