<P><B>Dr. GEOFFREY MICHAEL JACKSON will say:</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A>
<B>1.  PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P>1.1  I hold a Bachelor's degree (with Special Honours) in Physics, a Masters
degree in Applied Acoustics and a Doctorate in Applied Acoustics, from the
University of London. I am a Fellow of the Institute of Acoustics, a Member of
the Institute of Physics and a Chartered Physicist. I am a Chief Acoustics
Consultant with WS Atkins Noise and Vibration, a division of WS Atkins
Consultants Ltd.</P>
<P>1.2  I have worked in acoustics for over 25 years, being concerned with
transportation and environmental noise for most of that time. During that time I
have given evidence to many Public Inquiries involving the effects of various
types of development involving construction plant and the generation of noise by
heavy vehicles.
</P>
<P>1.3  I have been involved with the noise aspects of the site investigations
process for a repository since late 1989 and have visited the area on a number
of occasions.  I presented noise evidence at the Public Inquiry in November 1992
into the drilling of exploratory geological boreholes in the Lake District
National Park.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2.  SUMMARY</B></P>
<P><B>Reasons for refusal of Planning Permission</B></P>
<P>2.1  Cumbria County Council cite general environmental issues as one of the
grounds for refusal. Noise and vibration are not specifically mentioned. The
Secretary of State also wishes to be informed of the environmental impact of the
proposed Rock Characterisation Facility ('RCF') at Longlands Farm.</P>
<P><B>Scope of Evidence</B></P>
<P>2.2  This evidence considers noise and vibration standards and planning
guidance most applicable to this type of development. Comparison is also made
with noise conditions attached to currently approved borehole permissions.
</P>
<P>2.3  Noise level surveys have been conducted in the area around the Appeal
Site in order to establish the existing noise climate under a range of
atmospheric conditions. Vibration surveys have also been conducted at the
closest property.</P>
<P>2.4  Predictions of noise and vibration levels during the various phases of
the development have been made and compared to the measured existing levels, and
national and international standards.</P>
<P><B>Noise Legislation and Guidance</B></P>
<P>2.5  The noise guidance most appropriate to the early stages of the
development is that contained in MPG11 [GOV/111]<SUP>11,12,13</SUP>  relating
principally to long-term open cast and similar quarrying activities. MPG11
recommends a daytime free-field limit of 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq, lh </SUB> and notes
that even in particularly quiet rural areas there is no need to set daytime
limits any lower than 45 dB L<SUB>Aeq, lh</SUB>. A night-time limit of 42 dB L<SUB>Aeq,
lh </SUB> is also suggested.</P>
<P>2.6  These MPG11 limits are generally in accordance with those cited by the
World Health Organisation ('WHO'), of 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq, lh</SUB> externally
during the day and 35 dB L<SUB>Aeq, lh</SUB> internally at night, corresponding
to an external night-time limit no lower than 40 dB L<SUB>Aeq, lh </SUB>
[GOV/122]<SUP>8 </SUP>.
</P>
<P>2.7  PPG &quot;Planning and Noise&quot; [GOV/108]<SUP>2</SUP>, in relation
to long term noise conditions for new housing, suggests that noise should not be
considered as a planning issue when the external free-field level during the day
is less than 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq
</SUB>and less than 45 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> at night.</P>
<P>2.8  By way of comparison, the maximum free-field levels allowed by the
Planning Permissions for the drilling phases of the RCF/RCM Boreholes on the
Appeal Site are 47 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>,<SUB> lh</SUB> during the day and 40 dB
L<SUB>Aeq, lh</SUB> at night. The night-time standard equates to the WHO
recommendation, but the daytime limit is 8 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> more stringent
than that recommended by the WHO and PPG24, and 2 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> more
stringent than the MPG11 standard for particularly quiet rural areas.</P>
<P><B>Vibration Legislation and Guidance</B></P>
<P>2.9  British Standard 6472 [GOV/903]<SUP>16,17</SUP> recommends residential
limits for day and night-time periods, for both continuous and impulsive sources
of vibration. The acceptable levels for up to 3 blasts in each period are 8.5
mm/sec and 2.8mm/sec respectively. If the number of blasts were to increase, the
acceptable vibration levels reduce, depending upon the duration of the blast.
Even for 5 blasts a night, each of 10 seconds duration, the acceptable level is
1 mm/sec. The corresponding daytime acceptable level is 3.1 mm/sec.</P>
<P><B>Existing Noise Conditions</B></P>
<P>2.10  Noise levels in the area around the Appeal Site have been periodically
surveyed using fully calibrated equipment. The main surveys were conducted
between the Autumn of 1989 and Spring 1992 with repeat measurements in June1995.
These surveys were concentrated into periods having wind speeds generally below
the average of 4.5 m/sec for the area, thus biasing the average of the
measurements towards the lower end of the range of levels currently experienced.
Algorithms have also been developed relating background noise levels to
windspeeds and the presence of trees, bushes and hedges.
</P>
<P>2.11  Measured daytime background levels in the areas closest to the Appeal
Site are typically in the mid 30s to low 40s dB(A), dropping to typically the
upper 20s to upper 30s dB(A) at night.
</P>
<P><B>Existing Vibration Conditions</B></P>
<P>2.12  Ambient groundborne vibration levels have been measured at the closest
property to the Appeal Site. Background levels were typically 0.0005 mm/sec,
increasing to about 0.01 mm/sec during the passage of a tanker on the A595(T).
</P>
<P><B>Future Noise Conditions</B></P>
<P>2.13  Noise levels emanating from the Appeal Site will be greatest during
the initial levelling phase of the development. This work will not be conducted
at night. At only the closest 2 or 3 properties will the L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels
marginally exceed the average of the measured existing levels. These predicted
levels will be lower than the long-term daytime limit of 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
recommended in PPG24 [GOV/108]<SUP>2</SUP> and by the WHO [GOV/122]<SUP>8</SUP>
and in most instances the long-term minimum level of 45 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
recommended in MPG11 [GOV/111]<SUP>13</SUP> for particularly quiet rural areas.
Similar levels would be produced during restoration of the Surface Site.</P>
<P>2.14  As foreshaft construction, shaft sinking and gallery construction
progress, noise from the site will reduce, with predicted L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
levels approximating to or being lower than the typical measured background
levels. Although these activities will take place as 24-hour underground
operations, the noisiest activity of soil disposal, will only take place during
the daytime. The only night-time source of continuous noise will be the
ventilation fan.</P>
<P>2.15  The fan will continue as the only source of day and night noise during
the Science Programme. Resulting noise levels will be no more than 15 dB L<SUB>aeq</SUB>
at the nearest property, so satisfying the WHO night-time criteria and being
well below the measured night-time background level.</P>
<P>2.16  Additional traffic on the A595(T) will, even during the busiest stage
of the development, increase noise levels by less than 1 dB L<SUB>A10, 18h</SUB>.
</P>
<P><B>Future Vibration Conditions</B></P>
<P>2.17  Even during near surface blasting, vibration levels will be well below
those recommended in BS6472[GOV/903]<SUP>16</SUP>.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusions</B></P>
<P>2.18  It has been shown that the site levelling stage of the development
would generate the most noise, but be restricted to daytime working only. These
noise levels would satisfy all current planning guidelines and authoritative
advice. For the majority of the properties in the vicinity of the Appeal Site
and for most of the lifetime of the development, the daytime noise levels would
also satisfy recommended night-time noise criteria.</P>
<P>2.19  Additional traffic would have no discernable effect upon noise levels
at properties adjacent to the A595(T).</P>
<P>2.20  Vibration levels from even near-surface blasting would satisfy the
recommendations of BS6472.
</P>
<P>2.21  There are therefore no noise or vibration grounds upon which to
justify the refusal of planning permission.
</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3.  INTRODUCTION AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE</B></P>
<P>3.1  United Kingdom Nirex Limited ('Nirex') is carrying out a series of
investigations around Sellafield in order to ascertain the area's suitability
for an underground repository for solid, intermediate and low level, radioactive
waste. As part of that series of studies Nirex has identified the need for a
Rock Characterisation Facility ('RCF') at Longlands Farm.</P>
<P>3.2  This evidence considers the noise and vibration levels which are likely
to be experienced at potentially sensitive properties in the area and at
properties alongside the A595(T) in the vicinity of the Appeal Site. Where
relevant the evidence considers the effects resulting from changes to the
original RCF planning application.
</P>
<P>3.3  Predicted noise and vibration levels are compared with existing
measured levels in the area and with local, national and international standards
and guidance.</P>
<P><A NAME="Description"></A>
<B>4.  DESCRIPTION OF UNITS AND PREDICTION METHODS</B></P>
<P>4.1  This section outlines some of the factors that affect the perception of
noise and vibration. This will aid in the interpretation and appreciation of the
significance of the predicted levels.</P>
<P><B>Human Hearing and Noise Units</B></P>
<P>4.2  The human ear is less sensitive to low and high frequencies than to mid
frequency sounds. For this reason, noise levels are usually expressed in dB(A)
units, resulting from a frequency weighting network having similar
characteristics to the human ear. The smallest noise change that is generally
detectable by an individual is about 3 dB(A), while a 10 dB(A) increase
corresponds, subjectively, to an approximate doubling of loudness.
</P>
<P>4.3  Noise levels generally fluctuate with time and can be described by
various percentiles. For example, the L<SUP>A1</SUP> level is the dB(A) noise
level that is exceeded for 1% of the measurement period and approximates to the
maximum level. L<SUB>A10</SUB> is the level exceeded for 10% of the measurement
period and is the conventional statutory descriptor for road traffic noise. The
background level, often defined as the L<SUB>A90</SUB> level, is the level
exceeded for 90% of the measurement period. The noise unit used for the
assessment of 'mixed' and some specific noise sources is the L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
level. This unit takes account of the fluctuating nature of noise and represents
the equivalent steady noise level that contains the same acoustic energy as the
actual fluctuating level.</P>
<P>4.4  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table4.1">Table 4.1</A> lists a number of &quot;everyday&quot;
noise levels and will aid in the interpretation of the predicted levels.</P>
<P><B>Traffic Noise Assessment</B></P>
<P>4.5  Research into the effects of road traffic noise has shown a reasonably
good correlation between community responses and the noise levels when expressed
as the average of the 18, 1-hourly L<SUB>10</SUB> dB(A) noise levels between
06.00 and 24.00 hours. This unit has been validated as a predictor of noise
annoyance at many sites having 18 hour L<SUB>10</SUB> noise levels between
about 45 and 85 dB(A).</P>
<P>4.6  The noise level changes associated with changed traffic flows on
existing roads are governed by changes in the total flow, the percentage of
heavy vehicles greater than 1525 kg (30 cwt.) and the average speed. Because of
the logarithmic relationship between the traffic flow and L<SUB>10</SUB> noise
level, large changes in traffic are needed to produce measurable changes in
community response. For example, with speed and percentage of goods vehicles
held constant, a doubling of the total flow would be needed to produce an
increase of 3 dB(A), while a 1 dB(A) change would correspond to an approximate
20-25% change in traffic flow.</P>
<P><B>Noise Propagation</B></P>
<P>4.7  Various factors affect the propagation of noise between a source and
receiver, especially when their separation is in excess of a few hundred metres.</P>
<P>4.8  Across acoustically hard ground the noise level from an acoustic &quot;point&quot;
source of noise attenuates at a rate of about 6 dB(A) per doubling of distance.
Depending upon the type of acoustically absorbent or &quot;soft&quot; ground and
the average height of noise propagation, the attenuation rate may increase to
typically 7 to 9 dB(A) per doubling of distance. A source of noise may be
considered as being a &quot;point&quot; when the observation distance from it is
large compared to the physical size of the source.</P>
<P>4.9  Landforms, buildings, earth bunding or other solid objects that cut the
sight line between the noise source and receiver have the potential to reduce
noise levels. When the obstruction just cuts the line of sight, noise levels	 
are reduced by about 6 dB(A). The practical upper limit for barrier attenuation
is between about 15 and 20 dB(A), depending upon the height of barrier and
topography of the site.</P>
<P>4.10  Atmospheric stability, wind speed and direction may have an effect
upon the propagation of noise over large distances. The difference between up
wind and down wind levels may be 10 to 20 dB(A), although for speeds of about
2m/s the difference is nearer 5 dB(A).</P>
<P><B>Noise and Sleep</B></P>
<P>4.11  Research has shown that the ability to get to sleep and, when asleep,
the probability of experiencing a change of sleep state or ultimately of
awakening are related to both the ambient and peak levels at the ear of the
sleeper. <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table4.2">Table 4.2</A> gives, for a range of
internal peak noise levels, an indication of the probability of either being
awakened or of experiencing a change in sleep state (defined as a change in the
electroencephalographic (EEG) response) for a typical population [NRX/3/1]<SUP>1</SUP>.
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table4.2">Table 4.2</A> also shows the probabilities
quoted by the World Health Organisation ('WHO').
</P>
<P>4.12  These internal peak noise levels may be translated into corresponding
external levels. Single glazed windows, when closed, produce a noise reduction
of typically 20 dB(A). When partially open their attenuation reduces to about 10
dB(A) and to about 5 dB(A) when wide open. Well fitting closed factory sealed
thermal double glazing units produce reductions of typically 25 to 30 dB(A).
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A> indicates the external peak noise
levels corresponding to different probabilities of awakening, for various window
types and degrees of ventilation.</P>
<P><A NAME="Legislation"></A>
<B>5.  LEGISLATION AND GUIDANCE</B></P>
<P><B>PPG24 - Planning and Noise, 1994</B></P>
<P>5.1  Planning Policy Guidance Note 24 [GOV/108]<SUP>2</SUP>, published in
September 1994, defines various Noise Exposure Categories (NECs) to aid planning
authorities when considering the acoustic suitability of an area for new
dwellings. The defining noise levels, expressed in terms of free-field L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
levels should be representative of typical conditions.</P>
<P>5.2  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> summarises the advice
with respect to &quot;mixed&quot; sources, defined as any combination of road,
rail, air and industrial noise sources.</P>
<P>5.3  PPG24 [GOV/108]<SUP>3</SUP> states that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The NEC procedure is only applicable where consideration is being
given to introducing residential development into an area with an existing noise
source, rather than the reverse situation where new noise sources are to be
introduced into an existing residential area. This is because the planning
system can be used to impose conditions to protect incoming residential
development from an existing noise source but, in general, developers are under
no statutory obligation to offer noise protection measures to existing dwellings
which will be affected by a proposed new noise source. Moreover, there would be
no obligation on individuals with an interest in each dwelling affected to take
up such an offer, and therefore no guarantee that all necessary noise protection
measures would be put in place&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>5.4  Clearly this reasoning applies to those situations where some measure
of noise protection is needed, i.e. NEC bands B and C. If, even with the
introduction of new noise sources, the NEC of the area remains in band A (&lt;55
dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> (day) and &lt;45 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> (night)), the NEC
procedure remains valid.</P>
<P><B>British Standard 4142, 1990</B></P>
<P>5.5  British Standard 4142 [GOV/902]<SUP>4</SUP> notes that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;In general, a noise is likely to provoke complaints whenever its
(L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> ) level exceeds the background (L<SUB>A90</SUB>) noise level
by a certain margin; or when it attains a certain absolute level&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The BS4142 method uses the comparative rather than absolute level approach,
although it notes [GOV/902]<SUP>5</SUP> that the method for predicting whether
or not the noise will provoke complaints does not apply to situations where the
background level is less than about 30 dB(A).</P>
<P>5.6  The method entails the measurement or prediction of the L(Aeq) level
from the new noise source, applying a correction if appropriate and then
comparing the resulting &quot;Rating Level&quot; with the measured background
level. If the Rating Level is around 10 dB(A) or more above the background level
this indicates that complaints are likely. A difference of around 5 dB(A) is of
marginal likelihood there is that complaints will occur. A difference of -10
dB(A) is a positive indication that complaints are unlikely [GOV/902]<SUP>6</SUP>.
</P>
<P>5.7  The British Standard [GOV/902]<SUP>7</SUP> notes that the background
noise level should be measured when weather conditions are typical of the area;
extreme conditions should be avoided. The restriction of the method for
predicting the likelihood of complaints to areas where background levels are
greater than 30 dB(A) [GOV/902]<SUP>5</SUP> implies that even a marginal
complaint situation would not be expected if the absolute value of the Rating
Level was 35 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> or lower.</P>
<P><B>World Health Organisation</B></P>
<P>5.8  Unlike BS4142, the World Health Organisation considers absolute, rather
than comparative noise levels. In their publication &quot;Environmental Health
Criteria 12: Noise&quot; [GOV/122]<SUP>8</SUP> they state that general daytime
outdoor L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> noise levels of less than 55 dB(A) are desirable in
order to prevent any significant community annoyance. They also note that there
are difficulties in falling asleep when internal levels are higher than 45 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
and that an internal level of no more than 35 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> is recommended
to preserve the essential and restorative process of sleep.</P>
<P><B>British Standard 5228, 1984</B></P>
<P>5.9  British Standard 5228, entitled &quot;Noise Control on Construction and
Open Sites&quot; [NRX/3/2]<SUP>9</SUP> gives methods for the prediction of L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
noise levels from construction and demolition sites. This Standard contains an
extensive data base [NRX/3/2]<SUP>10</SUP> of sound power levels from plant and
machinery. The Standard is used for predicting the noise from all major
developments.</P>
<P>5.10  Planning authorities and other responsible authorities, such as the
Highways Agency, set construction noise standards for large civil engineering
projects. Typical road construction noise limits are shown in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A>. These levels are expressed as
free field levels, away from the reflective effects of building facades. Most
major road contracts are of typically two years duration.</P>
<P><B>MPG11, 1993</B></P>
<P>5.11  Mineral Planning Guidance Note 11 [GOV/111]<SUP>11,12</SUP> suggests
a daytime limit of 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> or no more than 10 dB(A) above the
background level in the vicinity of residential properties. It also notes
[GOV/111]<SUP>13</SUP> that, even in exceptionally quiet rural areas, defined
as those having a daytime background level of below 35 dB(A), there is generally
no need to set daytime limits any lower than 45 dB L(Aeq,1h). A night-time
nominal limit of 42 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> is suggested in the vicinity of noise
sensitive dwellings [GOV/111]<SUP>11</SUP>.</P>
<P>5.12  Gardens and other open spaces heavily used by the general public may
also be regarded as noise sensitive. MPG 11 [GOV/111]<SUP>14</SUP> suggests
that a level of 65 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> during the normal working day and 55
dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> at other times would be reasonable. Footpaths and
bridleways should not normally be regarded as noise-sensitive.</P>
<P>5.13  MPG11 also recognises [GOV/111]<SUP>15</SUP> that higher noise levels
will be justified during short term activities such as soil- stripping, removal
of spoil heaps and the construction of baffle mounds and new permanent
landforms, especially if those activities lead to longer term noise benefits. It
is suggested that a free- field level of 70 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> for periods
of up to 8 weeks a year should be permitted.</P>
<P><B>Previous Borehole Noise Conditions</B></P>
<P>5.14  Cumbria County Council, on advice from Copeland Borough Council, and
the Inspector at Appeal in the case of Boreholes 8A and 9A have specified
various noise conditions, as shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.3">Table 5.3</A>.</P>
<P>5.15  For Boreholes on the Longlands Farm site construction noise limits
were set at 75 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> and for the drilling and testing phases a
daytime/evening limit of 50 dB L<SUB>Aeq,1h</SUB> and night time limits of 43
dB L<SUB>Aeq,1hr</SUB> and 50 dB L<SUB>Amax</SUB> at the nearest residential
property.</P>
<P><B>British Standard 6472, 1992</B></P>
<P>5.16  British Standard 6472 [GOV/903]<SUP>16</SUP> specifies satisfactory
vibration levels for human occupancy of buildings. A set of numbered curves are
presented for various axes of the body. The most vibration sensitive
head-to-foot (ie z-direction) set of curves are reproduced in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>. This family of curves represent
the vibration levels below which the probability of adverse comment is low. A
doubling of these values may result in adverse comment and this may increase
significantly if the magnitudes are quadrupled.</P>
<P>5.17  The acceptability of a given level of vibration depends upon the
environment in which it is experienced. <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.4">Table
5.4</A> gives the recommended Curve Numbers for various human activities, for
both continuous vibration and for up to 3 impulsive events per day. Residential
limits for continuous vibration are usually set at Curve 2 for daytime and Curve
1.4 at night. The corresponding curves for up to 3 impulsive events are set at
Curves 60 and 20 respectively.</P>
<P>5.18  The acceptability of a given level of impulsive vibration, such as
that from blasting, also depends upon the number and duration of the blasts
[GOV/903]<SUP>17</SUP>. <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.5">Table 5.5</A> gives
acceptable vibration levels (mm/sec) for a selection of blast durations and
number of blasts. The Table also shows the vibration levels corresponding to
Curves 1.4, 2, 20 and 60 shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table5.4">Table 5.4</A>.
and <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.</P>
<P><B>British Standard 7385 Part 2, 1993</B></P>
<P>5.19  British Standard 7385 classifies building damage into three categories
of severity:</P>
<P>  a)  Cosmetic. The formation of hairline cracks on drywall surfaces or the
growth of existing cracks in plaster or drywall surfaces; in addition, the
formation of hairline cracks in mortar joints of brick/concrete construction;</P>
<P>  b)  Minor. The formation of large cracks or loosening and falling of
plaster or drywall surfaces, or cracks through bricks/concrete blocks;</P>
<P> c)  Major. Damage to structural elements of the building, cracks in support
columns, loosening of joints, splaying of masonry cracks etc.
</P>
<P>The Guide values given in the Standard [GOV/904]<SUP>18</SUP> are
associated with the first category - the onset or threshold of cosmetic damage.</P>
<P>5.20  The Standard suggests Guide values for various types of structure. For
residential buildings the peak particle velocity should be no more than 15mm/s
at 4 Hz, increasing to 20 mm/s at 15 Hz and then to 50 mm/s at 40 Hz and above.
This threshold curve has been plotted on <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure
5.1</A> to show the relative insensitivity of buildings compared to that of the
occupants.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Existing"></A><B>6.  EXISTING CONDITIONS</B></P>
<P><B>Noise</B></P>
<P>6.1  Various noise level surveys, using equipment calibrated by an
accredited laboratory, have been conducted around the Sellafield area, as part
of the noise studies relating to the potential location of the repository. The
main  noise study area extended from Seascale in the south-west to Gosforth and
Blengdale in the east, the Ponsonby area and Calder Bridge in the north to
Beckermet and High Sellafield in the north-west. These areas have been
periodically surveyed, principally between the Autumn of 1989 and Spring of
1992.</P>
<P>6.2  Measured noise levels at the ten main survey sites most relevant to
this Inquiry are summarised in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>,
showing the arithmetic average and range of the measured existing free-field L<SUB>A90</SUB>
and L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> noise levels during the day (07.00-22.00) and night-time
(22.00-07.00) periods.
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> includes the results of a series
of repeat measurements recently carried out in conjunction with Copeland Borough
Council at locations A to G, covering both weekday and weekend periods. These
measurements showed no consistent difference between weekday and weekend noise
levels and were generally within the previously measured range of levels.</P>
<P>6.3  The measurement locations A to G and J to L are shown in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> and the full measurement results
in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.2">Table 6.2</A> including commentary on weather
conditions and the main sources of noise influencing the measured levels.
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.2">Table 6.2</A> includes the results of facade
noise level measurements conducted outside the Red Admiral Hotel during recent
vibration trials. <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> also shows the
location of two further measurement points, H and I, which in conjunction with
points A and B were used to investigate the effect of near ground windspeeds
upon background levels.</P>
<P>6.4  The effect of windspeed is shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure
6.2</A>, for locations A (Fleming Hall, with several roadside trees), B (Newton
Manor area, surrounded by trees), H (Deepdale, with a few local trees and
hedges) and I (Bleng Fell, with a few local trees and distant woodland).</P>
<P>6.5  Although there is a wide scatter amongst the data points for each
individual site, the trend is clear - increasing wind speeds lead to increasing
background noise levels. Also shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure
6.2</A> are straight line fits to each set of data points, in the form y = mx+c.
The equations for each site, relating background L(A90) levels to Wind Speed
(WS) in metres per second are:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="75"></TD>
<TD>L(A90) = 3.1 WS + 26 dB (Location I)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD>L(A90)= 3.8 WS + 26 dB (Location H)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD>L(A90) = 4.5 WS + 26 dB (Location A)</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
<TD>and</TD>
<TD>L(A90) = 4.9 WS + 34 dB (Location B)</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>These equations indicate that for every 1 m/s increase in windspeed, the
background level in areas with relatively few trees increases by approximately 3
to 4 dB(A) above a still air background level in the mid 20s dB(A). For heavily
wooded areas the background level increases by about 5 dB(A) for every 1 m/s
increase in windspeed above a still air noise level in the mid 30s dB(A).</P>
<P>6.6  The main sources of noise in areas such as Fleming Hall and The
Bungalow (Location A), Newton Manor and Saddlebank (Location B) and Low Boonwood
Farm (Location F), which are all relatively remote from the A595(T), are farming
activities and the wind-induced movement of trees and bushes. Under some
atmospheric conditions, noise from the direction of the Sellafield works is also
audible in those areas to the west of the A595(T).  Areas such as Sides Bungalow
(Location C), High Lingbank (Location D),  the dwellings near the Boonwood Lane
Garden Centre (Location E), the north-western outskirts of Gosforth (Location G)
and southern side of Gosforth (Location L) are affected by noise from traffic on
the A595(T). Existing noise levels in Gosforth are also affected by local
traffic and human activities within the village (Locations J and K).</P>
<P>6.7  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> shows that the measured
daytime background (L<SUB>A90</SUB>) levels in the areas closest to the Appeal
Site (locations A to G) are typically in the mid 30s to low 40s dB(A), dropping
to typically the upper 20s to upper 30s dB(A) at night. Background levels may
drop to about 20 dB(A) during occasional periods of still air conditions at
night.</P>
<P>6.8  The existing noise climate in areas potentially affected by activities
on the Appeal Site may be divided into two broad categories. In areas remote
from the A595(T), noise levels are typical of a rural area, being governed by 
sources such as farming activities, birdsong and the wind-induced movement of
trees and bushes. Noise levels are somewhat higher in those areas affected by
traffic, especially adjacent to the A595(T) and through Gosforth, and in the
vicinity of working farms such as Low Boonwood Farm and Fleming Hall.</P>
<P><B>Vibration</B></P>
<P>6.9  Ambient vibration level measurements were conducted in June 1995 on the
pavement outside the Red Admiral Hotel, adjacent to the A595(T) and at Newton
Manor. These measurements were conducted during blasting trials on the Appeal
Site.</P>
<P>6.10  The measured levels at the Red Admiral Hotel are shown superimposed on
the BS6472 curves in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>. Although
the levels vary with frequency, the background level is typically about 0.0005
mm/sec in the absence of traffic or any other specific vibration source. During
the passage of a tanker on the A595(T) vibration levels increased, giving a
level of typically 0.01 mm/sec over the frequency range of most interest. As the
road surface is free from potholes or badly reinstated trenches, no significant
levels of groundborne vibration would have been expected.</P>
<P>6.11  It will be seen that lorries on the A595(T) produced vibration levels
an order of magnitude lower than Curve 1 of BS6472.</P>
<P><A NAME="Predicted"></A><B>7.  PREDICTED CONDITIONS</B></P>
<P>7.1  The various activities associated with the proposed development have
been assessed in order to identify those which have the greatest potential for
producing noticeable levels of noise and vibration at the nearest residential
properties and areas. The activities listed in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.1">Table
7.1</A> have been assessed in detail, so as to given an indication of the range
of noise levels that may be experienced during the life time of the facility.
The quoted sound power levels are either drawn from BS 5228 [NRX/3/2]<SUP>10</SUP>
or from manufacturers' data.</P>
<P>7.2  Comparatively minor noise sources, such as the headgears and
ventilation fan, have also been included to give an indication of the noise
emanating from the Surface Site when the noisier activities, associated with
construction, are not taking place.</P>
<P>7.3  Typical predicted dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> daytime noise levels associated
with each of these main activities or noise sources are summarised in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A>. These predictions take account of
the distance of each receiver from the noise source, acoustic screening provided
by the intervening land form, amenity bunds etc. and the enclosure of stationary
items of plant.</P>
<P><B>Site Establishment</B></P>
<P>7.4  The Site Establishment stage will last for approximately 1 year from
July 1996. The potentially noisiest activities during this period will involve
soil stripping/bund formation and the cut and fill earthworks for the Platform
Site.</P>
<P> Soil Stripping/Bund Formation</P>
<P>7.5  These activities, programmed to last for about 2 weeks will involve the
stripping of topsoil and subsoil from the Platform Site, construction of the
Access Road and relocation of some of the RCF/RCM Borehole topsoil mounds. These
soils will be formed into perimeter bunds located around the south-eastern
corner of the Platform Site and will remain until restoration takes place. These
bunds will help to contain the spread of noise towards Gosforth.</P>
<P> Platform Site Earthworks</P>
<P>7.6  This activity, programmed to be conducted over an approximate 15 week
period, will follow on from the Platform Site topsoil stripping and bund
formation works.</P>
<P>7.7  The majority of the rock excavation will take place in the northern
corner of the Platform Site. As the excavation deepens into the rising ground to
the north-east, the edge of the cutting will help to screen these activities
from the properties around Boonwood Lane and from High Lingbank. The majority of
rock removal will be with a ripper, although as the excavation deepens it may be
necessary to resort to low level blasting techniques. This method, if needed at
all, would be restricted to the final stages of excavation. The predicted levels
given in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A> are based upon the use of
a ripper. If blasting were employed, the combined noise from four simultaneously
operated hand drills would be 1 dB(A) higher than the ripper.</P>
<P>7.8  The south-western area of the site would be built up and surmounted by
a 2 metre high perimeter bund.</P>
<P> Other Activities</P>
<P>7.9  Site Establishment would also involve other activities such as the
delivery of materials, drainage works, erection of buildings and pipe laying
work in the Services Corridors to Sellafield. These activities would be
considerably quieter than the Platform Site earthworks.</P>
<P>7.10  All the Site Establishment activities would be conducted during normal
daytime working hours.</P>
<P><B>Construction Phases</B></P>
<P>7.11  Phase 1 construction, lasting for about 46 months, will overlap the
Site Establishment phase and will involve the excavation and construction of the
foreshafts to a depth of about 36 metres below Platform Site level and the
sinking of both shafts to a depth of about 680 metres bOD, but possibly up to
935 metres bOD.</P>
<P> Foreshaft Excavation</P>
<P>7.12  Excavation and construction of the South Shaft and North Shaft
foreshafts is programmed to take place during an approximate 30 week period.
Conventional drill and blast methods would be employed, with noise levels
diminishing rapidly as the excavation proceeded below the Platform Site level.
</P>
<P> Shaft Sinking/Gallery Construction</P>
<P>7.13  Phase 1 shaft sinking will last for approximately 29 months following
on from the completion of the foreshafts. During this period the main sources of
potential noise will be the transportation and placing of spoil in the Spoil
Disposal Area and other at-surface sources such as batching plant, crane and
ventilation fan. Underground workings are not expected to be a source of noise
in the neighbouring areas.</P>
<P>7.14  Phase 2 construction will last for about 16 weeks, with Phase 3
lasting for about 36 weeks.</P>
<P>7.15  The spoil disposal activities associated with all these construction
phases will only take place during normal daytime working hours, although
excavation at depth will continue on a 24-hour basis. The only continuous
night-time noise from the Surface Site will be the ventilation fan.
</P>
<P> Science Programme</P>
<P>7.16  During the Phase 2 and Phase 3 Science Programme, the only continuous
noise source will be the ventilation fan. The headgears will operate
intermittently to transport personnel and scientific equipment to the working
depth.</P>
<P>7.17  A number of the above activities will overlap, so that the resulting
noise levels emanating from the Surface Site will vary depending upon the start
and finish dates for each activity.</P>
<P>7.18  Predictions have been performed to identify the lowest, average and
highest L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels at each of the prediction points A to G, in each
3-month period of the programme. The results are presented in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.3">Table 7.3</A>, together with the L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
levels averaged over the whole development and restoration period.</P>
<P>7.19  The quarterly average L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels from
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.3">Table 7.3</A> are also shown in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A> to 7.7, together with the
measured existing average L<SUB>A90</SUB> and L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels given in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>. The noise effects from the
various phases of the development are clearly seen.</P>
<P>7.20  During the third quarter of 1996 the effect of soil stripping and
Platform Site earthworks produces the highest noise levels, with the earthworks
continuing into the following quarter, together with the start of near surface
work on the South Shaft collar and foreshaft. The first quarter of 1997 sees the
continuation at depth of work on the South Shaft foreshaft and the start of near
surface work on the North Shaft foreshaft. Work at depth continues on the North
Shaft foreshaft and on the South Shaft sinking during the second quarter of
1997.</P>
<P>7.21  Sinking of both shafts, the construction of various underground
facilities and the surface disposal of generated spoil continues into the last
quarter of 1999. A period of comparatively quiet construction activity is then
followed in the second quarter of 2000 by the start of Phase 2 Construction and
Mapping of galleries, continuing into the last quarter of 2000.</P>
<P>7.22  The following 18 months or so (year 2001, first quarter to 2002,
second quarter) is taken up by the Phase 2 Science Programme, during which time
the ventilation fan and occasional use of the headgears will be the major noise
sources on the site.</P>
<P>7.23  Phase 3 Construction and Mapping is then programmed to start during
the third quarter of 2002, continuing to the end of the first quarter of 2003.
The Phase 3 Science Programme may then commence and is programmed to last for
the following three years.</P>
<P>7.24  Restoration of the Surface Site would start during the third quarter
of 2006 and be completed by about the end of the third quarter of 2008.</P>
<P><B>Predicted Noise Levels</B></P>
<P>7.25  During the soil stripping/bund formation and Platform Site earthworks
periods it will be seen from <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A>,
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.3">Table 7.3</A> and
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A> to 7.7 that daytime L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
noise levels of about 40 dB will be experienced at Fleming Hall/The Bungalow (<A
HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A>), Low Boonwood Farm (<A
HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.6">Figure 7.6</A>) and the north-western outskirts of
Gosforth (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.7">Figure 7.7</A>). Noise levels at
Newton Manor/Saddlebank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.2">Figure 7.2</A>) will
be typically in the low 40s dB(A), reaching a level of about 60 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
for a few days when the topsoil and subsoil mounds are being constructed in
their vicinity. Noise levels at Sides Bungalow (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.3">Figure
7.3</A>) are typically in the low to upper 40s dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> , the upper
40s dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> at High Lingbank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.4">Figure
7.4</A>) and the mid 40s to about 50 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> at Boonwood Lane
Cottages (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.5">Figure 7.5</A>).
</P>
<P>7.26  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A> (Fleming Hall/The
Bungalow) and <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.7">7.7</A> (N.W. Gosforth) show that
during this period of surface construction, typical L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels will
be below the typical background levels. At some other locations the L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
noise levels will, on average, be above the background level but below the
existing L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> average levels. Only at Newton Manor/Saddlebank (<A
HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A>) and Sides Bungalow (<A
HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.3">Table 7.3</A>) will the average daytime L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
levels exceed the present day levels. Inspection of
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> and
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.3">Table 7.3</A> shows that even at these
properties, the predicted maximum L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels from the development
will fall within the range of currently experienced measured levels.</P>
<P>7.27  This period of the construction programme may also necessitate the use
of drill and blast methods to level some areas of the Platform Site. Predicted
vibration levels at the Red Admiral Hotel, based on the levels measured during
the blasting trials, are below the acceptable night time level of 2.8 mm/sec.
Any necessary near surface blasting will, however, be restricted to the daytime
period. The noise impact from blasting will be contained using conventional
methods such as blast mats and strict site management. The nearest residents
will be pre-warned of an impending blast and monitoring of noise and vibration
levels will be conducted, at least during the early stages of blasting.</P>
<P>7.28  The next stage of the construction programme involves the excavation
of the collar and foreshafts and sinking of the shafts. The major sources of
noise during this period relate to spoil handling and its placing in the Spoil
Disposal Area. Below ground works will be carried out on a 24-hour basis, but
the movement and deposition of spoil will only be conducted during the normal
daytime period.</P>
<P>7.29  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A> to 7.7 show that
daytime L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> noise levels during this period, from about the first
quarter of 1997 to the end of 1999, will generally be less than or comparable to
the presently experienced background levels and, in the case of the
north-western outskirts of Gosforth (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.7">Figure 7.7</A>),
typically 15 dB(A) below background.</P>
<P>7.30  If it were found necessary to develop the galleries at a greater depth
than that previously assumed, this period could be extended up to about 4
months. Clearly, such an extension will have the minimum noise effects in
surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>7.31  Similar noise levels will be experienced during Phase 2 Construction
and Mapping (up to the end of the year 2000) and Phase 3 Construction and
Mapping (mid 2002 to end of the first quarter of 2003).</P>
<P>7.32  Noise levels during the main Science Programme periods, extending from
the beginning of the year 2001 to mid 2002 and from the second quarter of 2003
to the middle of 2006, will be about 5 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> in the outskirts of
Gosforth (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.7">Figure 7.7</A>), less than 10 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
at Fleming Hall/The Bungalow (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure 7.1</A>),
Newton Manor/Saddlebank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.2">Figure 7.2</A>) and
Low Boonwood Farm (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.6">Figure 7.6</A>) and no more
than 15 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> at Sides Bungalow (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.3">Figure
7.3</A>), High Lingbank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.4">Figure 7.4</A>) and
Boonwood Lane Cottages (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.5">Figure 7.5</A>)</P>
<P><B>Restoration</B></P>
<P>7.33  The plant used in the closure of the RCF, removal of the surface
facilities and the restoration of the Surface Site, is likely to have similar
sound power outputs to those used during the initial soil stripping and Platform
Site earthworks phase, as shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.1">Table 7.1</A>.</P>
<P>7.34  Daytime L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels at Sides Bungalow will be comparable
to those typically experienced at present (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.3">Figure
7.3</A>), while those at High Lingbank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.4">Figure
7.4</A>), Boonwood Lane Cottages (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.5">Figure 7.5</A>)
and Low Boonwood Farm (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.6">Figure 7.6</A>) will be
intermediate between typical existing background and L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> levels.
Noise levels at Fleming Hall/The Bungalow (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.1">Figure
7.1</A>), Newton Manor/Saddlebank (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.2">Figure 7.2</A>)
and the north-western outskirts of Gosforth (<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure7.7">Figure
7.7</A>) will be below the currently experienced typical background levels.</P>
<P><B>Traffic Noise</B></P>
<P>7.35  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.4">Table 7.4</A> shows the greatest
change in the L<SUB>A10,18h</SUB> level in each year between 1996 and 2008.
These changes have been calculated using the algorithms contained in the
Department of Transport/Welsh Office memorandum &quot;Calculation of Road
Traffic Noise&quot; [GOV/115]<SUP>19</SUP> for those months during which the
RCF traffic contributes most to the traffic noise environment. It will be seen
that the largest effects will occur during the Site Establishment phase and also
during part of the Restoration in 2006. The increase of 0.4 dB L<SUB>A10,18h</SUB>
will last for about 2 months during 2006.</P>
<P>7.36  <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.5">Table 7.5</A> shows the likely
hour-by-hour traffic noise changes corresponding to the noisiest period of 1996.
Noise level increases throughout the day will generally be below 1 dB L<SUB>A10</SUB>.</P>
<P>7.37  As changes of less than about 1 to 3 dB L<SUB>A10,18h</SUB> are not
discernable, and existing day-to-day variations alongside main roads are
typically 2 to 3 dB L<SUB>A10,18h</SUB>, the traffic generated by the RCF will
have a negligible effect upon the noise environment at properties adjacent to
the A595(T).</P>
<P><A NAME="Consultations"></A>
<B>8.  CONSULTATIONS</B></P>
<P><B>Gosforth Parish Council</B></P>
<P>8.1  In their petition to the Secretary of State for the Environment, dated
November 1994, Gosforth Parish Council express the view that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Operational Noise from heavy earth moving plant, rock tipping,
explosives, conveyors, ventilation fans and other sources too numerous to list
will cause 24-hour disturbance to both visitors and locals&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.2  The majority of these potential noise sources will not be operating on
a 24-hour basis. It has never been proposed that heavy earth moving plant, rock
tipping, near surface blasting and surface conveyors would be used at night.</P>
<P>8.3  Since publication of the RCF Environmental Statement [COR/101]<SUP>20</SUP>,
the need for ground freezing has been reviewed and replaced by grouting as the
favoured technique. The previously envisaged 24-hour operations using mobile
drilling rigs to drill the freeze holes will now be replaced by a quieter
daytime-only operation.</P>
<P>8.4  The only continuous night time source of noise will be the ventilation
fans. As noted in section 7 of this proof, and in the Environmental Statement,
fan noise levels at even the closest property to the site will be below the
existing background level.
</P>
<P>8.5  Predicted daytime levels during the various phases of the development
have been discussed in the previous section. Clearly the Gosforth Parish
Council's concern regarding &quot;24-hour disturbance to both visitors and
locals&quot; is without foundation.
</P>
<P>8.6  The Council go on to state that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The ventilation fans are quoted to produce a noise level of 78 dB.
With the surmounted ducting and tower, these noise levels will be significantly
amplified&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.7  In their petition to the Secretary of State they fail to point out that
the level of 78 dB(A) is at a distance of 1 metre from the fan, whereas Gosforth
Village is at a distance of at least 1 kilometre from the fan. The fans will be
set in conventional resilient mountings, thus minimising the transmission of
vibration to connecting structures which may otherwise vibrate and generate
noise. The Parish Councils assumption that &quot;noise levels will be
significantly amplified&quot; is therefore invalid.</P>
<P>8.8  Resulting levels in the closest area of Gosforth will be about 5 dB(A),
so will be inaudible.</P>
<P>8.9  They also state that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Consideration does not appear to have been made regarding the
effect of continuous noise or rock tipping during silent hours. In a rural area,
it is acceptable to have the normal rural sounds of the animals, wind , rain and
other natural noises, but the imposition of industrial noise is totally
unacceptable, especially after the hours of daylight. The area affected will
extend as far as the villages of Gosforth, Seascale and Calderbridge&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.10  Rock tipping in the spoil disposal area has never been proposed as a
24-hour operation. The Environmental Statement points out [COR/101]<SUP>21</SUP>
that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;All the shaft sinking and gallery construction activities, except
for the placing of spoil in the spoil disposal area, and all but the early
stages of foreshaft excavation, could be conducted at night without exceeding
the previously agreed limit for the borehole development in the National Park&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.11  The villages of Seascale and Calderbridge are approximately 2.5 and 3
km to the south-west and north-west of the Appeal Site respectively. As there is
no material noise impact on the outskirts of Gosforth, at a distance of about 1
km, there is no reason to suppose that Seascale and Calderbridge will be
affected at all by noise from the site.</P>
<P><B>Copeland Borough Council</B></P>
<P>8.12  The Officers report that was discussed at the Council meeting on the
1st November 1994 states that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Ambient sound pressure levels reported in the Gosforth area are
higher than would normally be expected by this Council. No joint monitoring has
been carried out with NIREX and the view is held that NIREX have misrepresented
the local noise climate. This area is generally quiet and noise, especially at
night and weekends will be intrusive. The principal concern here relates to 24
hour working within an essentially quiet rural area, which although not heavily
populated would normally expect to have a quiet environment&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>8.13  Measured noise levels in the Gosforth area were presented to the Lake
District National Park boreholes inquiry in 1992. At that time noise monitoring
conducted by both Copeland Borough Council and on behalf of Nirex in the
National Park produced comparable results. Unlike isolated individual properties
in the National Park, Gosforth is a fairly large village straddling a through
road and bordered by the A595(T). Noise levels might be expected to be higher
than in an isolated area of the National Park.
</P>
<P>8.14  Existing noise levels measured in Gosforth are presented in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.2">Table 6.2</A>, summarised in
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> and the measurement locations
shown in <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A>. Locations G, J, K and
L are in Gosforth. Location G, being the nearest Appeal Site was used in the
Environmental Statement to characterise the to the existing noise climate in the
potentially worst affected area of the village. The predicted levels presented
in section 7 of this proof also relate to that same area of the village. More
distant areas of the village may, on occasions, experience lower existing noise
levels than at location G, but will also experience lower noise levels from the
activities on the Appeal Site</P>
<P>8.15  Within the context of the Environmental Statement relating to the
noise effects of this application, it is difficult to see why Copeland Borough
Council consider that the reported measured noise levels at location G
misrepresent the existing &quot;local noise climate&quot;. (see paragraph 6.2).</P>
<P>8.16  Copeland Borough Council acknowledge that their main concern relates
to 24-hour working which, by implication, implies night time noise intrusion. At
the time of publication of the Environmental Statement it was envisaged that the
highest night time noise levels in the closest area of Gosforth village would be
from drilling the freeze holes (31 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>) and the ventilation fans
(5 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>) [COR/101]<SUP>22</SUP>. Both these levels would satisfy
the WHO night time noise limit and those set by Cumbria County Council, on
advice from Copeland Borough Council, for the isolated properties in the
National Park. It is difficult to see why Copeland Borough Council now consider
that a night time noise level in Gosforth that is some 10 dB(A) below the levels
set for the Lake District National Park boreholes should be considered as
intrusive.</P>
<P>8.17  As night time freeze hole drilling is not now proposed and the only
continuous night time noise source will be that of a ventilation fan, it must
follow that Copeland Borough Council's principal concern relating to night time
noise, is now even more unfounded.</P>
<P><B>Cumbria County Council</B></P>
<P>8.18  Cumbria County Council do not cite specific noise or vibration issues
in their Reasons for Refusal but produce a Draft Schedule of Conditions in the
event of Approval. Those draft conditions have been and are the subject of
on-going discussions. Those conditions having a bearing on Noise and Vibration
are considered below, in respect of the June 1995 draft [COR/118]<SUP>23</SUP>.</P>
<P>8.19  Condition 7: Blasting. The vibration limits are in agreement with
those set in BS6472, not BS6742 as noted.</P>
<P>8.20  Condition 12: Noise levels and hours of operation. The noise levels
are in agreement with those suggested in MPG11, with the use of L<SUB>A01</SUB>
(rather than L<SUB>Amax</SUB>) as recommended in BS5228.</P>
<P>8.21  Condition 13: Short period noise levels. The noise levels and duration
are in agreement with those suggested in MPG11.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>9.  CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P>9.1  Typical daytime noise levels emanating from the Appeal Site will, for
most of the lifetime of the development, be at or below the measured existing
background levels in the nearest area of Gosforth and at most of the scattered
properties in the area.</P>
<P>9.2  At only two properties (Newton Manor/Saddlebank) will daytime noise
levels exceed the World Health Organisation recommended external limit of 55 dB
L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> . That recommendation will be exceeded for just a few days
during construction of the nearby top and subsoil mounds, with levels being
about 10 dB(A) below the limit suggested in MPG11 for soil stripping/bund
formation activities lasting for up to 8 weeks a year.</P>
<P>9.3  Night time noise levels from the site will be up to 15 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
at the nearest property, reducing with distance to about 5 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
in the outskirts of Gosforth, thus meeting the World Health Organisation
internal recommended limit of 35 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> . Even daytime noise levels
from the site will, for the majority of locations and lifetime of the
development, satisfy this night-time limit with fully open windows.</P>
<P>9.4  The PPG24 Noise Exposure Category A limits of 55 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB>
during the day and 45 dB L<SUB>Aeq</SUB> at night will be satisfied at all
locations. At only a few locations and periods during the development will
daytime levels exceed the night time criterion.</P>
<P>9.5  Vibration levels due to near surface blasting will be below those
recommended in BS 6472 for night time blasting and well below the daytime limit.
Vibration levels will attenuate further as work progresses below ground level.
</P>
<P>9.6  Increased traffic flows on the A595(T) will, even during the busiest
period of site development, produce no noticeable change in the dB L<SUB>A10,18h</SUB>
level.</P>
<P>9.7  In conclusion, there are no justifiable noise or vibration reasons for
refusing the granting of planning permission.</P>
