<P><B>Supplementary Proof of Evidence Dr. G.M. Jackson
</B>
</P>
<P><B>1. Introduction.
</B>
</P>
<P>1.1. Various queries have been raised regarding the Sound Power Output of
various plant items used in the noise assessment.
</P>
<P><B>2. Noise Sources
</B>
</P>
<P>Concrete Batching Plant
</P>
<P>2.1 The Sound Power Level of 106 dB(A) is given in NRX/3/2, Table 9, Ref
No.l0 and <B>PE/NRX/3</B>, <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.1">Table 7.1</A>. The
Batching Plants were in the open air, as is usual.
</P>
<P>2.2 Developments in the design of these plant have led to significant noise
reductions since the original data in BS5228 was collected in the early 1970s.
Present day batching plant of capacity similar to that used in the evidence have
sound power levels of typically 92 dB(A); 14dB(A) quieter than that assumed in
the calculations
<SUP>1</SUP> 
</P>
<P>2.3 The &quot;Concrete Batching&quot; noise levels shown in the Noise
Evidence (<B>PE/NRX/3</B>, <A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A>, ),
which already satisfy W.H.O. night time noise criteria, would therefore be
nomore than 17 dB(A) at the closest properties of Sides Bungalow and Boonwood
Lane Cottages (31 - 14=17) No advantage would therefore be derived from
enclosing the Batching Plant.</P>
<P>Kibble Unloading
</P>
<P>2.4 The Sound Power Level of 7OdB(A) quoted in <B>PE/NRX/3</B>,
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.1">Table 7.1</A> relates to the situation with a
partial enclosure around the base of the crane, as described by Mr Smith.
</P>
<P>Headgear/Winder
</P>
<P>2.5 The sound power level of 60 dB(A) quoted in <B>PE/NRX/3</B>,
<A HREF="nrx3fig.htm#Table7.1">Table 7.1</A> relates to the situation described
by Mr. Smith, with the lower portions of the tower enclosed.
</P>
<P>Reference
</P>
<P>1. Results of Noise Survey of Steelfields Readymix Concrete Plant, Noise
Reduction Limited. July 1987.
</P>
<P></P>
