<P><B>Dr NEIL GILLAN BAYFIELD will Say:</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1.  PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P>1.1  I am a Grade 7 Officer of the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology (ITE),
which is a part of the Natural Environment Research Council. I am Leader of the
Applied Ecology Group and Deputy Head of the ITE Research Station at Banchory in
Scotland.  I have a degree in Agricultural Botany from the University of North
Wales and a PhD in Botany from the University of Aberdeen. </P>
<P>1.2  I am a professional research and consultant ecologist.  My main
research interests are moss and invertebrate ecology and techniques of
reinstating damaged habitats, particularly in upland Britain.  My consultancy
experience includes providing reinstatement advice to the Countryside
Commission, Scottish Natural Heritage, Shell UK, British Alcan and other private
and public organisations, and undertaking Environmental Impact Assessments,
monitoring and survey work for Grampian Regional Council, Highland Regional
Council, Nevis Range, Central Scotland Water Development Council, Nature
Conservancy Council for Scotland and others.  Members of my team have wide
experience of botanical, mammal and bird survey and monitoring work.</P>
<P>1.3  I have written more than eighty contract reports and forty technical
papers, book chapters and articles.  My current research includes studies of the
small mountain ringlet butterfly, developing a database for footpaths in the
Cairngorms Mountains, setting up a monitoring scheme for diurnal lepidoptera in
Scotland and developing a methodology for defining the renewability of natural
heritage resources.</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2.  SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>2.1  There are no designated nature conservation sites around or within the
proposed Appeal Site that will be affected by the development.</P>
<P>2.2  The area around Longlands Farm has been the subject of detailed surveys
of the vegetation, birds and badgers.  The area around the site is mainly
agricultural land, plantation or game woodland that is of no special ecological
interest.  No identified rare or locally uncommon plant or animal species would
be affected.</P>
<P>2.3  There are populations of natterjack toads in the coastal strip south of
the mouth of the River Calder.  There will be no effect on the natterjack toad
habitat or breeding areas downstream of the development.  Potential impacts
caused by pollution or abnormal flows in Newmill Beck should be prevented by
measures to control effluents and limit drainage from the Surface Site.</P>
<P>2.4  The bird surveys show that the area is not of special interest, and
should be little affected by the development.</P>
<P>2.5  Badgers occupy setts around and within the Appeal Site.  Noise and
vibration from construction work could disturb them but mitigation measures
should minimise any adverse effects and the setts should be more secure from
persecution.  There will be some reduction of current foraging areas which will
be compensated for by new plantings and vegetation management.</P>
<P>2.6  Landscaping around the Appeal Site will locally increase the nature
conservation interest of the area and will be of benefit to birds, small
mammals, woodland herb species and invertebrates.</P>
<P>2.7  The direct effects of the development are confined to loss of habitat
through land take and fragmentation.</P>
<P>2.8  There will be no significant indirect effects on the ecology of the
Surface Site, Services Corridors and the surrounding area.</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3.  BACKGROUND AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE</B></P>
<P>3.1  The evidence given here concerns the terrestrial ecological aspects of
the proposed RCF.  The main focus is on the vegetation, soils and animals of the
Surface Site and Services Corridors and their immediate vicinity.  The
development will have direct effects on the flora and fauna of the Surface Site
as a result of land take, fragmentation of habitats and as a consequence of the
proposed restoration measures.  The development may also indirectly affect flora
and fauna through atmospheric emissions, noise and vibration, aqueous
discharges, waste and spoil disposal and through potential pollution resulting
from accidental spillage of materials used in the construction and operation of
the RCF.</P>
<P>3.2  I have considered the likely ecological impacts of the development in
the light of a literature review, consultation with interested parties and field
surveys of ecological resources of the area around Sellafield, which have been
carried out since 1989.  In particular, vegetation, mammal and bird surveys have
been conducted during this period and have included the monitoring of a clan of
badgers whose main sett is in the immediate vicinity of the Surface Site.</P>
<P>3.3  Measures to mitigate the impacts identified will be outlined. These
include tree planting around the Surface Site that will improve the nature
conservation value of the vicinity, and precautions to minimise impacts on the
foraging areas of badgers and interference with their movement around these
areas.  An evaluation of the short and longer-term potential gains and losses
from the development proposals will be presented.</P>
<P>3.4  The importance of a flexible management strategy will be outlined. </P>
<P><A NAME="Ecological"></A><B>4.  ECOLOGICAL RESOURCES</B></P>
<P><B>The Appeal Site and Local Area</B></P>
<P>4.1  There are no designated sites of conservation interest or trees
protected by Tree Preservation Order (&quot;TPO&quot;) within the Surface Site
or Services Corridors.  The natterjack toad breeding and foraging area adjacent
to the Newmill Beck is a site of conservation interest and has been proposed as
a Site of Special Scientific Interest.  It is 2 km downstream of the Surface
Site.</P>
<P>4.2  Within 2 kms of the Surface Site, the main factors which influence the
pattern of flora and fauna are topography, drainage, soil type, climate and use
of land, in particular, agricultural or industrial use.  A large part of the
Surface Site and Services Corridors and the surrounding land is under
agricultural production with grassland predominating.  Woodland covers only a
small fraction of the total area, with the largest area being the coniferous
plantation at Lingbank.  Other local blocks of woodland in the immediate
vicinity which provide habitat and cover include the Wet Wood and Bluebell Wood
to the north and east of the Surface Site and Long Wood and the Roundel which
lie adjacent to the Spoil Disposal Area.  Some way to the south there is
Quarryflatts Wood.  None of these areas has any special botanical interest.</P>
<P>4.3  The vegetation around the Appeal Site has been recorded at several
levels of detail [COR/101]1.  The Institute of Terrestrial Ecology and English
Nature have undertaken general mapping of the whole area between Gosforth and
Sellafield.  More detailed mapping (English Nature Phase II level) has been
undertaken in the immediate vicinity of the Surface Site and the Services
Corridors between the Platform Site and Sellafield Works [NRX/4/1]2.  These
surveys show that there are few features of conservation interest; most of the
area comprises planted commercial and sporting woodland, or farmland.  The
farmland is predominantly arable or improved pasture, with no examples of
species-rich or unimproved pasture that might be judged of special nature
conservation interest.  There are a few areas of wet pasture but these are not
of special interest either. There are no Nationally Rare or Nationally Scarce
species in the woodlands or farmlands.</P>
<P><B>Soils</B></P>
<P>4.4  Most of the area has been affected by farming practice, so that there
are no areas of special importance for soil conservation.  The principal effect
on the soils relate to the conservation of soil fertility and soil animal
populations (principally earthworms) as a resource for long term farming use of
the area and as a source of food (earthworms) for badgers.</P>
<P><B>Birds</B></P>
<P>4.5  The Surface Site is generally moderate to poor in a local, Cumbrian
context.  No rare species have been recorded as using the area or breeding
there.  The interconnecting system of hedgerows and woodland offers the best
habitat for birds on the Surface Site. There is a heronry near to Newton Manor.</P>
<P><B>Natterjack Toads</B></P>
<P>4.6  Natterjack toads have a restricted distribution in the UK and are
largely confined to seasonally flooded coastal dune areas.  The Drigg Nature
Reserve is an important site for the species. Natterjacks are also found in the
coastal strip south of the mouth of the River Calder.  There has already been a
positive conservation initiative in this area, with special breeding ponds
provided for the species, fed by water from the Newmill Beck</P>
<P><B>Badgers</B></P>
<P>4.7  Badgers are a protected species and the protection applies to both the
animal and its habitat.  Nevertheless, badgers in parts of West Cumbria are
subject to persecution by people, and some of the populations around Gosforth
have apparently been exterminated. There is, however, a healthy clan of badgers
in a sett in Lingbank Plantation north-west of the Appeal Site.  There are also
a number of abandoned or infrequently used setts at locations within a few
kilometres, but nearly all have been unused for several years.  In 1994 badgers
from the Lingbank clan re-occupied a sett in Bluebell Wood, within the Appeal
Site.  This sett is in current use and will have the added security of being
adjacent to the Surface Site.  The re-occupation took place at a time when there
was considerable construction traffic and activity in the vicinity, associated
the RCF/RCM Boreholes.</P>
<P><B>Aquatic Fauna and Flora</B></P>
<P>4.8  Aquatic invertebrates and fish are good indicators of water quality. 
As will be shown by the evidence of Dr Chambers, a survey of the aquatic
invertebrate fauna of the Newmill Beck has indicated that the stream is already
contaminated to some extent.  Eels, trout and three spined sticklebacks are,
however, present in the Beck. All three species are taken by herons.  Overall
the quality of the water is mainly NRA class 1B to 2 ( good to fair quality)
although the water quality sometimes falls to class 3 (poor quality).  The
streamside vegetation is of no special interest.</P>
<P><B>Other Ecological Resources</B></P>
<P>4.9  Other wildlife such as small mammals and amphibians (other than
natterjack toads) have not been the subject of detailed surveys. This is because
there is no reason to believe that they are of special interest for nature
conservation in this area and the populations are likely to be typical of much
of West Cumbria. Neither English Nature nor the Cumbria Wildlife Trust have
identified any important groups of animals or plants requiring a detailed
assessment of possible impacts.</P>
<P><A NAME="Description"></A><B>5.  DESCRIPTION OF EFFECTS</B></P>
<P>5.1  The construction of the Surface Site and the Services Corridors is
bound to have both direct and indirect effects on the vegetation and fauna.  The
construction of the Platform Site by the extension of the existing borehole
platforms, the cutting into the side of the valley and the placing of the
excavated material, including that stockpiled from the excavation of the RCF/RCM
boreholes platforms to create an embankment will require the felling of up to 15
trees and the removal of hedgerows and gorse scrub.  Stripping and storage of
topsoils and subsoils from the Surface Site will have an effect on soil
fertility and soil animal populations (principally earthworms). The area to the
west of the Platform Site, which forms part of the foraging area of the local
badger population, will be reduced during the period when spoil is being
disposed and until that particular area has been restored to its former
condition</P>
<P>5.2  It is likely that the RCF landscaping proposals will improve some
aspects of the nature conservation interest in the vicinity of the site,
providing shelter and food for birds and mammals and habitat for various
invertebrates and woodland herb species.  There will be only short-term effects
of construction work on the ecological interest of the Services Corridors
between the Platform Site and the Sellafield Works, resulting from pipeline and
cable laying and drainage work.  Vegetation reinstatement of pasture vegetation
will follow immediately after construction in the Services Corridors, as will
replacement of hedges using native species appropriate to the area.</P>
<P>5.3  Potential impacts of the development on the herons include disturbance
by noise, or effects of pollution of the Newmill Beck on food supplies for the
birds.  None of these possibilities is likely to have a significant effect on
heron populations.  The species is exceptionally tolerant of noise and
disturbance, and even if there was an effect on this heronry the population
would be likely to move to another site nearby without any impact on numbers. As
will be shown by the evidence of Dr Chambers, potential impacts on heron food
species (eels and sticklebacks) from the Newmill Beck are unlikely to be
realised since there will be special precautions to prevent any significant
changes in the quality of the water. Discharges to the Beck will be within
limits stipulated by the NRA.</P>
<P>5.4  If there were a pollution event affecting the Newmill Beck or
substantial changes in volumes of flow, natterjack toad numbers or breeding
success might be affected.  Possible impacts could come from flooding, changes
in invertebrate food availability or direct toxic effects of pollutants.
Juvenile stages would be most vulnerable.  However, as will be shown by the
evidence of Dr. Chambers, such impacts are unlikely because of controls on
runoff from the Surface Site and removal of effluents from the Platform Site via
a separate drainage system.  Furthermore the special ponds can be isolated from
the Newmill Beck by closing the access sluices.</P>
<P>5.5  The grasslands and in around the proposed Surface Site, including the
Spoil Disposal Area, are used as foraging areas by the badgers from both setts. 
Badgers will eat a wide range of foods, but about 90% of their diet is
earthworms.  The present population of badgers appears to be unaffected so far
despite the development of the RCF/RCM Boreholes, and indeed the clan has
expanded to occupy the Bluebell Wood sett.  However, potential effects to
badgers include the reductions in the areas of forage, disruption of their
access routes, disturbance by traffic, blasting noise, and site lighting.</P>
<P>5.6  Gosforth Parish Council have expressed concern that there could be a
fly problem resulting from proposals to plant areas of trees to landscape the
site.  This is unlikely to occur since flies are generally associated with
rubbish, very wet ground conditions or with deposits of ordure.  None of these
features will be associated with the tree plantings.</P>
<P><A NAME="Mitigation"></A><B>6.  MITIGATION</B></P>
<P>6.1  A number of mitigation measures have been incorporated in the RCF
proposals that will reduce the potential impacts of the development.  They
include tree planting for landscaping, that will increase the nature
conservation interest of the area by providing more deciduous tree and scrub
cover which will be of benefit to birds, mammals and invertebrates.  Loss of
hedges will be mitigated by new plantings.  A small wetland area will also be
created.  The details of these landscaping proposals are discussed in the
evidence of Mrs Wilson.</P>
<P>6.2  To mitigate potential impacts on badgers the following will be
undertaken:</P>
<UL>
<LI>  Crossing tunnels will be provided where fencing would obstruct access,
particularly across the fenced access road between the Platform Site and
Borehole 5.  These tunnels should be in place before spoil disposal begins so
that the badgers have time to become accustomed to them.
</LI>
<LI>  The main foraging areas will be maintained as short unploughed grassland
in order to encourage high populations of worms.  The reinstated spoil areas
will similarly be maintained as short grassland, with the sward not more than 10
cm high.
</LI>
<LI>  An unworked short grassland corridor will be left around the edge of
fields containing spoil in order to provide a continuous access corridor for
badgers around the Spoil Disposal Area.
</LI>
<LI>  Lights on the access road will be as dim as practicable, consistent with
security.
</LI>
<LI>  A balance will be maintained between tree planting and areas of short
grassland to ensure a satisfactory area is available for foraging by badgers;
</LI>
<LI>  Measures have been proposed to try and conserve the earthworm populations
in soil stripped and replaced on spoil heaps. Specifically this will involve a
system of stripping and replacing soil with the least amount of handling and
storage, so that the impact on worm populations is kept to a minimum
</LI></UL>
<P>6.3  Measures to prevent pollution or abnormal flows in Newmill Beck are
mentioned in the evidence of Mr Smith and Dr Chambers.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>7.  CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P>7.1  The area proposed for the Surface Site and Services Corridors does not
contain any sites designated nationally or locally as being of nature
conservation importance.  No designated nature conservation sites will be
affected by the development.</P>
<P>7.2  The area around the Appeal Site is mainly agricultural land, plantation
or game woodland that is of no special ecological interest.  None of the trees
within the Surface Site are protected by a TPO.  7.3  The Surface Site and its
immediate vicinity is of little value ornithologically, even in a local Cumbrian
context.  No rare species have been recorded as using the area or breeding
there.</P>
<P>7.4  Adjacent to the Newmill Beck, 2 km from the Surface Site there are two
artificially created pools within the sandy dunes to the south of the River
Calder which is an important breeding and foraging habitat of the natterjack
toad.  The toads could be affected by pollution or abnormal flows in the Newmill
Beck, but these potential impacts should be prevented by measures to control
effluents and limit drainage from the site.</P>
<P>7.5  A clan of badgers lives and forages within and near the Appeal Site.
They could be affected by disturbance, or by temporary reductions in the area or
accessibility of ground suitable for foraging, part of the foraging area forms
the Spoil Disposal Area. A number of mitigating measures are proposed to
minimise these potential impacts.</P>
<P>7.6  Although the Newmill Beck is already contaminated to some extent, eels,
trout and sticklebacks help support a local heronry and the overall water
quality varies between good to fair and poor</P>
<P>7.7  No rare species of mammals or invertebrates have been notified on the
Surface Site or its surroundings.</P>
<P><A NAME="References"></A><B>8. REFERENCES</B></P>
<P>1. COR/101<BR>Rock Characterisation Facility, Longlands Farm, Cumbria. 
Environmental Statement, July 1994, Chapter 5.</P>
<P>2. NRX/4/1<BR>French, D. D. (1993).  Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF):
Survey of access corridors.  Report to United Kingdom Nirex Limited.  ITE
Banchory.</P>
