<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS
</B></P>
<P>1.1 This Proof of Evidence has been prepared by Marcus Rex Chambers, aged 52
years. I have a BSc degree in Zoology and Botany (Upper Second Class Honours)
from the University of Aberdeen, awarded in 1965. I also have a MSc degree in
Ecology from the same university, awarded in 1966. My PhD degree was awarded by
the University of Liverpool in 1971 for researches into the ecology of
freshwater animals.
</P>
<P>1.2 I am a Senior Environmental Consultant with WS Atkins, and a member of
the company's Environmental Assessment Division. I joined the company in March
1990. The Division's principal work is in carrying out Environmental Impact
Assessments and the preparation of Environmental Impact Assessments for a wide
range of development projects in the UK and overseas. I have been involved with
many of these, typical examples being roads, airports, industrial concerns,
irrigation, watershed management, pipelines, sewage treatment plants, water
supply projects and power stations. I have been involved in environmental
assessment studies for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>1.3 I have researched, prepared and presented evidence for a civil
arbitration hearing in Bahrain. This was concerned with actions arising from a
major coastal construction programme. I have also overseen the preparation of
evidence for a possible public inquiry into major road constructions associated
with the proposed Terminal 5 at Heathrow.
</P>
<P>1.4 The Company has worked with United Kingdom Nirex Limited (`Nirex') since
1988 and I have been continuously associated with the proposals to build the
Rock Characterisation Facility ('RCF') at Longlands Farm. I am currently
responsible for WS Atkins' work associated with the non- nuclear water
assessment of this proposed development. I have undertaken consultations with
the National Rivers Authority and have visited the Appeal Site on a number of
occasions.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2. SUMMARY
</B></P>
<P>2.1 The Water Proof of Evidence has been prepared by Dr Marcus Rex Chambers,
a Senior Environmental Consultant in WS Atkins' Environmental Assessment
Division. He has been associated with the RCF's environmental impact assessment
studies from the beginning of the project.
</P>
<P><B>Scope of Evidence
</B></P>
<P>2.2 The Proof of Evidence considers the types and significance of
environmental effects that could occur during the RCF's construction, operation
and restoration to the surface, groundwater and coastal marine waters at and/or
close to the site. Possible effects on freshwater quality and fauna and flora
are compared with the existing situation and with national and international
criteria designed to maintain a high environmental quality.
</P>
<P><B>Description of Methods
</B></P>
<P>2.3 Water quality and the invertebrate fauna of Newmill Beck and its
southern tributary were studied from 1991 to 1995 by regular monitoring
programmes that established the baseline conditions. The chemical parameters
most likely to be affected by the RCF project were monitored during this period.
The animal studies concentrated on assessing standard indices that relate the
streams' fauna to water quality. Thus changes in chemical and biological
conditions can be readily detected. Additional information on the baseline
conditions was obtained from the National Rivers Authority ('NRA').
</P>
<P><B>Water Legislation and Guidelines
</B></P>
<P>2.4 The NRA classifies surface waters by the recently - introduced General
Quality Assessment ('GQA') scheme which sets standards for the evaluation of
water quality irrespective of river uses. Newmill Beck and the southern
tributary attain Grades B and C (fair to good quality) in their middle reaches
whilst in its lower parts Newmill Beck is Grade D (fair quality).
</P>
<P>2.5 Nirex has adopted the policy that the RCF development will have no
significantly adverse effects on existing surface water quality. Whilst there
are no absolute criteria to gauge this the pre-project GQA grades and the
European Union ('EU') Directives on the standards to be maintained for drinking
water sources and protecting fish life provide appropriate criteria. To maintain
these standards Nirex will adhere to relevant UK legislation which forbids
wilful contamination of surface waters and to guidelines imposed by the NRA. The
latter stipulate design criteria for controlling the emissions from the RCF's
drainage system (maximum discharge to Newmill Beck of 600 litres per second
('l/s'), suspended solids less than 50 milligrams per litre (`mg/l') and no
visible oils or grease) and sewage treatment system (suspended solids not more
than 45 mg/l and Biochemical Oxygen Demand not more than 30 mg/l).
</P>
<P>2.6 Groundwaters will be protected by adopting design features to minimise
inflow of polluted water from the Platform Site. This will minimise the
possibility of groundwater contamination and thus comply with the policies and
practices of the NRA for the protection of groundwater. These encompass the
relevant EU Directive for groundwater protection.
</P>
<P>2.7 To further maintain environmental standards, Nirex will adhere to the
good practice and guidelines contained in the NRA's Pollution Prevention
Guidelines. These cover many of the activities to be undertaken during the
construction, operation and restoration of the RCF.
</P>
<P><B>Existing Situation
</B></P>
<P>2.8 The Surface Site lies entirely within the catchment of Newmill Beck and
is crossed by a small valley containing an intermittently flowing rill fed by
springs and rainfall. This connects with the larger southern tributary which
joins Newmill Beck about 2 km below the Site. Both streams are small, rarely
exceeding 2 metres in width and 15 centimetres in depth. Flows at Seascale Farm
average about 143 l/s There are several pools alongside lower Newmill Beck which
are important for the rare natterjack toads found there.
</P>
<P>2.9 Groundwater levels are about 10 metres below the Platform Site. They
typically fluctuate naturally by about 1 to 4 metres over the year. Below the
surface soils and glacial deposits (up to 5 metres thick) is a 450-metre depth
of sandstone which contains an aquifer tapped by BNFL. Below the sandstones are,
successively, layers of Brockram and Borrowdale Volcanic Group rocks. All of
these rocks have low conductivities i.e. groundwater passes only slowly through
them.
</P>
<P>2.10 The water quality in Newmill Beck and its southern tributary are
typical of small, upland streams in agricultural areas. They exhibit some
contamination from the surrounding agricultural lands. Typically, they are of
GQA Grades B and C in their middle reaches and generally comply with the
European standards for drinking water sources and fish protection. Groundwater
quality is also high near the surface. Below about 400 metres depth the
groundwater is saline.
</P>
<P>2.11 The biological (invertebrate animal) data also indicate that Newmill
Beck and the southern tributary are contaminated to some extent. The Biological
Monitoring Working Party ('BMWP') scores range up to 80. A BMWP score of 100 is
regarded as an indication of good quality river water. The presence of eel,
trout and stickleback in the streams indicate water of at least reasonable
quality. The few aquatic plants in the streams are all common species.
</P>
<P><B>Predicted Effects
</B></P>
<P>2.12 There are a number of activities and features of the RCF project which
could have effects on surface water, groundwater, the sea or domestic water
supplies. The principal ones are:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>earthworks involving soil stripping and cut-and-fill;
</LI>
<LI>embankments created from stored topsoil;
</LI>
<LI>on-site storage of potential contaminants;
</LI>
<LI>sanitation;
</LI>
<LI>shaft construction through the sandstone aquifer;
</LI>
<LI>saline groundwaters arising from deep underground;
</LI>
<LI>contamination of pumped underground water; and
</LI>
<LI>additional demands on domestic supplies.
</LI></UL>
<P>2.13 To minimise or avoid potential effects from the above during the
construction, operation and restoration of the RCF a number of design features
have been incorporated into the development. These include cut-off drains and
settlement ponds to intercept Platform Site run-off, a surface water drain to
carry treated run-off to Newmill Beck, immediate re-vegetation of permanent
earthworks, on-site sewage treatment plant discharging to sea, underground
pumped water discharged to sea, specially constructed storage area for chemicals
and progressive lining of the shafts as construction proceeds.
</P>
<P>2.14 The possible environmental effects of the RCF's activities and
features, after incorporation of the mitigating design features, are assessed by
evaluating them against the adopted criteria and standards summarized in section
4. Effects are considered significant only if they are predicted to cause these
to be exceeded.
</P>
<P>2.15 Most effects on surface waters could occur during the RCF's
construction and site restoration due to the necessary earthworks at these
times. Any high loads of sediments in surface run-off will be temporary however
and coupled with the distance to the southern tributary effects there will be
little or nil. Any contaminants released at the Platform Site will be
intercepted and treated in the drainage system and no effects from such a source
are expected. The spoil disposal area will be freely draining but no effects are
anticipated from its run-off. The spoil is almost inert and will be rapidly
covered in topsoil and revegetated.</P>
<P>2.16 The Platform Site's drainage system during the operational phase is
designed to ensure there is little chance of on-site flooding and that the first
and most contaminated flush of storm water will be retained and treated.
Permitted discharges of 600 l/s to Newmill Beck will cause minor (5 centimetre)
rises. As such rises already occur naturally, discharge of Platform Site run-off
will have no effects on the flora and fauna. Water for wheel, plant and
equipment washings and for use in concrete batching areas will be mainly
recycled from settlement tanks thereby making no demands on domestic supplies.
Water from washing activities will be treated on-site before disposal to Newmill
Beck whilst that from concreting areas will be discharged to sea. None of these
activities will therefore adversely affect surface or ground waters.
</P>
<P>2.17 Sewage water from the on-site treatment plant will meet NRA standards
and be discharged directly to sea without ill effect on the marine fauna and
flora. Similarly, water arising from underground activities and seepage from the
rocks will be pumped to and treated on the surface before discharge to sea,
again with no effects on watercourses or receiving water.
</P>
<P>2.18 Inflows of waters to the shafts from the sandstones will be controlled
by appropriate grouting techniques. These will limit water inflows to a few tens
of cubic metres per day. There will be no discernible effects on groundwater
flows or levels. Some drilling fluids, consisting of domestic water to which
non-toxic tracers are added, will be lost to the groundwater during
construction. The amounts will be small and there will be no significant effects
on groundwater quality.
</P>
<P>2.19 To minimise the risk of pollution from chemicals stored on-site, they
will be kept in specially-bunded and imperviously floored areas. During
restoration excess chemicals and fluids will be removed from the site.
Throughout the project therefore there is minimal risk of pollution to surface
and groundwaters from chemicals. Should accidents occur then clean-up procedures
will be immediately undertaken to deal with contamination levels that cannot be
handled by the RCF's built-in containment and treatment system.
</P>
<P>2.20 Water requirements at Gosforth and other nearby areas will be
unaffected by the RCF project. A booster station and additional necessary works
will be installed by North West Water Plc.
</P>
<P>2.21 Additional mitigation procedures to those already incorporated into the
RCF's design and operational measures will be undertaken to further minimise and
avoid environmental effects. Procedures will be drawn up and emergency equipment
provided for the containment and clean up of any accidental spills. There will
be regular monitoring of oil interceptors and settlement tanks with clean out
and off-site disposal of their contents as required.
</P>
<P> 2.22 Programmes for monitoring the chemical and physical qualities of
discharges will be put into operation after discussion with the NRA. The factors
to be monitored are likely to include as a minimum those which will be subject
to consent conditions by the NRA and those used for classifying water quality.
The fauna of Newmill Beck will be monitored on a regular basis. If any
monitoring activities detect adverse effects arising from the RCF project then
corrective actions will be developed and implemented.
</P>
<P><B>Conclusions
</B></P>
<P>2.23 The RCF project as designed and managed for its construction, operation
and restoration incorporates many measures to reduce and avoid environmental
effects. In view of these it is most unlikely that any significantly adverse
effects will occur to surface, ground or marine waters and domestic water
supplies.
</P>
<P>2.24 In addition to these comprehensive environmental safeguards, Nirex will
operate a rigorous monitoring programme to continuously check water quality and
the fauna in Newmill Beck and the southern tributary. This programme will detect
any undue changes in the environmental quality of these areas. If these are due
to any RCF activity, immediate measures will be taken to correct that activity
and to restore any loss of environmental quality.
</P>
<P>2.25 Accordingly the RCF development will have no significantly adverse
effects on the water environment.
</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. SCOPE OF EVIDENCE
</B></P>
<P>3.1 Nirex is carrying out a series of investigations around Sellafield in
order to ascertain the area's suitability for an underground repository for
solid intermediate and low level radioactive wastes. As part of that series of
studies Nirex has identified the need for a RCF at Longlands Farm near
Sellafield.
</P>
<P>3.2 The Proof of Evidence considers the types and significance of
environmental effects that could occur (during the RCF's construction, operation
and restoration) to the surface, groundwater and coastal marine waters on and in
the neighbourhood of the RCF site. Environmental effects on the freshwater fauna
and flora (excluding amphibians) of the streams in the catchment in which the
RCF is located are also assessed. The evidence also considers the possible
effects on the supply of domestic water to nearby residents and communities.
</P>
<P>3.3 Possible environmental effects on the various waters and the streams'
fauna and flora are compared with the existing situation and with national and
international, standards and guidelines designed to maintain a high
environmental quality.
</P>
<P>3.4 Localities described and studied in this Proof of Evidence are shown in
<A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Figure3.1">Figure 3.1</A>.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Description"></A><B> 4. DESCRIPTION OF METHODS
</B></P>
<P>Two major investigations have been carried out to assess the aquatic
environment in the RCF's vicinity. These have studied the water quality in
Newmill Beck and its southern tributary and the fauna and flora of the same two
streams.
</P>
<P><B>Water Quality
</B></P>
<P>Water quality in Newmill Beck and the southern tributary has been studied
from June 1991 to June 1995. A number of key parameters were chosen for study:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>pH;
</LI>
<LI>Electrical conductivity;
</LI>
<LI>Suspended solids;
</LI>
<LI>Alkalinity;
</LI>
<LI>Dissolved oxygen;
</LI>
<LI>Biochemical Oxygen Demand (`BOD');
</LI>
<LI>Ammoniacal nitrogen;
</LI>
<LI>Nitrate;
</LI>
<LI>Orthophosphate;
</LI>
<LI>Chloride; and
</LI>
<LI>Total hydrocarbons.
</LI></UL>
<P>4.3 These are the parameters most likely to be influenced by any effects
arising from the RCF project. They also include the parameters that are used to
assess the biological and chemical quality of freshwaters by, for example, the
NRA.
</P>
<P>4.4 Water quality data for the various parameters were obtained from the NRA
[NRX/5/1](1) and from a specially conducted monitoring survey carried out three
times per year. A number of localities downstream of the RCF site were examined.
These were chosen as likely points to show up any effects that may arise during
the RCF project. Water samples were analysed by NAMAS-accredited analytical
laboratories.
</P>
<P> 4.5 Information on the quality of shallow groundwaters (less than 150
metres depth) in the vicinity of the RCF was obtained from the NRA [NRX/5/2](2).
Information on deeper groundwaters (200-1600 metres) was obtained from studies
carried out by Nirex [COR/101](3).
</P>
<P><B>Fauna and Flora
</B></P>
<P>4.6 Data on the occurrence of invertebrate fauna in lower Newmill Beck have
been obtained from the NRA [NRX/5/3](4). In addition the invertebrate
communities were sampled in a specially conducted baseline survey from June 1991
to June 1995.
</P>
<P>4.7 All these studies collected information to estimate the Department of
the Environment's BMWP scores [GOV/126](5). These scores represent the aggregate
of scoring categories of invertebrates found in the samples. Species sensitive
to pollution are given a high score and thus result in a higher BMWP score for
the localities at which they occur. Conversely, species insensitive to pollution
are given low scores and a sample dominated by such species will have a low BMWP
score, indicating poor water quality at that locality.
</P>
<P>4.8 Baseline survey samples were normally collected three times per year in
spring, summer and autumn. These are the standard sampling times best suited to
investigate the invertebrate fauna of a watercourse over a year. Samples were
collected by sweeping the water, substrates and any streamside vegetation for
three minutes with a 1-mm mesh pond net.
</P>
<P>4.9 To overcome statistical bias due to variable sample sizes the BMWP
scores are divided by the number of scoring categories (taxa) to provide an
additional indicator of biological quality, the average score per taxon
('ASPT').
</P>
<P>4.10 A further standard check on the biological quality of water is the
Environmental Quality Index ('EQI'). This is derived by dividing the measured
BMWP or ASPT value by the score for that type of stream derived from the River
Invertebrate Prediction and Classification System ('RIVPACS') [NRX/5/4](6). The
RIVPACS value predicts the BMWP and ASPT scores for a particular river or stream
assuming it has no pollution. Thus the EQI is a measure of the effects of
pollution. The amount by which the EQI falls below 1 indicates the degree to
which invertebrates have been affected by pollution.
</P>
<P>4.11 Newmill Beck was sampled in July 1993 by NRA fishery officers using
standard electro-fishing techniques [NRX/5/5](7). It was sampled in the upper
reaches and at the middle reaches around Seascale Hall.
</P>
<P>4.12 There is little aquatic flora in Newmill Beck or its southern
tributary. When aquatic macrophytes were seen, they were collected for
identification and estimates made of their abundance.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Legislation"></A><B>5. WATER LEGISLATION AND GUIDELINES
</B></P>
<P><B>Surface Water
</B></P>
<P>5.1 The NRA and the Department of the Environment have recently introduced
two complementary schemes for classifying surface waters. These are:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>The GQA scheme, which provides standards for the measurement of water
quality irrespective of river uses (Table 5.1) [GOV/127](8); and
</LI>
<LI>Statutory Water Quality Objectives (`WQOs') comprising different &quot;use
classes&quot; defining use-related standards for setting quality targets to
protect specific river uses according to local needs [GOV/128](9).
</LI></UL>
<P>5.2 The NRA has classified Newmill Beck as GQA Grade D. This indicates water
of fair quality and applies to lower Newmill Beck where the main NRA sampling
station is located. Results from the specially conducted survey (1991-1995)
indicate that water in the middle parts of Newmill Beck and the southern
tributary is of higher quality, mainly Grade B/C (fair to good quality).
Statutory WQOs for Newmill Beck have not yet been established.
</P>
<P>5.3 Nirex has adopted the policy that the RCF development will have no
significant adverse effect on surface water quality. There are no absolute
criteria for determining such effects but they could include the standards
contained in, for example, the GQA and WQO criteria and EU directives on
drinking water and the protection of freshwater fish [GOV/129](10),
[GOV/130](11). The former is intended to establish criteria which ensure the
watercourse is of sufficient quality to serve as a drinking water source. The
latter sets standards appropriate to the protection or improvement of surface
waters in order to support fish life. Selected parameters from the EU Directives
are presented in <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A>.
</P>
<P>5.4 Under current UK water protection legislation [GOV/803](12) it is an
offence to cause or knowingly permit any poisonous, noxious or polluting matter
to enter controlled waters (surface or ground). This includes silt, cement,
concrete, oil, petrol, sewage or other pollutants. Adherence to this legislation
therefore is an appropriate objective to be maintained throughout the life of
the RCF project.
</P>
<P>5.5 The provisions in UK and EU water quality legislation have been
reinforced by NRA guidelines/standards to be implemented by Nirex throughout the
RCF project. Thus a number of design criteria and features have been adopted for
the development to avoid or reduce the potential effects of emissions to surface
waters, groundwaters and seawater. For discharges of run-off to surface
freshwaters the NRA stipulates the following design criteria [COR/114](13):
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Maximum discharge to Newmill Beck to be 600 l/s;
</LI>
<LI>Suspended solids to be less than 50 mg/l; and
</LI>
<LI>No visible oils or grease.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.6 Discharges compliant with these criteria are intended to ensure that
water quality in Newmill Beck is not significantly affected, in accordance with
NRA objectives.
</P>
<P>5.7 The discharges of foul waters treated at the on-site sewage treatment
plant will meet the following criteria, set by the NRA [COR/114](13):
</P>
<UL>
<LI>BOD: not more than 30 mg/l;
</LI>
<LI>Suspended solids: not more than 45 mg/l; and
</LI>
<LI>Ammoniacal nitrogen: no limit.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Groundwater
</B></P>
<P>5.8 Groundwaters are protected by adopting design features (Section 7) to
prevent inflow of polluted water from the Platform Site. This will minimise the
possibility of groundwater contamination and thus comply with the policies and
practices of the NRA for the protection of groundwater [GOV/131](14). The
guidelines include the need for:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Protection of groundwater levels and flows from disturbance, lowering,
raising, impedance or interception; and
</LI>
<LI>Avoidance of chemical contamination.
</LI></UL>
<P>5.9 The NRA guidelines encompass the relevant EU Directive on the protection
of groundwater against contamination [GOV/132](15).
</P>
<P><B>Site Practice
</B></P>
<P>5.10 The RCF development will adhere to the good practice and guidelines
contained in the NRA's Pollution Prevention Guidelines [GOV/133](16).  These lay
down the necessary practices covering many of the activities to be undertaken
during the construction, operation and maintenance of the RCF.</P>
<P><A NAME="ExistingSituation"></A><B>6. EXISTING SITUATION
</B></P>
<P><B>Water Resources and Water Quality
</B></P>
<P>Hydrological Characteristics
</P>
<P>6.1 Freshwater run-off from the Cumbrian hills drains via a network of short
rivers flowing predominantly west or southwest onto the West Cumbrian Plain. The
main catchments are those of two rivers north of the Surface Site, the Ehen and
the Calder, which join and flow into the sea at Sellafield. The Bleng lies east
of the Surface Site and joins the Irt, which flows to the Ravenglass Estuary.
</P>
<P>6.2 The Surface Site lies entirely within the catchment (11 km(2)) of
Newmill Beck, which rises some 5 km to the north-east of the Sellafield Works on
the slopes of Ponsonby Fell and flows to the north and west of the Surface Site.
Newmill Beck drains predominantly agricultural land under pasture and also a
conifer plantation at Lingbank.
</P>
<P>6.3 The Surface Site slopes generally to the south-west. It is crossed by a
small valley containing an intermittently flowing rill which is fed by surface
springs and run-off after prolonged rainfall.
</P>
<P>6.4 The local surface drainage flows along a circuitous valley, mainly to
the south or south-east, until it joins an unnamed southern tributary of Newmill
Beck which has its origin between Seascale and Gosforth. It contributes only a
small proportion of the southern tributary's flow.
</P>
<P>6.5 Newmill Beck receives its southern tributary about 2 km to the
south-west of the Surface Site, then flows across Seascale Golf Links and enters
(via sluice gates) the estuary of the Calder and the Ehen near the Sellafield
Works. Both Newmill Beck and its southern tributary are small streams, rarely
exceeding 2 metres in width and 15 centimetres in depth. There are no long term
flow data available from the NRA for Newmill Beck or its tributaries. Median
flows in the vicinity of Seascale Hall Farm are estimated as 13.0 l/s/km(2) of
catchment, equivalent to 143 l/s.
</P>
<P>6.6 There are several pools alongside the lower reach of Newmill Beck, close
to the estuary, which are separated from the beck by sluice gates. The pools are
important for the conservation of the Natterjack Toad and are filled from the
beck during the breeding season.</P>
<P> Hydrogeological Conditions
</P>
<P>6.7 The Surface Site has a variable but generally shallow depth of surface
soil, alluvium and boulder clays (typically about 1 to 2 metres thick, generally
less than 5 metres thick), overlying about 450 metres of Triassic sandstones.
Data from Nirex deep borehole investigations indicate that the Calder Sandstone
has generally higher permeability than the underlying St. Bees Sandstone.
</P>
<P>6.8 Groundwater levels in the St. Bees aquifer are about 10 metres below the
Platform Site (which is at 84.5 metres AOD). These levels typically fluctuate
naturally by 1 to 4 metres over a year as a result of climatic effects, tidal
loading and river stage. A number of small perched aquifers are found in the
superficial glacial deposits in the area.
</P>
<P>6.9 BNFL abstracts water from the near surface sandstones in the vicinity of
the Surface Site. Three boreholes in the Calder Valley between Calder Abbey and
Prior Scales are used to supplement flows in the River Calder. Three boreholes
along Black Beck and one at Calder Bridge supply the Sellafield Works. These
abstractions cause groundwater drawdowns up to 60 metres.
</P>
<P>6.10 Below the sandstones is a layer of breccia called the Brockram, which
has a variable permeability, with higher values of hydraulic conductivity
measured where the rock is fractured.
</P>
<P>6.11 The Brockram overlies the Borrowdale Volcanic Group (`BVG'). Data from
the deep borehole indicate that the flow of water through the BVG is likely to
be controlled largely by the presence of fractures in the rock.
</P>
<P>Local Water Quality
</P>
<P>6.12 A water quality survey was undertaken for Newmill Beck and its southern
tributary over the period June 1991 to June 1995. A summary of the results is
shown in <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>. This table also makes
reference to water quality data from NRA sampling locations.
</P>
<P>6.13 <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> shows that overall water
quality characteristics are typical of small, upland streams in agricultural
areas. The NRA use the GQA quality classification system by which watercourses
are graded from A to F according to chemical criteria (<A
HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A>).
</P>
<P>6.14 Newmill Beck in its middle reaches has consistently achieved a GQA
grade B or C which is indicative of good to fair water quality. The southern
tributary is also classified as GQA grade B or C. Both watercourses, however,
are prone to poor water quality at times, due mainly to pollution from
agricultural land. Levels of nitrates are generally higher in the lower reaches
of the beck and the southern tributary, a feature typical of run-off from
agricultural land. The elevated concentrations of ammonia (maximum values)
observed at sample locations 3 and 4 also reflect possible contamination from
agricultural sources. In addition, low flow conditions, which are a common
feature in these streams, will also contribute to variable water quality.
</P>
<P>6.15 The values in <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A> indicate
that generally the waters of Newmill Beck and the southern tributary comply with
the EU standards for drinking water sources and fish protection (<A
HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A>).
</P>
<P>6.16 During sampling in June 1991 levels of dissolved oxygen were observed
to be highly variable at sample location 6 in the lower reaches of the beck, to
the west of the railway line. Here, impoundment of flows by the sluice gates at
the confluence with the estuary had resulted in algal growth and the subsequent
diurnal fluctuation of dissolved oxygen.
</P>
<P>Groundwater Quality
</P>
<P>6.17 Data provided by the NRA from shallow boreholes (less than 150 metres
depth) in the Sellafield area indicate that groundwater is generally of very
good quality (with reference to the EU Drinking Water Directive values).
</P>
<P>6.18 Data from drilling of boreholes on the West Cumbria coastal plain show
the groundwater at depth to be saline. For example, below about 400 metres in
Nirex Deep Borehole 2 (situated less than 400 metres from the Surface Site) the
chloride concentration is in the order of 15,000 mg/l (whilst that of seawater
is typically 19,300 mg/l). Further west below the coast the groundwater at depth
has a salinity up to six times that of seawater. For groundwaters in Boreholes 2
and 4, the variation with depth of the concentration of some major ions and
other elements, including metals, is shown in <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table6.2">Table
6.2</A>.
</P>
<P><B>Flora and Fauna of Newmill Beck
</B></P>
<P>Invertebrate Fauna
</P>
<P>6.19 <A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A> summarises the data on
invertebrate occurrence from the sampling sites shown in
<A HREF="nrx5fig.htm#Figure3.1">Figure 3.1</A>. The BMWP scores, which are an
indication of water quality, also indicate (as do the chemical data) that
Newmill Beck and the southern tributary are contaminated to some degree.
</P>
<P>6.20 The average BMWP scores from Newmill Beck and the southern tributary
range from 18 to 66 (seasonal maximum of 80) and the ASPT from 3.0 to 4.4. These
values indicate only moderate conditions. A BMWP score of 100 is regarded as an
indication of good quality waters, whilst the score may exceed 200 in some
rivers [GOV/134](17).
</P>
<P>6.21 Calculation of the Environmental Quality Index corroborated the
findings of the chemical and BMWP investigations. The values of the EQI (0.41 to
0.61) indicate a significant reduction in the quality of the invertebrate
population from that expected in a Newmill Beck and southern tributary
unaffected by pollution.
</P>
<P>6.22 The BMWP and other indices in the small rill crossing the Surface Site
will be less than for the southern tributary and Newmill Beck. This is because
of its small size and fluctuating flows which decline to zero at times.
</P>
<P>Fish
</P>
<P>6.23 Eels were observed in Newmill Beck at both sites and brown trout were
estimated at Seascale Hall to have a density of 4.16 per 100 m(2). It is
unlikely that trout migrate into Newmill Beck due to culverting downstream which
impedes migration from the lower reaches of the River Calder.
</P>
<P>6.24 On occasion, three-spined stickleback were found in the BMWP samples.
</P>
<P>6.25 The presence of eels, trout and three-spined sticklebacks indicate
water of at least reasonable quality. These species can tolerate some reduction
of water quality.
</P>
<P>Flora
</P>
<P>Aquatic plants were searched for at the times of the BMWP and water quality
surveys. The only species found (all at site 8 in the southern tributary) were
the mud water starwort (Callitriche stagnalis), small pondweed (Potamogeton
pusillus) and the watercress (Nasturtium officianale). All of these species are
common and widespread throughout the UK. Again, they are indicative of water of
at least reasonable quality.
</P>
<P><A NAME="PredictedEffects"></A><B> 7. PREDICTED EFFECTS
</B></P>
<P><B>Design Features
</B></P>
<P>7.1 To minimise or avoid potential effects arising from the construction,
operation and restoration of the RCF, a number of design features have been
incorporated into the development. These are:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Cut-off drains and settlement ponds to intercept Platform Site run-off
during all stages of the development thereby preventing it from immediately
entering surface waters;
</LI>
<LI>A surface water drain to carry Platform Site treated run-off for discharge
to Newmill Beck;
</LI>
<LI>A multi-bay settlement tank, numerous catchpits and oil/petrol interceptors
and grease-trapped gullies within the on-site drainage system. These will
improve the quality of the emissions before their discharge;
</LI>
<LI>All cut-and-fill slopes and embankments of topsoil will be formed at stable
angles and sown as quickly as possible to minimise any sediments washed from
them by rainfall;
</LI>
<LI>An on-site sewage treatment plant that will discharge its effluent via a
drain to the Calder Interceptor Sewer within the Sellafield Works prior to
discharge to the sea;
</LI>
<LI>Discharge of the underground pumped water via the sewage drain to the
Sellafield Works prior to discharge to the sea;
</LI>
<LI>Storage of materials with the potential to contaminate water resources in
covered, sealed or otherwise protected areas on hardstandings. Tanks will be
surrounded by bunds of impermeable material; and
</LI>
<LI>The use of impermeable material to line areas susceptible to ground
contamination.
</LI></UL>
<P>7.2 These features provide the most appropriate mechanisms for controlling
the quantities and qualities of aqueous emissions and protecting the groundwater
aquifer.
</P>
<P><B>Assessment of Activities
</B></P>
<P>7.3 The main activities and features of the development programme which
could have effects on surface water, groundwater or domestic water supplies are
listed below and described in the following paragraphs:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Earthworks involving soil stripping and cut-and-fill operations during
establishment of the Surface Site;
</LI>
<LI>Embankments created from stored topsoil;
</LI>
<LI>Potential contaminants stored on-site in covered, sealed or otherwise
protected areas;
</LI>
<LI>Sanitation and other site operations;
</LI>
<LI>Shaft construction through the sandstone aquifer;
</LI>
<LI>Underground operations giving rise to saline groundwaters;
</LI>
<LI>Water pumped from underground operations which may contain process
contaminants; and
</LI>
<LI>Demands for domestic water, for example for sanitation, surface and
underground dust damping and vehicle washings.
</LI></UL>
<P>7.4 Earthworks and embankments may result in the off-site discharge of
rainfall run-off containing elevated levels of suspended solids from exposed
areas. Additionally there will be alterations to surface water drainage flows
during cut-and-fill operations, construction of access roads and the laying of
impermeable surfaces.
</P>
<P>7.5 Removal of topsoil and subsoils combined with a level Platform Site will
increase the rate and amount of run-off draining from this area. The Platform
Site drainage and storage systems have been designed to ensure that there is
little chance of flooding on-site and that the first, and most contaminated,
flush of water during storm events can be contained and treated within the
system.
</P>
<P>7.6 Run-off effects during the operational stage of the development will
include increased rate and volumes from the Platform Site and discharges of used
domestic water. These have the potential to cause flooding downstream of the
Surface Site.
</P>
<P>7.7 Some of the materials brought onto the Surface Site could produce
adverse effects if released to watercourses or groundwater. The types and likely
quantities of materials which would be stored on site during the construction
and operation of the development are known. They principally comprise the
materials normally associated with a major construction project. Others, such as
groundwater tracers, are non- toxic.
</P>
<P>7.8 Underground water will arise from dust damping and underground drilling
activities. Water pumped to the surface for disposal will be contaminated with
suspended solids, drill cuttings and traces of chemicals such as oils.
</P>
<P>7.9 The peak water usage on the Surface Site (domestic, construction and
general usage) is estimated to be about 208 m(3)/day.
</P>
<P><B>Assessment of Effects
</B></P>
<P>7.10 The effects of construction and operation of the development and
restoration of the Surface Site are assessed against the adopted criteria and
requirements set out in Section 5. In addition the effects on the domestic water
supply to Gosforth and other local properties are considered. Effects are
considered significant only if they are predicted to cause adopted standards,
criteria and guidelines to be exceeded. Otherwise they are considered to be of
little or no effect.
</P>
<P>Surface Water Run-off
</P>
<P>7.11 Most of the effects on surface water quality will occur during the
RCF's construction and restoration stages because of the nature of the
activities, in particular movements of earth. At these stages, bare soil will be
exposed and heaped, leading to possible high sediment loads in surface run-off.
Any such effects will however be temporary and, coupled with the distance to the
nearest permanent watercourse (the southern tributary of Newmill Beck), are
expected to have little or no effect on water quality.
</P>
<P>7.12 Platform Site drainage could contain contaminants released from
accidental spillages and the vehicle and plant washings area. Any such
substances will be adequately treated in the oil interceptors and sediment traps
in the drainage system and removed off-site for disposal at a licensed site. All
accumulations of sediments in the drainage system will be routinely collected
for off-site disposal. These design features will reduce the likelihood of
released contaminants from reaching surface watercourses. Accordingly little or
no effect is predicted.
</P>
<P>7.13 Drainage water into the intermittent stream running underneath the
Platform Site will be reduced in volume as some rainfall falling onto the
Platform Site, which would normally supply this stream, will be intercepted by
the peripheral drain and discharged directly to Newmill Beck. The intermittent
stream will also be supplied, until after restoration, by drainage from above
and below the Surface Site. Water quality in Newmill Beck will be unaffected and
consequently there will be no effects on flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>7.14 The Spoil Disposal Area on the Surface Site will be freely draining.
Run-off will not be collected and stored prior to entering surface watercourses.
It is anticipated that the saline water contained in the underground rocks will
have drained away before their surface disposal. The proportion of fine
sediments will be low. The BVG rocks of the Spoil Disposal Area are relatively
inert and therefore very resistant to weathering. They will be rapidly covered
in topsoil and re-vegetated. Accordingly, the storage of these rocks on the
surface is not expected to have any effect on water quality in surface
watercourses or groundwater.
</P>
<P> 7.15 The Platform Site drainage system and other storage capabilities have
been designed to ensure that there is little chance of flooding on-site and that
the first, and most contaminated, flush of water during storm events can be
contained and treated within the system. There is therefore no significant
effect predicted from storm events.
</P>
<P>7.16 In the unlikely event that storms will cause the retention capacity of
the Platform Site to be exceeded, excess water will fall to the south-east of
the Platform Site and spill over into the existing natural drainage system.
</P>
<P>7.17 Permitted discharges to Newmill Beck of 600 l/s will produce a
calculated water level rise of 5 cm in some downstream locations near Seascale
Hall Farm. This area is already subject to minor flooding and the effects of the
discharges will not significantly increase the frequency or magnitude of
flooding. Therefore, there will be no effects on the fauna of Newmill Beck
additional to those already experienced. Minimum flows in Newmill Beck will be
unaffected by the RCF development.
</P>
<P>7.18 Drainage water will arise from vehicle wheel washes, water bowsers and
washing down of plant and equipment. Water for these purposes will be met
largely from water recycled from the surface settlement tanks. Its discharge
after treatment will have no significant effects on water quality in Newmill
Beck.
</P>
<P>7.19 Water used for the washing down of areas where concrete has been made
or used is liable to be alkaline and contain fine particulate matter. Drainage
from this area will be collected in a separately bunded sump and sediments
disposed at a licensed facility off-site. The water will be re-cycled and
eventually disposed of to the sea via the Sellafield works outfall. There will
therefore be no effect on surface watercourses.
</P>
<P>7.20 Site Restoration will involve earth movements and the consequent risk
of polluted run-off similar in nature to Site Establishment. Any surface
material found to be contaminated will be disposed of at a licensed site. There
is therefore little likelihood of any pollution of surface waters.
</P>
<P>7.21 After restoration, surface run-off will return to pre-development
levels.
</P>
<P>Sewage Water
</P>
<P>7.22 Sewage water from the on-site treatment works will meet NRA emission
standards and be discharged to sea from the Sellafield works outfall. The
capacity of the treatment plant is twice the estimated average maximum flow per
day. There will therefore be no effect on surface watercourses and no
significant effect on the marine environment.
</P>
<P>7.23 The on-site sewage treatment plant will be decommissioned during
restoration. Any foul water arisings during this time will be retained and
stored on-site prior to off-site disposal or treatment at appropri- ate
facilities. There will be no effects on water resources.
</P>
<P>Underground Water
</P>
<P>7.24 Underground water will arise from inflow seepage from the sandstones
through the construction joints in the hydrostatic shaft lining, from the
Brockram and BVG rocks, the flushing of drill cuttings and the underground
damping of dust. The groundwater at depth is saline whilst small amounts of
contaminants will come from the drill cuttings, dust damping and possible
occasional accidental spillages.
</P>
<P>7.25 The peak pumping requirement during construction is estimated to be
about 425 m(3)/day for one shaft (4.9 l/s). This volume will be reduced to an
agreed level between Nirex and the contractor. During the operational phase of
the RCF the long term average water arisings (from inflow and process water) is
an estimated 185 m(3)/day (2.1 l/s). The RCF pumping capacity will be 7.5 l/s so
that it can deal with daily water inflows by pumping for only a few hours per
day and provide spare capacity.
</P>
<P>7.26 All underground waters will be pumped to an appropriately sized
interceptor/settlement tank on the surface and disposed of to sea via the
effluent pipeline to the Calder Interceptor Sewer. The disposal of underground
water will therefore have no effect on surface watercourses. Similarly, no
significant effects are predicted on the marine receiving waters.
</P>
<P>7.27 Pumping of underground water and discharge to sea will cease during
site restoration.
</P>
<P>Groundwater
</P>
<P>7.28 Inflows of water to the shafts from the sandstones will be controlled
during construction by appropriate grouting techniques. During the shaft sinking
cover grouting will be used to treat zones in the sandstones where groundwater
inflows may otherwise exceed the pumping capacity. Such zones will be identified
by routine probe drilling and testing ahead of excavation.
</P>
<P>7.29 Permanent control of shaft inflows will be provided by hydrostatically
designed concrete shaft linings extended from the surface through the sandstones
and into the Brockram. As excavation proceeds through the sandstones the shaft
linings will be progressively cast. Once these have reached sufficient strength
any voids between them and the rocks will be sealed by grout injection. Seals
will be installed at the base of each lining to prevent residual water flowing
down into the BVG formation.
</P>
<P>7.30 The ground treatment techniques employed in shaft sinking will limit
maximum groundwater inflows to a few tens of cubic metres per day during shaft
construction. There will therefore be little effect on the flow of groundwater
or its levels near the surface. Any such effects will be insignificant against
the natural fluctuations in levels of 1 to 4 metres.
</P>
<P>7.31 During the construction and operation of shafts and galleries, seepages
and inflows of groundwater will move towards the RCF. This inward flow will
substantially reduce the potential for contaminants to migrate out into the
surrounding rocks and groundwater. There will be little or no effect on
near-surface groundwater levels or flow rates compared to those occurring
naturally.
</P>
<P>7.32 During underground drilling operations, drilling fluid will be
circulated in the borehole at sufficiently high pressures to enter the rocks.
The volumes of drilling fluids involved are likely to be very small, and the
pressures will be controlled during drilling. The loss of drilling fluid to the
rocks is therefore likely to be extremely low during underground drilling
operations. The drilling fluid is primarily made up of domestic water to which a
tracer such as lithium chloride will be added. There will therefore be little
effect on groundwater quality.
</P>
<P>7.33 The galleries and shafts will be plugged, backfilled, sealed and capped
during site restoration. These activities are expected to have little effect on
groundwater levels, quality or flow rates.
</P>
<P>Chemical Storage and Disposal
</P>
<P>7.34 The storage and use of chemicals on-site leads to the possibility of
pollution of both surface and groundwater supplies. Measures are incorporated in
the design of the Platform Site to avoid or reduce the likelihood of accidental
releases to surface and groundwaters and maximise the opportunities for
treatment should they occur.
</P>
<P>7.35 The areas where drilling fluids are used will be separately bunded. All
drilling fluids will be placed in pits with an impermeable lining for subsequent
treatment and recirculation. Waste fluids will be pumped into a tanker and
removed from the Surface Site to an authorised disposal point. There will
therefore be no effect on surface water resources from the use of drilling
fluids.
</P>
<P>7.36 During restoration excess materials of the types stored and used on
site will be disposed of to a licensed waste site or recycling facility,
returned to suppliers or, in the case of explosives, by controlled explosions.
There will therefore be no effect on surface and groundwaters.
</P>
<P> Water Requirements
</P>
<P>7.37 The RCF's water supply will be connected into the existing public water
mains along the A595(T). North West Water Plc will ensure that the RCF's
requirements will have no effect on the supply to Gosforth and other properties
in the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>Significance of Effects
</P>
<P>7.38 Run-off from the Platform Site will comply with NRA requirements before
discharge to Newmill Beck. Consequently there will be no significant effects on
existing water quality in Newmill Beck or the southern tributary. Their existing
high levels of compliance with national and European water quality criteria for
protection and conservation of water quality and aquatic life will continue.
</P>
<P>7.39 Emissions of treated sewage effluents and underground water arisings
will comply with NRA requirements before disposal to the sea via the effluent
pipeline to the Calder Interceptor Sewer. These emissions will therefore have no
effects on surface or groundwaters and no significant effects on the marine
environment.
</P>
<P>7.40 Measures to avoid or reduce accidental contamination by chemicals
stored or used on the Surface Site will ensure there are no significant effects
on surface or groundwater supplies. Shafts and galleries are not anticipated to
have any significant effects on surface groundwater levels or flows.
</P>
<P>7.41 The demands of the development will have no significant effects on the
supply of domestic water to Gosforth and other local properties around the
Surface Site.
</P>
<P><B>Additional Mitigation
</B></P>
<P>7.42 In addition to the RCF's design and operational measures to minimise
and avoid environmental effects, a number of additional measures will be
undertaken.
</P>
<P>7.43 Procedures will be drawn up and emergency equipment provided for the
containment and clean up of spills. Regular monitoring of oil interceptors and
settlement tanks will be carried out with clean out and off-site disposal of any
contamination.
</P>
<P>7.44 Programmes for monitoring the chemical and physical qualities of
discharges will be put into operation after discussion with the NRA. The factors
to be monitored are likely to include as a minimum those which will be subject
to consent conditions by the NRA.<BR>
</P>
<P>7.45 The fauna of Newmill Beck will be monitored on a regular basis. This
will be discussed with English Nature and the NRA. It is likely to include
monitoring the invertebrate fauna of the beck and the Natterjack Toad
population.
</P>
<P>7.46 If the monitoring activities detect any adverse effects arising from
the RCF corrective actions will be developed and implemented.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B> 8. CONCLUSIONS
</B></P>
<P>8.1 The RCF project as designed and managed for its construction, operation
and restoration incorporates considerable measures designed to reduce and avoid
environmental effects.
</P>
<P>8.2 In view of these it is considered most unlikely that any significant
environmental effects will occur to surface, ground or marine waters and
domestic water supplies in the RCF's vicinity.
</P>
<P>8.3 In addition to these comprehensive environmental safeguards, Nirex will
also operate a rigorous monitoring programme designed to continuously check
water quality and fauna and flora in Newmill Beck and the southern tributary.
This programme will detect any undue perturbation in the environmental quality
of these areas. If these are due to any RCF activity, immediate measures will be
taken to correct that activity and to restore any loss of environmental quality.
</P>
<P>8.4 Accordingly, the RCF development will have no significantly adverse
effects on the water environment.
</P>
