<P><B>ROLAND HUGH WOODBRIDGE will say:</B>
</P>
<P><B>1. <A NAME="PERSONAL">PERSONAL DETAILS</A>
</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am a Senior Environmental Scientist in WS Atkins Environment which is
based in Epsom, Surrey. The consultancy provides services in a range of fields
including landscape, planning, noise, land contamination ecology, water and air
quality.
</P>
<P>1.2 I hold a Master of Science degree in Environmental Pollution Science
from Brunel University. I am a Licentiate of the Royal Society of Chemistry.
</P>
<P>1.3 I have been involved in air quality issues since 1979, when I worked for
2.5 years as an analytical chemist in a research engineering company
characterising diesel engine emissions. I subsequently worked on air quality
matters in a London Borough including advising the Planning Committee on consent
conditions. Since joining the consultancy in 1990 I have become increasingly
involved in dispersion modelling studies. These have included dust assessments
of opencast coal mines, limestone quarries and gravel extraction operations.
</P>
<P>1.4 I have contributed to various air quality studies for the Highways
Agency including the Polegate Bypass, and the assessment of the air quality
impact of motorway links to the Second Severn Crossing. I presented air quality
evidence at the Public Inquiries on the A1 widening between Alconbury and
Fletton Parkway, and the M11 Junction 5 Slip Roads. My personal involvement in
Nirex assessments for the RCF commenced in January 1993.</P>
<P><B><A NAME="SUMMARY">2. SUMMARY</A></B>
</P>
<P>2.1 The possible effects of the proposed RCF development upon local air
quality were considered. This involved an initial appraisal of all stages of the
development's construction, operation and Surface Site restoration with regard
to potential releases to the atmosphere. A qualitative assessment of all
activities eliminated the majority as being likely to have an insignificant or
nil effect on air quality. Quantitative estimates of dust emission rates were
made for those stages of the development involving the highest rates of movement
of soils and spoil. These estimates were used together with local meteorological
data as the basis for a dispersion modelling exercise, which provided an
indication of the rate and range of dust deposition in the area surrounding the
development. 
</P>
<P>2.2 The increment to monthly average dust deposition rates at the
residential properties closest to the Surface Site which may result from the
development is not likely to exceed 20 mg/m(2)/day. This is only 10% of the
nuisance threshold. This may occur for three months during the entire programme.
</P>
<P>2.3 Dust deposition measurements have been carried out at a number of
locations. The results have shown that there is a wide natural variation in
monthly average deposition rates due to meteorological and other factors which
may be as much as 100 mg/m(2)/day. The dust generated by the development will be
from natural soil and rock, and will be similar in nature to dust currently
arising from local agricultural activities. During much of the programme while
shaft sinking is in progress there will be virtually no effect even on the
closest properties. At other stages of the development the small predicted
increments to dust deposition rates at residential properties will be
indistinguishable from the large natural variations in monthly dust fall.</P>
<P><B><A NAME="BACKGROUND">3. BACKGROUND AND SCOPE</A></B>
</P>
<P>3.1 The possible effects of the proposed development upon local air quality
were considered. This involved an initial appraisal of all stages of the
development's construction, operation and Surface Site restoration with regard
to potential releases to the atmosphere. A qualitative assessment of all
activities eliminated the majority as being likely to have an insignificant or
nil effect on air quality. Quantitative estimates of dust emission rates were
made for those stages of the development involving the highest rates of movement
of soils and spoil. These estimates were used together with local meteorological
data as the basis for a dispersion modelling exercise, which provided an
indication of the rate and range of dust deposition in the area surrounding the
development. 
</P>
<P>3.2 The local meteorological factors which affect dust release and its
subsequent dispersion are described, as are air quality standards and
guidelines. The significance of the modelled dust deposition rates has been
assessed in the context of these air quality criteria, the existing variation in
monthly average deposition rate and the general standard of air quality in the
vicinity of the development.
</P>
<P>3.3 The assessment does not take account of dust control measures which are
inherent in the design, and no allowance has been made for dust suppression on
haul roads, although it is planned to employ water sprays as necessary. The
assessment also used conservative emission factors which will tend to
overestimate the rate of dust emission from certain operations. </P>
<P><B><A NAME="AIR">4. AIR QUALITY AND METEOROLOGY</A>
</B></P>
<P><B>Existing Air Quality</B></P>
<P>4.1 Potential sources of air pollution in the vicinity of the Surface Site
include domestic premises and vehicles using the local roads, as well as a
background contribution from industrial sources that are some distance away.
There is a low housing density in the immediate vicinity of the Surface Site, so
that the effects of heating facilities and other domestic sources are limited. 
</P>
<P>4.2 Given the above factors and the primarily rural nature of the immediate
surroundings, the background air quality is expected to be generally of a good
standard. This was confirmed by a review of measurements of nitrogen dioxide,
suspended particulates and dust deposition rate which were carried out between
August 1991 and April 1992. Measurements of monthly mean dust deposition rates
have been made at four locations since May 1993 as part of a long term
monitoring programme.
</P>
<P>Nitrogen Dioxide</P>
<P>4.3 During a two month survey in 1989 and an eight month survey in 1991-2 in
the Sellafield area, long term average concentrations of nitrogen dioxide were
found to be typical of those experienced by rural communities, with a range of
between 15 mg/m(3) and 25 mg/m(3) at sixteen background locations. As would be
expected, road traffic exhaust is the main local source of nitrogen dioxide, and
this was reflected in the higher concentrations observed at the A595(T) (29
mg/m(3) to 39 mg/m(3)) and roadside locations (25 mg/m(3) to 30 mg/m(3)). These
levels are commonly found in urban or small town environments and reported
roadside measurements near heavily used trunk roads elsewhere in the UK are
often much higher than the present findings.
</P>
<P>4.4 The background nitrogen dioxide levels are well below the World Health
Organisation ('WHO') Air Quality Guidelines for Europe [GOV/124](1), which give
a 24 hour guideline of 150 mg/m(3). The European air quality standards for
nitrogen dioxide given in Council Directive 85/203/EEC [GOV/125](2) are in terms
of percentiles of hourly values measured throughout one year. There is a limit
value of 200 mg/m(3) as a 98th percentile, and guide values of 135 mg/m(3) and
50 mg/m(3) as 98th and 50th percentiles respectively. These</P>
<P>percentiles have been empirically related to annual mean concentrations,
Nitrogen Dioxide [NRX/6/1](3). The limit value and guide values quoted in the
Directive are likely to be met at locations where the annual mean values are
less than 83 mg/m(3) and 55 mg/m(3) respectively. On this basis the background
and roadside survey locations appear to have nitrogen dioxide concentrations
well below both the limit and guide values.
</P>
<P>Suspended Particulates</P>
<P>4.5 Average twelve hour total suspended particulate concentrations were
measured at the Calder Gate entrance to the Sellafield Works over four one week
periods between August 1991 and April 1992. The four average measurements for
these weeks were in the range of 33 mg/m(3) to 96 mg/m(3). The WHO Air Quality
Guidelines for Europe [GOV/124](1) recommend a twenty four hour limit of 120
mg/m(3) for total suspended particulates. Inspection of daily readings during
these monitoring periods shows that this value was exceeded on three occasions
in January 1992 due to construction work being carried out adjacent to the
sampling location.
</P>
<P>Dust Deposition</P>
<P>4.6 Dust deposition measurements were carried out between August 1991 and
April 1992 using directional dust gauges which were located at the Sellafield
Works Calder Gate and Gosforth School throughout this period. Total monthly
deposition rates were in the range 63 mg/m(2)/day to 119 mg/m(2)/day and
28mg/m(2)/day to 136 mg/m(2)/day respectively. These dust levels are well below
the 200 mg/m(2)/day monthly average deposition rate generally accepted as an
empirical threshold for potential dust nuisance.
</P>
<P>4.7 Since May 1993 further measurements of monthly average dust deposition
rates have been carried out using British Standard deposit gauges in the
vicinity of the Surface Site. Newton Manor, Longlands Farm, Town End Farm and
Boonwood Garden Centre were chosen as monitoring sites, as they include some of
the properties nearest the development. These locations are shown in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figures 6.1</A> to 6.4. The results shown in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table4.1">Table 4.1</A> tend to confirm that although
there is considerable variation from month to month, most readings</P>
<P>are in a range similar to that observed at Gosforth School.
</P>
<P><B>Meteorology</B></P>
<P>4.8 The weather near the Sellafield meteorological station is characterised
by moderate to strong westerly winds. Rainfall there is relatively high, 1026 mm
per annum, when compared to Squires Gate, Blackpool, (852 mm per annum) and
generally occurs on between eleven and nineteen days in each month at both
sites. Annual average maximum and minimum daily temperatures are 12 C and 6 C
respectively at both sites. The high rainfall will tend to reduce dust
emissions, but once released, dust dispersion will depend upon atmospheric
stability and the windspeed and direction.
</P>
<P>Wind speed and direction</P>
<P>4.9 Hourly sequential meteorological data measured at Squires Gate,
Blackpool were obtained as electronic files. The Meteorological Office advised
that data for the period 1987 to 1990 are representative of conditions at the
Surface Site. These data were used to generate a joint frequency analysis of
wind speed and direction, which is shown as a wind rose in the Environmental
Statement [COR/101](4) and in tabular form in <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table4.2">Table
4.2</A>. The four cardinal points are represented by 30 sectors and the twelve
intermediate directions by 20 sectors. If winds were evenly distributed there
would be a frequency of 8.33% from the cardinal points and 5.56% for other
sectors. Above average wind frequencies are recorded in the south-west to
north-west sector and from the east, whereas winds from the north-north-west to
east-north- east sector are of less than average frequency.
</P>
<P>Atmospheric Stability</P>
<P>4.10 Atmospheric stability and wind speed frequencies are shown in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A>.Very unstable conditions with
rapid convection do not occur in this part of the country, and the stable E and
F conditions associ- ated with night time or early morning inversions are
typical at a total frequency of 16%. Neutral conditions are very common (75%),
and wind speeds tend to be relatively high.
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="ASSESS2">5. ASSESSMENT OF ACTIVITIES</A>
</B></P>
<P>5.1 The activities associated with the proposed development have been
assessed for the purpose of identifying all potential emissions. Many activities
were discounted as having zero emissions, or involving releases of such small
amounts that there would be little effect at any distance from the source. All
activities will involve standard construction procedures. Mitigation measures
for such operations are well established and are inherent in the development
design. 
</P>
<P>5.2 Gaseous emissions will be caused by engine exhaust from vehicles and
plant operating on the Surface Site and vehicles travelling to and from the
Surface Site on the A595(T). During the initial four years of the project RCF
generated traffic will in general be below 250 vehicles per day in each
direction. These flows will be less than 200 per day during the following four
years and below 150 per day subsequently. In the context of the 1994 daily flow
of 4200 vehicles on the A595(T), the numbers of generated vehicle movements will
not be sufficient for their emissions to have any appreciable effect on ambient
air quality near this road or in the vicinity of the Appeal Site.
</P>
<P>5.3 It is possible that underground gases such as methane, carbon dioxide
and radon may be released by the excavations. Although these releases are not
quantified, they are expected to be minor. Any traces of gases which are
released will be rapidly dispersed at the surface by the shaft ventilation
system, and will have no discernible effect on air quality.
</P>
<P>5.4 Dust emissions from earthmoving operations such as opencast mining and
mineral working have been the subject of many studies and emission factors for
specific operations have been compiled. These factors can be applied to various
operations such as bulldozing, haulage on unmade roads, wind erosion and the
loading and unloading of bulk material. This has allowed a quantitative
assessment of dust emissions from specific stages of the development programme.

</P>
<P>5.5 The activities in the programme have been assessed to determine those in
which emissions of dust are likely to be highest. Most operations produce
quantities of dust which are directly proportional to the amount of bulk
material moved. Three activities in the programme have been identified which
will involve the highest rates of material movement and therefore the greatest
potential to release dust. These are:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Soil stripping;
</LI>
<LI>Platform Site earthworks; and
</LI>
<LI>Restoration. 
</LI></UL>
<P>5.6 A fourth activity, shaft sinking, produces a low rate of
materialmovement, but this has also been addressed for the period of work when
spoildisposal is closest to Newton Manor.
</P>
<P>Soil stripping
</P>
<P>5.7 Soil stripping will involve excavating approximately 16,000 m(3) of
topsoil and hauling it to storage mounds to the east of the Platform Site. This
activity is planned to take place over about two weeks.
</P>
<P>Platform Site earthworks
</P>
<P>5.8 The Platform Site earthworks will involve excavating approximately
86,000 m(3) of rock and subsoil from the northern part of the Platform Site and
filling the valley in the southern part of the Platform Site. This activity is
planned to take place over 102 days.
</P>
<P>Shaft sinking
</P>
<P>5.9 Shaft sinking and underground construction will produce spoil which will
be deposited, over a six and a half year period, in the Spoil Disposal Area.
This will be progressively developed. At any stage during the construction
process in addition to the area on which the spoil is being disposed there will
also be a further area which will have been recently covered with topsoil, and
another area from which topsoil and subsoil will be taken to cover the spoil
being disposed of. There will therefore be a possibility of up to three areas
being subject to wind erosion. 
</P>
<P>Restoration
</P>
<P>5.10 Site restoration will involve the redistribution of 60,000 m(3) of
material, primarily the sandstone fill used to create the Platform Site. This
will be recontoured in a manner reflecting the original valley form. 16,000 m(3)
of topsoil from the storage mounds, created during site stripping, will be used
to restore the Surface Site to agricultural use if planning permission is not
granted for further development. These restoration operations are likely to take
place in phases over a period of nineteen months.
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="ASSESSMENT">6. ASSESSMENT OF EFFECTS</A>
</B></P>
<P><B>Method of Assessment</B>
</P>
<P>Emission rates
</P>
<P>6.1 The United States Environmental Protection Agency (`US EPA') publishes
emission factors for estimating the dust produced for given levels of specific
types of operation. The Agency's publications on pollution are widely accepted
as an authoritative reference for emission factors and were used to estimate
dust emission rates from each of the four activities described above.
</P>
<P>6.2 The information used in calculating the emission rates for each of the
various operations comprising each activity is shown in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>.
</P>
<P>6.3 The emission factors for each of the operations are listed in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.2">Table 6.2</A>.The emission rates developed from
this information for each of the four activities modelled are then given in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A>.
</P>
<P>6.4 <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A> shows that the total
emission rate estimated for soil stripping is 1.4 g/s, followed by an increased
emission rate during the Platform Site earthworks of 2.7 g/s. This will be the
most intense period of activity of those considered. Spoil disposal results in a
much lower emission rate of  0.25 g/s. Emissions will approach 1.5 g/s during
site restoration. 
</P>
<P>Dispersion Modelling
</P>
<P>6.5 The US EPA Fugitive Dust Model (`FDM') was used to calculate the
dispersion of dust from the above activities. This model is the most highly
developed for this type of situation and extensive validation tests have been
carried out.
</P>
<P>6.6 The sources described above were assigned to particular locations shown
in <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figures 6.1</A> to 6.4. Sources are
designated schematically in the model as either rectangular area sources or line
sources. A grid of 651 receptors was specified at 75 metre intervals over the
Appeal Site and adjacent land. The model calculates the cumulative deposition at
each of the receptors, for each wind speed, wind direction and stability
combination in the joint frequency distribution of meteorological data for 1987
to 1990.
</P>
<P>6.7 The FDM model has a certain limitation in that it does not address local
topography; it treats sources and receptors as being on flat ground. In fact,
much of the material movements will be at a lower elevation than the surrounding
area, which will impede dust dispersion. The woodland belts will also remove
dust from the air to some extent. The effect of the FDM model in taking terrain
to be flat is therefore to overestimate the likely actual deposition rates.</P>
<P><B>Description of Effects</B>
</P>
<P>Soil Stripping
</P>
<P>6.8 <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> shows the model results
in terms of monthly average dust deposition rate around the Surface Site caused
by soil stripping as a contour plot. The east to west bias in the frequency of
wind directions is evident in the elongated shape of the deposition rate
contours. The highest deposition rate beyond the Surface Site boundary will
occur on fields to the north-east and will be greater than 50 mg/m(2)/day for up
to 80 metres from the boundary. A rapid reduction in dust deposition rate with
increasing distance from the Surface Site will occur. The deposition rate at
Newton Manor and the Boonwood Garden Centre will be about 7 mg/m(2)/day, less
than 4% of the 200 mg/m(2)/day nuisance threshold.
</P>
<P>Platform Site Earthworks
</P>
<P>6.9 <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A> shows the modelled
monthly average dust deposition rate for the Platform Site earthworks as a
contour plot. During this phase, more dust will be released from the Surface
Site than during soil stripping as quantified in <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.3">Table
6.3</A>. The highest deposition rates will occur to the north-west of the
Platform Site, and may exceed 100 mg/m(2)/day for up to 40 metres beyond the
Surface Site boundary. A level of 50 mg/m(2)/day will be exceeded over a small
area of fields immediately to the south-east of Longlands Farm. The deposition
rate at Newton Manor and the Boonwood Garden Centre will be some 16 mg/m(2)/day
during this three month operation, an increment to existing ambient levels of 8%
of the nuisance threshold. 
</P>
<P>Shaft Sinking
</P>
<P>6.10 <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A> shows the modelled
monthly average dust deposition rates during the stage of shaft sinking when
spoil disposal is closest to Newton Manor as a contour plot. This will be
broadly representative of other stages of the construction programme. As a
consequence of the low number of movements to the Spoil Disposal Area low
deposition rates are predicted. Newton Manor will be virtually unaffected, as
below 3 mg/m(2)/day is expected at this location. Properties to the north and
east of the Surface Site will not be affected by dust from this activity.
</P>
<P>Restoration
</P>
<P>6.11 <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.4">Figure 6.4</A> shows the modelled
monthly average dust deposition rate for site restoration as a contour plot. The
emission rate during this phase is less than during the Platform Site earthworks
and the contours show a comparable distribution of dust, at proportionally lower
levels. The deposition rate at the nearest properties, Newton Manor and Boonwood
Garden Centre will be about 12 mg/m(2)/day, which is approximately 6% of the
nuisance threshold.</P>
<P><B><A NAME="EVALUATION">7. EVALUATION OF EFFECTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>7.1 The increment in monthly average rates of dust deposition at the
residential properties closest to the Surface Site which may result from the
development is not likely to exceed 16 mg/m(2)/day. This may occur for three
months during Platform Site earthworks. This increment is less than 10% of the
nuisance threshold.
</P>
<P>7.2 Dust deposition measurements have been carried out at a number of
locations. The results have shown that there is a wide natural variation in
monthly average deposition rates due to meteorological and other factors which
may be as much as 100 mg/m(2)/day. The dust generated by the development will be
from natural soil and rock, and will be similar in nature to dust currently
arising from local agricultural activities. During much of the programme while
shaft sinking is in progress there will be virtually no effect even on the
closest properties. At other stages of the development the small predicted
increments to dust deposition rates at residential properties will be
indistinguishable from the large natural variations in monthly dust fall.</P>
<P>7.3 The development will have no appreciable effect on air quality in terms
of human health or amenity. There are no emissions that have the potential to
affect vegetation or archaeological features.
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="MEASURES">8. MEASURES TO MINIMISE ADVERSE EFFECTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>8.1 The estimates of the dust emissions resulting from various phases of the
site preparation, construction and restoration of the development are summarised
in <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A>. The estimates are based on
published factors for uncontrolled emissions. No allowance was made for dust
suppression procedures. The assessment for the uncontrolled case indicates that
dust generating activity will be so low that mitigation measures will not be
required to deal with off-site effects. However, dust control measures will in
any event be established including a range of specific measures to minimise
dust, such as procedures for use of the vehicle wheel wash and recommendations
regarding covering of potentially dusty loads.
</P>
<P>8.2 Dust from the batching plant will be controlled by inbuilt containment
and good working methods to ensure operator health and safety close to the
plant. As a result, residual dust at the Surface Site boundary will be at a very
low level.</P>
<P><B><A NAME="CONCLUSIONS">9. CONCLUSIONS</A></B>
</P>
<P>9.1 Even without any allowance for dust control measures on the Surface
Site, the increase in monthly average deposition rates caused by the most
intense site activity will be less than 10% of the nuisance threshold of 200
mg/m(2)/day at the closest dwelling. This small increment to existing ambient
deposition rates will not be significant. The current month to month variation
in deposition rate at a particular location may be as much as 100 mg/m(2)/day.
Deposited dust originating from the Surface Site will be natural material
similar to the dust emitted from certain agricultural activities. Any increased
dust deposition at residential property will be indistinguishable</P>
<P>from existing variations due to meteorological and other factors. 
</P>
<P>9.2 Best practice techniques and good site management procedures will be
used for operations that may generate dust. These will be the only operations
associated with the development which have the potential to affect air quality
materially. However, the assessment shows that there is not likely to be any
significant effect on air quality. Regular monitoring for dust deposition will
be carried out to confirm this assessment.</P>
<P><B><A NAME="REFERENCES">10. REFERENCES</A></B>
</P>
<P>1. GOV/124<BR>World Health Organisation, Air Quality Guidelines for Europe.
WHO regional publications, European Series No. 23. Copenhagen 1987, p310, p357.</P>
<P>2. GOV/125<BR>Council of the European Communities, Council Directive on air
quality standards for nitrogen dioxide 85/203/EEC, Official Journal of the
European Communities No L87/1 -L87/7. 27 March 1985.
</P>
<P>3. NRX/6/1<BR>Nitrogen Dioxide, London Environmental Supplement No. 14.
Winter 1985/6. The Greater London Council, p6.
</P>
<P>4. COR/101<BR>Environmental Statement, figure 3.8.5</P>
