<HEAD>
<TITLE>PE/NRX/6/S1 - AIR QUALITY</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF"><IMG SRC="../../images/nirsmlog.gif" ALT="Nirex Logo">
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><B><FONT SIZE="5">PE/NRX/6/S1</FONT></B><BR></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="2">Appellant Ref: DB/CD 8.5.1</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">LPA
Ref: 4/94/9011</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="2">DOE Ref: APP/HO900/A/94/247019</FONT><BR><BR></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">UNITED KINGDOM NIREX LIMITED</FONT><BR></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Rock Characterisation Facility</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="4">Longlands Farm, Gosforth, Cumbria</FONT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">SUPPLEMENTARY</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">PROOF OF EVIDENCE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">OF</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">Mr R H WOODBRIDGE</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="4">MSc, LRSC</FONT><BR><BR></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="5">AIR QUALITY</FONT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P></P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD><A HREF="../nrx6ix.htm">Back to NRX6 Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../poe.htm">Back to POE Menu</A></TD>
<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>1.1 Introduction
</B>
</P>
<P>A number of issues have been raised regarding the method of calculating the
likely effects of dust on air quality.
</P>
<P><B>2 Cumbria County Council
</B>
</P>
<P>2.1 Cumbria County Council raise a concern relating to episodic dust
generation.
</P>
<P>2.2 The purpose of assessment is to predict whether nuisance is likely to
occur. As recognised by the County Council the generally accepted threshold is
200 mg/r<SUP>2</SUP>/day, above which complaints may begin to arise regarding a
build up of dust on surfaces such as window sills. This criterion results from
empirical findings around dust sources where <U>monthly</U> deposition
measurements have been carried out using deposition gauges. This is appropriate
as accumulation on surfaces that may become noticeable is a long term process
and short term fluctuation is inherent in the monthly mean criterion. A &quot;nuisance&quot;
implies a frequent event impairing amenity, or a continuing observable emission
over a sustained period of time. There are no appropriate criteria by which to
judge deposition rates over periods of much less than one month.
</P>
<P>2.3 The rate of activity during each of the stages of development assessed
will be relatively constant throughout that operation. These activities have
been taken into account in the assessment, and variations in dust emissions will
not arise as a result of site activity.
</P>
<P>2.4 Episodic variations in dust emission rates over short time scales will
occur due to meteorological factors within the monthly periods which have been
assessed. Dust deposition rates may vary on individual days, but provided the
monthly mean deposition rate is low, complaints are not expected to arise. This
is because nuisance due to soiling is a cumulative process, and the mass
deposited over short time periods will be low, compared to the long term dust
loading, even at times of peak short term deposition rate.
</P>
<P><B>3. Gosforth Parish Council
</B>
</P>
<P>3.1 Gosforth Parish Council raise two concerns, firstly that the regular use
of unsurfaced roads will cause dust emissions, and that tipping of spoil should
be limited to those times when the wind speed is low.
</P>
<P>23.2 All roads in regular use will be concreted. A crushed stone road
surface will be used to serve the Spoil Disposal Area and this has been taken
into account in the assessment. As is clear from the assessment tile use of such
a surface in this area will not give rise to unacceptable levels of deposition
rate.
</P>
<P>3.3 Spoil tipping of on average approximately 10 loads of material per day
results in very low levels of dust, as is evident in
<A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A>. <A HREF="nrx6fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure
6.3</A> shows that dust deposition from the tipping of spoil will be extremely
low. Higher wind speeds will not lead to any increase in the dust deposition
rate.
</P>
<P></P>
