<TD><FONT COLOR="FFFFFF">.</FONT></TD>
<TD><A HREF="../../index.htm">Back to Homepage</A></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>JEREMY NEIL SHORT </B>will say:
</P>
<P><B>1. <A NAME="PERSONAL">PERSONAL DETAILS</A>
</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am a Chartered Engineer, a Member of the Institution of Agricultural
Engineers, a Member of the Institute of Professional Soil Scientists and an
Associate Member of the Institute of Quarrying. I am employed by Wardell
Armstrong as a Senior Environmental Scientist with specific responsibility for
issues relating to soils and landuse.
</P>
<P>1.2 I have over 12 years experience in soil assessment and land restoration
including mineral site development, the reclamation of derelict and contaminated
land and revegetation following land disturbance from road schemes and
industrial/commercial development.  
</P>
<P><B>2. <A NAME="SUMMARY">SUMMARY</A>
</B></P>
<P><B>Scope of Evidence</B></P>
<P>2.1 This proof of evidence considers the effects of the RCF development on
the soil resources and agricultural potential of that land within the Appeal
Site that will be directly affected by the site operations. The effects will be
considered in relation to the nature and quality of the existing soils, the type
of land disturbance and the proposed scheme of restoration. 
</P>
<P><B>Land use and Quality</B></P>
<P>2.2 The land affected by this proposed development is
predominantlyagricultural. It is centred around Longlands Farm, although this
farm is not at present an operational unit. The farm buildings are redundant and
the land is let on short term licences. The land is presently used for livestock
and arable production with a larger proportion put down to grass leys associated
with the livestock.
</P>
<P>2.3 Soils are generally loamy or fine loamy over weathered sandstone, or
sandy soils overlying a gravel horizon. These become clayey within the lower
sections of the Services Corridors.
</P>
<P>2.4 The Agricultural Land Classification of the Surface Site is
predominantly grade 3b, the main limitation being climatic. Land on the valley
sides in the centre of the site has a gradient limitation and is further down
graded to grades 4 and 5. The climatic limitation on the Services Corridors is
not so severe; however this area is still predominantly grade 3b or lower, due
to land gradient and poor drainage. One small area of grade 3a is present. 
</P>
<P>2.5 Government policy on agricultural issues is set out in PPG7 &quot;The
Countryside and the Rural Economy&quot;. Under this guidance, protection is
generally only given to agricultural land grades 1, 2 and 3a. None of the land
within the Surface Site, and only a small proportion of that in the Services
Corridors, is afforded protection under this policy. 
</P>
<P><B>Potential Impacts</B>
</P>
<P>2.6 The stripping and long term storage of soils from the Platform Site area
will inevitably lead to a reduction in soil quality. However storage and
handling will be designed to minimise this effect. On restoration, replaced
profiles will be similar to the existing profiles, and the aftercare schemewill
help soil quality to recover.
</P>
<P>2.7 On the Spoil Disposal Area, a majority of the soils will be lifted and
directly placed to restore the tip, without the need for storage. This should
result in very little damage to soil quality, leading to a rapidre-establishment
of existing land quality.
</P>
<P>2.8 Although there will be some detriment to soil quality resulting from
this development, the main limitation to agricultural production on the Surface
Site is climatic and not soils related. The overall long term impacts on
agricultural potential will therefore be small.
</P>
<P>2.9 On the Services Corridors, the duration of the operation is short at
some 6 months. Soils will be lifted and placed in store beside the trench and
replaced, following installation of the services. The practices for carrying out
such works are well understood and should not lead to any significant long term
impacts. 
</P>
<P><B>Conclusion</B></P>
<P>2.10 The agricultural land classification of the Surface Site is
predominantly grade 3b, the main limitation being climatic. On the Services
Corridors grades are similar, with the exception of a small area of grade 3a.
</P>
<P>2.11 Soil handling and storage techniques will be specified to minimise the
impact on soil quality. However, some reduction in soil quality is inevitable
but the impact of this on agricultural potential will be small, due to the
overriding climatic limitation. 
</P>
<P>2.12 Within the Services Corridors soil stripping and replacement will take
place over a relatively short period of time. It is not anticipated that this
operation will cause a significant impact on the agricultural potential of this
area.  
</P>
<P><B>3. <A NAME="SCOPE">SCOPE</A>
</B></P>
<P>3.1 This Proof of Evidence considers the effects of the RCF development on
the soil resources and the agricultural potential of that land within the Appeal
Site which will be disturbed as part of this development. These effects will be
considered in relation to the nature and quality of the existing soils, the type
of land disturbance involved, and the proposed scheme of restoration. The impact
of the development on agricultural land use is considered by Mr Balch in his
proof of evidence (<A HREF="../nrx11/nrx11.htm"><B>PE/NRX/11</B></A>).</P>
<P>3.2 It also considers the comments received from consultees and responds to
these with reference to the above information. 
</P>
<P>3.3 For the purposes of assessing the impacts on soils and land quality, two
areas of the Appeal Site are considered. These areas are the Surface Site
(38ha), which includes the Platform Site and the Spoil Disposal Area, and the
Services Corridors (34ha). These areas are considered separately, as the
limitations to agricultural production and the nature of the impacts from the
proposed development are significantly different in each. The remaining areas of
the Appeal Site are unaffected by direct surface disturbance. </P>
<P><B>4. <A NAME="EXISTING_LAND_USE_AND">EXISTING LAND USE AND QUALITY </A>
</B></P>
<P><B>Surface Site</B></P>
<P>Land use</P>
<P>4.1 Detailed assessments of the current land uses and holdings affected by 
the RCF development are given in Mr Balch's evidence [<A
HREF="../nrx11/nrx11.htm"><B>PE/NRX/11</B></A>]. This evidence identifies
Longlands Farm as the holding most significantly affected. However this land is
currently let on short term licences and therefore cannot be considered as an
individual farm holding. This land is farmed at present as a mixed livestock and
arable unit with the larger proportion of the farm down to grass leys associated
with the livestock farming [see COR/101](1). The arable areas are mainly
cereals, but include a small area of root crops.
</P>
<P>Soil types</P>
<P>4.2 The soils found at Longlands Farm are broadly divided into two main
groups. In the north-eastern part of the site there are sandy loams and sandy
clay loams overlying the weathered sandstone surface. The depth to this rock
varies from 500mm to over 1000mm. In the south- western part of the site the
textures are coarser with sandy loams, loamy sands and sands, often overlying a
gravel horizon.</P>
<P>Agricultural Land Classification</P>
<P>4.3 The soils at Longlands Farm have been surveyed and the quality of the
land assessed in accordance with the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food
(MAFF) Revised Guidelines for Agricultural Land Classification (ALC) 1988
[GOV/121](2). This system is based on an assessment of the main physical factors
that affect agricultural production, namely; the prevailing climate, land
gradients, soil profiles and interaction between these factors. The results of
this survey are presented in Nirex Report 378 [NRX/7/1](3) and illustrated in
the Environmental Statement Figure 3.6.1 [COR 101](1).</P>
<P>4.4 The over-riding limitation at Longlands Farm is climatic, the site
receiving a moderately high rainfall combined with low accumulated temperatures.
These factors limit the agricultural potential of the site, irrespective of all
other factors, resulting in a land classification of grade 3b. This is described
in the MAFF Guidelines as land of only moderate quality. A steep sided valley
exists in the central portion of the Longlands Farm site with gradients in
excess of 1 in 5. These gradients result in a further limitation to the
potential agricultural use of the land, resulting in a downgrading of this area
to ALC grades 4 and 5. This is land of poor quality with very limited
agricultural uses.</P>
<P><B>Services Corridors</B>
</P>
<P>4.5 A preliminary soil survey and agricultural land classification has also
been carried out on the land forming the Services Corridors. Details of this
survey are presented in Nirex Report 672 [NRX/7/2](4).  
</P>
<P>4.6 These corridors are mostly at a lower altitude than the Surface Site and
do not suffer the same climatic limitation. However the land grade is still
predominantly 3b or worse, the limitation resulting from a variety of factors.
These are: steep gradients on the fields sloping up to Longlands Farm, drainage
restrictions resulting in high groundwater in the valley and poor drainage due
to slowly permeable subsoils on some fields adjoining the brook. One small area,
totalling less than 1ha, of grade 3a land was identified, associated with the
more freely draining soils on raised ground. </P>
<P>4.7 The land use of these corridors is predominantly grassland for stock
rearing. One small area of arable land is crossed at the end of the northern
corridor.
</P>
<P><B>Policy Consideration</B></P>
<P>4.8 Government policy on agricultural issues is set out in PPG 7 &quot;The
Countryside and the Rural Economy&quot; [GOV/102](5). The protection of
agricultural land is discussed in paragraph 2.5 and 2.6. Paragraph 2.6
identifies land of grades 1, 2 and 3a as the &quot;best and most versatile&quot;
and notes that considerable weight should be given to the protection of such
land against development, because of its special importance. The only exception
to this is noted in paragraph 2.5, which states
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;...little weight need normally be given to the loss of such land,
except in areas such as hills and uplands where particular agricultural
practices themselves contribute to the quality of the environment, or to the
rural economy in some special way&quot;.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>This exception does not apply to any part of the Appeal Site. 
</P>
<P>4.9 None of the land at Longlands Farm comes within the category of best and
most versatile and therefore is not afforded protection under government
guidance. Within the Services Corridors, one small area of grade 3a land was
identified. However, over 98% of the land in these corridors is not classified
as best and most versatile.</P>
<P><B>5. <A NAME="DEVELOPMENT">DEVELOPMENT PROPOSALS</A>
</B></P>
<P>5.1 The development of the RCF will affect three discrete areas of land, the
Platform Site (including soil storage areas and access roads), the Spoil
Disposal Area and the Services Corridors. 
</P>
<P><B>Platform Site</B></P>
<P>5.2 The Platform Site is located partly within the steep sided valley and
partly on the more gently sloping land to the south-west of the Longlands Farm
buildings. As the platform will be in place for the duration of the development,
all soils from this area will be lifted and placed in store. A large proportion
of these soils have already been moved and placed in store as part of the works
for the present RCF borehole site platforms. Topsoils and subsoils from the
additional areas required as part of the RCF development, will be lifted and
stored separately and will be available for use in the restoration of this area.
</P>
<P>5.3 Most of the soil stores will be grass seeded during the operational
phase of the RCF. A small proportion (under 15%) will have trees planted where
this is regarded as necessary for screening purposes. All stores will be shaped
to ensure that no excess water accumulates on the surface and all vegetation
will be managed. 
</P>
<P>5.4 Following closure of the RCF, the Platform Site will be regraded to
recreate both the steep sided valley feature and the more gently sloping land
leading up to the Longlands Farm buildings. Soils will then be placed on top of
this regraded surface. Details of the restoration proposals are illustrated in
Sue Wilson's evidence,  <A HREF="../nrx2/nrx2fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A>,
<B>PE/NRX/2</B>. On the steep valley sides the replaced soil profiles will
consist of a 300mm topsoil layer placed directly on to the loosened fill. On the
more gently sloping areas, subsoils will be placed to a depth of 450mm on top of
the loosened fill surface and covered with 300mm of topsoils. Details of the
volumes and soil profiles are given in the Restoration and Soil Use proposals
[COR/117](6) 
</P>
<P><B>Spoil Disposal Area</B></P>
<P>5.5 The Spoil Disposal Area will be filled and restored progressively as the
development proceeds. Here the topsoils and subsoils from the first area of
tipping, and topsoils from the second area of tipping, will be lifted and placed
in stores to the south-west of the tip area. Tipping will then commence in the
first area and once complete and graded to approved contours, subsoils will be
lifted from the second area, together with topsoils from the third area, and
placed directly on the fill surface to complete the restoration. This process
will then continue across the site, until the final area is filled. This latter
area will be restored using the soils placed in store from areas one and two.
All profiles will consist of 300mm of topsoil over 1000mm of subsoil. In total,
approximately 80% of topsoils and 90% of subsoils moved on this Spoil Disposal
Area will be lifted and placed directly on the fill surface without the need for
storage.
</P>
<P><B>Services Corridors</B></P>
<P>5.6 Where buried services are to be installed within the Services Corridors,
sufficient land will be taken to allow the separate stripping and storage of
topsoils and subsoils, prior to excavation of the services trench. These soils
will be stored in low ridges running alongside the open trench. On completion of
the pipework or cable installation and backfilling of the trench, soils will be
replaced and any disturbance to existing drainage systems made good. The
installation of the services represents a temporary disturbance with a projected
construction period of about 6 months. 
</P>
<P><B>Aftercare</B></P>
<P>5.7 Once restored, all areas will be put down to grass leys and entered into
an aftercare programme. This will include annual inspections of the soils and,
based on the results of these inspections, appropriate remedial action will be
specified if required. This is common practice on the restoration of mineral
sites where the return of land to productive agriculture has been achieved on
many sites and the process of restoration is well understood. Aftercare works
will include the installation of an agricultural under-drainage scheme (where
appropriate), soil cultivation, application of fertilizers and possible
incorporation of organic matter.</P>
<P><B>6. <A NAME="IMPACTS">IMPACTS</A>
</B></P>
<P><B>The Platform Site</B></P>
<P>6.1 The long term storage of soils will cause a deterioration in quality in
terms of the soil structure, stability of soil aggregates and the viability of
the microbiological communities. However, this impact will be minimised by the
control exercised on soil storage and handling and by the works undertaken
during the aftercare period.
</P>
<P>6.2 In terms of the replaced soil profiles at the Platform Site, the depths
placed on the gently sloping land will be similar to the existing profiles in
this area where the weathered stone layers (or other stone horizons) are
generally encountered at between 750mm to 1000mm. The principal difference
between the existing and restored profiles will be the drainage status of the
lower subsoils. The existing weathered sandstones are permeable, providing good
deep drainage for the existing surface soils. The replaced fills are likely to
be less permeable. The proposed agricultural under-drainage scheme is designed
to recreate the existing soil drainage status and so avoid potential problems of
waterlogging of the replaced surface soils. 
</P>
<P>6.3 On the valley sides only a rough grazing pasture will be established, as
is the current use. The 300mm profile, over loosened fill, will be capable of
supporting this use. Drainage of these soils is not likely to be a problem and
the installation of under-drainage is considered unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>6.4 Taking account of the existing soils and land quality, and the measures
discussed above, it is considered that this development will not significantly
affect the long term agricultural potential of the Platform Site area.
</P>
<P><B>Spoil Disposal Area</B></P>
<P>6.5 During the construction of the Spoil Disposal Area, only some 20% of the
soils lifted and used for restoration will be placed in store. As discussed
above, the long term storage of soils is detrimental to soil quality but the
progressive restoration of this area will reduce this impact to a minimum. This
is achieved by the direct placement of the remaining 80% of the soils, using
careful soil handling techniques, which removes the need for storage of these
materials and will ensure a rapid re-establishment of the existing uses. The
depth of soils being placed over the spoil will ensure that no rock intrudes to
within the cultivation layer. The permeable nature of the place rock, which will
be broken and fragmented during excavation of the shafts etc, will also provide
adequate deep drainage, removing the need to install under-drainage.  
</P>
<P>6.6 The main impact on the Spoil Disposal Area will be the short term loss
of the existing land uses during tipping. However, the progressive filling and
restoration techniques will limit the land that is unavailable for use at any
one time to a maximum of 3ha. With the working and restoration proposed there
will be no significant medium or long term impacts on land use. 
</P>
<P><B>Services Corridors</B></P>
<P>6.7 Soils stripped as part of the construction of the Services Corridors
will be stored by loose tipping in low bunds running the length of the
corridors. The relatively small size of the bunds, the loose placing technique
and the short duration of this operation, should result in little long term
damage being done to the soils. On restoration, the aftercare programme will
ensure that the land taken within the Services Corridors is returned to its
normal use as soon as practical.
</P>
<P>6.8 As with the Spoil Disposal Area, the principal impact of this element of
the development will be the short term loss of the existing land uses. In the
medium and long term the restoration proposals will allow for full integration
of the corridor areas into the adjoining fields with no lasting impact.
</P>
<P><B>Land Quality</B></P>
<P>6.9 It is relevant, when considering the impacts on the soils and their
subsequent use for agricultural production, to take note of the over-riding
limitations to that use. As noted above, the agricultural land classification at
the Surface Site is limited to grade 3b, principally on the basis of the
prevailing climate and is not limited by existing soil types or depths. As such,
a slight reduction in soil quality is unlikely to affect the land classification
of the disturbed ground, post restoration. 
</P>
<P><B>7. <A NAME="CONSULTATIONS">CONSULTATIONS</A> 
</B></P>
<P><B>Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries and Food</B><BR></P>
<P>7.1 The Ministry's response to consultation is contained in their letter to
Cumbria County Council dated 27th October 1994. In summary the points raised
are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">a)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">They are unlikely to object on the grounds of protecting
agricultural land and confirm agriculture as a suitable afteruse.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">b)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">Restoration should be in accordance with para 3(1) of Schedule
5 of the Town and Country Planning Act (as amended) [NRX/7/3](7).
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">c)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">Concern was expressed regarding tree planting on top of soil
storage mounds.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">d)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">More detailed information was requested on the existing and
restoration soil profiles and land uses.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>7.2 My responses to these points, excluding a) where no comment is required,
are as follows.
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">b)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">The proposed restored soil profiles reflect the existing
conditions found on site and therefore the requirements of this paragraph are
met.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">c)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">In light of these comments, the landscape design for the Appeal
Site has been amended to remove some of the tree planting from the topsoil and
subsoil bunds and there has been some relocation of soil stores. Where planting
is retained it is considered essential as part of the landscape proposals. As a
result, tree planting is now present on under 15% of the total topsoil resource
for the Platform Site. However it is considered that tree planting on soil
storage mounds will have no adverse affect on soil quality and in fact may be
more beneficial, as a result of their potentially deeper rooting systems, than a
grass cover. Removal of the vegetation to reclaim the soils for restoration
purposes requires more work than with grass but can be carried out without undue
damage to the soil quality.</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">d)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">More detailed information has been presented to MAFF in the
Wardell Armstrong reports &quot;Restoration and Soil Use Proposals&quot;
[COR/117](6) and &quot;Longlands Farm/Service Corridors Soil Data&quot;
[NRX/7/4](8). In response to these, MAFF have commissioned a soil survey to
confirm the Appeal Site's physical characteristics and agricultural land
classification. It is intended that the results of these surveys will form part
of an agreed statement. In relation to the Restoration and Soil Use Proposals,
MAFF have no fundamental objection to the scheme and it is intended that these
issues will also form part of an agreed statement.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Copeland Borough Council</B></P>
<P>7.3 The issues raised in relation to this application are noted in their
report to Council (dated 1.11.94). No comments are made on issues relating to
soils and land quality.
</P>
<P><B>Gosforth Parish Council</B></P>
<P>7.4 In their response to the planning application (dated Nov 1994) two
points, additional to those already discussed above, are raised. These are:
</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="50">a)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">concern regarding weed seeds spreading to adjoining land;</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH="5">b)</TD>
<TD WIDTH="800">dust blow from soil stockpiles etc. affecting surrounding
areas;</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>7.5 In response to a) the Landscape Planting and Management Plan
[COR/704](9) for the site specifies the weed control and general vegetation
management required. The operation of this plan will control any noxious weed
growth. In relation to b), all soil stockpiles will have a vegetation cover so
removing the potential for dust blow from their surface.</P>
<P><B>8. <A NAME="CONCLUSIONS">CONCLUSIONS</A>
</B></P>
<P>8.1 The Agricultural Land Classification of the Appeal Site is principally
grade 3b with smaller areas of grades 4 and 5. This is moderate to poor quality
land. The Services Corridors are of a similar grade, although one small area of
grade 3a was identified. On the basis of this land quality, MAFF have not
objected to the proposed development.
</P>
<P>8.2 Surface soils will be lifted and separately stored prior to the
development and used for restoration of the site, to recreate conditions similar
to those of the existing site. An aftercare scheme will be developed with the
aim of correcting any damage caused during the long term storage of some of the
soils.
</P>
<P>8.3 On the Spoil Disposal Area some 80% of the soils will be lifted and
direct placed to restore the surface, with no requirement for storage. This will
allow the rapid re-establishment of the existing land uses and minimise the
damage caused to the soils. 
</P>
<P>8.4 The disturbance to soils and landuse along the Services Corridors will
be of short duration. Soil handling and site restoration should ensure no long
term effects on this area.
</P>
<P>8.5 The major limitation to agricultural use on much of the Appeal Site is
climatic. As such, a slight reduction in soil quality should not affect the
agricultural land grade of the site post restoration. 
</P>
