<P><B>IAN RALSTON will say:
</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P><B>Position</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am the Director of the Centre for Field Archaeology, and a Senior
Lecturer in the Department of Archaeology at the University of Edinburgh.</P>
<P><B>Qualifications and Affiliations</B>
</P>
<P>1.2  I have an Honours degree and a PhD in Archaeology, and I am a Fellow of
the Society of Antiquaries of London and of Scotland (FSA(Scot)). I am also a
Member of the Institute of Field Archaeologists.</P>
<P><B>Principal Experience</B></P>
<P>1.3  I have wide experience in British and North-Western European field
archaeology, and have been actively involved in the development of
archaeological studies for environmental statements.  I was appointed Research
Fellow in Archaeology at Aberdeen University in 1974, and since that time have
been in continuous employment as a professional archaeologist. I have held my
current position, Senior Lecturer in Archaeology at Edinburgh University, since
1990.</P>
<P STYLE="superscript">1.4  I directed the archaeological studies for Shell
Chemicals UK Ltd North West Ethylene Pipeline Project, the first major
Environmental Assessment project conducted in Scotland in which archaeological
considerations were prominent.  Since that time, I have been appointed by the
University Court as Director of the Centre for Field Archaeology within the
University of Edinburgh, which has the remit of conducting applied
archaeological research on behalf of private sector developers and local and
central government agencies. I have thus directed all Centre for Field
Archaeology work on behalf of United Kingdom Nirex Limited ('Nirex') in the
Sellafield area and have participated in the fieldwork and was a co-author of
the Cultural Heritage chapter of the RCF Environmental Statement [COR/101]<SUP>1</SUP>.</P>
<P>1.5  I am a former Chairman of the Institute of Field Archaeologists ('I F
A'), and am presently Vice-President of the Council for Scottish Archaeology,
although I do not speak in either of these capacities on the present issue. As
well as having written or co-authored a range of academic articles and books, I
have recently contributed to and edited texts on both Archaeological Resource
Management in the UK (I F A / Alan Sutton, 1993) and the Institute of Field
Archaeologists' Occasional Paper on Environmental Assessment and Archaeology.  I
am the author or co-author of over 125 published papers and reports.
</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2.  SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>2.1  The known and reputed cultural resources within the RCF Appeal Site and
its vicinity have been collated and assessed by desk-based work and
ground-perspective fieldwork, including limited amounts of archaeological
excavation. These remains comprise of a range of generally small-scale, and 
primarily post-medieval, features, the majority of which are of minor or very
minor archaeological significance..  In all, 18 features have been recorded.
These are mapped in <A HREF="#Figure3.1">Figure 3.1</A> and listed in paragraph
3.8 of my evidence.  A number of these features have been excavated and
recorded, and these are dealt with in the following paragraph (2.2).  It is
proposed that one further known feature (no.15) will be excavated and recorded
prior to development; such an approach complies with the guidance in PPG 16
[GOV/106]<SUP>2</SUP>.</P>
<P>2.2  Since the initial archaeological survey, there have been some changes
in the known surviving archaeological resources within the Appeal Site. These
affect minor features within the Platform Site; and the supposed sites of stone
circles and other features at Gretigate. A programme of fieldwork has been
carried out with the knowledge of the local authority  to examine archaeological
sites prior to the sinking of the RCF/RCM Boreholes within the Platform Site:
this both examined three sites threatened with destruction (nos 3, 5 and 6 in
the list in paragraph 3.8) in order to ensure preservation by record and tested
some of the other features in the vicinity, to clarify their nature and
significance. Work commissioned by Nirex and with the involvement of the local
authority archaeological service at the sites of the Gretigate stone circles was
designed to discover whether any significant features or deposits survived at
their reported location: the results were negative.</P>
<P>2.3  These cultural resources were ideprogramme for the RCF.  This means
that all but one known or reputed ntified well in advance and thus the positions
of these archaeological features were  incorporated in the design archaeological
feature currently extant will remain in-situ at the end of the Nirex RCF
project.  There are no cultural resources protected by statutory designations
within the Appeal Site.</P>
<P>2.4  Nirex has agreed that it will underwrite archaeological intervention to
examine and record the  feature that  will be threatened with destruction by the
Company's proposed programme of work within the Appeal Site. Moreover, it is
acknowledged that further archaeological resources may only be revealed during
the preliminary stages of the development programme: the RCF Environmental
Statement thus identifies mitigative measures to deal adequately in terms of
current archaeological guidance (Planning Policy Guidance Note 16: Archaeology
and Planning, 1990 [GOV/106]<SUP>2</SUP>) and standards (as being established
by I F A) with any additional cultural resources that may subsequently be
revealed within the RCF Appeal Site as a result of the proposed development.</P>
<P>2.5  It is concluded that the value of the known cultural resources within
the Appeal Site  is not high and that the proposed courses of action would be
able to fulfil all obligations under current government guidance and standard
archaeological practice. Further, these proposed actions are not in conflict
with any policies within Cumbria and Lake District Joint Structure Plan
[COR/303]<SUP>3</SUP> and other Local Plans, including those in draft.</P>
<P>2.6  None of the statutory consultees or representations received up to 11
of July 1995 has raised cultural resources as a reason for their objection to
the proposed development.</P>
<P><A NAME="BackgroundAndScope"></A><B>3.  BACKGROUND AND SCOPE</B></P>
<P><B>Introduction</B></P>
<P>3.1  This statement summarises Chapter 11 of the RCF Environmental Statement
[COR/101]<SUP>1</SUP>, which deals with Cultural Heritage, and updates that
chapter in the light of further archaeological work, conducted in close liaison
with the archaeological service of Cumbria County Council, within the Appeal
Site.  It thus outlines what is now known about cultural resources within the
Appeal Site proposed for development by United Kingdom Nirex Limited ('Nirex'),
provides an outline assessment of these resources in wider context, and
addresses the issue of, and potential for, appropriate reactions should further
archaeological discoveries be made during the RCF development within the Appeal
Site.</P>
<P>3.2  The following comments draw on the series of Reports produced by the
Centre for Field Archaeology, University of Edinburgh ('C F A'), and which
contain the results of all archaeological work conducted at Sellafield which is
relevant to the Appeal Site [NRX/8/1- 8]<SUP>4,5,6,7,8,9,10,11</SUP>.</P>
<P><B>Absence Of Designated Cultural Resources Within The Appeal Site</B></P>
<P>3.3  There are no sites affected by any of the designations currently taken
to indicate cultural importance at national or international level (e.g. World
Heritage Sites, Scheduled Ancient Monuments, Listed Buildings, Conservation
Areas, Historic Parks) within the Appeal Site which would come directly within
the aegis of English Heritage.</P>
<P>3.4  It thus follows that the principal curatorial responsibility for all
sites and monuments already known or that may subsequently be detected within
the development area rests with the appropriate local authority curatorial
archaeologist.  The archaeological service of Cumbria County Council has been
kept informed of all the desk-based and fieldwork stages identified hereafter;
and copies of all reports and associated illustrations have been forwarded to
that service.</P>
<P><B>Survival And Detection Of Archaeological Features</B></P>
<P>3.5  Recent agricultural land use in this lowland coastal zone means that
the visibility of archaeological features, with few exceptions such as certain
monuments incorporating substantial stones, is not good.  Improved pasture as a
dominant land-use certainly inhibits the effectiveness of ground-based
archaeological survey.  The application of this approach was preceded, as is
routine, by desk-based assessment of written sources, including the Cumbria
Sites and Monuments Record (including relevant aerial photographic cover) and
other literature.</P>
<P><B>Assessment And Evaluation Of Archaeological Features</B>
</P>
<P>3.6  The desk-based assessment was extended over a wider area of west
Cumbria to enable the evaluation of the remains encountered and listed in the
RCF Environmental Statement to be conducted against a local, sub-regional,
background.</P>
<P>3.7  Archaeological field inspection was conducted by C F A staff over the
entire area of the Appeal Site, including the Service Corridors. Fieldwork was
carried out at a variety of times, but always in generally favourable lighting
conditions.  As a result of these procedures, 18 sites of real or potential
archaeological interest have been identified within, or close to the boundaries
of, the Appeal Site (See <A HREF="#Figure3.1">Figure 3.1</A>), and information
on these is incorporated in the Cultural Heritage section (Chapter 11) of the
RCF Environmental Statement. These sites have been mapped and described, and
selected examples have been partially excavated to attempt to enhance
information on dating and function.</P>
<P>3.8  When the RCF Environmental Statement was prepared these sites were
described as follows [COR/101]<SUP>12</SUP>:</P>
<OL>
<LI>Ruinous dyke: This appears to have been a continuation of the northern
boundary of the adjacent wood, and survives only as discontinuous spreads of
stone and turf mounds.  These are considered to be of very minor archaeological
importance.</LI>
<LI>Quarry scoop: This is a small scoop in the hillside, probably resulting
from quarrying.  It is considered to be of negligible archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Causeway: This appears to be a drystone causeway across the meltwater
channel.  It is considered to be of very minor archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Artefact findspot: A barbed and tanged arrowhead was found in 1924. No
other artefacts have ever been reported from this location, and the site is
considered to be of negligible archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Rig and furrow cultivation: Vestigial remains of rig and furrow with a
width of about 2 metres ridge to ridge survive on the south facing slope to the
north of the valley.  These are considered to be of very minor archaeological
importance.</LI>
<LI>Terrace/field dyke: This is the remains of a boundary which ran round the
eastern base of the slope of the valley.  Different sections survive variously
as a 1.5 metre high terrace, segments of stone wall, and trees surrounded by
sections of Cumberland dyke. These remains are considered to be of minor
archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Buried dyke: This appeared on the surface as a stone cairn. Excavation
revealed the remains of a substantial stone dyke.  It is considered to be of
minor archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Cairn/pump site: This appeared on the surface as a stone cairn. Examination
of historical cartographic sources showed this location to be the site of a
water pump.  It is considered that these remains are of very minor
archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Dyke: This is the remains of a Cumberland dyke.  It is considered to be of
minor archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Stone lined drainage lade: The stream running through the valley has been
kerbed with stones to form a narrow channel.  This modification is considered to
be of negligible archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Dyke: This is the remains of a stone dyke made of large boulders. It is
considered to be of minor archaeological importance.
<P></P>Three sites represent the reported locations of the Gretigate stone
circles and associated cairns.  These are:
</LI>
<LI>Site of stone circle</LI>
<LI>Site of cairns</LI>
<LI>Site of stone circle<BR>No visible evidence of these sites remains.  If
any remains were present they would be of moderate archaeological significance.
Subsequent archaeological examination of these locations suggests that these
features were probably the result of stone clearance and are of negligible
archaeological importance (see para 4.5 below).
<P></P></LI>
<LI>Rig and furrow cultivation: Vestigial remains of rig and furrow with a
width of about 5 metres ridge to ridge survive on the brow of a ridge running
north-west to south-east.  These are considered to be of very minor
archaeological importance, but they may preserve earlier remains beneath them,
especially given their topographic location, which would have been favourable
for settlement.</LI>
<LI>Field banks: Immediately outwith the Surface Site are the remains of banks,
some of which appear to be former plantation boundaries, while others are
probably the remains of former land boundaries, pre- dating the field systems
introduced with enclosure.  They are considered to be of minor archaeological
importance.</LI>
<LI>Mill water management system: A complex of water channels and ponds that
are the incomplete remains of the water supply system for Seascale Mill survive
here.  They are considered to be of moderate archaeological importance.</LI>
<LI>Rig and furrow cultivation: These are the faint traces of rig and furrow
with a distance between crests of about 4 metres.  They are considered to be of
very minor archaeological importance.</LI></OL>
<P>3.9  A further walk-over survey of the potential expansion of the Spoil
Disposal Area was conducted in April 1995, with negative results (CFA Report 220
[NIR/8/8]<SUP>11</SUP>).</P>
<P><A NAME="Identified"></A><B>4.  IDENTIFIED SITES AND THEIR SIGNIFICANCE</B></P>
<P>4.1  None of the 18 identified archaeological sites is considered of greater
than moderate archaeological importance, most being isolated relict features of
agricultural cultivation and other practices of likely post-medieval date, which
are assessed as of minor or very minor importance.  This assessment is informed
by general knowledge of archaeological resources within the UK, and more
particularly by the desk-based assessment of the remains recorded in the wider
study area surrounding the Appeal Site [NIR/8/1]<SUP>4</SUP>.</P>
<P><B>In-Situ Survival And Mitigation In The Case Of Adverse Affects</B></P>
<P>4.2  The advance identification of these sites means that most of the 18
features will not be disturbed by works associated with the proposed RCF,
including those affecting the Service Corridors.  This has been achieved by the
incorporation of archaeological information as a constraint in the design
process.  Thus 14 of the 18 real or potential sites would survive in-situ to the
completion of the Nirex project and only one of the 18 (no 15, rig and  furrow)
will be directly affected by works associated with the Rock Characterisation
Facility.</P>
<P>4.3  The remaining  three have already been examined and recorded according
to approved procedures (as identified in PPG, 16: 1990 [GOV/106]<SUP>2</SUP>)
as a preliminary to the establishment of boreholes within the Appeal Site.</P>
<P>4.4  A programme of archaeological work to examine and record the single
site that would be directly affected by works associated with the RCF has been
designed and will be implemented by Nirex in consultation with the
archaeological service of Cumbria County Council during the works preparatory to
the establishment of the Spoil Disposal Area.</P>
<P><B>Investigations Since The Preparation Of The Environmental Statement
</B></P>
<P>4.5  Since the preparation of the RCF Environmental Statement, further
archaeological work has been conducted within the Appeal Site, in particular to
assess any surviving evidence which might clarify the nature of the stones
formerly described as the Gretigate stone circles. A programme of geophysical
survey and trial trenching produced no satisfactory evidence of the former
existence of these sites as archaeological features (CFA Reports 118 and 176
[NIR/8/4&amp;7]<SUP>7,10</SUP>. Although a number of large stones were
identified, none was in an archaeologically secure context, and when planned,
their distribution did not correspond with that mapped by the original
excavator.  Taken in conjunction with the scepticism of other archaeologists who
had visited, or have commented on, the supposed monuments at varying dates after
their initial reporting in 1961, it is considered that there are unlikely to be
any surviving remains at their recorded location which would merit this area
being considered as a moderate constraint on development on archaeological
grounds. The Cumbria County Archaeologist has written of CFA's work: &quot;This
proved conclusively that if the supposed stone circles and cairns ever existed
at all, and this must now be considered as very doubtful, no trace has survived
nineteenth century clearance or previous excavation, and that the supposed site
is much more likely to have been the result of stone clearance from adjacent
fields&quot; (Daniels 1995 [NIR/8/9]<SUP>13</SUP>).</P>
<P>4.6  Any significant archaeological remains subsequently encountered will
however cause the review of tree-planting and other landscaping initiatives at
their location.</P>
<P><A NAME="Strategies"></A>
<B>5.  STRATEGIES FOR FURTHER MITIGATION</B></P>
<P>5.1  A further programme of archaeological mitigation, comprising watching
briefs and trial trenching, has been proposed  in the RCF Environmental
Statement to take account of the low visibility of archaeological features
within the Appeal Site [COR/101]<SUP>14</SUP>.  It is acknowledged that the low
tally of significant archaeological features within the proposed RCF area may be
attributable to the characteristics of recent landuse, more especially the high
proportion of  improved pasture.  This programme will also be implemented in
association with the archaeological service of Cumbria County Council and will
proceed in tandem with the preparatory work associated with development at any
given locality where that is appropriate.</P>
<P>5.2  Nirex will ensure that the field stage of all archaeological
investigations will have been completed before development at that locality
proceeds, and is prepared to countenance a planning condition imposing the
requirement for such a further programme of archaeological work (to include
fieldwork and all ancillary processes through to and including publication).</P>
<P>5.3  The potential use of planning conditions is addressed further in para
8.2.</P>
<P><A NAME="Consultations"></A><B>6.  CONSULTATIONS</B></P>
<P>6.1  Throughout this programme of work to date, there have been
consultations with the archaeological service of Cumbria County Council.  These
have ranged from discussions on the archaeological resources of neighbouring
areas of Copeland (including the incorporation of data from the Sites and
Monuments Record for Cumbria), to a site visit to the trial trenching at the
Gretigate putative stone circles.</P>
<P><A NAME="Objections"></A>
<B>7.  OBJECTIONS FROM STATUTORY CONSULTEES AND OTHERS: COMMENTS</B></P>
<P>7.1  None of the documentation on representations received up to 11 July
1995, including that from the relevant local authority (Cumbria County Council),
has cited any objection to the scheme on cultural heritage grounds. English
Heritage, as the Secretary of State's advisers on cultural heritage matters,
notes that it has no significant comment to make [COR/107]<SUP>15</SUP>
(undated letter from Mr D Higgins).</P>
<P>7.2  The Friends of the Lake District [COR/107]<SUP>16</SUP> (Letter to J
Hetherington, Cumbria County Council, dated 24.11.94) remark that the:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;archaeological interest of the area would need to be properly
surveyed, recorded and monitored in full discussion with the County
Archaeologist as stated in the application&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> and it is considered that the programme of past and future archaeological
work identified in the RCF Environmental Statement and commented on also in this
submission fully satisfies this request.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>8.  CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P><B>Presently-known Cultural Resources</B></P>
<P>8.1  The confirmed archaeological and cultural resources within the RCF
Appeal Site are of minor or very minor significance. A set of procedures has
been advocated in the RCF Environmental Statement to ensure that they are none
the less avoided wherever this is feasible, or are the subject of mitigation
measures to ensure preservation by record in the one case where avoidance is not
possible for technical reasons.</P>
<P><B>Further Discoveries</B></P>
<P>8.2  The RCF Environmental Statement also addresses the issue of the
discovery of additional archaeological features, not presently known, as a
by-product of an identified range of ground-disturbing activities associated
with the preliminary stages of development. An archaeological mitigation
strategy of trial trenching, watching briefs during topsoil removal, and
fieldwalking after ploughing, partly to precede and partly to run concurrently
with, these preliminary activities, has been advocated in the RCF Environmental
Statement. The draft list of conditions, [COR/113]<SUP>17</SUP>, contains a
condition which addresses this issue and is acceptable to Nirex.</P>
<P><B>Conclusions On The Nature And Extent Of The Cultural Resources Of The
Appeal Site</B></P>
<P>8.3  <A HREF="#Figure8.1">Figure 8.1</A> offers a generalised
representation of the archaeological potential of the Appeal Site .  It uses a
simple colour scheme to delineate the likelihood of the survival of
archaeological features, in accordance with current conventions.  The
archaeological data included are those mapped in
<A HREF="#Figure3.1">Figure 3.1</A>.  In this convention, red indicates sites
accorded protection under the schedule attached to the Ancient Monuments and
Archaeological Areas Act, 1979 [GOV/805]<SUP>18</SUP>; yellow indicates areas
including other known archaeological or cultural heritage remains; green is used
for areas which may include currently unrecognised archaeological features; and
blue areas where subsequent activities are likely to have eliminated any
formerly existing archaeological features.  The sector containing the Gretigate
stone features is hatched yellow and blue, to indicate that any significant
archaeological features which may once have been present here once are now
considered very unlikely to survive in any recognisable form.</P>
<P>8.4  I conclude that the nature of the known cultural resources within the
Appeal Site and the programme of archaeological investigation that has been put
forward means that the proposed development will not lead to the loss of any
significant archaeological information without the opportunity for it adequately
to be recorded; nor would development of the Appeal Site have any affect on
Listed Buildings and Conservation Areas.  The Historic Buildings and Monuments
Commission / English Heritage, as the relevant agency of Central Government, has
not proffered any  significant comment on the Environmental Statement, nor has
it otherwise intervened as its role as a statutory consultee would permit.</P>
<P>8.5  I further consider that the Company's actions to date and its proposed
future actions in respect of real and potential cultural heritage issues on the
RCF Surface Site are fully in accordance with the principles elucidated in
Planning Policy Guidance Note 16 on Archaeology and Planning [GOV/106]<SUP>18</SUP>,
and that no grounds have been advanced for considering cultural resources to
form any part of sustaining an objection to Nirex's proposed RCF facility.</P>
