<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am a Divisional Director of WS Atkins Planning Consultants and a
Chartered Engineer, being a Member of the Institution of Civil Engineers, a
Fellow of the Institution of Highways and Transportation and a Member of the
Institution of Management Consultants. I hold a degree in Bachelor of Science
(Honours) from the University of London and am head of the Traffic Engineering
Division of WS Atkins. The Division undertakes consultancy commissions for the
Department of Transport, local highway authorities and private organisations. We
are regularly commissioned to undertake Traffic Impact Assessments of
developments for submission to planning authorities and are frequently requested
to provide witnesses to present evidence at public inquiries.</P>
<P>1.2 I have been involved in transport planning and traffic engineering for
30 years, being engaged on major projects in the UK and overseas and have
presented traffic evidence at a number of public inquiries.</P>
<P>1.3. The Company has been involved with United Kingdom Nirex Limited
('Nirex') since 1988 and I have been associated with the proposals to build a
Deep Waste Repository ('DWR') since November 1990. I am Project Director for WS
Atkins Planning Consultants' work associated with the non-nuclear transport
assessment of the proposed DWR at Sellafield. I have been involved in the
development of the transport aspects of the scheme and have undertaken
consultations with the highway and railway  authorities.</P>
<P>1.4 WS Atkins Planning Consultants were appointed by Nirex in 1992 to assist
in identifying the traffic and highway aspects of the Rock Characterisation
Facility ('RCF') and I have been responsible for this work to the current time.</P>
<P>1.5 I have visited the area of the works on a number of occasions and am
familiar with the road network and traffic flows in the vicinity of the Appeal
site.</P>
<P>1.6 I presented traffic evidence on behalf of Nirex at the Public Inquiry in
November 1992 into the drilling of exploratory geological Boreholes 8 and 9 in
the vicinity of Gosforth, for which planning permission was granted.</P>
<P>1.7 I was responsible for gaining approval from the Department of Transport
for the current access to the site of the proposed RCF, for its design and for
the supervision of its construction.</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2. SUMMARY</B></P>
<P>2.1 My proof of evidence is based on an established analytical process to
estimate the volume of traffic to be generated by the Rock Characterisation
Facility ('RCF') development and to determine the potential impact of generated
traffic on the local road network.</P>
<P><B>Analytical Process</B></P>
<P>2.2 Sequential steps in the process can be summarised as shown below.</P>
<P>The existing transport system:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>inspect and prepare an inventory of the local road network;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>establish the capacity of the local road network;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>obtain survey information to quantify the volume and characteristics of
existing traffic flows and movements by cyclists and pedestrians;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>analyse the traffic accident records in the area to determine if there are
any  locations which are particularly vulnerable to accidents;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>review transport policies from the statutory local plans.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Traffic generated by the development:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(f)</TD>
<TD>from an understanding of the nature of the development, determine the
categories of traffic to be generated by the development in each stage of
construction, operation, and restoration on completion of the works; traffic is
categorised by heavy goods vehicles ('HGVs') moving construction material, cars
conveying the workforce and visitors, and light goods vehicles;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(g)</TD>
<TD>identify whether there are any other untypical traffic flows likely to be
generated in the area concurrently with the development; in this case the
traffic effects of the concurrent Nirex Deep Boreholes have been taken into
account;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(h)</TD>
<TD>establish peak flows of traffic generated by the RCF development for each
month of the life of the development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(j)</TD>
<TD>determine which roads the generated traffic is likely to use;</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>Assessment of traffic impacts:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(k)</TD>
<TD>establish how the existing traffic flows on the local system will increase
through natural growth over the life of the development to establish base
traffic flows;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(l)</TD>
<TD>add the traffic flows generated by the development to the base flows on the
network and compare the total forecast flows to the assessed capacities of the
network;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(m)</TD>
<TD>inspect the results to determine if there are any overloaded road sections
or junctions and consider whether any mitigating action needs to be taken.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Rail Access</B></P>
<P>2.3 It was concluded that the use of rail in the development of the RCF was
not a viable alternative to road access for a number of reasons. These include:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the topography between the Cumbrian Coast Line and the site which renders  
a  direct connection impracticable;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the variable mix of material flows which does not lend itself to the use of
rail;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>the excavated spoil remains on site; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>the highest materials flows occur for only a short duration.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The Local Road Network</P>
<P>2.4 The Surface Site is served from the A595(T) which is a trunk road for
which the Highways Agency is the highway authority. The A595(T) can be seen on
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A> of my  proof. Other roads in the
area are mainly the responsibility of Cumbria County Council.</P>
<P>2.5 Access to the Surface Site from the A595(T) is via a T-junction as shown
in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.4">Figure 4.4</A>. This junction was
constructed in 1993 to the Department of Transport's design requirements and has
a high traffic carrying capacity.</P>
<P>2.6 Most of the traffic to and from the Surface Site will be from the north.
Junctions to the north with connections to the Sellafield Works are the
Blackbeck roundabout (<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure 4.2</A>) and the
traffic signals at Calder Bridge (<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.3">Figure 4.3</A>).</P>
<P>2.7 A number of traffic surveys have been undertaken and summary data are
presented in graphical form as described below:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD><A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.8">Figure 4.8</A> shows the hourly weekday
variation of traffic flows on the A595(T) north of Blackbeck roundabout. The
figure shows a pronounced peak hour flow in the morning and that traffic volumes
at this location have changed little between 1993 and 1995. Spare capacity
exists either side of the peak hour;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD><A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.10">Figure 4.10</A> shows the monthly
variation of traffic flows on the A595(T) south of Gosforth. The figure shows
that traffic flows have declined significantly at this location over 3 years.
The reduction in traffic flows matches the reduction in employment levels at the
Sellafield Works as shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.2">Table 4.2</A>;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>Traffic to the Sellafield Works from the north can use the A595(T) or the
secondary roads serving the local villages. A number of the secondary roads were
surveyed at the locations shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.9">Figure 4.9</A>
and the hourly variations in traffic flows on these roads are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.11">Figure 4.11</A>. Again, the peak hour
characteristics can be seen; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>Typical traffic flows during the working day (12 hours) on the local road
network in the area are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.12i">Figure 4.12</A>.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.8 The 1991 to 1993 accident rate between Blackbeck roundabout and Gosforth
is slightly higher than the national average for that type of road during 1993.
Year by year comparison of the rate for all Class A roads in non-built up areas
shows a  declining trend. Overall, for the 60km (38 miles) section of the
A595(T) south of Blackbeck roundabout, traffic flows are relatively low and the
accident rate is less than  the average for that type of road.</P>
<P><B>Traffic Generated by the RCF Development</B></P>
<P>2.9 Traffic volumes generated by the RCF development can be computed from
information on:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the quantities and delivery periods of construction material needed for the
RCF development; these enable the HGV movements to be identified; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>workforce and visitor estimates to provide forecasts of the movements of
cars and light goods vehicle.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The resulting traffic flow profile is shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>. The traffic volumes vary in
each phase of the RCF development.</P>
<P>2.10 Estimates have also been made of the traffic associated with the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes during the RCF development.  The combined totals of
traffic from the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes at Longlands Farm and from the RCF
development are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>
(Central Case) and <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A> (Variant
Case).</P>
<P><B>Assessment of Traffic Impacts</B></P>
<P>2.11 The Department of Transport forecasts how traffic will grow. The
forecasts are provided as a range bounded by low and high growth rate scenarios.
For the assessment of effects of generated traffic, flows derived from count
data have been increased to produce future year baseline traffic estimates.</P>
<P>2.12 Considering, as a reference point, a location on the A595(T) to the
north of the Longlands Farm access road to the Surface Site,
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> shows how traffic may be
expected to grow. The grey shaded columns show traffic flows without the RCF
development. The black bands show the extra traffic generated by the RCF
development, and the borehole works.</P>
<P>2.13 It can be seen that the RCF development and the boreholes traffic is
relatively small and does not in any year exceed the traffic flows that may be
expected on the A595(T) some 6 years ahead. The RCF development does not
therefore generate exceptional traffic flows for which new road construction may
be justified.</P>
<P>2.14 To look more closely at the operation of important junctions an
analysis of hourly traffic has been made. Conclusion from this analysis are
that:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>in the peak hour <B>Blackbeck roundabout</B> operates close to its
practical capacity although recent surveys have shown conditions to be eased
from those observed a few years ago. Traffic on the southbound A595(T) entry to
the roundabout in the morning peak period no longer queues into and on the
roundabout. Gaps in the traffic flows now occur even in the peak hour and spare
capacity exists;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the  <B>Calder Bridge traffic signals</B>  operate  within   their
capacity  for A595(T)  traffic  throughout  the  day. The  only  time  there is
a queue is in the afternoon peak  when  employees  of  the  Sellafield  Works 
leave the site.  Traffic queues  on  the  C4013  but  recent surveys have shown
the queues to be much reduced from  those  observed  in previous years. The
traffic signals are vehicle actuated  and automatically take account of changing
traffic flows; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>the <B>Longlands Farm junction</B> has substantial spare capacity.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.15.The potential adverse effect of HGVs will be minimised: </P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>access shall be only via the Longlands Farm access road except in
emergencies and for construction in the western sections of the Services
Corridors;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>wheelwashing and weighing facilities will be provided on the Surface Site;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>vehicles carrying loose or dusty material shall be covered;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>contractors will be required to adhere to identified access routes; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>route direction and advance site signs can be provided.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>2.16.Controls on the hours of operation of HGVs are not necessary or
appropriate.</P>
<P>2.17 Adequate facilities will be provided on-site for parking. There will be
no parking on the A595(T) or Longlands Farm access road.</P>
<P>2.18 The RCF development generates relatively low volumes of traffic and the
traffic will be similar in character to that already using the A595(T). No
changes in the accident rates are therefore anticipated as a consequence of the
RCF development.</P>
<P><B>Consultations</B></P>
<P>2.19 The content of this proof of evidence is similar to the details
contained in the Environmental Statement submitted with the planning application
and circulated to statutory consultees.</P>
<P>2.20 As a result of the consultation it is pertinent to note that:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the Highways Agency has no comment on the Environmental Statement.   Their
view is that there are no highway considerations;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the Cumbria Constabulary has no objection to the application; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>Cumbria County Council has no objections with regard to trunk road   
interests.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<H2> </H2>
<P><B>Conclusion</B></P>
<P>2.21 In view of:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the relatively low volumes of traffic generated by the RCF development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the fact that the total of RCF traffic and other A595(T) traffic will be
less  than the flows on the A595(T) some 6 years in the future;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>the junctions on the A595(T) can accommodate the forecast traffic flows;
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>the RCF development is temporary;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>there are no inherent road safety risks; and </TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(f)</TD>
<TD>there will be no effects from new road construction,</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>I believe that planning permission should not be withheld on traffic or
highway grounds.</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. BACKGROUND AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE
.BACKGROUND AND SCOPE OF EVIDENCE</B></P>
<P><B>Analytical Procedure</B></P>
<P>3.1 The construction and operation of the RCF will generate traffic flows
which will add to existing traffic flows on the local road network.  Analyses
and forecasts have been made of: </P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the traffic carrying capacity of the road network;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the base load of traffic on the road system, now and in the future; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>the traffic generated by the RCF over its finite life.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>3.2 To assist in the assessment of existing conditions, surveys have been
undertaken of the road network, traffic and pedestrian flows and traffic
generated by the Nirex Deep Boreholes ('Boreholes') drilling and testing
activities at Longlands Farm.</P>
<P>3.3 The planning application for the  RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes at Longlands
Farm included the provision of a new access junction on the A595(T). The
application was approved and the junction was constructed to the design and
safety requirements of the Highways Agency (then, the Department of Transport)
who are the highway authority for the A595(T) which is a trunk road. The RCF
planning application proposed the continued use of this junction to serve the
RCF development.</P>
<P><B>Changes Since Publication of the Environmental Statement</B></P>
<P>1.4 A description of the site, its location, planning context, and details
of the changes to the RCF design and planned operations since the preparation of
the Environmental Statement are contained in other submissions to the Inquiry
and are not contained in this Proof of Evidence.</P>
<P>3.5 The analysis of the traffic effects of the RCF as forecast in 1994 were
included in the Environmental Statement ('ES') [COR/101]1, principally in
Chapter 4 of Section 3:  Effects on the Environment. Since the preparation of
the ES there have been a number of changes affecting the traffic analysis. The
presentation in my proof of evidence follows the style of the ES and takes
account of these changes, which are:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>changes to the design, construction methods and proposed programme of  
activities, and the size of and the time when the workforce will be on site -  
these changes are described in the proof of Mr A J Smith; </TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the planned start of the RCF construction is now scheduled for July 1996 
which is ten months later than that contained in the ES;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD>more recent traffic flow and accident data are now available; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD>a programme of Saline Interface Boreholes between the A595(T) and the coast
is planned. Parts of this programme will be coincident with the RCF construction
and will have associated traffic effects. The Boreholes programme is described
in the proof of Dr R Chaplow.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>3.6 Additionally, an assessment of a Variant Case for the RCF construction
is presented. The Variant Case will extend the period of shaft construction with
consequent changes to the traffic flow profile.</P>
<P>3.7 No significant effects result from either the changes listed in
paragraph 3.5 or the Variant Case.  However the reduction in the overlap between
the Borehole programme at Longlands Farm and the RCF construction results in the
cumulative traffic flows of the two activities being lower. The RCF/RCM/PRZ
Boreholes drilling will be complete and the subsequent testing generates only
low traffic flows. The most significant change in the traffic case since
preparation of the ES is in the base traffic flow on the A595(T). The effect of
the Sellafield Works on traffic flow on the A595(T) is clearly significant. The
employment at the Sellafield Works has reduced since 1990, mainly as a result of
the reduced contractor workforce following completion of construction of the
THORP project. Between 1990 and 1994 the employment level has dropped 33
percent. The effect of this can be seen in the reduced traffic flows on the
A595(T).</P>
<P>3.8 The permanent Department of Transport ('DOT') automatic traffic counter
('ATC') on the A595(T) south of Gosforth recorded an average annual daily
traffic ('AADT') of 5900 vehicles per day (vpd) in 1990 [NRX/9/1]2. The
comparable 1992 data used in the ES was 5000 [NRX/9/2]3. In 1993 the recorded
AADT was 4500 [NRX/9/3]4 and  in 1994 it was 4200 vehicles per day, a reduction
of 29 per cent since 1990. These levels of traffic flow reduction far exceed the
levels of traffic forecast to be generated by the RCF development.</P>
<P>3.9 The traffic effects of the scheme are shown to be not significant and no
new road construction is required.</P>
<P><B>Consultation</B></P>
<P>3.10 The  Environmental  Statement  was  formally  circulated   to 
statutory consultees and their  observations  have  been  mainly  summarised  in
 the  report  by Cumbria County Council's  Director of Economy and Environment
[COR/104]5. Responses to these observations  and those of Copeland Borough
Council and other representations are included at Section 7 of this Proof of
Evidence.</P>
<P><B>Environmental Effects</B></P>
<P>3.11 The environmental effects of the generated traffic on public roads are,
in the main, negligible. Environmental evaluation criteria investigated in
preparation for the Inquiry  and their significance are described in the Proofs
of Evidence of the environmental witnesses, namely:</P>
