<P><A NAME="Local"></A><B>4. THE LOCAL ROAD NETWORK .THE LOCAL ROAD NETWORK</B></P>
<P><B>Access Roads to the RCF Access Roads to the RCF</B></P>
<P>4.1 The roads which will serve the proposed development are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A>. The principal  road is the
A595(T) which is a trunk road for which the Highways Agency is  the highway
authority. This is also the principal road in the Copeland district. It forms
the north-eastern boundary of the Appeal Site. The next highest class of road in
the vicinity of the Appeal Site is the B5344. This road is to the south of the
Appeal Site and provides access to Seascale from the A595(T). The remaining
roads in the area surrounding the Appeal  Site  are  minor  roads,  byways  or 
bridleways.  Cumbria  County  Council is the highway authority for all the
public roads in the vicinity of the  development, other than the A595(T). The
County's Transport Policies and Programme ('TPP') [NRX/9/3]10 records in Policy
3/1 the County Council's efforts to maximise investment by the Highways Agency
on motorways and trunk roads.</P>
<P>4.2 Between Gosforth and Calder Bridge the A595(T) is a single carriageway
road. The road from  Gosforth  climbs  towards  Boonwood Lane,  initially  at  a
gradient of 14% and  then runs along flatter terrain through the Longlands Farm
junction before falling towards New Mill. The horizontal alignment of the road
is sinuous and in some places the width is less than the normal standard of 7.3
metres for a new single carriageway  road. Approximately 95% of the road between
Calder Bridge and Gosforth is less than 7.3 metres in width with a minimum
recorded width of 5.7 metres just north of Gosforth, near Hardingill. Horizontal
and vertical alignments in places lead to limited visibility. North of Calder
Bridge the road continues as a single carriageway to the Egremont Bypass. The
bypass is a wide single carriageway (10 metres width).  Between Calder Bridge
and the Nursery Road junction the A595(T) is similar to the section south of
Calder Bridge. To the north of Nursery Road the road is predominantly 7.3 metres
wide, or more, and has a higher standard of vertical and horizontal alignment.</P>
<P>4.3 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.1">Figure 4.1</A> identifies the main
highway junctions on the A595(T) within the vicinity of the development. These
junctions provide access from the A595(T) to the Sellafield Works, the Appeal
Site, Gosforth and Seascale.</P>
<P>4.4 The Blackbeck roundabout links the Main and Station Gates of the
Sellafield Works to the A595(T) via the C4037 (<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.2">Figure
4.2</A>). The junction is a conventional roundabout with a circular  central 
island.  In  addition  to  the  A595(T) north and south, and the C4037, the
roundabout provides connections with the C4031 to the nearby village of
Beckermet and with the C4016 to Haile. The road markings at the roundabout are
in  accordance with the 'offside priority rule' with the exception of the entry
from the A595(T) north, which has priority over the circulating carriageway.
This arrangement has been adopted to accommodate the large roundabout entry
volume from the north and the relatively small circulating volume affected by
this movement. This priority arrangement also serves to limit the volume of
traffic in the peak commuter periods using roads through Beckermet (C4014 and
C4031) to travel to the Sellafield Works.</P>
<P>4.5 At Calder Bridge there is a junction of the A595(T) with the C4013,
which runs to the North Gate of the Sellafield Works.  This junction, which is
shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.3">Figure 4.3</A>, is a traffic signal
controlled T-junction. There is a dedicated right turn lane on the A595(T) for
southbound traffic turning to the C4013. Right and left turning traffic on the
C4013 also has dedicated lanes at the approach to the junction stopline.</P>
<P>4.6 The Longlands Farm junction provides access from the A595(T) to the
RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes and Longlands Farm and will be the access point to the
Appeal Site. The junction layout is shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.4">Figure
4.4</A> and <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.5">4.5</A>. The junction has a ghost
island on the A595(T) which incorporates a segregated lane for traffic turning
right from the north into the Appeal Site. There is good visibility at the
junction, which complies with the requirements of the DOT Departmental Advice
Note TA 20/84 [GOV/116]11. The carriageway edge is kerbed and the access road is
surfaced through the junction. It was designed and constructed in 1993 to DOT
design and safety standards.</P>
<P>4.7 The junctions of the A595(T) with Boonwood Lane and the B5344 which runs
to Seascale are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.6">Figure 4.6</A> and
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.7">4.7</A> respectively.</P>
<P>4.8 Between Gosforth and Calder Bridge a number of unclassified roads and
farm accesses link into the A595(T). The majority of these minor roads form
T-junctions with the A595(T) and have sub-standard visibility. Sides Lane, which
is a bridleway, runs through the Appeal Site and has a junction with the A595(T)
at Gosforth. Except for emergency use it will not provide access from the
A595(T) to the Appeal Site, see paragraph 6.39.</P>
<P><B>Highway Capacity</B></P>
<P>4.9 Advice  on  the  traffic  capacity  of  roads  is  provided  in  DOT 
Departmental  Standard TD  20/85 [GOV/117]12. South of the Blackbeck roundabout
the A595(T) is a rural two-lane road and TD 20/85 indicates an AADT flow
capacity of 13000 vehicles for a new road link of this type. Roads can
accommodate higher flows than their design capacity, but between the Nursery
Road junction and Gosforth the poor alignment, variable width and limited
junction design tends to limit the capacity of the A595(T).  A realistic
assessment of capacity for the A595(T) is approximately 12000 vehicles per day
('vpd').</P>
<P>4.10 From the north side of the Nursery Road junction to the Egremont
bypass, the A595(T) has a higher capacity. TD 20/85 indicates a design capacity
of between 13000 vpd and 18000 vpd. Traffic flow during the morning peak hour
between 7.00 am and 8.00 am has been observed in excess of 1700 vehicles per
hour ('vph')  (two way) north of Blackbeck roundabout. Outside peak periods
lower flows are observed as  illustrated in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.8">Figure
4.8</A> which shows ATC data from 1993 and 1995. The daily operational capacity
can be assessed on the basis of the peak hour flow being 8% to 10% of the daily
flow, indicating a daily capacity in the range 17000 vpd to 21000 vpd. By
consideration of design capacity and observed operational characteristics, a
capacity of 18000 vpd has been assumed for this section of the A595(T), although
in practice flows at the higher end of the range may be experienced in future
years.</P>
<P>4.11 Surveys and analysis of the Blackbeck roundabout in the morning peak
hour show the roundabout to be operating at or close to its practical capacity.
In the peak hour there is a heavy flow of traffic southbound on the A595(T) into
and around the roundabout and taking the C4037 exit to the Sellafield Main Gate.
Spare capacity is available either side of the peak period.</P>
<P>4.12 Theoretical analysis of the Calder Bridge traffic signal controlled
junction using traffic turning movements observed in April 1995 demonstrates
that the junction can accommodate the traffic flows on the A595(T) with spare
capacity. The only significant queue  is  on  the  C4013  approach  in  the 
afternoon  peak  period  when  traffic leaves the Sellafield Works. This
theoretical analysis is supported by observation of the operation of the0
junction.  The queue on the C4013 in the afternoon peak was observed on 25 April
1995 to extend to approximately 35 vehicles for a short period.  Observations in
August 1993 showed queues of up to 60 vehicles in the afternoon peak on the
C4013.</P>
<P>4.13 The junction of Longlands Farm access road and the A595(T) has been
constructed to generous capacity standards. Substantial spare capacity exists to
accommodate through flows on the A595(T) and turning movements to and from the
Longlands Farm site.</P>
<P><B>Existing Traffic Flows</B></P>
<P>4.14 The DOT has a permanent ATC station (Reference No. 072024) located on
the A595(T) 1km (0.6 mile) to the south of Gosforth. The location of the station
is shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.9">Figure 4.9</A>. Information from
Cumbria County Council's TPP shows the traffic flows on the A595(T) to be 5900
vpd (AADT) in 1990(2) and 4500 vpd in 1993(4). Monthly  data are available from
the ATC station from January 1992 to December 1994 and are  shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.1">Table 4.1</A> and
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.10">Figure 4.10</A>.</P>
<P>4.15 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.10">Figure 4.10</A> shows the monthly
variation in traffic with a peak in the summer months.  The decline in the
traffic flows on the A595(T) is closely related to the activities of the
Sellafield Works. Since 1990 the number of employees has reduced; between 1990
and 1994 the reduction was 33 per cent, mainly due to the completion of
construction of the THORP project but the number of BNFL direct workforce
employees was also reduced in 1994. <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.2">Table 4.2</A>
shows the relationship between the workforce at Sellafield Works and traffic
flow on the A595(T) south of Gosforth. It can be seen that reduction of 33 per
cent in employment between 1990 and 1994 is matched with a reduction of 29 per
cent in traffic flows. In the current year direct employment has dropped by a
further 4.7 per cent but contractors' data and traffic flow data are not
available.</P>
<P>4.16 Junction traffic turning counts have been undertaken at the following
four sites on  the A595(T):</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
