<TD>B5344 Gosforth.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.17 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.9">Figure 4.9</A> shows the locations of
ATCs undertaken in September and October 1993 on the A595(T), Sites 8 and 9.
ATCs were also undertaken in January and February 1995 on a number of the roads
serving as access routes to the Sellafield Works from the north. The locations
of these ATCs are also shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.9">Figure 4.9</A> and plots of the average weekday
traffic flows are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.11">Figure 4.11</A>.
From this figure the directional characteristics of the flow pattern and the
pronounced peak hours can be seen.</P>
<P>4.18 The average 12 hour daily flows (7.00 am to 7.00 pm) on the local road
network, determined from surveys, are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.12i">Figure 4.12</A>.
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A> gives a summary of the ATC and
manual count data on the A595(T) from south of Gosforth to north of Blackbeck
roundabout and also shows the derivation of AADT flows from the count data, with
an assessed daily capacity for each section of road.</P>
<P><B>Pedestrians and Cyclists</B></P>
<P>4.19 The A595(T) has no footpath or verge along much of its length between
Gosforth and New Mill and presents an unattractive route for pedestrians. A
survey of pedestrians and cyclists using the A595(T) was undertaken on a typical
weekday and on a public holiday. The surveys were undertaken in May 1994 in the
vicinity of the Red Admiral Hotel and to the south of Calder Bridge.  The
results are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.4">Table 4.4</A> and indicate
that few pedestrians or cyclists are observed to use the road.</P>
<P>4.20 Cumbria County Council has identified the Cumbria Cycle Way on roads
and tracks between the A595(T) and the coast in the vicinity of the Appeal site.
This facility and other routes which are available to cyclists as an alternative
to the A595(T) and local roads are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.13">Figure
4.13</A>. Facilities for cyclists will be provided at the Surface Site as are
warranted by demand.</P>
<P><B>Accident Records</B></P>
<P>4.21 The DOT summary statistics [GOV/118]13 for accidents in the periods
1989 to 1991, 1990 to 1992 and 1991 to 1993 on the A595(T) are provided in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.14">Figure 4.14</A>.</P>
<P>4.22 Within the 25.7 km (16 miles) length of the A595(T) between Blackbeck
roundabout (the Sellafield access, C4037) and Bootle (C4027), which includes the
Longlands Farm junction, the accident rates are 0.36 personal injury accidents
('PIA')/ million vehicle-kilometres  ('vkm')  (1989 to 1991),  0.31  PIA/million
 vkm  (1990 to 1992)  and  0.33 PIA/million vkm (1991 to 1993). The average rate
in Great Britain for all Class A roads in non-built up areas was 0.28
PIA/million vkm [GOV/119]14 in 1993. Year by year comparison of the rate for all
Class A roads in non-built up areas shows a declining trend. The 1991 to 1993
accident rate between Blackbeck roundabout and Gosforth is slightly higher than
the national average for that type of road during 1993. The TPP [NRX/9/3]15
records that, overall, for the 60 km (38 miles) section of the A595(T) south of
Blackbeck roundabout, &quot;<I>traffic flows are relatively low ..............
and the accident rate is less than the average for that type of road</I>&quot;.</P>
<P>4.23 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table4.5">Table 4.5</A> provides PIA data
recorded by Cumbria County Council between January 1992 and December 1994 (3
years) for the A595(T) from Blackbeck roundabout to Hallsenna Lane, south of
Gosforth.</P>
<P>4.24 The  locations  of  these  accidents  and  accidents  northwards  to 
Egremont are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.15i">Figure 4.15</A>. There
have been no PIA accidents at the Longlands Farm junction.</P>
<P>4.25 In 1992 two pedal cyclists were involved in slight injury accidents. In
1994 pedal cyclists were involved in one serious injury and one slight injury
accidents. None of the accidents recorded between 1989 and 1994 involved
pedestrians.</P>
<P>4.26 Accident statistics include only those accidents involving reported
personal injury or fatalities. Vehicular damage-only accidents also occur and
national statistics published by the Transport Research Laboratory [NRX/9/4]16
enable the estimate to be made that for each PIA on rural roads there are likely
to be  4.6 damage-only accidents. This would indicate that, typically, some 8
minor, damage-only accidents are likely to occur each year between Calder Bridge
and Gosforth.</P>
<P><A NAME="Traffic"></A><B>5. TRAFFIC GENERATED BY THE DEVELOPMENT .TRAFFIC
GENERATED BY THE DEVELOPMENT</B></P>
<P><B>Categories of Traffic Categories of Traffic</B></P>
<P>5.1 The volumes of traffic generated by the development will vary according
to the activities on  the  site  in  successive  stages of the development. In
general terms, the traffic will comprise:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>heavy goods vehicles ('HGVs') transporting construction materials, plant   
and equipment to the site;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>cars conveying the workforce and visitors; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>light goods vehicles ('LGVs').</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P><B>Site Establishment and Phase 1</B></P>
<P>5.2 Part of the Surface Site will be levelled to construct the Platform
Site. Infrastructure will be constructed and installed and there will be a
requirement for imported crushed stone. The first few months of the development,
and two months during Restoration, will be the busiest periods in terms of HGV
movements.</P>
<P>5.3 Following Site Establishment, the trips to and form the Surface Site
will be predominantly personnel movements. Spoil from the shafts and underground
excavation will remain on the Surface Site with the possible exception of up to
15000t of BVG (about 10% of the total excavated BVG) which may be taken off the
site to evaluate its potential use. The traffic analysis assumes that BVG will
be taken off site to evaluate its potential usefulness as an aggregate or fill
material.</P>
<P>5.4 The number of contractors' personnel will peak during the first few
months of the development. Thereafter the number will continue at a lower level
with a further reduction in the last few months of Phase 1.</P>
<P><B>Phase 2 and Phase 3</B></P>
<P>5.5 Construction and the Science Programme will continue through Phase 2 and
Phase 3.  The highest number of trips will occur during Construction when
materials will be transported to the Surface Site. During the Science Programme,
traffic will be predominantly cars and light goods vehicles used by management,
scientific personnel and visitors.</P>
<P><B>Restoration</B></P>
<P>5.6 After completion of the Phase 3 Science Programme, the shafts will be
backfilled, capped and sealed and all buildings and infrastructure above ground
will be removed.  This will be followed by remodelling of the Surface Site to
blend in with the local topography. Traffic will be generated by the transport
of personnel, deliveries of  materials for shaft backfilling and removal of
demolition materials from the Surface Site.</P>
<P><B> Assessment of Development Generated Traffic Assessment of Development
Generated Traffic</B></P>
<P>Basis of Traffic Assessment</P>
<P>5.7 Estimates of numbers of personnel, visitors, and quantities of
construction and service materials have been made for each month of the
development. The estimates of generated traffic have been based on an assessment
of the average daily volume  of  traffic in each month for each category of 
personnel  movement  and  material  delivery.  The highest average daily volume
occurring on any day in the month is taken to be representative of that month.
The traffic figures are presented as one-way trips unless otherwise stated.
Therefore the two-way flows on the road system will be twice the numbers quoted.</P>
<P>5.8 Changes to the basic data since the Environmental Statement was prepared
relate  to:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the anticipated date of the start of construction (now 1 July 1996) and   
subsequent phases;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the phasing of work within the construction programme;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>the anticipated manning levels;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>the removal from or import of materials to the site to suit the revisions
to    design and construction phasing:</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>design options: the Central Case with galleries at 650 metres bOD and the
Variant Case with galleries at up to 900 metres bOD; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(f)</TD>
<TD>a programme of Saline Interface Boreholes which may be undertaken
concurrently with the RCF construction.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.9 The Central Case and the Variant Case represent the highest and lowest
depths envisaged for RCF gallery construction, and are considered in this
assessment to be the bounding options. However, gallery construction could be
undertaken at any intermediate depth between the bounding options.</P>
<P>Personnel</P>
<P>5.10 The workforce profile shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.1">Table
5.1</A> of this evidence shows an estimate of the average number of people who
would travel to the Surface Site during a normal working day for each month of
the development. The workforce is divided into contractors, management and
scientific personnel and <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> includes
an allowance for visitors. Each workforce estimate in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> represents the daily total (i.e.
the sum of shift and day workers).</P>
<P>5.11 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.1">Table 5.1</A> shows data for the
Central and Variant Cases. The Variant Case shows a change in site personnel
totals at Year 4 Month 7 when four months' additional time is required for shaft
sinking. Thereafter, at Year 4 Month 11, the Variant Case site personnel totals
revert to the personnel profile of the Central Case.</P>
<P>5.12 Vehicle occupancy factors and trip generation rates have been applied
to convert numbers of site personnel and visitors into vehicular trips, as shown
in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A> .  The estimates of trips take
account of the workforce category (contractor, management  or  scientific),
shift pattern and location of work (i.e. surface or underground).</P>
<P>Construction Materials</P>
<P>5.13 Quantities of the main construction materials to be transported to the
Surface Site have been estimated. Delivery periods within the development
programme have been identified for each material. The number of loads which will
be generated are based on a maximum weight, volume or quantity which can be
carried per vehicle, with an allowance for part loads where appropriate. The
total quantities of materials, vehicle loadings and delivery periods are shown
in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.3">Table 5.3</A>.</P>
<P>5.14 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.3">Table 5.3</A> also shows the
construction material profile for the Variant Case. There are changes during
Year 4 when extra material is required for the deeper shaft but otherwise
material deliveries remain the same as for the Central Case except at
Restoration. In view of the deeper shaft, more material is required at that time
for backfilling the shaft.</P>
<P>5.15 Construction planning identifies the need for the movement of a small
number of abnormal indivisible loads during Site Establishment. This represents
a change from the Environmental Statement. At the time of preparation of the
Environmental Statement no abnormal loads were envisaged. The geometric design
of the Longlands Farm junction and access road will accommodate abnormal loads
manoeuvring into and out of the Surface Site.</P>
<P>5.16 The material source locations have not been identified. It is assumed
in the subsequent analysis that all materials are delivered to the Surface Site
from the north as this will represent the worst case in terms of the number of
extra HGVs added to existing traffic flows on the local road network. If some of
the materials were delivered from local sources to the south this would reduce
the number of vehicles on the northern section of the A595(T). It is not
expected that materials will have a journey origin in the south.  Most
deliveries will be from local sources to the north or will be from further
afield, travelling via the M6, A66(T) and A595(T) as described in paragraph
6.26(e). In the event that some materials were imported from quarries located to
the  south of the RCF site the number of HGVs will be low and is considered to
be part of the normal commercial activities of the quarries.</P>
<P>BVG Off-site Testing</P>
<P>5.17 The HGV estimates take into account the option to remove 15,000t of BVG
for off-site testing. This would be likely to take place during a despatch
period of 14 months subdivided into 8 months and 6 months, as detailed in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.4">Table 5.4</A>, commencing when shaft excavation
enters the BVG. The assumptions used in the derivation of estimates of generated
traffic associated with BVG movements are also shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.4">Table 5.4</A>.</P>
<P>Generated Traffic Volumes</P>
<P>5.18 Estimated volumes of generated traffic are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.5">Table 5.5</A> for the Central and Variant Cases.
The figures represent, for each month, the average number of vehicles visiting
the Surface Site per day, subdivided into two categories: cars and LGVs, and
HGVs. The additional traffic flow on the roads to the Surface Site will be twice
the number of vehicles identified in the table, i.e. one trip to the Surface
Site and one trip from the Surface Site.</P>
<P>5.19 The estimate of generated traffic is shown diagrammatically in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.1">Figure 5.1</A>.  This shows that the busiest
period in terms of traffic generation will be during the first few months of the
development with the highest average number of vehicles forecast shown to be
about 275 vpd, of which around 25% are HGVs. After this period the total number
of  vehicles will decline to about 240 vpd and the HGV content will drop
substantially to about 15 vpd.</P>
<P>5.20 In order to assess the traffic generated by all Nirex work in the area
the cumulative effect of borehole traffic and development traffic has been taken
into account. Traffic is generated from the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes at Longlands
Farm and from the Saline Interface  Boreholes. The volumes of Boreholes traffic
used in this assessment and their assumed access routes are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.6">Table 5.6</A>.</P>
<P>5.21 The combined RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes and development traffic flows,
assuming that Site Establishment for the development commences in July 1996, are
shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.7">Table 5.7</A> for both the Central Case
and the Variant Case and in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.2">Figure 5.2</A>
(Central  Case) and in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure5.3">Figure 5.3</A> (Variant
Case).</P>
<P><A NAME="Para5.22"></A>5.22 The assessment of traffic flows on the A595(T)
is based on the assumption that the additional flow in each direction to the
north of Longlands Farm junction will be 100% of the HGV figures and 80% of the
car and LGV figures shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.7">Table 5.7</A>. The
remaining 20% of the car and LGV trips are assumed to be from the south. The
80%/20% directional split was assessed by analysis of the existing vehicular
turning movements at junctions on the A595(T) with roads providing access to the
Sellafield Works. This directional split has been applied to all traffic
generated by the RCF and the RCF/ RCM/ PRZ Boreholes and Saline Interface
Boreholes. The routeing of the development generated traffic from the A595(T) to
other roads is assumed to follow the existing local traffic patterns which are
shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.12i">Figure 4.12</A>.</P>
<P><A NAME="Effects"></A><B>6. EFFECTS OF GENERATED TRAFFIC ON THE LOCAL ROAD
NETWORK .EFFECTS OF GENERATED TRAFFIC ON THE LOCAL ROAD NETWORK</B></P>
<P><B>Traffic Growth Traffic Growth</B></P>
<P>6.1 During the life of the development, there will be natural growth of
non-Nirex traffic on the local road network. The DOT publishes estimates of
annual growth of traffic in the form of National Road Traffic Forecasts ('NRTF')
[GOV/120]17. The forecasts are provided as a range bounded by low and high
growth rate scenarios. For the assessment of effects of generated traffic, flows
derived from count data have been increased by NRTF factors to produce future
year baseline traffic estimates.</P>
<P>6.2 The increased traffic flow due to the development can be compared to
natural traffic growth predicted by NRTF. This assists in gauging its effects.
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> shows estimates of Boreholes and
RCF development generated traffic superimposed on NRTF low growth flows on the
A595(T). The starting point for the NRTF growth curve is the estimated July 1993
peak 24 hour flow. In forecasting future non-Nirex traffic flows on the A595(T)
it has been assumed that there will be no further reduction in the traffic
associated with the Sellafield Works and that future traffic will grow from the
1993 recorded levels.  This is a conservative assumption in view of the further
decline in the total number of employees at Sellafield since 1993.</P>
<P>6.3 The traffic flows illustrated in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure
6.1</A> represent vehicles per day generated by the combined RCF and Boreholes
works  in the busiest month for each year added to the peak monthly flows (in
July) on the A595(T). The figure shows flows on the A595(T) north of Longlands
Farm junction.</P>
<P>6.4 The low growth NRTF data shows the greatest effect of the generated
traffic: the high growth data would show the generated traffic as a lower
proportion of total traffic. The high growth forecast of A595(T) traffic in the
year 2009 north of the Longlands Farm junction is 5500 vpd in each direction. It
can be seen from <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> that the
combined increase in traffic due to the boreholes and the development is small
in the context of the daily flow of traffic on the A595(T). The highest
combination of RCF development and Boreholes traffic would occur in 1996. This
represents an increase of approximately 10% above the estimated  average daily
traffic in that year. </P>
<P>6.5 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> shows a total flow of
4220 vpd in each direction during 1996. However, that flow would be exceeded in
2002 by the natural growth in baseline traffic. During the finite life of the
development, total flows would be similar to those likely to be experienced
within six years without the development.</P>
<P>6.6 <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.2">Figure 6.2</A> shows data similar to
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.1">Figure 6.1</A> for the Variant Case. The
Variant Case generates traffic flows which are not significantly different from
those of the Central Case. The changes result from the extended programme of
work in Phase 1 and the additional restoration work as a consequence of deeper
shafts.</P>
<P><B>A595(T) Trunk Road</B></P>
<P>6.7 Traffic travelling from the north to the Surface Site will use the
Egremont bypass and continue southwards on the A595(T) through the Blackbeck
roundabout and Calder Bridge traffic signal junction to the Longlands Farm
junction. Traffic from the south will use the A595(T) on the western side of the
village of Gosforth, passing through the junction with the B5344 and the
A595(T)/Boonwood Lane junction. All traffic will normally enter the Surface Site
at the Longlands Farm junction.</P>
<P>6.8 The highest combined traffic flows from the RCF development and
Boreholes are likely to occur during 1996. The maximum forecast two-way traffic
flow on the A595(T) north of the Longlands Farm junction in 1996 is 8440 vpd. At
the end of the development, the equivalent forecast, taking into account natural
traffic growth, is 9550 vpd. As the estimated capacity of the A595(T) in the
vicinity of the Longlands Farm junction is 12,000 vpd, the additional flow
produced by the generated traffic would still result in a significant reserve
capacity in terms of daily flow.</P>
<P><B>Blackbeck Roundabout</B></P>
<P>6.9 In the Environmental Statement it was noted that traffic queues occurred
during peak periods at Blackbeck roundabout. In the morning peak southbound
Sellafield traffic had been observed to queue on the A595(T) approaching the
roundabout.  Observations on many occasions in 1995 however showed a change to
the morning peak traffic conditions. Southbound traffic was observed to be
queuing on the Egremont bypass but, south of this, traffic moved freely on the
A595(T) up to the Blackbeck roundabout. In the morning peak there were no queues
on the A595(T) at the approach to Blackbeck roundabout. Nevertheless traffic
flows in the area are heavy in the peak period and unstable traffic flow
conditions prevail.</P>
<P>6.10 As a result of commuter traffic to and from the Sellafield Works, the
peak periods are particularly pronounced (<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.8">Figure
4.8</A> and <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.11">Figure 4.11</A>). Analysis of
these traffic flow distributions shows that the peak traffic flows are limited
to the hours ending at 08.00 hours and 17.00 hours. Either side of the peak
periods spare capacity exists which can accommodate the temporary traffic
increases resulting from the RCF construction.</P>
<P>6.11 The RCF workforce will include employment on a shift system with
typical shift change times of 06.00 hours, 14.00 hours and 22.00 hours.
Personnel arriving and leaving at these times will not add to the peak
conditions at Blackbeck roundabout.</P>
<P>6.12 The category of staff whose times of employment could impinge on the
periods of peak traffic flow at Blackbeck roundabout are day workers. The
distributions of shift and day workers during RCF construction are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table6.1">Table 6.1</A>.</P>
<P>6.13 The working hours of personnel at the development could be arranged to
take account of local traffic conditions to minimise the effects of the
development on peak period traffic if the need were demonstrated.</P>
<P><B>Calder Bridge Traffic Signals</B></P>
<P>6.14 The intersection of the Sellafield access road to the North Gate and
the A595(T) is controlled by traffic signals at Calder Bridge. Traffic counts
were undertaken at the junction in March 1993 and in April 1995. Observations
showed queues forming on the access road in the afternoon at the main employment
finish time. The queues observed  in 1995 were about half the length of those
observed in 1993. This reflects the reduction in employment levels of the
Sellafield Works and the reduction in traffic on the A595(T).</P>
<P>6.15 The capacity of traffic signals can be assessed by application of the
DOT standard  analysis program OSCADY (Optimised Signal Capacity and Delay).
OSCADY analyses have been undertaken with the traffic flows observed in 1993 and
1995 and with the highest flows forecast in the life of the RCF, i.e. in  1996.
The analysis shows that the operation of signals in 1995 had higher reserve
capacities than in 1993 due to the overall reduction in traffic flows. The
analysis for 1996 with the RCF construction  showed operation similar to that of
1993.</P>
<P>6.16 The OSCADY analysis is based on fixed time signals. However, the
installation at the Calder Bridge junction is vehicle actuated such that the
signal green times vary automatically to adjust to changing flow patterns and
has accommodated traffic flows which are higher than the forecasts which include
traffic generated by the RCF and boreholes. Therefore it is expected that the
generated traffic can be absorbed by automatic adjustment of the green times.
The observed reduction in 12 hour flow between 1993 and 1995 on the A595(T)
south of the junction, i.e. through Calder Bridge village, is about 500
vehicles, which is similar to the maximum forecast of daily generated traffic in
Site Establishment and Phase 1, see <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>.
</P>
<P><B>Longlands Farm Junction</B></P>
<P>6.17 Daily turning movements at the Longlands Farm junction are forecast as
shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>.  The changes in
traffic flow forecasts since the Environmental Statement have no effect on the
suitability of the form of junction selected for the Longlands Farm access i.e.
the ghost island junction shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.5">Figure 4.5</A>.</P>
<P>6.18 The selection of the junction form was based on consideration of daily
traffic flows. As a check on the capacity of the junction an analysis is made on
peak hourly conditions.  To identify peak hourly flows on the Longlands Farm
access road, reference is made to the traffic counts observed during the
Borehole works at the Appeal Site.</P>
<P>6.19 The Borehole works at the Longlands Farm site can be considered in two
phases:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>site preparation, when there were mostly HGVs bringing material to the site
 to construct the drilling platforms, and few cars; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>drilling and testing when there were few HGVs but more cars visiting the
site   - up to 250 per day.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>6.20 Traffic surveys were undertaken during both of these periods which give
measures of the traffic flow profile of cars and light vehicles and of HGVs at
the construction site through the day. These distributions can be considered as
indicative of the traffic patterns which could occur during RCF construction and
allow the daily traffic forecasts to be analysed in more detail.</P>
<P>6.21 The traffic surveys were undertaken on a number of days and summary
statistics are shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table6.2">Table 6.2</A>. From the
table it can be seen that, typically, the maximum percentage of the 24-hour car
flows that occur in the peak hour is 9% to 16% and for HGVs it is about 20%.
However, these two peaks do not necessarily coincide. For the combined traffic
flows, the peak hour is from 08.00 hours and has 13% to 16% of the daily
traffic.</P>
<P>6.22 For the purpose of analysis it is assumed that in the peak hour 20% of
the daily total of  both the HGV and cars/light vehicles enter and leave the
Surface Site. These percentages are applied to the peak daily traffic flow
forecast for the RCF/RCM/PRZ Boreholes and the RCF development; e.g. referring
to <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table5.7">Table 5.7</A> and
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.3">Figure 6.3</A>, the 20% factor is applied to
the flow of 301 vehicles per day in each direction in November 1996 to provide
the peak hourly flows.</P>
<P>6.23 The resulting peak hour flows for the month of busiest daily traffic in
each Phase of the RCF development are shown diagrammatically in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure6.4">Figure 6.4</A>.</P>
<P>6.24 The capacity of T-junctions is determined by the application of the DOT
standard  analysis program PICADY (Priority Intersection Capacity and Delay).</P>
<P>6.25 Using the estimated traffic flows and the geometric dimensions of the
Longlands Farm junction the PICADY analysis shows that the junction has ample
capacity. The programme shows that, theoretically, the highest number of
vehicles that may queue to turn right into the Surface Site from the A595(T)
north is less than one. Up to three HGVs can be readily accommodated in the
ghost island. </P>
<P><B>HGV Controls</B></P>
<P>6.26 A number of controls on the operation of HGVs will be imposed. HGVs
visiting the Surface Site will be under contract to Nirex to provide services or
deliver materials to the development and these controls will be clearly defined
in the contractual arrangement with Nirex. The controls will be as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>Normal access to the site from the A595(T) shall only be via the Longlands
Farm junction  and  access  road.  An  exception  to  this may be at the start
of Site Establishment when pipes and material to be laid in the western sections
of the Services Corridors may be more conveniently delivered via the
B5344/Calder Gate access road or the Sellafield Works;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>All vehicles shall be required to leave the site with clean tyres.
Wheelwashes shall be provided on-site in order that wheels may be cleaned before
vehicles leave the site;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>In the event that vehicles may be near their statutory axle weight limit a
weighbridge shall be provided on-site to verify compliance with the regulations.
This will ensure that no exceptional damage shall be caused to the local road
network;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>Vehicles carrying loose and dusty material to or from the site shall be
covered to minimise air pollution; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>The preferred route to the site from the M6 is via the A66(T) from Junction
40 at Penrith westwards to the junction of the A66(T)/A595 at Bridgefoot from
where it continues south along the A595(T) via Blackbeck roundabout to the
Longlands Farm junction. Contractors will be required to adhere to this route.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>6.27 Route direction signs and signs giving advance notice of the site and
turning traffic will be erected by Nirex to the requirement of the highway or
planning authority.</P>
<P><B>Draft Conditions</B></P>
<P>6.28 Cumbria County Council and Nirex have prepared a list of draft
conditions [COR/113]18  as agreed at the pre-Inquiry meeting held on 15 May
1995.</P>
<P>6.29 Draft conditions numbered 7, 8, 19, 20 and 21 relate to the use of
vehicles and highways. The controls described in paragraph 6.26 accord with
proposed conditions  8, 19, 20 and 21 which are acceptable to Nirex. Condition 7
relates to the hours of HGV movements. The hours specified in the draft
conditions are more restrictive than those required on the movement of HGVs
through Gosforth for borehole works in the Lake District National Park and are
considered to be inappropriate to the RCF development which is accessed directly
off the A595(T). The only periods in the life of the RCF development when HGV
movements may be significant are during Site Establishment and Restoration.
These operations will normally occur in the working day. In the event that
abnormal loads require traffic management to facilitate movement on the A595(T)
it would minimise delays to other road users if these  movements were made at
night. The condition on hours of operation of HGVs is therefore not necessary or
appropriate.</P>
<P><B> Traffic Management During Work on Boreholes Accessed Through Gosforth</B></P>
<P>6.30 Planning permission was granted to Nirex for Boreholes 8 and 9 in the
Lake District National Park following the Public Inquiry in 1992. Access to the
borehole sites was via Boonwood Lane and Gosforth respectively. The planning
permission was conditional upon traffic management and controls including
restrictions similar to those described above. It is pertinent to note that
Gosforth Parish Council were complimentary about the manner in which the
operations were carried out.</P>
<P>6.31 The sensitivity of the management of traffic associated with the
boreholes accessed through Gosforth was acknowledged at the meeting of Gosforth
Parish Council on 1 August 1994 when a parish councillor proposed that Nirex be
congratulated on the traffic control through the village [NRX/9/5]19:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;<I>He was impressed by the slow moving vehicles through the village,
other heavy goods vehicles .... could well learn from the example set by Nirex
and their contractors.</I>&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>Vehicle Parking</B></P>
<P>6.32 An adequate number of parking spaces is provided on the Surface Site
for employees' vehicles and HGVs. This aspect is covered in the proof of
evidence of <A HREF="../nrx1/nrx1.htm">Mr A J Smith</A> and is acknowledged in
Cumbria County Council's letter included in Appendix A1.</P>
<P>6.33 In addition to the provision of adequate vehicle parking spaces on site
there will be capacity for waiting on the  approach  to  the  security  gate,
which is approximately  0.25 km (0.15 miles)  from the Longlands Farm junction.
Therefore as there would be no reason for vehicles to park or wait in the
vicinity of the junction there will be no effects due to stationary vehicles on
the operation of the Longlands Farm junction or the A595(T).</P>
<P><B>Other Local Roads</B></P>
<P>6.34 The low volume of development generated traffic on other roads will
follow the existing local traffic patterns and its effect will not be
discernible within the existing traffic flow.</P>
<P><B>Significance of Effects on Local Road Network</B></P>
<P>6.35 Planning Policy Guidance 13: Transport [GOV/105]20 was issued by the
Departments of the Environment and Transport in March 1994. Annex B, Planning
Application Procedures, Paragraph 4 refers to the guideline that the DOT would
regard an increase in traffic using any link in a junction in the order of 5% as
material in most cases. The combined Boreholes and RCF development generated
traffic could impose an average increase of approximately 550 vpd, two way, in
the first five years of development construction. This represents an increase of
7% on the A595(T) traffic in the vicinity of the Appeal Site. Thereafter,
development generated traffic will continue at a lower level, which represents
an increase on the A595(T) in the order of  4% of the AADT, taking into account
natural traffic growth.</P>
<P><B>Road Construction</B></P>
<P>6.36 The evaluation of traffic flows confirms that there will be no
requirements for the construction of new off-site transport infrastructure in
association with the development. There will therefore be no effects due to new
road construction.</P>
<P><B>Road Safety</B></P>
<P>6.37 The nature and characteristics of the traffic generated by the
development will be similar to those of traffic currently on the A595(T) and
other local roads. The accident rates shown in <A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Figure4.14">Figure
4.14</A> would not be expected to vary as a result of the development.</P>
<P>6.38 Where the generated traffic turns into the Surface Site, the Longlands
Farm junction on the A595(T) provides facilities to current design and safety
standards. Safety features at the junction include a realignment of the major
road through the junction, good visibility for turning traffic and a segregated
right-turn late on the A595(T) to protect right turning vehicles and to minimise
delay to through traffic. Traffic signs at the junction are in accordance with
DOT requirements.</P>
<P><B>Emergency Access</B></P>
<P>6.39 Access to the Surface Site for construction and operational purposes
will be from the Longlands Farm junction, except as noted in paragraph 6.26(a).
If as a result of an accident or incident, access to the Surface Site via the
Longlands Farm junction was not possible then alternative access for emergency
vehicles could be provided via Sides Lane.</P>
<P><B>Summary of Effects on the Local Road Network</B></P>
<P>6.40 Development of the RCF would potentially have an effect on the access
road to the Surface Site, the A595(T) and the junctions on the A595 (T).</P>
<P>6.41 Estimates of the capacity of the A595(T) and the highest forecast
traffic flows during all phases of the RCF development are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table6.3">Table 6.3</A>. This shows that the A595(T) can
accommodate the Boreholes and RCF generated traffic in addition to natural
traffic growth as predicted by the DOT. Junctions on the A595(T) which have been
examined in detail are identified below together with commentary on their
operation.</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD><B>Junction:</B></TD>
<TD><B>Commentary</B></TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Blackbeck roundabout</TD>
<TD>The junction is heavily used in the peak period but recent experience shows
that spare capacity exists at that time.
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Calder Bridge traffic signals</TD>
<TD>Additional traffic may result in an automatic adjustment to the timing of
the signals
</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>Longlands Farm access road</TD>
<TD>New junction with adequate spare capacity
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>6.42 The development has a finite life span and the analyses contained in
this proof relate to the peak conditions which will occur for a limited time
only. At other times traffic flows are significantly lower. The forecast traffic
levels will, in any event,  be exceeded in a few years by anticipated natural
traffic growth.</P>
<P>6.43 No new roads or improvement to the existing roads are required as a
consequence of the development.</P>
<P><A NAME="Consultations"></A><B>7. CONSULTATIONS </B></P>
<P><B> Statutory Consultees' Comments on the Environmental Statement</B></P>
<P>7.1 The traffic and highway aspects of the RCF proposals as described in the
Environmental Statement have been the subject of consultation with the statutory
consultees through circulation of the Statement by Cumbria County Council.</P>
<P>7.2 The observations by statutory consultees on the Environmental Statement
are mainly recorded in the Cumbria County Council's report by its Director of
Economy and Environment [COR/104]5. Observations by Copeland Borough Council are
recorded in the report to their Council of 1 November 1994.
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table7.1">Table 7.1</A> summarises the observations and
notes the Nirex positions.</P>
<P>7.3 It is to be noted that the Highways Agency as highway authority for the
A595(T) trunk road and the police have no objections to the development. Cumbria
County Council's Highways and Engineering Division has no objection from a
highway point of view with regard to trunk road interests. Their letters of
response to the statutory consultation are enclosed at Appendix A1 to this proof
of evidence.</P>
<P>7.4 In general, observations on traffic and highway issues by most
consultees would appear to have taken little cognisance of two key points
regarding the generation of traffic by the RCF proposals:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>the changes in traffic flows are low in relative terms and within the
volumes of traffic which are likely to occur on the roads in a few years' time
due to natural traffic growth; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>the development to which the application relates is temporary only.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>7.5 Regarding Cumbria County Council's observations recorded in their letter
contained in Appendix A1, traffic signs are discussed above at paragraph 6.27,
the traffic signals at Calder Bridge are discussed in paragraph 6.14 and Nirex
confirms that Cumbria County Council's requirements regarding bridleways will be
met.</P>
<P><B>Representations</B></P>
<P>7.6 In addition to the responses from statutory consultees, many
representations on the planning application have been made. These have been
examined and those with a reference to traffic or highways have been reviewed.
The main points of their representations are shown in
<A HREF="nrx9fig.htm#Table7.2">Table 7.2</A>. Many are supportive of the
concept of a DWR at Sellafield, mainly due to the increased transport required
to alternative sites; predominantly, the comments do not relate directly to the
RCF. Comments against the development focus on the limitations on the road and
rail network and potential environmental effects. These concerns have been
addressed in the proof.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>8. CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P>8.1 The conclusions to the assessment of the traffic impacts remain as
identified in the Environmental Statement, that is:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(a)</TD>
<TD>The  development  generated traffic effects will be restricted to road
users in the vicinity of the Appeal Site during the finite life of the
development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(b)</TD>
<TD>The  Highways  Agency  is  satisfied  that  the A595(T) and the Longlands
Farm junction have capacity to accept the traffic that will be generated by the
development The Highways Agency does not require any new road construction as a
consequence of the RCF development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(c)</TD>
<TD>The  effects  of  the  development  generated  traffic on the A595(T) and
other roads are assessed as being not significant;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(d)</TD>
<TD>The increase in traffic flows as a result of the development will be within
the increase that can be expected on the A595(T) due to natural growth in
traffic levels over the planned life of the development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(e)</TD>
<TD>There  will  be  no significant effects on road safety arising from the
development;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(f)</TD>
<TD>As there will be no new road construction required to facilitate
construction of  the RCF, there will therefore be no effects from new road
construction; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(g)</TD>
<TD>The incidence of  pedestrians and cyclists on the A595(T) is low and the
small increase in traffic due to the development is judged to have an
insignificant effect on their use of the road.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>8.2 Additionally, since production of the Environmental Statement, it is now
observed that traffic flows on the A595(T), as recorded at the DOT's ATC site,
have reduced significantly over the last few years, to an extent greater than
the traffic to be generated from the RCF.</P>
<P>8.3 In the light of the surveys, analyses, evaluations and consultation
responses contained in this Proof of Evidence I believe that planning permission
should not be withheld on traffic or highway grounds.</P>
