<P><B>LETTER 2</B><BR></P>
<P><FONT SIZE="+2"><B>CUMBRIA CONSTABULARY</B></FONT></P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT"><BR>Chief Constable: A G Elliott QPM<BR><BR>Police
Headquarters<BR>Carleton Hall<BR>PENRITH<BR>Cumbria  CA10 2AU</P>
<P>The Director of Economy &amp; Environment<BR>Cumbria County Council<BR>Planning
Division<BR>County Offices<BR>KENDAL     LA9 4RQ<BR><BR></P>
<P>FAO - Mr J Hetherington<BR>Environmental Planning Manager</P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT">7 September 1994<BR><BR></P>
<P>Dear Sir</P>
<P>CONSULTATION ON PLANNING APPLICATION - NIREX FACILITY, GOSFORTH</P>
<P>I refer to your correspondence dated 8 August 1994 relating to the above
application for the proposed Nirex Development on land adjacent to Longlands
Farm, Gosforth, Whitehaven.</P>
<P>I can confirm that Nirex had indeed forwarded a copy of the planning
application and environmental- statement documents relating to this application
to Cumbria Police in advance of your correspondence.  Officers from the Traffic
Management Department had previously been involved in consultation on proposed
access road to the development and junction arrangements to the A595 trunk road.
 These arrangements are satisfactory.</P>
<P>Police, therefore, have no objections to the application.</P>
<P>Yours faithfully</P>
<P>Chief Inspector</P>
<P><BR><BR><BR><BR></P>
<P><B>LETTER 3</B></P>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT">Cumbria County Council<BR>Highways and Engineering<BR>Viaduct
Estate<BR>Carlisile</P>
<P>19 September 1994</P>
<P>Your Ref:  4/94/9011<BR>Our Ref:  0552/0403/DF/HJR<BR>Enquiries to:  Mr D
Ferguson Ext 329<BR>Minicom:  (0028) 812381<BR>Fax:   (0900) 825515<BR>Reply
to:  Cockermouth</P>
<P>Department of Transport<BR>Wellbar House<BR>Gallowgate<BR>Newcastle Upon
Tyne</P>
<P>Dear Sir</P>
<P>WESTERN AREA<BR>TRUNK ROAD NO A595 AND UNCLASSIFIED ROAD NO 4465<BR>PROPOSED
ROCK CHARACTERISATION FACILITY ON LAND<BR>ADJACENT TO LONGLANDS FARM, GOSFORTH<BR>FOR
UNITED KINGDOM NIREX LIMITED</P>
<P>I refer to the above consultation which I received on 15 August 1994 and
would recommend that there are no objections to the proposal from a highway
point of view with regard to Trunk Road interests.</P>
<P>Access to the site will be by way of the existing approved means recently
constructed to the Trunk Road as the main access to the overall borehole complex
at Longlands Farm which was given conditional planning permission in May 1993. 
It is noted from the submitted details that adequate parking is to be provided
on site to cater for staff and Contractors and there is ample room within the
curtilage of the site on which to provide additional parking should the need
arise.</P>
<P>Authorised advance works warning signs should be provided by the applicant
and sited to the satisfaction of the Highway Authority and Local Planning
Authority.  The signs should remain in position for the duration of the works.</P>
<P>Whilst it is considered that the traffic associated with the proposed
development can be accommodated on the adjacent Trunk Road there are concerns as
to the likely effect of the additional traffic at Calder Bridge traffic lights,
which are already working to capacity at peak traffic times.  No doubt you will
wish to seek clarification and assurance from the applicant in this respect.</P>
<P>Public Rights of Way</P>
<P>It is noted from the submitted details that there will be temporary
disruption to some public rights of way which cross the site during the
establishment of the Services Corridors, but they will be restored to their
existing condition immediately following completion of the works ie within a
maximum timescale of 7 months.</P>
<P>My principal concern is that the public user is not obstructed.  Therefore,
where any proposed works encroach onto a path alignment so that passage is
obstructed then a safe alternative route must be provided for the duration of
the works.  The alternative route must be no less compatible for the public to
use.  Where any re-routing is necessary then a temporary closure of the path
must be obtained by application to the County Council's Area Manager.  Such
application must be made no less than 3 months prior to the programmed start of
the works.</P>
<P>Proposed effluent pumping station.</P>
<P>The site adjoins the Unclassified Road from Seascale to Calder Gate and the
proposal involves the provision of a service lay-by adjoining the carriageway of
the highway.</P>
<P>There are no objections, in principle, to the details indicated on the
layout plan (Drawing no 008017) subject to the following amendments and
conditions which I recommend should be included on any Notice of Consent which
may be issued.</P>
<OL>
<LI> The proposed layby shall be constructed and drained to the satisfaction of
the Local  Planning Authority.
</LI>
<LI> The existing footway/cycleway shall be continued around the rear of the
layby to the same width and construction standards.
</LI>
<LI> An amended drawing incorporating the requirement of Condition No 2 shall
be submitted to, and approved by, the Local Planning Authority before any works
commence on site.
</LI></OL>
<P>As the layby will be within highway limits it can not be reserved
specifically for visiting maintenance vehicles to the pumping station.  Any user
of the highway will be entitled to use it.  Further, if the layby is occupied by
a vehicle it will be necessary for a cyclist or pedestrian to use the adjoining
carriageway, hence the reason for Condition No 2 above.</P>
<P>With regard to Conditions 1 and 3, the applicant should seek the advice of
Mr Sam Meteer, the Local Maintenance Engineer on Cleator Moor 815780 as all
works within, and immediately adjoining, the highway will need to be carried out
to his satisfaction.</P>
<P>I would point out that the scale of the plan is indicated as 1:100 and this
is incorrect.  The correct scale is 1:200.</P>
<P>Yours faithfully</P>
<P>D Ferguson</P>
<P>Highway Control Officer West</P>
<P></P>
