<P><B>DONALD IAIN MACKAY will say:</B></P>
<P><A NAME="PersonalDetails"></A><B>1. PERSONAL DETAILS</B></P>
<P>1.1 I am a founding director and Chairman of <B>P</B><I>ieda</I> plc,
Planning, Industrial and Economic Development Advisers, and Chairman of Scottish
Enterprise. I am a Director of Grampian Holdings and an Honorary Professor of
Heriot Watt University, Edinburgh. I am a Governor of the National Institute of
Economic and Social Research, a member of the Scottish Economic Council and have
acted as economic consultant to the Secretary of State for Scotland since 1971.
I was previously Professor of Political Economy at Aberdeen University and
Professor of Economics at Heriot Watt University. I have served as an
Independent member of the Sea Fish Industry Authority and the South of Scotland
Electricity Board. As an applied economist, I have over 30 years experience in
directing major consultancy and academic assignments and have published widely
on many aspects of labour market and regional economics.</P>
<P>1.2 I hold the degree of Master of Arts in Economics from the University of
Aberdeen. I hold honorary degrees from the University of Aberdeen and the
University of Stirling, and am a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh.</P>
<P>1.3 I have had particular experience of assessing the economic impact of
existing, new or declining activities. Over 1972-1975 I was an adviser to The
Scottish Office and HM Treasury on the economic impact of North Sea oil and gas.
Subsequently, I have studied the employment and economic impact of industries
(including the car assembly and Scotch whisky industries), proposed new
activities (including Wytch Farm; commercial ship repairing in Gibraltar; the
redevelopment of the Suez Canal Region and Terminal 5 at Heathrow) and the
rundown or closure of existing activities (including steel plants, the Dounreay
nuclear power station and the reduction in construction employment following the
completion of the Thermal Oxide Reprocessing Plant, 'THORP'). Since 1987 I have
been responsible for advising United Kingdom Nirex Limited, 'Nirex', on the
potential economic impact of its proposed activities. I have a long-term
interest in regional and local economic development reflected in my present
appointments as an economic consultant to the Secretary of State for Scotland
and Chairman of Scottish Enterprise.</P>
<P><A NAME="Summary"></A><B>2. SUMMARY</B></P>
<P><B>Scope of Evidence</B></P>
<P>2.1 This proof presents a summary of the likely socio-economic impact of the
proposed Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF). I shall show that the local
economic impact of the construction and operation of the RCF is beneficial.
These activities will create additional employment and the area will benefit
through employment of local residents, additional local expenditure by persons
presently resident outside the area who obtain RCF employment, the sourcing of
inputs from local businesses and the 'multiplier' impact of these activities. I
will argue that the nuclear industry has provided high wage and salary
employment and that there is no evidence that it has had a net adverse impact on
other activities. In short, the RCF will provide economic gain which will not be
offset by economic losses in other sectors.</P>
<P><B>The Local Economy</B></P>
<P>2.2 The Study Area is defined to be the two local authority districts of
Allerdale and Copeland. An analysis of employment in the Study Area shows that
nuclear fuel production, construction, hotels/catering (which is partly
dependent on tourism), and agriculture are key economic sectors within the Study
Area.</P>
<P>Nuclear Fuel Production</P>
<P>2.3 The nuclear industry is the biggest single local employer with some
8,760 'permanent' employees at Sellafield in March 1994. Directly, it accounts
for almost 13% of all employees in employment in the Study Area. BNFL employment
peaked in 1993 (at 8,370) and has fallen to 7,680 in 1995. However, BNFL has
provided considerable stability of employment in the local area, particularly
when viewed against the rapid and substantial changes in employment witnessed in
many other sectors in West Cumbria and in the rest of the UK.</P>
<P>2.4 Sellafield also offers 'high wage' employment. As at April 1994, average
weekly earnings for all BNFL employees were 33% above average male earnings for
Cumbria. Such stable and high wage/salaried employment brings substantial
additional benefits to the community.</P>
<P>Construction</P>
<P>2.5 The completion of the THORP project at the Sellafield Works has been
reflected in a rundown in construction employment. BNFL's contractual workforce
peaked in 1991 at 7,330 but has been cut-back sharply since then to 1,600 in
1994, a loss of 5,730 jobs.</P>
<P>Tourism</P>
<P>2.6 The Impact of Tourism - Cumbria 1992, [COR/408]<SUP>7</SUP> estimates
that there were 6,190 jobs directly dependent on tourism in Allerdale and
Copeland. These jobs constitute an important sector of activity which benefits
accommodation providers, catering outlets, visitor attractions and retailers.</P>
<P>Agriculture, Forestry and Fishing</P>
<P>2.7 In 1991, some 3,200 residents of Allerdale and Copeland were employed in
agriculture, forestry and fishing, with approximately half of these persons
self-employed.</P>
<P>Unemployment</P>
<P>2.8 Data on the unemployment rates are available for the Travel to Work
Areas (TTWAs) of Workington and Whitehaven. Throughout the period from 1983,
male and female unemployment rates for Whitehaven have been below those for
Workington, reflecting the location of Sellafield within the Whitehaven TTWA.
Indeed, over the period up to 1993, the Whitehaven male unemployment rate was
below the GB average.</P>
<P>2.9 It would be expected that the reduction in construction employment at
Sellafield from 1991, and the accompanying UK recession of 1990-92, would have a
substantial, adverse impact on employment in the Whitehaven TTWA. This is shown
by the sharp rise in male unemployment from 1992 and the deterioration in the
unemployment rate relative to the national average, particularly for males in
the Whitehaven TTWA.</P>
<P>Future Prospects</P>
<P>2.10 As in the UK as a whole, manufacturing employment in West Cumbria has
been in decline and is unlikely to provide substantially increased employment in
the future. Employment in agriculture has been declining over a long period and
employment opportunities are limited as a consequence of restricted market
opportunities, increasing productivity and the reform of the Common Agriculture
Policy.</P>
<P>2.11 The Sellafield Works has been the most important local employer because
of the level of employment it has provided and because these jobs have offered
relatively high wage and salary levels. Therefore, Sellafield will remain an
important employer in the future, as employment prospects in some important
sectors of the local economy are poor, for reasons quite unconnected with
Sellafield itself. That is, declining employment in agriculture and
manufacturing is a feature of most modern industrial societies and is not
specific to West Cumbria.</P>
<P><B>RCF Employment</B></P>
<P>2.12 The assessment of employment of the RCF should be considered against a
background of some reduction in BNFL direct employment and a large reduction in
contractor employment at Sellafield.</P>
<P>Direct Employment</P>
<P>2.13 Direct employment comprises those persons employed at the development
who would receive wages and salaries. For the period 1996-2008 inclusive, Nirex
estimate their direct labour requirement to be 1,261 person years. Over the
period, the RCF's direct labour requirements will be an annual average of 97,
with a peak requirement of 185 person years in 1999. Both these figures are
substantially below the employment losses in BNFL direct and contractor
employment since 1991.</P>
<P>Indirect/Induced Employment</P>
<P>2.14 It is not possible in advance of a development to be certain as to the
number of indirect and induced jobs which would be associated with any level of
direct employment. However, it is possible to estimate the likely number of
indirect/induced jobs based on the employment multipliers calculated by studies
of other developments.</P>
<P>2.15 Using a multiplier of 1.34 yields an estimate of indirect/induced
employment of 429 person years over the period 1996-2008 inclusive. Hence, total
person-years of employment (direct, indirect and induced) are estimated at
1,690.</P>
<P>Employee Relations Policy</P>
<P>2.16 While the employment created by the development will be of benefit to
the economy of West Cumbria, the project will require an input from persons with
specialist skills as well as technical and scientific expertise which may not be
available in the local labour market. The mix of local and non-local
requirements cannot be determined precisely at this time, but an important
determinant will be the employment policy framework established by Nirex.
Nirex's &quot;Model Code of Employees Relations&quot; is intended to apply to
all construction contracts. These conditions require contractors, where
practicable, to recruit local labour and to source inputs of goods and services
locally.</P>
<P>Local Recruitment</P>
<P>2.17 The extent to which direct employment will be filled through local
recruitment cannot be determined with certainty. It is probable that the
percentage of local recruitment will vary over the life-time of the RCF.</P>
<P>The extent of local employment in the contractor labour force is expected to
be higher in the site establishment activities. Shaft sinking, gallery
construction and the scientific and technical programme require specialised
skills, but the extent of local recruitment can be maximised by early
identification of need and the adoption of suitable training and recruitment
policies.</P>
<P>2.18 Even at the anticipated maximum level of local recruitment, the number
of jobs generated by the RCF would not be large as compared with the numbers
presently employed at Sellafield or compared with the number of contractor jobs
lost since the completion of THORP. Such levels of local recruitment could be
met comfortably by the local labour market.</P>
<P><B>Public Services</B></P>
<P>2.19 It is that element of the RCF's direct labour force recruited from
outside the area, and who would take up residence within the area, which would
constitute the additional demand on local public services. Even during the peak
period and assuming a high percentage of external recruitment, the in-migration
involved would not constitute a significant additional demand for local public
services.</P>
<P>2.20 In reaching this conclusion, it is important to remember that the West
Cumbrian labour market was able to adjust to a substantial construction
workforce during the construction of THORP when on-site construction employment
was over 7,000 persons.</P>
<P><B>Impact</B></P>
<P>2.21 The available evidence indicates that the nuclear facilities at
Sellafield have had a significant positive impact on local economic activity.
However, it has been argued that the existence of Sellafield may have attendant
disadvantages. These concerns are not new, but no evidence has been provided to
substantiate their importance. I consider the issues in the remainder of this
section.</P>
<P>Dependency and Wage Costs</P>
<P>2.22 The Windscale Inquiry [NRX/10/4]<SUP>15</SUP> considered the argument
that West Cumbria had historically been too dependent on a small number of
dominant employers and that THORP would increase the local dominance of the
nuclear industry. The Inspector concluded that there was no evidence that this
was the case and the experience since THORP supports his conclusion regarding
dependency.</P>
<P>2.23 On wage costs there is little direct evidence on way or another.
However, it is difficult to attach much weight to an argument that a development
should be resisted because it offers favourable conditions of employment. The
process of economic development is intended to achieve this very goal.</P>
<P>The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local Development</P>
<P>2.24 I consider the issue of whether the nuclear industry at Sellafield
might have an adverse impact on other types of activity by reference to a study
based on a survey of companies, development agencies and property agents in the
vicinity of Sellafield and a survey of development agencies in other parts of
the country with major nuclear facilities [COR/402]<SUP>19</SUP>.</P>
<P>2.25 The major locational concerns reported by the companies surveyed
related to the area's poor transport infrastructure, its peripherality and
higher costs relating from both these factors. Indeed, the study [COR/402]<SUP>29</SUP>
concludes that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;...while there is a level of concern among some companies that the
presence of Sellafield and the possible DRP (Deep Repository Project)
development, has or may have a blighting effect, the weight of evidence does not
indicate that this effect is widespread or that it is a major factor inhibiting
company development.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.26 As with the companies, the development agencies consider the poor
transport infrastructure and perceived remoteness to be the major constraints to
economic development.</P>
<P>2.27 The general view of estate agents was that in-migration resulting from
Sellafield has had a favourable impact on residential property values in West
Cumbria and that any negative impact due to the existing and future nuclear
activities at Sellafield would be localised and limited in duration.</P>
<P>Blight and Nuclear Facilities</P>
<P>2.28 There is quite a substantial body of literature on the issue of adverse
impacts falling into two main categories - evidence relating to actual behaviour
and evidence relating to perceptions or intended behaviour.</P>
<P>2.29 A literature review based on actual behaviour suggests that the net
impact of nuclear facilities is favourable. As regards their impact on other
sectors/activities the available literature provides relatively little evidence
on mobility and output, but what there is does not support a contention that
there is a net adverse impact. The evidence is stronger for property values,
tourism and investment and is to the effect that the net impact of nuclear
facilities is either neutral or beneficial. [COR/409]<SUP>20</SUP></P>
<P>2.30 There is extensive literature relating to perceptions or intended
behaviour which suggests that nuclear facilities could have a blighting impact
on local economic activity. However, it is not possible to use this to
demonstrate that an adverse impact has occurred from the construction and
operation of nuclear facilities.</P>
<P>2.31 Three studies reviewed perceptions which relate specifically to
Sellafield and local residents. While each of these studies provide an
interesting perspective and demonstrate there are real concerns to be addressed,
none provide evidence of the extent to which perceptions may result in behaviour
which impacts on local economic development.</P>
<P>2.32 There are therefore good grounds for the Department of Environment
[GOV/306]<SUP>38</SUP> view that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;perceptions of risks that cannot be substantiated and which cannot
be demonstrated to have clear land-use implications, are not material to
planning decisions&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Foreign Direct Investment and Residential Property Values</P>
<P>2.33 A 1995 study [NRX/10/7]<SUP>21</SUP> found no evidence to suggest that
the difficulty in attracting foreign direct investment projects to Cumbria
reflects the presence of the nuclear facilities at Sellafield. On the contrary,
potential inward investors regarded other factors as decisive. These factors
include the higher incentives available in other parts of the North West and
Northern Regions and the disadvantages experienced by Cumbria in respect of
access to suppliers and markets, skills availability and unversity links.</P>
<P>2.34 Data provided by the Halifax Building Society on residential property
values, indicate that there is no statistically significant difference between
the immediate, intermediate and outer areas around Sellafield in average
residential property values by house type. This suggests that if any blighting
impact exists in the immediate area, it must be highly localised or offset by
the beneficial economic impact of the employment associated with Sellafield.</P>
<P>2.35 With regard to inward investment a study in 1994 [COR/406]<SUP>41</SUP>
concluded that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;...Sellafield is not a significant deterrent to inward investment
in West Cumbria, and with the proper infrastructure for the transfer or
exploitation of its technologies, could be turned into a considerable asset&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>2.36 On tourism, the same study [COR/406]<SUP>42</SUP> commented:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The majority of respondents were aware of the Sellafield site and
the Visitors Centre which was perceived to be one of the major attractions
within the area. Our sample survey revealed that the vast majority of persons
are no less likely to visit West Cumbria because of the presence of BNFL at
Sellafield, indeed some 6% of respondents were more likely to visit the area to
see the heavily promoted Sellafield Visitors Centre&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory and Dounreay</P>
<P>2.37 The Aspo hard rock laboratory, located close to Oskarshamn nuclear
power station offers close parallels to the proposed RCF. The power station is
also the site for the interim storage facility for spent fuel (CLAB).</P>
<P>2.38 Discussions have been held with a number of key personnel in the Aspo
area and all respondents were of the view that the impact of the nuclear
facilities has been positive and significant. Initially, the power station had
attracted some local opposition , but it is now seen as an important element in
the local economy. Other benefits identified were an improved local
infrastructure, a favourable impact on the educational standards achieved by
local schools and the enhanced scientific and technical base provided by Aspo as
a 'Centre of Excellence'.</P>
<P>2.39 The report on the Dounreay European Demonstration Reprocessing Plant
(EDRP) Public Inquiry (1987) concluded <I>&quot;there is no evidence to support
a general assertion that Dounreay has deterred other economic activity in
Caithness&quot;.</I></P>
<P><B>Conclusions</B></P>
<P>2.40 In my opinion, Sellafield has introduced an important source of high
wage and salary employment to an area with restricted opportunities for
alternative economic development. The RCF would build on this base, offering
additional local employment opportunities. Such 'dependence' on the nuclear
industry might be undesirable if it prevented new activities from developing or
by causing existing activities to relocate from the area. There is no evidence
to suggest that this occurs.</P>
<P>2.41 I would therefore conclude that the nuclear industry at Sellafield has
resulted in a significant addition to local income and employment over the level
which would exist in its absence and that the impact of the RCF would also be
beneficial.</P>
<P><A NAME="ScopeOfEvidence"></A><B>3. SCOPE OF EVIDENCE</B></P>
<P><B>Purpose of Evidence</B></P>
<P>3.1 The purpose of this proof is to consider the likely socio- economic
impact of the proposed Rock Characterisation Facility (RCF), which I have
treated, for these purposes, as most closely analogous to a mining activity
whose operating function is to provide facilities for scientific research and
which would create a Centre of Excellence. Associated with it are scientific
personnel whose activities will be directed to investigating the site geological
conditions.</P>
<P>3.2 I shall show that the local economic impact of the construction and
operation of the RCF is beneficial. These activities will create additional
employment and the area will benefit through employment of local residents,
additional local expenditure by persons presently resident outside the area who
obtain RCF employment, the sourcing of inputs from local businesses and the
'multiplier' impacts of these activities. This proof assesses these benefits in
terms of the direct, indirect and induced employment which will be created. I
will argue that the nuclear industry has provided high wage and salary
employment and that there is no evidence that it has had a net adverse impact on
other activities. In short, the RCF will provide economic gain which will not be
offset by economic losses in other sectors.</P>
<P><B>Structure of Evidence</B></P>
<P>3.3 My proof falls into four main parts. First, in Section 4, I describe the
main features of the local economy and, in particular, the significance of the
Sellafield Works (referred to in this document as 'Sellafield') as the dominant
local employment site within the local economy.</P>
<P>3.4 Second, I consider the economic impact of the RCF, viewed as a mining
and scientific facility . Hence, in Section 5, I analyse the direct, indirect
and induced employment likely to be associated with the RCF; and in Section 6, I
consider the number of persons who might be expected to be recruited from
outside the area to work at the RCF and the scale of this in relation to the
available accommodation and existing public services.</P>
<P>3.5 Third, I consider, in Section 7, the available evidence on whether the
nuclear industry has had or could be expected to have an adverse effect on other
sectors which could offset the beneficial employment impact of the nuclear
industry at Sellafield and the RCF.</P>
<P>3.6 Fourth, in Section 8, I provide a summary of my main conclusions.</P>
<P><B>Nature of Evidence</B></P>
<P>3.7 In my evidence I will seek to establish the following:</P>
<UL>
<LI> British Nuclear Fuels plc ('BNFL') and, to a lesser extent, the United
Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority ('UKAEA'), are the principal local employers and
this employment is co-located at Sellafield; they provide full-time employment
and comparatively high wage and salary levels for a substantial number of
persons; the bulk of the labour force at Sellafield comprises male, full-time
employees;
</LI>
<LI> The construction and operation of the RCF would occur in a period after
the completion of THORP and the consequent reduction in construction employment;
</LI>
<LI> The employment opportunities associated with the RCF are small relative to
this run-down; some employment opportunities will be filled by local residents
and others by persons from outside the area, but both the impact on the local
labour market and on public services can be accommodated comfortably;
</LI>
<LI> The existence of the nuclear facilities at Sellafield, the waste disposal
facility at Drigg and the site characterisation programme for the RCF have not
had an adverse impact on other aspects of the local economy and there is no
reason to suppose this would change if the RCF were constructed;
</LI>
<LI> In particular, the nuclear industry has not had a net adverse impact on
residential property values, on inward investment, or on tourism; indeed, the
importance of the nuclear industry may have attracted some inward investment and
the Sellafield Visitor Centre, opened in June 1988, has become the major visitor
centre in West Cumbria, and in 1994 attracted 90,000 visitors; and
</LI>
<LI> Consequently, it is my view that the overall economic impact of the
nuclear industry at Sellafield has been substantially positive and the
construction and operation of the RCF would create additional local employment
opportunities.
</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="LocalEconomy"></A><B>4. THE LOCAL ECONOMY</B></P>
<P>4.1 In this section of my evidence I describe the main features of the local
economy and the importance of Sellafield within that economy. This evidence is
based on work undertaken by <B>P</B><I>ieda</I> and presented, in the RCF
Environmental Statement [COR/101]<SUP>1</SUP>. It is a necessary background to
considering the likely impact of the RCF.</P>
<P><B>Study Area</B></P>
<P>4.2 The relevant Study Area is defined by the travel to work distance within
which the locally resident labour force could be expected to be recruited. As
the RCF would be a new development, the Study Area was established by reference
to data on the place of residence of the workforce employed by BNFL at
Sellafield. In 1988, almost 90% of BNFL's direct workforce were resident in West
Cumbria (ie. the two local authority districts of Allerdale and Copeland) which
is taken as the relevant Study Area.</P>
<P><B>The Local Economy</B></P>
<P>4.3 The population of the Study Area in 1991 was 164,200 - this representing
a fall of almost 1% from the 1981 level. The working population, which is taken
as the male population aged 16-64 years and the female population aged 16-59
years, was 102,300 in 1991.</P>
<P>4.4 A total of 68,800 persons were in employment in the Study Area in 1991.
This figure includes both employees in employment and the self-employed. A
breakdown of employees by sector is shown in Table 4.1 for employees in
employment only. The table also shows the relative importance of primary
industries and construction in the Study Area, which is largely a result of
activity at Sellafield.</P>
<P><A NAME="Table4.1"></A></P>
