<P><B>Nuclear Fuel Production</B></P>
<P>4.6 The nuclear industry is the biggest single employer in the Study Area.
In March 1994, BNFL employed 8,060 persons directly, with a further 1,600
employed on site by contractors (see <A HREF="#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A>). The
direct employees are involved in the reprocessing of spent nuclear fuel,
management of the production of nuclear energy and its associated waste streams.
In addition to BNFL employment shown in <A HREF="#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A>, a
further some 700 persons were employed by UKAEA Technology at Sellafield in
March 1994, giving a total of some 8,760 'permanent' employees at Sellafield.
The importance of the nuclear industry in the Study Area is seen by the fact
that it accounts directly for almost 13% of all employees in employment.</P>
<P>4.7 Recent trends in BNFL employment at Sellafield are shown in
<A HREF="#Table4.3">Table 4.3</A>. BNFL employment peaked in 1993 (at 8,370)
and has fallen to 1995 (7,680). Nonetheless, present employment is still
substantially above the level of the early 1980s. BNFL has provided considerable
stability of employment in the local area, particularly when viewed against the
rapid and substantial changes in employment witnessed in many other sectors in
West Cumbria and in the rest of the UK.</P>
