<P>4.9 Over 1981-91 only 6 SIC Classes within the economic base showed an
increase in employment in West Cumbria and the largest increase in employment
(in absolute terms) was in nuclear fuel production. There were substantial
reductions in employment in many 'basic' industries, including the primary
sectors of agriculture &amp; horticulture and forestry, and most manufacturing
sectors. The only SIC Classes outside nuclear fuel production to show an
increase in employment were 24, 32, 34, 46 and 48. All the other Classes
contracted and in a number the fall in employment was substantial in the context
of the local economy. Overall, manufacturing employment fell from 18,056 in 1981
to 13,680 in 1991, (a fall of 24%) and employees in employment in the primary
sectors fell from 1,877 to 1,605 (a fall of 14.5%). Over the same period,
employment in nuclear fuel production increased from 6,278 to 7,707 (an increase
of 22.8%).</P>
<P>4.10 Sellafield also offers 'high wage' employment. As at April 1994,
full-time male and female average weekly all-industry earnings (excluding
overtime) in Cumbria were &#163;311.20 and &#163;220.80 respectively,
[NRX/10/1](4). Average weekly earnings (excluding overtime) for all BNFL
employees in the same period were &#163;413.70, 33% above average male earnings
for Cumbria. Such stable and high wage/salaried employment brings substantial
additional benefits to the community, a conclusion supported by the Swedish
experience (see 7.68 et seq).</P>
<P>4.11 Information on the contractor labour force is more dated but, at March
1990, average weekly earnings (including overtime and bonuses) on the Sellafield
construction site were &#163;320 for skilled employees and &#163;264 for
semi-skilled and unskilled employees 'Sellafield Redundancies: Research into
Labour Market Effects [NRX/10/2](5). The April 1990 New Earnings Survey shows
that average gross weekly earnings (including overtime and bonuses) for males in
Cumbria were &#163;276.70 and, for females, &#163;148.7 [NRX/10/3](6).</P>
<P>4.12 The scale of operations is illustrated by the following data. In
1993/1994 the BNFL wage and salary bill for Sellafield was &#163;179 million and
local purchases of goods and services in Cumbria amounted to &#163;65 million.
The Sellafield Business Rate for 1994/95 was &#163;16 million and is expected to
rise substantially when THORP is fully assessed.</P>
<P><B>Construction</B></P>
<P>4.13 Data from the Census of Employment for 1991 show that some 5,600
employees worked in the construction industry in West Cumbria. This figure had
fallen from 6,900 in 1989, reflecting the rundown of construction activity at
the Sellafield Works with the completion of the THORP project.</P>
<P>4.14 Analysis of BNFL's contractual workforce (<A HREF="#Table4.3">Table
4.3</A>) highlights the rundown in construction employment following the
completion of THORP. The contractual workforce peaked in 1991 at 7,330 but has
been cut-back very sharply since then to 1,600 in 1994, a loss of 5,730 jobs.</P>
<P><B>Tourism</B></P>
<P>4.15 The Impact of Tourism - Cumbria 1992 [COR/408](7) estimates that there
were 6,190 jobs directly dependent on tourism in West Cumbria (Allerdale and
Copeland). These jobs are included within 'Services' in <A HREF="#Table4.1">Table
4.1</A> and constitute an important sector of activity which benefits
accommodation providers, catering outlets, visitor attractions and retailers.</P>
<P><B>Agriculture, Forestry and Fishing</B></P>
<P>4.16 According to the 1991 Census of Population, some 3,200 residents of
West Cumbria were employed in agriculture, forestry and fisheries. Approximately
half of these persons were self-employed, this highlighting the importance of
self-employment to this sector.</P>
<P><B>Unemployment</B></P>
<P>4.17 Table 4.5 shows the recent history of unemployment in the Whitehaven
and Workington Travel to Work Areas (TTWAs) in terms of the percentage of male,
female and total unemployed; and Table 4.6 shows these percentages as a ratio of
the respective GB unemployed rates. A map illustrating the boundaries of
Copeland and Allerdale and of the TTWAs is shown in <A HREF="#Figure4.1">Figure
4.1</A>. The Whitehaven TTWA is almost coterminous with Copeland. The same does
not apply to the Workington TTWA and Allerdale, although the TTWA accounts for
the greater part of Allerdale's population.</P>
