years except 1995 where data refer to March</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>4.18 Throughout the period from 1983, male and female unemployed rates for
Whitehaven have been below these for Workington, reflecting the location of
Sellafield within the Whitehaven TTWA. Indeed, over the period up to 1993, the
Whitehaven male unemployed rate was below the GB average (as reflected in ratios
less than unity in the left hand column of <A HREF="#Table4.5">Table 4.5</A>).
In short, the employment provided by Sellafield has been reflected in low
unemployment in Whitehaven compared to Workington and is particularly important
for males, this reflecting the high percentage of male employment within the
Sellafield workforce. As at March 1995, males accounted for 80.6% of Sellafield
direct employment. While detailed information is not available for the
construction labour force at the same date, it is overwhelmingly male - 94.8% as
at November 1990 [NRX/10/2](8).</P>
<P>4.19 In view of the above, it would be expected that the reduction in
construction employment at Sellafield from 1991, and the accompanying UK
recession of 1990-92, would have a substantial, adverse impact on employment in
the Whitehaven TTWA. This is shown by the sharp rise in male unemployment from
1992 and in the rise in the Whitehaven to GB male unemployed ratio. As
<A HREF="#Table4.5">Table 4.5</A> and <A HREF="#Table4.6">4.6</A> demonstrate,
female unemployment rose much less sharply.</P>
<P>4.20 It is against this background that the socio-economic impact of the RCF
should be considered. The Sellafield Works (referred to as 'Sellafield') is a
major employer in the local economy. As of end 1994, employment offered by BNFL
and contractors on site was 9,660 but this number was substantially below its
1991 peak of 14,880, the bulk of this run-down involving a reduction in the
contractor labour force. In consequence, the unemployed rate relative to the
national average has deteriorated in recent years, particularly for males in the
Whitehaven TTWA.</P>
<P><B>Future Prospects</B></P>
<P>4.21 As in the UK as a whole, manufacturing employment in West Cumbria has
been in decline and is unlikely to provide substantially increased employment in
the future.</P>
<P>4.22 Employment in agriculture has been declining over a long period. It
appears unlikely that it will continue to fall at the historic rate but
employment opportunities are limited as a consequence of restricted market
opportunities, increasing productivity and the reform of the Common Agricultural
Policy.</P>
<P>4.23 In contrast, the nuclear industry, while it has experienced a reduction
in &quot;permanent&quot; employment since 1993, has witnessed long- term growth
and remains the dominant local employer. Despite the much more rapid reduction
of construction employment, it is likely to remain the dominant local employer
in the foreseeable future.</P>
<P>4.24 The future level of employment at the Sellafield Works will depend on
whether a number of key projects proceed. Outline planning permission was
granted for a Mixed Oxide Fuel ('MOX') plant on 23 February 1994. Failing such
new projects, Sellafield employment might be expected to decline slowly in line
with the underlying growth rate of productivity.</P>
<P>4.25 The Sellafield Works has been the most important local employer because
of the level of employment it has provided and because these jobs have offered
relatively high wage and salary levels. It has also provided BNFL/UKAEA
employees with secure employment in a period of rapid economic change within the
UK economy.</P>
<P>4.26 Therefore, Sellafield will remain an important employer in the future,
as employment prospects in some important sectors of the local economy are poor,
for reasons quite unconnected with Sellafield itself. That is, declining
employment in agriculture and manufacturing is a feature of most modern
industrial societies and is not specific to West Cumbria.</P>
<P><A NAME="Figure4.1"></A><I>FIGURE 4.1: BOUNDARIES  OF LOCAL AUTHORITY
DISTRICTS &amp; TTWAs IN THE WEST CUMBRIA STUDY AREA</I></P><IMG
SRC="images/pe1051.jpg" ALT="Figure 4.1: Boundaries of Local Authority Districts & TTWAs in West Cumbria study area." ALIGN="LEFT" BORDER="0" VSPACE="5" HSPACE="5" WIDTH="421" HEIGHT="533">
<P><BR><BR CLEAR="left"></P>
<P><A NAME="RCFEmployment"></A><B>5. RCF EMPLOYMENT</B></P>
<P>5.1 In this section I estimate the scale and timing of employment likely to
be associated with the RCF, viewed as a mining and scientific facility. This
requires estimation of the direct, indirect and induced employment which would
flow from the nature and size of the planned RCF construction and operational
programme. I also refer to Nirex's Employee Relations policy and the extent to
which persons directly employed might be recruited from persons presently
resident in the area.</P>
<P>5.2 It useful to divide the employment effects into three elements. These
are:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="50">(i)</TD>
<TD>Direct employment: this is persons employed at the development who would
receive wages and salaries;</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(ii)</TD>
<TD>Indirect employment: this is persons employed in local firms who supply
goods and services to the development; and</TD></TR>
<TR ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<TD></TD>
<TD>(iii)</TD>
<TD>Induced employment: this is employment supported by persons employed
directly and indirectly because of the development, who would spend part of
their incomes in the reference area.</TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>5.3 The assessment of the employment impact of the RCF should be considered
against the background of some reduction in BNFL direct employment and a large
reduction in contractor employment at Sellafield. Although the employment
created by the RCF is significantly lower than the job losses already
experienced, it must be expected that the employment impacts would be beneficial
ie. they would occur in a period when it would be desirable to generate
additional local employment opportunities.</P>
<P><B>Employment Impacts</B></P>
<P>5.4 In assessing the employment effect of a development it is usual to
consider the construction and operational phases separately. However, given that
there is a good deal of overlap between the construction and the Science
Programme (operational phases) of the RCF, their effects are considered
together.</P>
<P><B>Direct Employment</B></P>
<P>5.5 The information on direct employment supplied by Nirex was summarised in
the Environmental Statement [COR/101](9) and, on that basis, direct, indirect
and induced employment was estimated (Table 3.3.9). As a consequence of changes
in working methods and timetabling since the Environmental Statement was
prepared, it is estimated that direct employment will be lower than shown in the
Environmental Statement (1,261 compared to 1,398 person years) and the
employment impacts will be delayed by approximately one year on those shown in
the Environmental Statement.</P>
<P>5.6 Table 5.1 below summarises the latest Nirex estimate of direct labour
requirements for the period 1996-2008 inclusive.</P>
<P></P>
<P><A NAME="Table5.1"></A></P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
