<P>5.10 The value of the multiplier varies with the size and structure of the
local economy and with the scale and nature of the project considered (and,
indeed, with other factors). Ideally, it would be preferable to base our
multiplier estimate for the RCF on a facility similar to the RCF, previously
constructed in a local economy with a similar structure to West Cumbria.
However, I have not been able to locate such an estimate or, indeed, to base my
multiplier estimate on detailed analysis of a mining activity in a similar local
economy.</P>
<P>5.11 The published multiplier estimates shown in <A HREF="#Table5.2">Table
5.2</A> are those which are most appropriate in this instance, in that they
relate to developments in predominantly rural locations and include multiplier
estimates for construction projects.</P>
<P>Hence, I have applied the same multiplier value as employed in the
Environmental Statement, namely 1.34, this being the lowest mid-point multiplier
estimate shown in <A HREF="#Table5.2">Table 5.2</A>.</P>
<P>The adoption of the mid-point estimates for Hinkley Point or Torness
(operational phase) would have produced higher estimates of indirect/induced
employment than those carried forward in the analysis below.</P>
<P>5.12 Using a multiplier of 1.34 yields indirect/induced employment as
estimated in Table 5.3 below.</P>
