<P>5.13 On the basis of the present working methods and timetabling, peak
employment is expected to occur over 1997-1999 during the site establishment and
shaft sinking activities. Total person-years of employment (direct, indirect and
induced) are estimated at 1,690 (compared to 1,870 in the Environmental
Statement) [COR/101](11).</P>
<P><B>Employee Relations Policy</B></P>
<P>5.14 While the employment created by the development will be of benefit to
the economy of West Cumbria, the project will require an input from persons with
specialist skills as well as technical and scientific expertise who may not be
available in the local labour market. The mix of local and non-local recruitment
cannot be determined precisely at this time, but an important determinant will
be the employment policy framework established by Nirex.</P>
<P>5.15 Nirex's &quot;Model Code of Employee Relations&quot; (as at July 1995)
(Appendix I), is intended to apply to all construction contracts. Special
conditions of contract which give effect to that code are reproduced in Appendix
1. These conditions require contractors, where practicable, to recruit and/or
train labour and to source inputs of goods and services locally.</P>
<P>5.16 I understand that to encourage local sourcing Nirex have worked with
the Northern Development Company (NDC) to establish a local supplier base. This
has involved supporting NDC's Cumbria Purchasing Initiative and holding a &quot;Meet
the Buyer&quot; event in June 1994. This was attended by over 50 potential
suppliers and I am advised by Nirex that a number of these are now their regular
suppliers. Nirex's expenditure in Cumbria was &#163;0.518 million in 1993/94 and
&#163;1.110 million in 1994/95. It is intended to repeat the &quot;Meet the
Buyer&quot; event in the middle of 1996.</P>
<P>5.17 In short, Nirex intends to source locally where this is practicable and
to require contractors to recruit locally where that is appropriate in terms of
the availability of persons with the appropriate skills, or in terms of
providing suitable training to local recruits. Nirex will require contractors to
demonstrate that they have taken appropriate action to maximise local
recruitment and to train local personnel to meet that objective.</P>
<P>5.18 Nirex intends to put in place arrangements for skills training for the
local workforce, both for surface jobs and underground work. In order to
implement the strategy, Nirex has established a Steering Group, with strong
local representation, to identify RCF employment opportunities and to devise and
implement a skills - training programme, appropriate to the predicted
operational needs and legal, contractual and safety requirements.</P>
<P><B>Local Recruitment</B></P>
<P>5.19 The impact of these employment opportunities on the local labour market
(and, consequently, on public services) will depend on the extent to which the
direct employment opportunities provided by the RCF will be filled by local
personnel or persons migrating into the area. Where employment is taken up by
persons already resident in the area this will reduce local unemployment, with
little, if any, additional demand for public services.</P>
<P>5.20 Indirect employment would be created in existing local businesses which
supply the RCF and induced employment would be created in other local businesses
as a result of expenditure by persons employed directly or indirectly. Indirect
or induced employment can be expected to be taken up by persons already resident
locally. Hence, where we are concerned with the likely level of in-migration and
the consequent demand for public services, direct employment is the relevant
variable.</P>
<P>5.21 At this juncture, the extent to which direct employment will be filled
through local recruitment cannot be determined with certainty. It is probable
that the percentage of local recruitment, particularly for the contractor labour
force, will vary over the life-time of the RCF. The extent of local employment
in the contractor labour force is expected to be higher in the site
establishment activities. Shaft sinking, gallery construction and the science
programme require specialised skills, but the extent of local recruitment can be
maximised by early identification of need and the adoption of suitable training
and recruitment policies.</P>
<P>5.22 In the Environmental Statement [COR/101](12) it was assumed that the
percentage of local recruitment might be as follows:</P>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50"></TD>
