<P>5.25 Table 5.4 considers the peak level of employment in Phase 1 (for site
establishment, shaft sinking and scientific operations) and in Phase 2 and Phase
3 (for Nirex management staff) and Nirex's estimates of the minimum and maximum
percentage levels of local employment. It shows that even at the anticipated
maximum percentage level of local recruitment, the number of jobs would not be
large as against the numbers presently employed at Sellafield or against the
number of contractor jobs lost since the completion of THORP. Such levels of
recruitment could be met comfortably by the local labour market.</P>
<P><A NAME="PublicServices"></A><B>6. PUBLIC SERVICES</B></P>
<P>6.1 The construction and operation of the RCF would not require an influx of
substantial numbers of persons into the area and would occur in a period when
contractor employment had fallen substantially. This reduction in employment is
substantially greater than the new employment which would be created by the RCF.</P>
<P>6.2 At peak employment (1997-1999) the RCF would provide 230-248 person
years of employment, either directly or through indirect/induced effects. The
indirect/induced jobs could be expected to be filled by persons already resident
locally, as such employment is generated in local businesses. Again, some of the
direct jobs would be filled locally. It is that element of the RCF's direct
labour force recruited from outside the area, and who would take up residence
within the area, which would constitute the additional demand on local public
services.</P>
<P>6.3 The basic details of existing accommodation, health and education
provision are provided in the Environmental Statement [COR/101](13). These are
not reproduced here. Rather, I concentrate on establishing the likely scale of
recruitment external to the area which is likely to occur at the peak employment
period, 1997-99. Even during the peak period and assuming a high percentage of
external recruitment, the in-migration involved would not constitute a
significant additional demand for local public services.</P>
<P>6.4 The estimated minimum and maximum percentage of peak direct jobs which
might be filled by local recruitment are shown in <A HREF="#Table5.4">Table 5.4</A>.
Subtracting these estimates from peak employment, I obtain the estimated minimum
and maximum percentage of external recruitment at peak levels of activity (see
Table 6.1).</P>
<P><A NAME="Table6.1"></A></P>
