<P><B>Accommodation and Housing Markets</B></P>
<P>6.5 The recruitment of labour from outside the local area will generate
additional demand for temporary and permanent residential accommodation. The
peak requirement for temporary accommodation in Phase 1 would be during shaft
sinking where the maximum external recruitment is estimated to be 87
contractors, (75% of 115).</P>
<P>6.6 This is less than 1% of the 31,464 bedspaces available in temporary
accommodation in West Cumbria and 2.8% of serviced tourist accommodation. This
is unlikely to lead to a noticeable effect on demand, although it will clearly
be of benefit to accommodation providers in the vicinity of the Appeal Site.</P>
<P>6.7 The main demand for permanent accommodation within the Study Area is
likely to be generated by the in-migration of Nirex's staff. At its peak this is
expected to number 35. With a stock of housing in West Cumbria of over 70,000
dwellings, there is unlikely to be a noticeable effect on the local housing
market.</P>
<P>6.8 Applying the same method as that applied in the Environmental Statement
[COR/101](14) to calculating in-migrant families would suggest additional demand
for school places of 28.</P>
<P>6.9 As with the Environmental Statement it is expected that compared to
previous construction projects there will be little impact on health services.</P>
<P>6.10 In reaching these conclusions it is important to remember that the West
Cumbrian labour market was able to adjust to a substantial construction
workforce during the construction of THORP when on-site construction employment
was over 7,000 persons.</P>
<P>6.11 Although the employment opportunities associated with the development
are clearly of benefit to the local economy, the impact on accommodation and
public service provision is minimal relative to the recent experience of the
area.</P>
<P><A NAME="Impact"></A><B>7. IMPACT</B></P>
<P>7.1 The available evidence indicates that the nuclear facilities located at
Sellafield have had a significant positive impact on local economic activity. As
has been demonstrated (Section 4), Sellafield is the dominant employer in the
local economy and average wage and salary levels at Sellafield are significantly
above the Cumbrian average.</P>
<P>7.2 Concerns have been expressed that the existence of Sellafield may have
attendant disadvantages, most noticeably that the community may be too dependent
on the nuclear industry, and that the existence of the nuclear industry may have
an adverse impact on sectors otherwise unconnected with Sellafield. These
concerns are not new but no evidence has been provided to substantiate their
importance. The remainder of this section demonstrates that, if any actual
adverse impact were to be identified, it would be very small by contrast with
the very real and quantifiable benefits flowing from BNFL and UKAEA employment
at Sellafield.</P>
<P>7.3 I discuss these issues as follows. First, I consider the report of the
THORP public local inquiry (presented to the Secretary of State in January 1978)
[NRX/10/4](15) to demonstrate that the Inspector explicitly considered and
rejected the concerns relating to 'dependency' and wage costs. I then
demonstrate, that the Egremont Local Plan [NRX/10/5](16), the Mid Copeland Local
Plan [NRX/10/6](17) and the Copeland Local Plan Deposit Version [COR/306](18)
identify economic benefits associated with Sellafield. Second, I describe the
results of a study 'The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local Development'
[COR/402](19) which considers the relationship between existing UK nuclear
industry activities and local area development. Third, I review the published
studies on the issue of blight 'Blight and Nuclear Facilities' [COR/409](20).
Fourth, I summarise 'Foreign Direct Investment and Residential Property Values
[NRX/10/7](21) which provides data on inward investment to Cumbria and
residential property values in West Cumbria. Fifth, I refer to the conclusions
reached by a study 'Perceptions of West Cumbria as a Destination for Leisure
Travel and Inward Investment' [COR/406](22) on the attitudes of inward investors
and tourist visitors to West Cumbria. Finally, I set out the main conclusions
reached on a field visit to the Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory in Sweden and
summarise the report on the Dounreay public local inquiry [NRX/10/8](23) as to
the economic impact of the Dounreay and its relationship with other industries.</P>
<P>7.4 I would summarise this evidence as follows. In employment terms, the
impact of the existing nuclear industry is clearly beneficial and the employment
provided by the RCF would occur at a period when the direct and contractor
labour force at Sellafield has declined (Section 5). The arguments regarding
dependency and wage costs were rejected by the Inspector in his Report following
the Windscale Inquiry [NRX/10/4](15) and subsequent experience supports his
conclusions (see paragraph 7.7. As regards blight, none of the studies reviewed
provide evidence that the nuclear industry has had a significant blighting
impact on other types of economic activity in the local economy. As far as
Sellafield itself is concerned, the available evidence is that any impact on
inward investment or tourism is likely to be beneficial rather than adverse and
there is no evidence of an adverse net impact on residential property values.
That this is not unusual as evidenced by the 'Feasibility Study for Siting of a
Deep Repository Within the Storuman Municipality', 1995, SKB [NRX/10/11](45) and
the Report of Dounreay EDRP Public Local Inquiry' [NRX/10/8](23) experience. In
each case there is clear evidence of substantial employment and other benefits
and no evidence of a net adverse impact on other sectors of the economy.</P>
<P><B>Dependency and Wage Costs</B></P>
<P>7.5 The Windscale Inquiry [NRX/10/4](15) considered the argument that West
Cumbria had historically been too dependent on a small number of dominant
employers and that THORP would increase the local dominance of the nuclear
industry. The Inspector suggested that the argument would have some force if
there was any evidence that planning refusal would lead to a similar number of
permanent jobs being provided by some less dominant but equally stable
employers. However, he concluded that there was no evidence that this was the
case.</P>
<P>7.6 Secondly, the Inspector rejected the argument that BNFL's demand for
skilled labour would or might cause difficulties to other firms in the area.
This was on the grounds that Copeland Borough had made enquiries of the 10
largest employers in the Borough and none had thought the problem to be
significant.</P>
<P>7.7 The experience since the THORP report supports the conclusion regarding
dependency. As is evident from Section 4, the area has, in common with many
other areas of the UK, witnessed substantial losses of employment across a wide
range of basic industries. In these circumstances there is no evidence to
support any suggestion that restraints on employment creation at Sellafield
would be compensated by alternative local job creation in other sectors.</P>
<P>7.8 On wage costs there is little direct evidence one way or another.
However, on general principle it is difficult to attach much weight to an
argument that a development should be resisted because it offers favourable
conditions of employment. The process of economic development is intended to
achieve this very goal and Sellafield has made an important local contribution
in this regard.</P>
<P>7.9 Moreover, the favourable impact of Sellafield is noted in Copeland
statutory local plans adopted in the period since the THORP report. The Egremont
Local Plan [NRX/10/5](24) notes that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;A major symptom of West Cumbrian industrial decline has been the high
level of outmigration amongst its population. Yet figures for the Egremont
Parish, the main statistical base of the Local Plan area show a steady increase
since 1951 and the latest 1981 census returns indicate a further rise of 657
people or 9% over the last 10 years. It is apparent that the Egremont population
has avoided the worst effects of economic decline due in large part to the
proximity of the Sellafield works ...&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.10 Again, although the plan considers that it would be unwise to be too
dependent on one large employer, it emphasises that the Egremont area &quot;provides
the best location for businesses generated by Sellafield linkage&quot;
[NRX/10/5](24).</P>
<P>7.11 The Mid Copeland Local Plan [NRX/10/6](25) recognises that BNFL is the
dominant local employer. It states that &quot;there is no other major source of
employment&quot; and declares that, in spite of this, there is &quot;little
economic deprivation in the area&quot;. The local plan underlines the loss of
jobs in other sectors in North Copeland and the difficulty of attracting new
employment.</P>
<P>7.12 Further, the Mid Copeland Local Plan [NRX/10/6](26) sees BNFL
employment as an asset in that it creates the possibility of &quot;attracting
industry with technological links with nuclear fuel processing&quot; and
establishes a higher skills base through its extensive training programmes. The
Plan remarks that there is evidence that enquiries for high quality industrial
and office accommodation associated with Sellafield had been turned away because
of a shortage of suitable accommodation. As the plan puts it:</P>
<P>&quot;In the West Cumbria context proximity to Sellafield and associated
spin off is the advantage to be grasped&quot; [NRX/10/6](27)</P>
<P>7.13 The importance of Sellafield to the local economy, the reduction in
manufacturing employment and the difficulties of attracting alternative
employment to the area are, again, explicitly recognised in the Copeland Local
Plan Deposit Version [COR/306](18). The Plan also states that the Westlakes
Science and Technology Park, established to help with the property requirements
identified in the Mid Copeland Local Plan, &quot;has proved very successful in
attracting new commercial and technology/research enterprises&quot;
[COR/306](28).</P>
<P><B>The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local Development</B></P>
<P>7.14 I now turn to the issue of whether the nuclear industry at Sellafield
might have an adverse blighting impact on other types of activity. The terms of
reference and structure of a study reviewed here [COR/402](19) were agreed
jointly with Cumbria County Council and Nirex. The study was based on two
surveys.</P>
<P>First, a local survey of companies, local development agencies and property
agents in the vicinity of Sellafield and, second, a survey of development
agencies in other parts of the country with major nuclear facilities.</P>
<P>7.15 The local surveys were intended to explore whether the existing nuclear
industry at Sellafield had had any blighting impact and whether the respondents
perceived that the proposed Deep Waste Repository ('DWR') would have a blighting
effect. In the present circumstances the relevant perceptions would relate to
the RCF project, but it seems unlikely that the latter would be perceived to
have a greater blighting impact than the DWR project.</P>
<P>7.16 The local surveys were based on samples and questionnaires agreed with
Cumbria County Council. 23 interviews were completed as follows:</P>
<UL>
<LI>companies    (10)</LI>
<LI>agencies involved in economic development    (9)</LI>
<LI>estate agents    (4)</LI></UL>
<P>Company Survey</P>
<P>7.17 The major locational concerns reported by companies related to the
area's poor transport infrastructure, its peripherality (and related recruitment
problems) and higher costs resulting from both these factors. One company cited
a few potential management recruits as declining employment offers due to the
proximity of Sellafield. Much more common was the view that to the extent that
Sellafield influenced recruitment, this was due to its favourable impact on
local employment and wages and salaries. The main deterrent factor in recruiting
labour was West Cumbria's perceived remoteness and lack of cultural, social and
sports facilities.</P>
<P>7.18 Only in one case did an interviewee abort an interview in circumstances
which suggest that he was concerned that being 'associated' with Sellafield
could adversely impact on company sales. However, the company is still in
production and its labour force is believed to be stable.</P>
<P>7.19 'The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local Development' [COR/402](29)
concludes that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;.... while there is a level of concern among some companies that
the presence of Sellafield and the possible DRP (Deep Repository Project)
development, has or may have a blighting effect, the weight of evidence does not
indicate that this effect is widespread or that it is a major factor inhibiting
company development&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.20 This is despite the fact that the initial selection of companies was
deliberately designed to identify those sectors, such as food processing, where
some adverse impact might be perceived.</P>
<P>Development Agencies</P>
<P>7.21 The agencies in this survey were locally based. As with the companies,
the poor transport infrastructure and perceived remoteness were considered to be
the major constraints to economic development. The nuclear industry is believed
by the agencies to have a blighting effect but the extent of this appears to be
limited and, occasionally, exaggerated. Hence, expressed concerns related mostly
to the food industry but it was erroneously believed that the two relocations
from Cumbria in this sector were due to the presence of Sellafield. This
conclusion was categorically refuted by the companies concerned who emphasised
that relocation had resulted from rationalisation programmes. None of the
companies interviewed suggested they would consider relocating in the light of a
decision to proceed with the DWR and it must be expected that the same
conclusion would apply to the RCF.</P>
<P>7.22 Some concern was expressed by the local development agencies regarding
a possible 'over-dependence' on the nuclear industry and the loss of Development
Area status due to the favourable impact of the nuclear industry on local
unemployment relative to the national average. However, an improvement in the
area's relative unemployment position must be regarded as desirable and is,
indeed, a major objective of regional policy.</P>
<P>Estate Agents</P>
<P>7.23 The general view was that the in-migration resulting from Sellafield
has had a favourable impact on residential property values in West Cumbria and
that any negative impact due to the existing and future nuclear activities at
Sellafield would be localised and limited in duration. Seascale is considered to
be the main location where property values may be adversely affected but the
general impact on residential property values in West Cumbria was considered to
be favourable.</P>
<P>7.24 By agreement with Cumbria County Council, the survey of development
agencies in other parts of the UK considered whether existing concentrations of
nuclear facilities had had any major impact on local economic development. The
concentrations considered were:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Sizewell A and B, Suffolk;
</LI>
<LI> Aldermaston, the Ministry of Defence establishment in Berkshire;
</LI>
<LI> Trawsfynydd, the Magnox Reactor in Snowdonia National Park;
</LI>
<LI> Hunterston, the Magnox and Advanced Gas Cooled Reactors to the south of
Glasgow; and
</LI>
<LI> Capenhurst, BNFL's fuel enrichment plant in Cheshire.
</LI></UL>
<P>7.25 The economic performance of the different areas vary markedly but these
differences in performance are not due to the presence of nuclear facilities.
The areas around Aldermaston and Hunterston have good records in attracting
inward investment and Aldermaston benefits from its location between the M3 and
the M4. Capenhurst has not been successful in attracting private sector inward
investment but has attracted three major public sector employers. Sizewell and
Trawsfynydd are both relatively rural, remote communities with poor
communications infrastructures and have not been successful in attracting inward
investment.</P>
<P>7.26 The experience of the latter two areas is most relevant to West Cumbria
and suggests that accessibility and the communications infrastructure are more
relevant to inward investment decisions that the presence of nuclear facilities.
Hence, 'The Impact of Nuclear Facilities on Local Development' [COR/402](30)
concludes that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;There was no evidence from the survey of any significant long- term
adverse impact on local economic development in any of the areas considered&quot;</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.27 Subsequent to the completion of the study, the Director of Economy and
Environment for Cumbria County Council remarked in his report on the planning
application [COR/104](31) that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>&quot;The Environmental Statement concludes that the development (the RCF)
is not expected to have an adverse impact on economic behaviour arising from
adverse perceptions of the development. However, it should be noted that there
is no independent research addressing those issues in depth&quot;.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.28 I would note that the conclusions reached in this section are based on
a study, the form and content of which were agreed with officials of Cumbria
County Council. Moreover, I believe that there is, in addition to this study, an
important body of research findings which does investigate whether nuclear
facilities have a blighting impact. This is summarised in a literature review of
'Blight and Nuclear Facilities' [COR/409](20). While much of the published
research is US in origin, it does point to the likelihood that the net economic
impact of nuclear related developments is positive or neutral. This is supported
by further studies of inward investment, tourism and property values in West
Cumbria [NRX/10/7](21) and [COR/406](22), and by the evidence relating to the
Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory in Sweden and Dounreay in Scotland. I have been unable
to uncover any study or evidence which demonstrates that nuclear facilities have
a significant adverse impact on local development, while there is a large body
of evidence which attests to the substantial employment and other benefits which
do arise to local communities.</P>
<P><B>Blight and Nuclear Facilities</B></P>
<P>7.29 Blight can be taken as the adverse impact on the economy from changes
in people behaviour and decisions, which, in turn, result from perceptions of
risk, image and stigma which may be associated with nuclear facilities. If it
exists, its impact on the local economy can be expected to be negative, whereas
the creation of employment by nuclear facilities can be expected to have a
positive impact on the local economy. It is an empirical question as to which
effect - positive or negative - is the stronger.</P>
<P>7.30 There is quite a substantial body of literature on this issue. This was
reviewed in July 1994 and based on all discovered articles and papers up to
September 1992. Subsequent to that date the literature search was maintained and
an updated study was completed in April 1995 [COR/409](20). Where new material
is included, it confirms the analysis and the conclusions reached in the first
study. I summarise the main conclusions below (the references relate to the
April 1995 study).</P>
<P>7.31 The published literature falls into two main categories. Evidence
relating to actual behaviour and evidence relating to perceptions or intended
behaviour. These throw up contrasting results and the reasons for this contrast
are discussed below.</P>
<P>7.32 The literature review based on actual behaviour suggests that the net
impact of nuclear facilities is favourable ie. that the positive impact of
employment creation outweighs any negative impact as a consequence of blight.
Often, the nuclear facilities are, as at Sellafield, major local employers. As
regards their impact on other sectors/activities the available literature
provides relatively little evidence on mobility and output, but what there is
does not support a contention that there is a net adverse impact. The evidence
is stronger for property values, tourism and investment and is to the effect
that the net impact of nuclear facilities is either neutral or beneficial.</P>
<P>7.33 There is an extensive literature relating to perceptions or intended
behaviour which suggest that nuclear facilities could have a blighting impact on
local economic activity. However, it is not possible to use this to demonstrate
that an adverse impact has occurred from the construction and operation of
nuclear facilities.</P>
<P>7.34 In the first place, the literature relates to perceptions or intended
behaviour. Few of the studies reviewed go on to demonstrate that the perceptions
or intended behaviour result in actual economic behaviour and a demonstrable
adverse impact. In the few instances where the authors have attempted to compare
intended and actual behaviour it was found that the initial survey results
overstate tendencies to avoid perceived hazards. Other methodological weaknesses
arise from the limited range of information available to respondents, the nature
of the sample and the risk of strategic bias ie. a possibility that respondents
may attempt to influence the outcome of their study to their benefit. Some
studies of perceptions and intended behaviour concentrate on the impact of
blight, rather than in the net impact of nuclear facilities which also provide
local employment and income benefits.</P>
<P>7.35 The only studies of perceptions which relate specifically to Sellafield
and local residents are those by Research and Auditing Services ('RAS') 'UK
Nirex Repository Proposal - A Survey of Public Opinion' [COR/404](32) and by
North East Market Surveys ('NEMS') 'Socio-economic Impact Study of the Nuclear
Industry Among Residents', 1995, North East Market Surveys [COR/410](33) both
for Copeland Borough Council, and by The Centre for the Study of Environmental
Change, Lancaster University (for Cumbria County Council), 'Public Perceptions
and the Nuclear Industry in West Cumbria', [COR/401](34). The RAS and NEMS
surveys set out to assess local attitudes toward the creation of the DWR and the
Lancaster University study to explain how these attitudes are formed.</P>
<P>7.36 The RAS study [COR/404](35) was commissioned by Copeland Borough
Council. It was based on a quota sample of 1,002 Copeland residents and
undertaken in August 1992. The study concluded that <I>&quot;On the whole, the
community appears to support the plans to build the Repository, though by a
slender margin&quot;</I>, with 50% of respondents tending to or completely
supporting, and 36% tending to or completely opposing, the DWR proposal. Not
surprisingly, support for the DWR is stronger amongst respondents who work (or
have immediate family working) with BNFL.</P>
<P>7.37 The NEMS study [COR/410](36) was based on 500 Copeland respondents
interviewed in April and May of 1995. Although one half of all respondents
underestimated the level of employment at Sellafield (50% believed it to be in
the 2,000 - 6,000 range), almost all respondents agreed that Sellafield
employment brought significant benefits to the area. Taking all considerations
into account, &quot;86% of all respondents were either 'very satisfied' or
'satisfied' with the presence of BNFL at Sellafield, rising to 97% amongst those
in the industry&quot;.</P>
<P>7.38 The Lancaster University study [COR/401](37) probes the <I>&quot;feelings
and opinions of people in West Cumbria towards the present and possible future
development of the nuclear industry in the area&quot;</I>. The study is based on
four socio-economic groups - BNFL apprentices, farmers and fishermen, working
professionals, and women and mothers - <I>&quot;who should not be seen as a
representative sample of public attitudes or opinions&quot;</I>. The study
demonstrates that attitudes are complex and vary significantly between and
within different groups. However, it is impossible to determine how widespread
are the reported concerns over &quot;dependency&quot; and &quot;stigma&quot;
amongst the respondents and still less to establish how representative the
respondents are of the community as a whole.</P>
<P>7.39 While each of these studies provide an interesting perspective and
demonstrate there are real concerns to be addressed, neither provides evidence
of the extent to which perceptions may result in behaviour which impacts on
local economic development.</P>
<P>7.40 There are therefore good grounds for the Department of Environment
[GOV/306](38) view that:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;perceptions of risks that cannot be substantiated and which cannot
be demonstrated to have clear land-use implications, are not material to
planning decisions&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.41 Studies of actual behaviour have two major advantages over those based
on perceptions. First, they provide a true measuring of observed outcomes and,
second, such outcomes identify the beneficial employment and income impact
associated with nuclear facilities, as well as any adverse impacts which may
have manifested themselves.</P>
<P>7.42 The literature review 'Blight and Nuclear Facilities' [COR/409](39)
concludes that:</P>
<UL>
<LI> <I>&quot;Blight impacts associated with nuclear facilities are
undoubtedly negative
</I></LI>
<LI> <I>In the cases analysed, blight impacts of nuclear facilities have not
been of significant magnitude to offset the positive economic impacts on local
income and employment. As regards nuclear related facilities, the balance of
evidence suggests that the positive income and employment effects tend to
outweigh negative blight effects&quot;.
</I></LI></UL>
<P>7.43 Most of the literature review relates to the US and may not be directly
applicable to Sellafield, However, the published literature for Sellafield is
consistent with the results of the US studies and below, I review studies of
actual behaviour directly relevant to Sellafield.</P>
<P><B>Foreign Direct Investment and Residential Property Values</B></P>
<P>7.44 A study was conducted based on two data sets, relating to foreign
direct investment (FDI) and residential property values [NRX/10/7](21). The main
conclusions are summarised below.</P>
<P>Foreign Direct Investment (FDI)</P>
<P>7.45 Data on FDI projects into the Northern and North West Regions were
supplied by the Northern Development Corporation (NDC) and by INWARD
respectively. These are the main agencies responsible for marketing and
promoting these two regions for FDI projects. A representative from each agency
was interviewed to establish those factors considered important in determining
the geographical pattern of FDI observed and, in particular, the relatively low
proportion of FDI projects and employment attracted to Cumbria.</P>
<P>7.46 The geographical pattern in both areas shows a heavy concentration of
inward investment projects in Development Areas and, within the Development
Areas, a concentration on sites readily accessible from the major road network
(the M6 in the North West) and the A1 (M1) in the North East. Within both
regions there is a tendency for sites to be in or adjacent to the major
population centres with relatively few sites in remote rural areas. The
concentration on Development Areas reflects the higher level of assistance
available compared to Intermediate Areas and the concentration within
Development Areas reflects the importance of accessibility and labour market
considerations.</P>
<P>7.47 INWARD's database provides details on 155 FDI projects into the
Northern Region over September 1985 - October 1994. NDC's database covers 334
FDI projects over 1985 - 1993 inclusive. Combining both databases, Cumbria
accounted for 16 (3.3%) of 489 FDI projects and for 2.3% of new jobs or
safeguarded jobs, compared to a population share of 4.7%.</P>
<P>7.48 In the view of NDC and INWARD, Cumbria's relatively low share of FDI
projects and jobs is due to the availability of better investment incentives in
other areas and to Cumbria's comparative disadvantages in respect of
communications, access to supplies and markets, skills availability and
university links. My personal experience of inward investment confirms that the
stated factors are significant influences on the location of such projects and
that West Cumbria will be seriously disadvantaged in these regards.</P>
<P>7.49 Neither NDC or INWARD have encountered a potential inward investor who
had voiced concern over the presence of nuclear facilities or over the potential
siting of a RCF or DWR in Cumbria. These results are fully consistent with the
results reported below in a study undertaken by the Government Enterprise
Communication Unit, Newcastle University [COR/406](22)</P>
<P>Residential Property Values:</P>
<P>7.50 The Halifax Building Society provided data, by postcode area, on
residential properties bought by their mortgage holders over 1983-94. The data
provided information on residential property values for detached, semi-detached
and terraced houses, and bungalows. The analysis was based on postcode areas
where the bulk of sales were within a 5 mile radius of Sellafield (called the
'immediate' area), a radius of greater than 5 miles and up to 10 miles (called
the 'intermediate' area) and a radius greater than 10 miles from Sellafield
(called the 'outer' area).</P>
<P>7.51 Residential property values in these areas may be expected to be
subject two opposing influences from the presence of Sellafield. Any adverse
blighting impact would be expected to depress residential property values and
any beneficial economic impact would be expected to raise property values. Both
effects would be expected to increase with greater proximity to Sellafield ie.
they would be expected to be stronger in the immediate area than in the
intermediate area, and stronger in both the immediate and intermediate areas as
compared with the outer area.</P>
<P>7.52 In fact the data show there is no statistically significant difference
between these areas in average residential property values by house type. This
suggests that if any blighting impact exists in the immediate area, it must be
highly localised or offset by the beneficial employment impact of Sellafield.</P>
<P><B>Perceptions of West Cumbria as a Destination for Leisure Travel and
Inward Investment</B></P>
<P>7.53 There are two publications bearing this title, dated May 1994 and
December 1994 [COR/406](22) respectively. I understand from the researchers that
the earlier report presented interim results and that the December 1994 report
reflects the final conclusions of the researchers based on the evidence
reviewed. I have therefore drawn on the latter report.</P>
<P>7.54 The study was undertaken for the West Cumbria Development Fund by the
Government Enterprise Communication Unit (&quot;GECU&quot;), Newcastle
University. The inward investment research was carried out in collaboration with
NDC, INWARD, the Economic Development Department of Cumbria County Council, the
West Cumbria Development Agency and the Cumbria Marketing Initiative. The
tourism research was carried out in collaboration with the Cumbria Tourist Board
and the West Cumbria Development Agency.</P>
<P>7.55 The conclusions on inward investment are based on interviews with:</P>
<UL>
<LI> 14 firms who had been offered a Cumbrian option by NDC but who chose to
relocate elsewhere in the North of England;
</LI>
<LI> A re-analysis by GECU of a survey of 212 companies originally carried
through by Scantel for the Cumbria Marketing Initiative; the companies had moved
to, or expanded within, the UK in the last 10 years; and
</LI>
<LI> Focus group meetings at NDC, INWARD, the Cumbria Marketing Group and the
West Cumbria Development Agency; the Cumbria Marketing Group contained a
representative of Copeland Borough Council.
</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="Para7.56"></A>7.56 The major conclusions with regard to inward
investment were [COR/406](40):</P>
<UL>
<LI> <I>&quot;Cumbria was perceived to be isolated from markets, commerce,
communities and culture and its serious geographical isolation to be compounded
by road, rail and air links&quot;
</I></LI>
<LI> <I>&quot;These perceived advantages of the area (Cumbria) are
inconsistent with the requirements of a destination for inward investment ...
the area is very unappealing to a majority of decision makers involved in
industrial relocation.&quot;
</I></LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="Para7.57"></A>7.57 As regards West Cumbria, the study
[COR/406](41) concluded:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;... Sellafield is not a significant deterrent to inward investment
in West Cumbria, and with the proper infrastructure for the transfer or
exploitation of its technologies, could be turned into a considerable asset&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.58 These conclusions are consistent with the conclusions reached in the
studies of the impact of nuclear facilities on local development [COR/402](19)
and inward investment and property [NRX/10/7](21). That is, to the extent that
West Cumbria has had difficulty in attracting inward investment, this is due to
factors such as remoteness and a poor communications infrastructure. Sellafield
is not a significant deterrent and, through vehicles such as the Westlakes
Science and Technology Park, can be used as an asset to attract inward
investment.</P>
<P><A NAME="Para7.59"></A>7.59 The study's [COR/406](42) conclusions on
tourism were based on 1,000 personal interviews with visitors to the Cumberland
Pencil Museum (Keswick), Haverthwaite Railway Station and the Brockhole National
Park Centre (near Ambleside). The study concluded that most perceptions of West
Cumbria are ill-defined. As regards Sellafield, the study commented:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;The majority of respondents were aware of the Sellafield site and
the Visitors Centre which was perceived to be one of the major attractions
within the area. Our sample survey revealed that the vast majority of persons
are no less likely to visit West Cumbria because of the presence of BNFL at
Sellafield, indeed some 6% of respondents were more likely to visit the area to
see the heavily promoted Sellafield Visitors Centre&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A NAME="Para7.60"></A>7.60 The Cumbria Tourist Board had previously
reported the results of an English Tourist Board 1987 survey [NRX/10/9](43) of
452 respondents as follows:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;Only 3% of respondents named Cumbria as a region they would not
want to visit or revisit, and of these, only one mentioned the nuclear plant as
a reason&quot;.</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.61 This was despite the fact that there was:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>&quot;.... a high level of detailed knowledge about the location of
Sellafield amongst respondents as a whole.&quot;</I></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>7.62 Like the English Tourist Board Study, the GECU study [COR/406](22) is
based on the views of persons who are directly engaged in tourism activity and
therefore represent 'markets' which West Cumbria would wish to attract.</P>
<P>7.63 A further study on the perceptions of West Cumbria as a destination for
inward handling based on telephone interviews with 1,000 of the top 3,000 UK
companies was conducted by MORI [NRX/10/10](44). The study was commissioned by
CBI Northern Region and designed by the Government Enterprise Communication Unit
of the University of Newcastle-Upon-Tyne.</P>
<P>7.64 Companies were asked to rate six specified areas in terms of their
attractiveness as locations for business and industry. The areas were selected
for &quot;peripherality&quot; although County Durham was chosen because its
industrial structure is considered to be similar to West Cumbria.</P>
<P>7.65 The responses rated the areas in the following order of preference:</P>
<UL>
<LI>East Riding of Yorkshire</LI>
<LI>County Durham</LI>
<LI>North Wales</LI>
<LI>West Cumbria</LI>
<LI>East Norfolk</LI>
<LI>Cornwall</LI></UL>
<P>7.66 These ratings reflect the importance businesses attached to <I>&quot;access
to markets, customers, suppliers, a labour force and good road and rail
communication&quot;</I>. Only 8% of respondents considered that West Cumbria was
a good location.</P>
<P>7.67 The study concludes:</P>
<P><I>&quot;Accessibility and proximity to customers, suppliers and skilled
labour, are the main attributes looked for in a location for business and
industry. West Cumbria is perceived to be poor in each of these areas. As a
destination for inward investment, it is therefore very disadvantaged. But
Sellafield is shown to play very little part in creating such a perception&quot;.</I></P>
<P><B>The Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory and Dounreay</B></P>
<P>Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory</P>
<P><A NAME="Para7.68"></A>7.68 On 22-23 May 1995 I visited the Aspo Hard Rock
Laboratory located close to the Oskarshamn nuclear power station in Sweden. The
nuclear power station is also the site for the interim storage facility for
spent fuel (CLAB). Aspo was chosen for the site visit because it offered close
parallels to the proposed RCF:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Although the rock laboratory is generic, rather than specific to a site
which might be developed as a repository, the construction method for the main
access drift (drill and blast) is the same as that for the RCF shaft and the
underground experiments are similar.
</LI>
<LI> It is located close to a nuclear power station which creates substantial
employment and in an area of Sweden remote from the main centres of population;
and
</LI>
<LI>The power station is also the site for the storage of spent fuel so that if
there were a blighting impact its impact might be expected to be discernible.</LI></UL>
<P>7.69 During the visit I had separate discussions with the Project Manager
for the laboratory, the Chairman of the Municipal Board, the socio-economics
consultant to SKB (Swedish Nuclear Fuel and Waste Management Company) and a
senior executive of the local SCANIA truck factory.</P>
<P>7.70 All the respondents were of the view that the impact of the nuclear
power station had been positive and significant. While initially, the power
station had attracted some local opposition it is now seen as an important
element in the local economy.</P>
<P>It provides around 1,000 permanent jobs, which were highly paid and
contained a high percentage of highly skilled jobs by local standards. In
consequence, local unemployment at 3.5% was much lower than in surrounding
communities.</P>
<P>7.71 Other benefits identified were:</P>
<UL>
<LI> An improved local infrastructure;
</LI>
<LI> A favourable impact on the educational standards achieved by local
schools; and
</LI>
<LI> The enhanced scientific and technical base provided by Aspo as a 'Centre
of Excellence'.
</LI></UL>
<P>7.72 None of the parties interviewed could identify any adverse blighting
impact on employment or tourism. As regards the former a recent (1995) SKB paper
[NRX/10/11](45) reports that, as in Oskershamn, all of the four Swedish nuclear
power plants had a favourable impact on population trends and employment, the
local availability of high wage, high skilled jobs, the educational system and
the local infrastructure.</P>
<P>7.73 As regards tourism, the study [NRX/10/11](46) concluded that the
Swedish nuclear power plants are visitor attractions in their own right; that in
three of the four nuclear power plant municipalities there was no adverse impact
on weekend cottage property values; and that there was no impact on the property
values of permanent homes in any of the four nuclear power plant municipalities.</P>
<P>Dounreay</P>
<P>7.74 The Dounreay Nuclear Establishment (DNE) offers another case study of a
nuclear development which provided substantial employment and whose impact on
other activities was positive rather than negative. The Reporter at the Dounreay
EDRP Public Inquiry [NRX/10/8](23) noted that the establishment of Dounreay had
reversed the area's population decline and <I>&quot;had a profound effect on
the economy and social welfare of Caithness&quot;</I> . The Report noted that
Dounreay was the third largest employer in the Highlands; that there were
spin-off benefits from the spending of DNE and its workforce; and that, <I>&quot;The
expansion of Thurso, the establishment of Thurso Technical College and the
provision of much improved infrastructure and social facilities all stem largely
from the establishment of Dounreay&quot;</I> .</P>
<P>7.75 Further, the Report, while it acknowledged the importance of farming,
fishery and tourism to the local economy and the possibility of blight,
concluded <I>&quot;there is no evidence to support a general assertion that
Dounreay has deterred other economic activity in Caithness&quot;</I>.</P>
<P><A NAME="Conclusions"></A><B>8. CONCLUSIONS</B></P>
<P><A NAME="Para8.1"></A>8.1 The RCF would increase local employment and
income in West Cumbria. The employment impact is estimated as 1,261 person-years
of direct employment and 429 person-years of indirect and induced employment.
This impact is unambiguously positive.</P>
<P>The scale of the development in relation to previous construction projects
in West Cumbria, indicates that the labour market could adjust to such
additional employment without difficulty and the scale of in- migration would
not put large demands on the existing social infrastructure.</P>
<P>8.2 The level of in-migration would be small and would have no significant
effect on the housing stock and public services in the area.</P>
<P>The local housing market and the existing supply of bedspaces are large
relative to the impacts of the development, given the scale of temporary
accommodation required and the recent rundown of construction activity at
Sellafield. The likely additional demand for health and education facilities
would be small, and would be unlikely to have any adverse effect on those
services.</P>
<P>8.3 The existing nuclear facilities form an extremely important sector of
the local economy. Indeed, the Sellafield site is the most important local
employer and wages and salaries are above the average for Cumbria. The
employment offered by BNFL/UKAEA has been a significant source of benefit and
stability in a period of rapid change in the national economy. This is
recognised by the Egremont Local Plan [NRX/10/5](16) the Mid Copeland Local Plan
[NRX/10/6](17) and by the Copeland Local Plan Deposit Version [COR/306](18).
There is also a recognition that the new technology and the skills level
associated with Sellafield provide important additional assets to the local
community.</P>
<P>8.4 There is no evidence that the existence of Sellafield has had a
significant adverse impact on other sectors of the local economy. The existing
evidence suggests that the impact of Sellafield is positive for inward
investment and tourism, both sectors of economic activity which are often
considered to be sensitive to an adverse blighting impact. The evidence does not
suggest that local residential property values are depressed by proximity to
Sellafield.</P>
<P>8.5 The evidence available for the Aspo Hard Rock Laboratory and for
Dounreay confirm that other major nuclear developments have produced similar
economic benefits in terms of local employment creation, without adverse impacts
on other sectors. The NEMS [COR/410](33) study provides strong evidence that
Copeland residents also recognise that significant economic benefits result from
BNFL employment at Sellafield.</P>
<P>8.6 In my opinion, Sellafield has introduced an important source of high
wage and salary employment to an area with restricted opportunities for
alternative economic development. The RCF would build on this base, offering
additional local employment opportunities. Such 'dependence' on the nuclear
industry might be undesirable if it prevented new activities from developing
(for example, by deterring inward investment or tourism) or by causing existing
activities to relocate from the area. There is no evidence to suggest that this
occurs. I would therefore conclude that the nuclear industry at Sellafield has
resulted in a significant addition to local income and employment over the level
which would exist in its absence and that the impact of the RCF would also be
beneficial.</P>
