<P><BR></P>
<P><A NAME="A1"></A><B>1.0 INTRODUCTION</B></P>
<P>1.1 The purpose of the RCF is to enable Nirex to make a decision on the
suitability of the site as a deep waste repository. This will entail
construction contractors and scientific contractors working together to this
end.</P>
<P>1.2 This document provides contractors wishing to tender for construction
work on the Nirex RCF contract a background brief on Nirex employee relations
policy and the values and philosophy which lie behind that policy. It also
offers guidance on the practical implementation of such policy through a model,
skeletal protocol, on which a contractor can base his own detailed procedures
and practices to ensure compliance with the spirit of the Code.</P>
<P><A NAME="A2"></A><B>2.0 EMPLOYEE RELATIONS POLICY</B></P>
<P><B>2.1 Underlying Philosophy and Values</B></P>
<P>2.1.1 Nirex believes in cooperative relationships with its contractors, and
between them and their subcontractors, on employee relations policies. This
demands a strong communications infrastructure within which to tackle issues
that may arise between Nirex, the contractors, subcontractors and the employees
of these panics.</P>
<P>2.1.2 Nirex places the health and safety of Nirex employees and those of its
contractors at the top of its priorities. In addition to the observance and
enforcement of all statutory requirements including the Construction Design and
Management Regulations 1994, Nirex believes in developing and nurturing a
'safety culture'. To this end Nirex supports the development and maintenance of
fora, comprising representatives of the parties, to provide a focus for the
discussion of health and safety matters, with a view to ensuring the constant
provision of the highest standards.</P>
<P>2.1.3 In the way in which it subcontracts its activities, Nirex is committed
to the creation of local employment opportunities and the development of skills
to help local personnel take advantage of those opportunities.</P>
<P>2.1.4 Nirex respects and values all its stakeholders including contractors,
employees, customers and shareholders, and expects all of its contractors to
mirror this philosophy and build it into their employee relations practices.</P>
<P><B>2.2 Objectives</B></P>
<P>The objectives of the Nirex Employee Relations Policy for the Rock
Characterisation Facility (RCF) are to:-</P>
<UL>
<LI> ensure a safe and healthy working environment, through the observance of
legal requirements and the development of a 'safety culture'
</LI>
<LI> foster an harmonious employee relations climate on the RCF site, based
upon cooperative relationships with contractors
</LI>
<LI> maximise productivity by ensuring good working practices, in accord with
all relevant agreements and a Code of Employee Relations Practice (see below)
</LI>
<LI>maximise employment opportunities for local personnel, where reasonable and
practicable, through suitably framed recruitment and training procedures</LI>
<LI> achieve compatibility of employee relations practices on the RCF site and,
where practicable and relevant, with the adjacent BNFL construction site at
Sellafield,
</LI>
<LI> achieve the above objectives within a climate of cooperation between
Nirex, its contractors and their subcontractors. A climate providing for
discussions of problems and concerns between all relevant parties.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>2.3 Policy Implementation</B></P>
<P>2.3.1 To implement the policy Nirex will require all its RCF contractors to
manage employee relations appropriately within their workforces and to liaise
with other RCF contractors to ensure that they promote compatibility. Nirex will
not intervene in any way between any of its contractors and their employees in
day to day employee relations issues, for which the contractor has total
responsibility. However, Nirex does reserve the right to withhold access to any
of its' premises, to individuals employed by contractors, if this action is
deemed necessary by Nirex.</P>
<P>2.3.2 As far as is reasonable and practicable, RCF contractors must maximise
employment opportunities for local personnel and, in collaboration with Nirex,
provide the necessary framework to make this policy succeed. 'Local personnel'
is defined by Nirex as 'those persons who are resident in the area, but who are
not in receipt of lodging allowance'. &quot;Lodging allowance&quot; is as laid
down in the appropriate working rule agreements for the trades concerned.</P>
<P>2.3.3 Where practicable and reasonable, RCF contractors (in association with
Nirex where necessary) should develop and set in place skills training
programmes for suitable local personnel. These programmes will be designed to
target skill gaps between skills needed for the RCF and those which are
currently available locally.</P>
<P>2.3.4 Nirex will expect its RCF contractors engaged in construction or
activities to be members of a relevant British national employer organisation
and to comply with applicable British national labour agreements, insofar as
current legislation allows, with the object of achieving well ordered employee
relations between themselves and their employees.</P>
<P>2.3.5 RCF contractors who are not members of a relevant British national
employer organisation and/or not party to the agreements referred to in
paragraph 2.3.4 must nevertheless ensure that their labour is employed under
comparable conditions to those contained in such agreements to promote
compatibility within their workforce and with other contractors and to achieve
well ordered employee relations as above.</P>
<P>2.3.6 All contractors shall ensure that their employees comply with all
relevant legislation including the Electricity at Work Regulations 1989 and the
Construction Design and Management Regulations 1994, Health and Safety<I> </I>Executive
Codes of<I> </I>Practice, Guidance notes, etc, and that they do not engage in
work practices which prevent other contractors from complying with such.</P>
<P>2.3.7 Nirex will require its RCF contractors to monitor the employee
relations conduct of each of their subcontractors, as appropriate) to ensure
compliance with this policy.</P>
<P>2.3.8 All RCF contractors must develop and adhere to a Code of Employee
Relations Practice, which reflects, and adds methodology to, the policy outlined
above and which is to the approval of Nirex.</P>
<P><A NAME="A3"></A><B>3.0 GENERAL</B></P>
<P>3.1 This Model Code of Employee Relations Practice (CERP) for work on the
RCF site, the Civil Engineering Construction Conciliation Board for Great
Britain Working Rule Agreement (WRA) and other national and any local agreements
as referred to in this CERP, shall apply insofar as they do not conflict with
the current employment legislation.</P>
<P>3.2 The term 'local agreements' refers to any local agreements which may be
formally entered into by any contractors undertaking Works on the RCF Site.</P>
<P>3.3 Civil Engineering and Building Works shall be carried out in accordance
with the WRA, or any other recognised agreement, which shall, where appropriate
(or in the case of conflict or ambiguity), take precedence over this CERP. Work
in other disciplines shall be carried out in accordance with appropriate
national agreements, as approved by Nirex.</P>
<P>3.4 So as not to prejudice the operations of other contractors or to produce
disharmony on the Site or the adjacent BNFL site at Sellafield, contractors
shall not enter into individual agreements with their workforce which are not in
accordance with this CERP.</P>
<P>3.5 Nirex will meet regularly with contractors to review jointly employee
relations policies and procedures.</P>
<P>3.6 Nirex approval given in accordance with this CERP shall not relieve the
contractor of any of his obligations or liabilities.</P>
<P>3.7 All references to the male person throughout this CERP, shall be
interpreted as applying equally to the female person.</P>
<P>3.8 All references to 'contractor' or 'contractors' should be interpreted as
applying equally to 'subcontractor' or 'subcontractors' of any tier.</P>
<P><A NAME="A4"></A><B>4.0 SUBCONTRACTORS</B></P>
<P>4.1 Where civil engineering and building contracts contain subcontract
Works, the execution of which is appropriate to national and/or local agreements
other than the WRA, those Works shall be carried out in accordance with those
agreements. Details of known relevant local agreements in operation are
available from Nirex.</P>
<P>4.2 In order to meet the policy objective of compatibility of site
practices, contractors shall ensure that their subcontractors comply with all
relevant policies, procedures and conditions with which they themselves have to
comply and also to any others specific to the particular subcontract discipline
involved.</P>
<P>4.3 Contractors shall furnish their subcontractors at tender stage with
details of any relevant national or local agreements and procedures particular
to the subcontract discipline involved and ensure that subcontractors' tenders
take appropriate account of any such agreements and procedures.</P>
<P><A NAME="A5"></A><B>5.0 RECRUITMENT AND SELECTION OF THE WORKFORCE</B></P>
<P>5.1 Contractors shall comply with all relevant legislation in respect of the
employment of personnel.</P>
<P>5.2 Contractors should develop and follow recruitment procedures which
ensure that suitable manpower is employed. Suitable manpower should include,
where reasonable and practicable, local personnel with relevant skills and
experience and/or those local personnel who can be suitably trained, and having
regard to equal opportunities legislation.</P>
<P>5.3 In order to ensure the practical application of paragraph 5.2 above, the
Contractor, with the assistance of Nirex, shall take all reasonable measures to
ensure that all recruitment agencies (and other recruitment sources) involved
use the Whitehaven Employment Service Job Centre as a focal point and/or
advertise locally, and that this practice is closely monitored.</P>
<P><A NAME="A6"></A><B>6.0 TRAINING OF THE WORKFORCE</B></P>
<P>6.1<B> </B>New recruits shall be given induction training to enable them to
integrate quickly and effectively into an efficient workforce. This induction
should include, as a minimum:-</P>
<UL>
<LI> a description of the project
</LI>
<LI> the Contractor's site organisation
</LI>
<LI> the geography of the project site
</LI>
<LI> health, safety and welfare arrangements including site emergency
procedures. [If directed by Nirex this will include the response to any nuclear
emergency at the adjacent BNFL Site at Sellafield]
</LI>
<LI> security (including random searching)
</LI>
<LI> details of any productivity schemes
</LI>
<LI> arrangements for trades union representatives
</LI>
<LI> arrangements for the payment of remuneration
</LI>
<LI> an understanding of the WRA and other relevant national and/or local
agreement
</LI>
<LI> an understanding of the current health and safety legislation and the
Nirex approach to health and safety, as detailed in section 11 of this CERP
</LI>
<LI> where applicable, specialist training for all personnel before going
underground
</LI></UL>
<P>6.2 Contractors shall ensure that their supervisors have had adequate
training to enable them to undertake their duties effectively. This training
should have included, as a minimum: -</P>
<UL>
<LI> the technical aspects of the role
</LI>
<LI> man management/supervisory skills
</LI>
<LI> the conditions of employment
</LI>
<LI> the structure and workings of the organisation
</LI>
<LI> the productivity scheme, if any
</LI>
<LI> the disciplinary and grievance procedures
</LI>
<LI> the health and safety policy and related procedures
</LI>
<LI> an understanding of demarcation practices, where applicable
</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="A7"></A><B>7.0 DISCIPLINARY AND GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES</B></P>
<P>7.1 Contractors shall have an effective disciplinary procedure based on that
contained in the WRA (or other national or local agreement, where applicable)
and in line with the ACAS Code of Practice. In particular, the procedure should
ensure that:-</P>
<UL>
<LI>no disciplinary action is taken against the representative of a recognised
trades union without prior consultation with a full time trades union official,
and that</LI>
<LI> Nirex is informed of the circumstances whenever an employee has been
dismissed or suspended for disciplinary reasons
</LI>
<LI> disciplinary action for unsafe acts is explicitly covered
</LI></UL>
<P>7.2 Contractors and their subcontractors shall have an effective grievance
procedure in accordance with the WRA or other agreement, as appropriate.
Personnel with designated responsibilities for the resolution of grievances
shall be clearly identified to the workforce and its designated representatives.</P>
<P><A NAME="A8"></A><B>8.0 CLAIMS AND DISPUTES</B></P>
<P>8.1 Employee relations issues arising could have site-wide effects as well
as effects on the adjacent BNFL sites at Sellafield. Contractors must,
therefore, discuss any actual formal or impending claims from or disputes with
their employees or their representatives (including those in respect of their
subcontractors) with Nirex as they arise, and advise Nirex of their intended
response.</P>
<P>8.2 Any employee relations issue or dispute arising or impending, which is
or could be of significance to the Site or the BNFL Sellafield complex as a
whole should be discussed between the Contractor and Nirex and, where necessary,
at collective Contractor/Nirex meetings of a regular or ad hoc nature, which
Nirex will convene as is necessary/practicable.</P>
<P><A NAME="A9"></A><B>9.0 TRADES UNION REPRESENTATION</B></P>
<P>9.1 Contractors shall respect the right of their employees to belong to an
appropriate trades union. Where the trades union is recognised they should
develop a relationship with, and promote the authority of, full-time trades
union officials.</P>
<P>9.2 Contractors shall ensure compatibility in affording recognition and
facilities for employees representatives. [Reference should be made to the ACAS
draft Code of Practice entitled &quot;Time Off for Trade Union Duties and
Activities&quot;].</P>
<P>9.3 Contractors shall ensure that trades union officials and other
representatives confine their activities on site to the people they represent.</P>
<P>9.4 Stewards committees and convenors representing contractors' employees
across the Site as a whole will not be recognised.</P>
<P><A NAME="A10"></A><B>10.0 FATALITIES AND BEREAVEMENT</B></P>
<P>Contractors shall have procedures in force to deal with employee relations
issues following the death of an employee.</P>
<P><A NAME="A11"></A><B>11.0 HEALTH, SAFETY AND WELFARE</B></P>
<P>11.1 To highlight the crucial importance of health and safety, the
Contractor should play a proactive and comprehensive role in meeting his
responsibilities as detailed within the CERP and the WRA, or other recognised
agreements. It would be particularly appropriate to bring relevant parties
together in regular fora<I> </I>to discuss health and safety issues and provide
a focus for the mission of providing a constantly and consistently safe and
healthy environment -i.e. to create a 'health and safety culture'.</P>
<P>11.2 In pursuing the policy outlined in paragraph 11.1 above, contractors
must ensure that they comply with:-</P>
<UL>
<LI> all current legislation and recognised codes of practice and guidance
notes covering health, safety and welfare at work
</LI>
<LI> the RCF Health and Safety Manual
</LI>
<LI> all site regulations and instructions produced by Nirex, and
</LI>
<LI> all other instructions and directives as may be issued, from time to time,
by Nirex.
</LI></UL>
<P><A NAME="A12"></A><B>12.0 RELATIONSHIP WITH THE COMMUNICATIONS MEDIA</B></P>
<P>12.1 The Contractor's Press Officer shall keep in regular communication with
the Nirex Head of Corporate Communications or nominated deputy and inform him of
any press statement concerning the Site, or employee relations matters which
might affect site operations, that the contractor would like to make prior to
releasing any such statement to external communications media.</P>
<P>12.2 Nirex and the Contractor will provide to one another a responsible
account of their respective management viewpoints on any employee relations
issue, before responding to media enquiries.</P>
<P>12.3 In matters concerning employee relations on the Site, Contractors shall
not attempt to negotiate, or to communicate any views which conflict with those
of Nirex or other contractors, via the media.</P>
<P></P>
